<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-GINGRICH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GINGRICH SAYS HE WALKED THE PLANK FOR HIS PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  WASHINGTON _ House Speaker Newt Gingrich, in his first
extended remarks since announcing his departure from Congress, says
he decided to step down to avoid a divisive battle for his job that
might damage the Republican Party and its chance to regain the
White House in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to make a decisive choice between my own interests and
what I believe to be the more important cause of the country and my
party,'' Gingrich told political supporters at a Washington hotel
Monday. ``On Friday it became clear to me that if I were to remain
in the House, I would be an excuse for divisiveness and
factionalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ideas are too big, the issues are too important for any
one person to put their office above the good of the country and
the party.''
</P>
<P>
   The speech before GOPAC, a political action committee that has
been a key part of Gingrich's election machinery, marked the first
lengthy comments by the speaker since he announced Friday he would
leave both his leadership post and his seat representing suburban
Atlanta. He resigned after Republicans lost five House seats in the
Nov. 3 election, rather than posting the gains party leaders had
promised.
</P>
<P>
   Before the speech, Gingrich, 55, warmly greeted Representative
Bob Livingston of Louisiana, a one-time political ally who helped
push Gingrich to retire by announcing his own candidacy for the
speaker's job on Friday. Livingston appeared to clinch the race for
speaker Monday, as the only other declared candidate dropped out.
In his address, Gingrich called Livingston ``the next speaker of
the House.''
</P>
<P>
   In his 45-minute address, Gingrich trumpeted the party's
successes of the past two decades and laid out an extensive agenda
for the Republican Congress. He appeared to address critics who
complained he had fumbled the election by focusing too much on the
possible impeachment of President Clinton and too little on winning
congressional achievements that would help Republican candidates at
the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich said the federal surplus, expected to total $1.6
trillion over the next decade, ``belongs to the American taxpayer,
not the Washington bureaucrats. ... Let's get it back home at a
rate faster than Al Gore and Teddy Kennedy can invent new
bureaucracies.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Congress should ``save'' the Social Security program,
which faces financial troubles early in the next century, by
allowing workers to pay their retirement taxes into individual
retirement accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich also said the surplus should be returned to voters
through tax cuts, including a 5 percent cut in capital gains taxes
and the elimination of inheritance taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Touching other traditional GOP themes, Gingrich also called on
Congress to boost spending for a system to defend against enemy
missiles and to create vouchers that allow parents to send their
children to the schools of their choice.
</P>
<P>
   He quoted from Alexis de Tocqueville and from the founding
documents of the nation. He offered no clues about his future
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewing the highlights of his own career, Gingrich said it was
``a tremendous honor'' to be the first Republican speaker since
1954 and the first to be reelected since 1928.
</P>
<P>
   To great applause, he displayed a copy of the original Contract
with America that appeared as an advertisement in TV Guide. He said
the Republican-led Congress had fulfilled the contract by passing
welfare reform, a balanced budget, IRS reform, antidrug
legislation, and a boost in military spending, among others.
</P>
<P>
   In speaking before GOPAC, Gingrich returned to an organization
that played a large part in both his rise and his fall.
</P>
<P>
   The political action committee was created in 1979 by Republican
governors to help fund candidates for state offices. When Gingrich
took control in 1986, he turned its attention to congressional
races.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
