<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-MCLAREN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCLAREN REJOINS BRUINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Six weeks into the new season, the Bruins finally got
their old team back together, reaching agreement on a three-year
pact with Kyle McLaren that will pay the 21-year-old defenseman at
least $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, expected to be signed Tuesday when McLaren reports to
practice, includes reasonably achievable bonuses that could boost
the total value to $5.175 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an all right deal,'' said a relieved but subdued McLaren,
reached at home Monday. ``I don't think it's the best deal for me,
but it's something that I can accept for now. I'll accept it, but I
don't like the way it was negotiated at all.''
</P>
<P>
   By agreeing to a three-year pact, McLaren surrendered his
opportunity to go to salary arbitration after the 1999-2000 season.
Had he not agreed to a three-year pact, however, McLaren wasn't
going to do better than a one-year deal at $800,000, a deal the
Bruins insisted be discounted for the month-plus of work he missed
while holding out.
</P>
<P>
   The sides had agreed to a one-year deal late last week, but it
fell apart when McLaren's lead agent, Doug Messier, insisted that
his client be remunerated for the lost wages. When talks resumed
Monday, following a phone conversation between McLaren and
assistant general manager Mike O'Connell on Sunday, the sides went
back to discussing a three-year pact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was getting on the bus (prior to the game Sunday in North
Carolina), talking to him by phone, and I said, `Kyle, this is
getting ridiculous,''' said O'Connell. ``They weren't going to get
that money back unless they gave up something in return _ and what
they gave up is term. Once we had (three years), we could make
adjustments _ and that's what we did.''
</P>
<P>
   McLaren's options, beyond sitting out and forfeiting a year's
pay, essentially were nil. The NHL requested last week that IHL
teams stop offering holdouts safe havens, places to keep their
games warm and their bills paid while they continue contract talks.
McLaren also couldn't have joined the Canadian national team
unless, essentially, the Bruins agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I don't think that was going to happen,'' said McLaren.
</P>
<P>
   It now is up to Pat Burns and his coaching staff to decide when
McLaren gets back in the lineup. Including training camp, McLaren
has missed two months of active duty. He believes he'll be
game-ready in short order, but he'll leave that decision to Burns &AMP;
Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in pretty good shape, but I don't want to rush myself,
either,'' said McLaren. ``I guess I could be ready this Thursday,
or the weekend, but I'll see how it goes starting (today), and then
I'll let them know how I feel, and they'll let me know how they
feel.''
</P>
<P>
   According to O'Connell, the deal was not made with the idea of
signing McLaren and shipping him out in a trade. The Bruins see him
as a key element on their blue line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We drafted him,'' said O'Connell. ``We know what we've got.''
</P>
<P>
   Potentially, the deal represents nearly a threefold salary
increase for McLaren, whose original three-year deal expired in the
spring. Initially, he was aiming for the $2 million-a-year
neighborhood but had to settle for considerably less.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy it's done,'' said McLaren. ``It gets me back on the
ice, playing for a team I love and a coach I love. But I still
feel, for what I've done the last three years, I could have done a
little better. But that's not the way Harry (Sinden) and Mike
looked at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing has left me with a bitter taste. This is
something that I'm never going to forget. Hopefully, I'll have a
long career and this is just a bump in the road. Hopefully, down
the road, I can earn the money, and deserve the money I think I can
get. I'm dedicated to my coach and my teammates, I'm glad to be
back. But this is going to leave something in my mouth the whole
season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
