A2654 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-LEADERS11-CO     11-10 0480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-LEADERS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TOP HOUSE JOBS TO BE DECIDED NEXT WEEK
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Here are descriptions of the major leadership posts
that Republican House members will fill at their Oct. 18
organizational meeting.
</P>
<P>
   These duties often shift slightly from one Congress to another,
depending on the personalities and experience of the people who
hold the jobs. But the general responsibilities are shaped by
decades of tradition.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker's salary is $175,000 and the majority leader's is
$151,800. All other leaders receive the standard House member's pay
of $136,700.
</P>
<P>
   SPEAKER
</P>
<P>
   The only House officer mentioned in the Constitution, the
speaker presides over the floor proceedings, controls the
legislative agenda, recognizes speakers in debates, and has a major
role in appointing committees and chairmen. The speaker _ who need
not be a member of Congress _ also stands third in line for the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans will pick their nominee for the post Oct. 18, but
the final vote takes place after the full House convenes Jan. 6.
The vote for speaker is generally cast along party lines, a
practice that has guaranteed that the majority party controls the
speakership.
</P>
<P>
   MAJORITY LEADER
</P>
<P>
   Chosen by the majority party in the House, this top assistant to
the speaker carries much of the day-to-day responsibility for
scheduling, managing and promoting the party's legislation on the
House floor. He or she also acts as a primary public spokesman for
party positions.
</P>
<P>
   MAJORITY WHIP
</P>
<P>
   The job of the whip is to keep track of support for major
legislative issues and to make sure party members are present for
close votes. The whip is assisted by scores of deputies and
assistants who constantly count votes and lobby party members to
vote for bills strongly backed by the House leadership. However,
the whip has no formal powers to require party loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   The name of the post comes from ``whipper-in,'' a British
hunting term for the person who keeps foxhounds from leaving the
pack.
</P>
<P>
   CONFERENCE CHAIRMAN
</P>
<P>
   This post calls for keeping the House Republican membership,
known as the party conference, up to date on provisions of
legislation coming to the floor. The conference sets party rules,
builds unity through retreats and other meetings, sends out
research on major issues, and faxes news releases to the news media
giving the party's views.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN COMMITTEE CHAIRMAN
</P>
<P>
   A key figure in election efforts, this official has the job of
raising campaign funds and distributing them, chiefly on behalf of
the party's incumbents. The campaign chairman puts candidates in
touch with a network of political action committees from various
business and special interests.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
