<HEADER>
A2660 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARCHDEACON-COLUMN11-C     11-10 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHDEACON-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    From sodier's uniform to basketball uniform
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ As a teenager growing up in Kefar Sava, a town
some 20 kilometers northwest of Tel Aviv, Israel, he heard Scud
missiles go across his house and destroy parts of nearby
neighborhoods during the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   A few years later _ playing for the 18-and-under Israeli
national basketball team that was touring Europe _ he ended up at a
game in Mannheim, Germany, where a mob of skinhead thugs outside
the gym jeered him and his teammates, shouting, as he called it,
``threats and Nazi trash talk.''
</P>
<P>
   And just a couple of years ago, he found himself on nighttime
patrol along the streets of the conflict-torn Gaza Strip. These
were the same streets were fellow soldiers had been ambushed and
killed by Palestinian terrorists, the same streets where he himself
had had rocks and spit and insults hurled his way.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, for everything he's heard and seen and endured, nothing
made the Wright State basketball debut of Israel Sheinfeld any
easier last week. As the freshman sat in the Nutter Center dressing
room with his teammates and waited to play a meaningless exhibition
game against a loosely-knit club of local players, he was on edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had real butterflies,'' Sheinfeld said. ``I was nervous
about how I'd do playing college basketball in America. I wasn't
sure, 'Would I fit in over here?'''
</P>
<P>
   That night and again Monday in the Raiders'final preseason game
against Athletes in Action, Sheinfeld came off the bench and showed
a promising mix of inside bulk and a soft, left-handed touch. And
that has prompted Wright State assistant coach Will Rey to assuage
the big man's fears: ``He's going to fit just fine. Israel is real
conscientious and has a ton of potential, he just needs to get
comfortable with the speed and intensity of the game over here.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, instead of the hunter green of Wright State,
Sheinfeld was dressed in the dark green uniform of the Israeli
army. Rather than those black and white Nike Face-Up shoes of the
Raiders, he wore combat boots, a beret and carried an M-16 rifle.
</P>
<P>
   The guy the other Wright State players simply call ''Big Is''
spent three years as a soldier in the Israeli Army. But while
military service was his duty, American college basketball was his
dream. And because he was 6-foot-10, 250 pounds and had an
impressive basketball resume _ playing on national teams that
toured Italy, Greece, Bulgaria, Sicily, Yugoslavia and Macedonia,
as well as playing as an amateur on three different teams in the
first division of the Israel pro league _ switching uniforms wasn't
that tough when his military duty ended in March.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Sheinfeld ending up at Wright State has been pure hoop
happenstance. His coaches had sent tapes of him to American
colleges, then talked him up at the basketball camps _ most notably
the Five Star Camps _ they participated in.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was set to go to Iowa, but it took a while to get his
transcript together after he left the army. The Hawkeyes said they
couldn't wait and signed a 7-foot- 1 All-America player instead .
</P>
<P>
   Sheinfeld finally took one recruiting trip _ a 48-hour whirlwind
visit to McNeese State _ but Lakes Charles, La., was too much of a
culture shock on his first visit ever to the United States. In
June, he returned to America for a look at Wright State, where
Raider coaches showed him the Nutter Center from a dozen different
angles, let him hobnob with a few players and, before he caught a
flight back to Tel Aviv, made sure they got his name on a letter of
intent.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner had Sheinfeld signed here when the University of Miami
(Fla.) made him an offer. ``It didn't matter because I gave Wright
State my word,'' he said. ``And I think Ohio and Dayton are best
for me and what I want to do. I like quieter places. If I went to
New York City, Boston or California, I might not concentrate on my
basketball like I should. Back in Israel, we consider America as a
promised land. This is like a dream coming here and I want to make
sure I do the best to make my dreams happen.''
</P>
<P>
   That the 22-year-old Sheinfeld is so able to look ahead, might
have something to do with what he can look back upon. His father
was a Russian Jew who experienced the bias and persecutions of the
pogroms in the Soviet Union. And several family members in the
generation before that were killed in the Holocaust. His mother's
family was driven from Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in Israel, which Sheinfeld _ using his fingers to
indicate quote marks _ calls ``a war country,'' meant developing a
special mindset: ``When you live somewhere where you never know
where the next act of terrorism might be, you get a certain point
of view on the world. It's not as carefree a life as America kids
live. For us, we go to a mall or a crowded spot and you always feel
a police presence. You never know when someone might try to hurt
people in a crowd. Lots of innocent people _ on both sides _ are
dying.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why now _ as Israeli and Palestinian leaders try to
cobble a Mideast peace accord against a backdrop of violence like
last Friday's deadly car bombing in Jerusalem _ Sheinfeld perches
himself in front of the television in the team's lounge: ``I try to
watch CNN to see what is happening. Peace is our only hope to
change things for the better.''
</P>
<P>
   As it is now, as soon as Israeli boys and girls turn 18, they
are required to spend three years in the military, Sheinfeld said.
In his service, he learned to handle weapons like an Uzi, Galil,
M-16 and grenades and he spent his time in places like the Gaza
Strip. Eventually, he got reassigned to administrative work because
he was designated a ``special athlete.'' That enabled him to play
in the Israel league and represent his country in international
tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, for all his experience, he said adjusting here has been
tough. When he first came came to Wright State 10 weeks ago, he was
terribly homesick. Since then, some Israeli military families who
are involved with projects at Wright Patterson Air Force Base have
taken him under their wing, inviting him for dinners of his beloved
schnitzel. Assistant coach Ken Barer, who is Jewish, has taken him
to the Beth Jacob synagogue on North Main.
</P>
<P>
   As for getting fully comfortable on the court, that may take a
little more time. ``Basketball is totally different here,''
Sheinfeld said. ``The speed and intensity are greater and I must
improve my strength, my technique. Coach Rey is a good big man
coach and he is building me over brick by brick. I want to be sure
I'm solid when he is done.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, anyone who saw Sheinfeld that day in Mannheim _ when
he used nothing but a basketball to dunk Nazi bile _ knows he
already is pretty solid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our coach had prepared us mentally and psychologically for
their hostility that day and I was ready,'' he said. ``I ended up
with 18 points, 10 rebounds and I made the game winning free throw
in the last second. It's the basketball moment I remember most...so
far.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Archdeacon writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
