</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kids' responses teach lesson about `Johnnies' of the world
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio. _ A while back one of my columns raised the
question: Who failed Johnny? Was it his teachers? His parents? The
system? Or was it Johnny himself?
</P>
<P>
   There were no ponderous solutions offered. Obviously, if I had
inside knowledge as to why kids aren't making it in school, we'd
have no more failures, and the folks at Mt. Rushmore would be
blasting out a new face on the side of the mountain. Mine.
</P>
<P>
   Response to the ``Johnny'' article was substantial. Mail from
concerned parents and educators flooded in from every corner of the
country - all echoing the same theme: We must do something about
Johnny. But what? The writers weren't pointing fingers or laying
blame on any particular doorstep, and none had a cure-all for
education's ills. All we're frustrated with the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   One reader, a teacher of Navajo children in New Mexico, went a
step further. He had his writing class (a group he refers to as ``a
bright little crew of mixed 9th- to 12th-graders'') read ``Who's
Failing Johnny?'' and write a critique. He mailed the results to
me. What his students had to say about the ``Johnnies'' in the
system was too good not to be shared.
</P>
<P>
   Eutovia writes: ``I really don't know what can be done, but all
I know is that maybe if I don't turn in more assignments, then I
probably could fit into that same position.''
</P>
<P>
   Almeria: ``In my opinion Johnny is failing Johnny. The parents
should understand that their child is not making an effort in
class. The student may just be fooling around and talking in class.
</P>
<P>
   ``The student probably doesn't even show up in class daily. That
is a problem teachers have to deal with. The teacher cannot teach
someone something if that person is not present to learn it.''
</P>
<P>
   Benson: ``Johnny is the one failing himself. It seems he does
not care about his education. He is not making any effort. On the
other hand his parents have the same attitude toward their child's
education. They are also not making any effort to be part of
Johnny's education. They get involved when it's too late. They get
mad and start blaming the teachers as well as how the school system
works, while they are the ones who are trying to help Johnny.''
</P>
<P>
   Shane: ``I think Johnny is failing himself, not because he's
stupid but just because he hasn't enough pride in himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should try to enforce school laws in the classrooms to
encourage and help students, not in a vain way but in a very
disciplined and courteous way.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can be done now is probably nothing at the moment, but
what the future will bring nobody knows. We could hire new teachers
with more integrity, not like Mr. ; he's too scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Kellie: ``My peers just don't realize what a good education can
do for you. If I could only blame one source, it would be the
parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how far a little support can go. I have a cousin
with the same problem and I know how frustrating it was for her. My
family spent many hours talking and listening. She had formerly
been in a place where little or no support was given. With the
change in the environment and support, she has changed. I have seen
what it can do, and this could be all that Johnny needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Amber: ``Well, I think that this short story is kind of weird.
It seems his parents don't care about Johnny's education. The
parents think the teacher is the one responsible for failing
Johnny. They don't think it's Johnny's fault
</P>
<P>
   for not doing the work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parents are setting a very bad example for Johnny. Who
knows - Johnny's kids might just be as bad as he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany: ``A concerned parent should not wait until a child
fails to speak up. As for Johnny, he caused his grades to drop. His
nonchalant attitude must have been learned somewhere. Children will
pick up and learn anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Jon comes right to the point: ``...the parents can raise dust
and cuss at the teacher, but that won't help. The parents and
teachers can try to help all they want; it still won't help Johnny.
It's only up to him to get the grade he wants or deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   And finally, a word from their teacher: ``They (the students)
were unanimous in the conviction that more than anybody else,
Johnny is failing Johnny. They all knew Johnnies of their own.''
</P>
<P>
   He suggests that one of these days I turn out a piece on
attendance though it's probably not the problem in Gibsonburg that
it is where he teaches. ``We run about 20 to 25 percent absence
each day. Then our constituents wonder why our poor kids are two or
three years behind grade level on all standardized
</P>
<P>
   tests. I computed, whimsically, that if we run 20 percent
absence for four years, then two to three years behind is about par
for the course. Twenty percent of 12 years is 2.4 years!''
</P>
<P>
   There are no easy answers to ``Who's failing Johnny?'' We're
educating more kids better than we ever did before, but we can't
overlook the fact that the wheels of education are not turning as
smoothly as they once did. Maybe it's just a case of figuring out
where to apply the grease.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett is a teacher in Gibsonburg, Ohio. She writes
for Cox News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
