<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Family wins car that's too fast to drive
 &HT;    By Mike Kelley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DRIPPING SPRINGS, Texas _ Spencer Davis, being 3 years old,
really wanted the little Hot Wheels car model that came with a
container of a new Valvoline fuel additive. His dad, Scott, being a
dad, got it for him. This was in July.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until a couple of days later that Scott noticed the
contest entry form that came with the package. What the heck, he
thought. Might win something.
</P>
<P>
   Monday morning, that something was delivered to the Scott home
in Dripping Springs. It's a 750-horsepower Winston Cup Ford Taurus
_ grand prize in the Valvoline Race Car Sweepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   The Davises learned of the prize in September but were
skeptical. Even when Valvoline said the family would be flown to
Phoenix for last month's Winston Cup race, a friend warned that
there was probably a time-share pitch lurking nearby. In Phoenix,
Scott and his wife, Becky Davis, Spencer and 8-year-old Mary
Catherine met NASCAR star Mark Martin, who has raced the Taurus.
</P>
<P>
   What they'll do with the 200-mph car, the Davises don't yet
know. For the moment, it goes in the garage where Becky's Suburban
has been.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lost my parking place,'' she says. They'll probably
display the car at the several tire stores Scott owns in the Austin
area.
</P>
<P>
   Driving it is not an option. It's not street-legal.
</P>
<P>
   And watching the 6-foot-3-inch Scott try to cram himself into a
car built for Martin, who is nine inches shorter, Davis'
brother-in-law Paul Wilson observed: ``He can't even drive it, poor
guy. It's every man's torture. Now he has the ultimate toy, and he
can't get in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Kelley writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
