A2666 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELRAY-DRUGS11-COX     11-10 1537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELRAY-DRUGS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Addicts discover treatment, forgiveness in Delray, Fla.
 &HT;    By Seth Mnookin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DELRAY BEACH, Fla. _ It's midnight on a Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   A hundred or so sweat-soaked, scantily clad dancers gyrate under
the glare of strobe lights, disco balls and smoke machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to Central House,'' Katie, a 19-year-old from
Pennsylvania, says as someone walks through the door. ``Tickets are
$5, but if you're in treatment, we might be able to swing you a
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Central House, located on the Delray Beach-Boynton Beach border,
is an Alcoholics Anonymous clubhouse. It is home to dozens of AA
meetings each week _ for women, men, beginners, alcoholics only _
and recently has become the site of a monthly ``rave'' modeled
after the ones at big-city all-night dance clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Central House is also a focal point of an unusual and vital
community in southern Palm Beach County _ a community of recovering
alcoholics and drug abusers that by experts' accounts is
surprisingly large for the area's size and suburban character.
</P>
<P>
   That size has in part fueled the area's reputation as a magnet
for substance abuse treatment centers for Florida and the East
Coast, according to dozens of treatment professionals, law
enforcement officers and city officials. Experts consider it on par
with well-known treatment meccas such as Minnesota's Twin Cities,
home to the Hazelden clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Gross, a Delray Beach psychiatrist who has worked with
several of the programs over the past decade, says the sheer number
and variety of resources are crucial to the area's reputation as a
center of recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only are there a number of options for longer-term
treatment,'' Gross says, ``but there's a vertical hierarchy of
care. You can go from a detox to a hospital to primary treatment to
a sober house or a halfway house all within a couple of miles of
each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``And a lot of the people you deal with are going to know one
another. So there's a continuity available here which is extremely
important,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Delray Beach's six residential programs _ along with three
others that have residences or offices in both Boca Raton and
Delray Beach _ can at any one time house about 300 patients,
according to state officials. An equal number remain in treatment
on a daily basis while living in halfway houses or on their own,
records show. Delray Beach has a population of about 53,000 _
that's one person in treatment for every 88 residents, and that's
not including people living in sober halfway houses.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison, Miami has more than six times the population but
only about 1 1/2 times as many residential treatment centers.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually every level of city official views the prominence of
Delray Beach's recovery community favorably.
</P>
<P>
   ``The community involvement in Delray is great,'' says Rick
Lincoln, the Palm Beach County Sheriff's Office's director of law
enforcement, who served two decades with the Delray Beach police.
``If we can take someone involved in drugs and get them to change
their life instead of throwing them in jail, that's a real
positive.''
</P>
<P>
   But the treatment centers are only one part of the community.
Often, addicts and alcoholics are sent to Delray Beach not to go to
treatment but to live in a halfway or sober house. There are more
than a dozen such in Delray Beach, ranging from the Lighthouse,
which holds AA meetings and has 60 beds to less formal arrangements
forged between groups of recovering people.
</P>
<P>
   David S., 29, is an example of someone who skipped treatment and
came to live in the Recovery Zone, a furnished sober house where
shared apartments go for $125 per week. ``I'd been in treatment for
two of the last eight years,'' David says. ``What else was I going
to learn in a residential treatment program?''
</P>
<P>
   David moved to Delray Beach about 18 months ago. Although he had
never been to Florida before, he had heard about the area during
his years bouncing in and out of treatment centers in New York.
And, now that he is here, he says Delray Beach is maybe the only
safe place for him right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``You meet so many people in recovery here,'' David says as he
gets coffee at The Old School Bread Company, which has employed
several recovering addicts. ``See you at the 6:30,'' he says to a
young woman behind the counter, referring to a meeting that night.
At one nearby restaurant, John knows six of the eight waiters from
either treatment centers or AA meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Treatment workers say the relationship between area businesses
and the recovering community is symbiotic. Most area treatment
centers require patients to get a job at some point. And newly
sober people are usually willing to work flexible hours and at a
relatively cheap wage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employers are really wonderful about hiring patients,'' says
Judy Crane, a counselor at Wayside House, an all-women's treatment
center. ``They know they're going to get a solid worker who's going
to be committed and is going to do their best.''
</P>
<P>
   Some employers, Crane says, look forward to working with
patients from treatment: One national company with its headquarters
in Delray Beach regularly hires patients from local treatment
centers for its in-house temporary agency. More than a dozen have
been hired permanently this year alone.
</P>
<P>
   Patients who live together and go to meetings together often end
up working together as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alcoholics and addicts need to stay together,'' says Tony
Allerton, a recovering alcoholic with over a decade of sobriety.
Allerton should know: He runs one of the city's most active
clubhouses, Crossroads, which was founded in the early 1980s.
Crossroads holds as many as a dozen meetings every day.
</P>
<P>
   Allerton says the importance of community is best understood
through the ``disease concept,'' perhaps the central tenet of AA,
which holds that alcoholism and addiction are deadly, incurable
diseases. While alcoholism cannot be cured, its progress can be
arrested, according to AA, and the most important form of treatment
is talking with other recovering drug addicts and alcoholics.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good comparison can be made with diabetics,'' Allerton says.
``A diabetic needs to have insulin daily. Our insulin is the
meetings.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, you have all these people in the field: treatment
workers, counselors, and then patients,'' Gross says. ``And all
these people are all going to the same meetings, and seeing each
other all the time. And the effect is just amazing. Recovery is a
dynamic process. Time, redundancy and consistency are the most
important ingredients.''
</P>
<P>
   Gross says the fact that few people are actually from Palm Beach
County helps the recovery community. Recovering people can easily
avoid their ``triggers'' _ people, places and things that cause an
addict to possibly relapse _ are likely to be thousands of miles up
the coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a number of individuals from the Northeast, even from
Europe, who come here because they have a real need to get out of
the environment where they were using,'' Gross says.
</P>
<P>
   Theories abound as to why Palm Beach County became home to such
an unusually large number of treatment centers. Some professionals
trace it to the southern migration of the first members of
Alcoholics Anonymous, founded in the 1930s. Another theory links
former Sen. Wilbur Mills' very public stay at the Palm Beach
Institute for alcoholism treatment and subsequent activism.
</P>
<P>
   Delray Beach's Drug Abuse Foundation, which began as an
outpatient counseling service in 1968, was one of the first to take
root in southern Palm Beach County. Central House was founded that
same year. By the 1980s, there was already a core of recovering
addicts and treatment centers that mushroomed, fueled by local
acceptance and insurance companies' willingness to pay up to $1,000
a day for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there's the weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the sunshine is a factor,'' Gross says only
half-jokingly. ``I know a lot of people get seasonal depression, so
maybe all the sunlight here helps.''
</P>
<P>
   For people like John, a 30-year-old who has more than two years
clean, the reason doesn't really matter. John spends a lot of time
talking to people who have recently arrived in Delray Beach for
treatment. At a Central House dance, he took some time to chat with
a 19-year-old who arrived at the Renaissance Institute, a Delray
Beach-based treatment center, eight days earlier and already wants
to go back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever you do, stay in South Florida,'' John says. ``Stay in
Delray Beach. This place is unlike anyplace else in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   John first came to Delray Beach in 1994. A year later, John
figured he ``had everything all figured out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was staying clean, I had a job, my family was talking to
me,'' he says. ``I had it all together.'' So he decided to move to
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Within months of leaving, John says he was using heroin again.
And within a year, he was back in a treatment center in Delray
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   He says, ``I just know it works.''
</P>
<P>
   Seth Mnookin writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
