A2667 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-LYNN-UNIV11-COX     11-10 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-LYNN-UNIV11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lynn reviewing leader's salary after IRS note
 &HT;    By Don Horine
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ Donald E. Ross, president of Lynn University,
is one of the highest paid college presidents in the nation _ and
deservedly so, in the opinion of Lynn's board of trustees. But the
trustees are concerned the Internal Revenue Service may not agree.
</P>
<P>
   Ross' $320,965 salary in 1996-97 _ the last year reported _ was
higher than that of the presidents of Harvard, Massachusetts
Institute of Technology and other larger, more prestigious private
universities.
</P>
<P>
   The trustees are reexamining the salary in light of a recent IRS
announcement. The IRS said it will assess stiff penalties against
officials of nonprofit organizations, including private colleges,
whose compensation is significantly higher than those of people
holding similar jobs at comparable institutions _ unless it can be
justified.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Lynn's board hasn't paid much attention to what
presidents of comparable colleges are paid, Chairman Hugh Carville
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been in touch with our attorneys,'' Carville said.
``Our compensation committee is reviewing (the IRS ruling) right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross, 59, is the highest paid university or college president in
Florida. The next highest, University of Miami President Tad Foote,
earned $318,509 in 1996-97, the most recent year for which private
colleges and universities had to report their top officers'
compensation to the federal government. Lynn has 1,958 students. UM
has 13,422.
</P>
<P>
   John Lombardi, president of the 42,103-student University of
Florida, the state's largest school, earned $223,700 in 1996-97.
Lombardi's salary this year is $243,399.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn, UM and most other private schools won't reveal their
presidents' current salaries. The 1996-97 salaries are public
information because they are included in a federal tax report that
nonprofits must file.
</P>
<P>
   Ross' 1996-97 salary put him ahead of the presidents of many
private universities with national reputations other than Harvard
and MIT. Among them: Brandeis, Carnegie Mellon, Cornell, Dartmouth,
Duke, Emory, Georgetown, Northeastern, Northwestern, Southern
Methodist, Syracuse and Wake Forest.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, Palm Beach Atlantic College in West Palm Beach,
slightly larger than Lynn with 2,122 students, paid President Paul
Corts $112,000 in 1996-97, along with $30,975 in benefits and a
$27,500 expense account.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his salary, Ross received $26,813 in benefits and
$160,656 for expenses, including an unspecified housing allowance.
</P>
<P>
   Ross' wife, Helen, who runs Lynn's summer camps, received
$101,798 in salary in 1996-97 plus $5,090 in benefits and $7,871
for expenses, according to federal tax forms.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the tax forms, the Chronicle of Higher Education
recently reported that 46 presidents of private universities and
colleges earned more than $300,000 in 1996-97. The highest paid,
according to that report, was Judith S. Rodin of the University of
Pennsylvania, at $498,536. Fifteen of the 46 made $330,000 or more.
Harvard President Neil L. Rudenstine earned $270,057. MIT President
Charles M. Vest earned $312,000.
</P>
<P>
   Ross' salary wasn't listed in the Chronicle report, which took
into account only schools categorized by the Carnegie Foundation
for the Advancement of Teaching as research universities, doctoral
universities, masters universities and colleges and baccalaureate
colleges.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn is listed as a business college by Carnegie.
</P>
<P>
   Ross declined to talk about his salary. In a letter, he pointed
out that Lynn is a private school and that its policy is not to
discuss publicly the compensation of its faculty, staff and
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 28 years as president of Lynn University including its
three international campuses, which, I believe, makes me the
longest-serving college president in the state of Florida, I feel
there are some matters best left to the university, its president
and its trustees,'' Ross wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Carville said he thinks Ross is well worth what he gets.
</P>
<P>
   ```We think he's more than worth what he's being paid,''
Carville said. ``The board probably would even pay him more if he
demanded.''
</P>
<P>
   Christine Lynn, a trustee of the university and wife of Eugene
Lynn, after whom the school is named, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our school wouldn't be where it is today if it hadn't been for
Don Ross,'' she said. ``When you have good people, you take good
care of your people. Most presidents burn out after five or 10
years. He's had the energy and the belief to go as far as we have
gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynn would not divulge the criteria the board uses to set Ross'
salary.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Miller, acting director of the IRS' exempt organizations
division, said ``there is no hard and fast rule'' for judging
whether a college president's salary is at a proper level. However,
he said certain factors are taken into account, including pay of
presidents at comparable colleges, what duties the college assigns
to its president and how much money the college collects in a given
year.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1996, the IRS looked at whether nonprofit officials' pay
seemed out of line, but any penalties were assessed against the
organization rather than the official. Under a new law, the IRS can
assess a 25 percent excise tax on the amount of the compensation
considered excessive and require the excess to be returned to the
organization. If the excess isn't returned, the organization can be
subject to a 200 percent tax.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn has a career-oriented academic program, with bachelor's
degrees in 32 programs, master's degrees in 10 programs, and a new
doctorate program in educational leadership. It is an expensive
school _ tuition is $16,700, plus $6,250 for room and board and
$500 for fees.
</P>
<P>
   Ross put together a consortium that took over the school in 1971
when it was a Catholic junior college for women known as Marymount
and nearly $6 million in debt. Renamed the College of Boca Raton in
1974, the school continued to flirt with bankruptcy for several
years, but its fortunes turned around in the mid-1980s, thanks to
large gifts from wealthy Boca Raton philanthropists including
Eugene Lynn.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, the school was named after Lynn and elevated to a
university. Since then, it has continued to prosper, raising $22.5
million for new buildings, including two residence halls, a
library, an international center and an academic building.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Ross has been aggressively trying to give Lynn
an international reputation. In 1991, he established a sister
school, the 350-student American College Dublin in Dublin, Ireland.
He is in the process of establishing another campus in Argentina
and has developed affiliations with universities in France, Russia,
Germany and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Ross' wife started the Pine Tree summer camps 19 years ago. In
1996-97, Lynn took in $1.5 million from the camps and conferences.
</P>
<P>
   Don Horine writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
