u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEG0-ROBOTS11-COX     11-10 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEG0-ROBOTS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For techno whizzes, building robo Legos is a snap
 &HT;    By Michele Chan Santos
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ We gave three techies an extracurricular
challenge: see what kind of robot you can build in 24 hours. Using
a Lego set.
</P>
<P>
   Lego Mindstorms, the latest Lego product, is not the toy you
remember from childhood. With Mindstorms, you get to build and
program your own robot. Using Lego pieces and gears, a robot is
assembled, with an eraser-size microcomputer, the RCX, at its core.
Next, you write a program on your PC, using a CD-ROM that comes
with the set. Your PC beams the program to the microcomputer via a
special infrared transmitter.
</P>
<P>
   The box says it's for kids 12 and up, but we suspect it's a toy
aimed at computer-savvy grown-ups who remember playing with Legos
as children. Though the price tag is steep _ $200, with $50
accessory kits _ it's likely to sell well in Central Texas, where
many of our computer experts recall creating their first machines
with Legos' familiar plastic blocks. The tracking robot Created by
Matthew Lamari His title programmer, Charybdis Enterprises What his
robot did It followed a black track around a piece of paper, one of
the challenges Lego suggests to Mindstorm players. The robot had a
light sensor that could detect the difference between dark and
light paper; it followed the dark oval around the sheet. Lamari
played with Legos as a child, building a whole village out of
them(It had a gas station, houses and shops) and later built cars
and other vehicles with more advanced Lego sets. If he still had
some of his old Lego toys, Mindstorm's microcomputer would be great
for putting inside another creation, like a race car or a boat,
Lamari says. How long it took him to build it About six hours. What
else you should know I wouldn't have minded if somebody had given
me this when I was 12 years old. The musical robot Created by Randy
Spurlock His title senior staff software engineer, 3Dfx Interactive
What his robot did The robot played music, using its light sensor
to read stripes on paper that were varying shades of gray (each
shade indicated a different note.) It played Mary Had a Little
Lamb. That's a robotic talent that arose sheerly from Spurlock's
imagination; it's not a function Lego suggested. Spurlock's
8-year-old daughter, Sarah, named the robot Bobby. Like Lamari's
robot, Bobby could also follow a track around a sheet of paper.
Bobby had antennae, too. If you let him loose on the carpet, he'd
go in a straight line until someone touched one of his antennae,
and then he'd back up and go in a different direction. Bobby had
tank-style treads on his wheels, a suggestion from Spurlock's
10-year-old son, Chris. How long it took him An hour to build the
robot; five or six hours to program it. What else you should know
Spurlock is an old hand at Legos, having built many sophisticated
Lego toys for his kids. They include a helicopter, a race car with
gears that shift, planes and boats. He got tips on building his
robot from the World Wide Web, where aspiring robot-builders have
already put up sites. (Two sites to try are www.legomindstorms.com
or www.globalserve.net/ 7/8dastolfo/.) The ping-pong ball robot
Created by Thomas Dundon His title software engineer, Applied
Science Fiction What his robot did Dundon's robot was able to find
a ping-pong ball in a given area, beep when it found it and bring
it back to the central part of the machine with a long, extended
arm, beeping again when it was done.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Dundon aspired to build a machine that would launch
the ping-pong ball, find it, bring it back and measure how far away
it had been. He ended up not using the launcher, but he was close
to having the robot measure distance when we arrived. To his
credit, Dundon's invention doesn't much resemble any of the
suggested robots Lego shows you how to build in the instructions
that come with the toy. It's based on a projectile experiment
Dundon once used in physics class. How long it took him 12 hours.
What else you should knowUnlike Spurlock and Lamari, Dundon hadn't
ever played with Legos before. I played with Lincoln Logs as a kid,
he says. Was Lego Mindstorms fun? Oh, yeah, he says. Otherwise, I
wouldn't have stayed up all night working on it.
</P>
<P>
   Michele Chan Santos writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
