A2670 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAYTON-DUNBAR11-COX     11-10 0398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAYTON-DUNBAR11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dunbar house a haven for health
 &HT;    (EDS: cq Thursday 11-12)
 &HT;    By Jim DeBrosse
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The Paul Laurence Dunbar House in Dayton would
seem an unlikely place to hold a free community health screening,
until one learns more about the famed poet's life.
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar, the son of slaves, watched his younger sister die at age
2 from a respiratory illness while his mother could apply only home
remedies. Dunbar himself suffered from recurring respiratory
problems for most of his 33 years, yet never saw a physician until
his childhood friend, William ``Bud'' Burns, became Dayton's first
black doctor in the 1890s.
</P>
<P>
   Lack of access to health care ``isn't so much racial today as it
is economic, but it's still a problem in the black community,''
said LaVerne Sci, historic site manager of the Dunbar House State
Memorial Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Sci said Dunbar would be proud that the museum is hosting the
Sixth Annual West Dayton Diabetes Day on Thursday. ``We want very
much to be a living museum with relevance to the community, and how
much more basic than taking care of health needs,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The free event offers screenings for blood sugar, cholesterol,
blood pressure and glaucoma, plus a healthy soul food lunch. There
also will be foot care clinics, stress management advice and
referrals to community support groups that can help people manage
their diabetes. A limited number of participants will receive free
groceries and neck massages.
</P>
<P>
   The primary symptoms of diabetes include frequent urination and
excessive thirst and hunger. The rate of diabetes runs nearly 40
percent higher among blacks than whites, affecting more than one in
10 black adults. Complications of diabetes include blindness, heart
disease and stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sooner diabetes is detected, the sooner people can begin
to make lifestyle changes that will help them live healthier and
happier lives with diabetes,'' said Joy Burgess, director of health
promotion programs at the Center for Healthy Communities.
</P>
<P>
   The center, Good Samaritan Hospital and the local chapter of the
American Diabetes Association will provide the health care
personnel at Thursday's screening.
</P>
<P>
   Jim DeBrosse writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
