<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 10:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2671 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEYTALK11-COX     11-10 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    _Saving grace: Ideas on setting aside money
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week came the puzzling news that Americans' ``personal
savings rate'' was a negative figure in September. We spent more
than we earned, measured by disposable income.
</P>
<P>
   The underlying methodology is a little quirky, and a one-month
statistic like this itself isn't very important. What is important
is the clear warning the numbers brought: Too many of us still
haven't gotten serious about saving and investing.
</P>
<P>
   We don't know how to motivate ourselves to get started. We don't
know how much we need to save. And we don't know how to find the
money to save.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves two core questions: How much should I save, and
where do I get it?
</P>
<P>
   The first may be the toughest one. In truth, there is no one
answer for everybody and no easy answer for any one of us. You have
to work it out for yourself, starting with a basic inquiry into
your goals, what they will cost, and how many years you have to
save and invest.
</P>
<P>
   The rule of thumb is this: Save 10 percent of your income for
your future needs. Personal finance guru Jane Bryant Quinn suggests
that you think of it as tithing. ``Most people can save up to 10
percent of their incomes and hardly notice,'' she writes. ``I can't
tell you why it works, only that it does.''
</P>
<P>
   But clearly that is more a technique than a plan. It moves you
along the way but won't tell you how close you're getting to your
goals.
</P>
<P>
   You can begin a more rigorous plan at the kitchen table, with a
pencil and note pad. List every goal you can think of, starting
with next year's vacation and working your way through college
costs to the really big one _ retirement. Next to each goal, record
an estimated cost and the number of months you have to save. Divide
each cost by the number of months and you have a savings goal for
each item.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously that works better for near-term, easily defined
expenses. but it's easier to evaluate the cost of your next new car
than the cost of retirement. For that, you will need some outside
help. Here are some resources:
</P>
<P>
   Quinn's book, ``Making the Most of Your Money,'' is packed with
sound advice.
</P>
<P>
   For a quick estimate of your retirement needs, check out the
worksheet at http://www
</P>
<P>
   .asec.org/toolshm.htm. You can order a written version of the
same thing, and other useful information, by calling the U.S.
Securities and Exchange Commission at 1-800-732-0330.
</P>
<P>
   Other useful worksheets are available at
http://www.accessatlanta.com/business
</P>
<P>
   /money&AMP;more/worksheets.html.
</P>
<P>
   The most important point is to start saving now, because that
will give you more time for your money to grow. The buzzword for
that growing process is ``the magic of compounding.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some other techniques for finding the money to save,
and making yourself do it:
</P>
<P>
   _ Examine your spending and cut back on non-essentials. You
might rent a movie rather than go to the theater, for example, or
eat at restaurants less often.
</P>
<P>
   Think of saving as a necessity rather than an option. When you
pay the water bill and the phone bill, pay yourself, too. Think of
it as your retirement bill.
</P>
<P>
   It may help if you actually write a check and mail it to the
bank, just like any other bill. Another alternative is to set up an
automatic transfer from your checking account to a savings account
each month. Or you can set up a payroll deduction, putting money
directly into a savings account before you even touch it.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you're putting away small amounts each week or month, drop
them into a bank account _ savings or money market _ that you won't
touch. You can move on to a long-term investment, such as a stock
mutual fund, when you have accumulated the minimum required to open
an account.
</P>
<P>
   If your company offers a 401(k) retirement plan, use it. You get
an income tax break. Even more important is the fact that most
employers will match at least part of your contribution. That's
free money.
</P>
<P>
   _ Take advantage of any other available tax breaks, such as the
ones that come from contributing to an individual retirement
account. The table shows the astonishing difference that
tax-deferred savings makes over the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   _ Save for specific goals.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
