<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 10:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2674 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KELLY-Q-AND-A11-COX     11-10 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELLY-Q-AND-A11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For R. Kelly, challenges are welcome
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Amazing what time away and a well-chosen
extracurricular project can do for you. Before the anthemic ``I
Believe I Can Fly'' from the ``Space Jam'' soundtrack earned him
three Grammys, R. Kelly was the million-selling, often
sexual-minded R&AMP;B singer sometimes condescendingly called ``the
Bump 'n' Grind Guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Kelly's doing TV commercials. ``Titanic'' pop singer Celine
Dion has included their duet of his ballad ``I'm Your Angel'' on
her new Christmas album. And after a three-year hiatus, his third
solo album, ``R.,'' ships today triple-platinum (3 million copies).
</P>
<P>
   Notably diplomatic, Kelly, 30, skillfully dodges any opportunity
to slam the world of N'Synclike pop confections he now must compete
with for chart position. ``I respect entertainment however it
comes,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to differentiate between working with Dion and
collaborating with hip-hop's Jay-Z and Noreaga on another ``R.''
single, ``We Ride,'' Kelly says, ``It's all the same because it's
all art. It's all music. And everybody is blessed with a talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Hmmm. Maybe Kelly becoming a born-again Christian has changed
him. It's quite the contrast _ a year ago he was crooning ``I'm
(expletive)- ing you tonight'' with the late rapper Notorious
B.I.G., and today he can be heard on Kirk Franklin's latest No. 1
contemporary Christian album, singing, ``I'm your brother, lean on
me.''
</P>
<P>
   In a lengthy phone conversation from his Chicago home, Kelly
explains:
</P>
<P>
   Q: So R., or is it Rob? What do you prefer people call you?
</P>
<P>
   A: Just call me, baby.
</P>
<P>
   Q: OK, Robert, how do you jibe your much-publicized newfound
religion with some of your more provocative songs?
</P>
<P>
   A: I wouldn't say it's changed how I do music. Life itself, and
traveling the world, has a way of grooming you. When I found Christ
I became more focused on my life and my music is a part of my life.
. . . It affects things like `How much do I party?' `Who do I go to
McDonald's with?' It gets me in bed earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is (the album's first single) ``Half on a Baby'' an
expression you'd heard before or just something you made up?
</P>
<P>
   A: That's just something I made up. Just being silly.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I would guess that's what also made you yodel on one song?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yeah, I just do whatever comes to mind. I love to go into a
territory that no man has ever gone musically. I love taking that
rocketship.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The last time you hit the stage here was New Year's Eve at
the Tabernacle. Some people were upset you didn't perform.
</P>
<P>
   A: That was just a New Year's party. My whole (plan) was to come
to Atlanta, rent a place and have a party. If they expected a
performance . . . hey, I would have been mad, too. But that's what
happens when you become successful. People use your name, your
voice for all kinds of things.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In a lot of your recent interviews, you seem to be hesitant
about your success. Why?
</P>
<P>
   A: Because it's not only about being successful but also
maintaining success. . . . When you do something like ``I Believe I
Can Fly,'' and you don't expect something big to happen, you have
to question it. And wonder whether you can top it. But I welcome a
challenge. I've decided to work extra hard. And when you stay
hungry, you stay fed.
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
