<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PIE-THROWING (San Francisco) _ The pie-throwing escapades that
targeted two of San Francisco's elected officials prompted
condemnation by several San Francisco supervisors. By RACHEL
GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SELECTIVE-MUTISM (Albany, N.Y.) _ Sandra Williams has a bright
and talented 10-year-old daughter. The only problem is she won't
talk in school _ not to teachers or friends. ``The common reaction
is `What's wrong with that kid?''' said Williams. The answer is a
rare and little understood behavioral disorder known as selective
mutism. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   SPRING-FASHION (New York) _ During the fall season, Ralph
Lauren's winter whites didn't even make it to the selling floor.
All those luxurious seven-ply hooded sweaters and elegant creamy
cargo pants were pre-sold. So it's a sure thing that the women who
bought them will absolutely love the paper-white pieces in Ralph's
new spring collection. By CYNTHIA ROBINS.
</P>
<P>
   ROOT-CELLARS (Albany, N.Y.) _ While refrigerators are good for
day-to-day and even week-to-week storage, they can't accommodate
vast quantities of produce in bulk. If you are having a storage
problem, consider the natural refrigeration of a cellar. By FRANCES
INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   WARDROBE-STORAGE (Albany, N.Y.) _ The season has changed and
with it our wardrobes. We put a great deal of money into clothing
and therefore must go to great lengths to take care of it,
especially vintage clothing or that one-of-a-kind piece, such as a
wedding gown. That is why safe and proper storage is essential. By
FRANCES INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MONEY-COLUMN (Undated) _ Despite the recent topsy-turvey nature
of the markets, the wise investor will stick with stocks for the
long haul. By PAMELA YIP.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAIMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SPRINGSTEEN-ALBUM (Undated) _ In Bruce Springsteen's new four-CD
box set of studio gems, ``Tracks,'' he more than lives up to his
own exacting standards. The set contains 66 songs, spanning
Springsteen's 25 year career is an intoxicating collection,
populated with living, breathing human beings. By CRAIG MARINE.
</P>
<P>
   AUTHOR-SUCCESS (Houston) _ Anita Bunkley stopped putting off her
dream to be an author. Her experiences and those of other
successful women who often took risks to achieve their goals are
the basis of Bunkley's latest book, ``Steppin' Out With Attitude:
Sister, Sell Your Dream!'' with photo. By BARBARA KARKABI.
</P>
<P>
   CAMERON-FILM-PROFILE (Houston) _ When ``Titanic'' director James
Cameron went to Houston last week, it was as an actor. Cameron did
his acting as part of TheatreVision, a new process that enables
blind persons to hear audio descriptions of films via wireless
earpieces as they're shown in theaters. By BRUCE WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   TYNER-MUSIC-REVIEW (Houston) _ It's an old story, in art as well
as in politics: The fiery young radical matures into a proud keeper
of the traditional flame. That would certainly seem to be the case
with jazz pianist McCoy Tyner. There's no question that Tyner has
mellowed since his percussive, keyboard-pummeling days with John
Coltrane's mind-expanding quartet of the early '60s. By RICK
MITCHELL.
</P>
