NYT-11-10-98 1122EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981110.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 11:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2731 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VETS-COX-1STLEDE     11-10 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VETS-COX-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Veterans Day not as solemn an observance as in years past(Eds:
fixes dateline.)
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It's dusk, and a chilly wind is blowing as a patrol
of 19 stone-faced infantrymen trudge grimly up a grassy knoll,
headed for an ominous stand of trees.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody says a word, except National Park Service ranger Michael
Balis. He tells a group of tourists that the 5 million men these
stainless-steel statues on The Mall in Washington represent _ the
men who fought in the Korean War _ are now old, or dead. They are
falling much faster than they did in the war, when 36,916 Americans
were killed in three years of combat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Korean veterans are now in their late 60s, 70s or 80s,''
says Balis. ``Unfortunately, we're seeing fewer and fewer, even
since this Korean War Veterans Memorial was dedicated three years
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Which begins to explain why Veterans Day doesn't seem to be such
a big deal anymore. With America's last major war now 23 years past
_ and its biggest, most noble one 53 years past _ war veterans
aren't in the limelight as they once were. World War II may be a
hot movie topic, with last summer's hit ``Saving Private Ryan'' and
the upcoming, star-studded ``Thin Red Line,'' but remembering the
real vets, at least on their official day, seems a waning
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Thaddeus Sobieski, an Atlanta lawyer, was wounded as a
lieutenant on a chilly day in 1952, leading a company of
infantrymen on patrol. Now he heads the Atlanta chapter of Korean
War Veterans, and will take part with 40 others from the metro area
in Wednesday's Veterans Day parade in midtown Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're disappearing,'' he said. ``A lot of the guys I was with
have gone on to their rewards.''
</P>
<P>
   Younger generations, he maintains, have a different view of war
and veterans, and that explains Veterans Day's lack of interest.
``The young people don't get it about ths country,'' he said.
``When I was a kid, it was Armistice Day, and we always had a
speaker from World War I.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Celente, publisher of the Trends Research Institute in
Rhinebeck, N.Y., agrees that Veterans Day is important mostly to
people whose numbers are quickly declining _ those who fought in
WWII and Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Veterans Day means so little any more,'' he said. ``Memorial
Day is a holiday, and starts off summer. On Veterans Day . . . most
people work _ and don't remember.''
</P>
<P>
   The Korean memorial, at least, was erected in time for most of
the veterans of that war to see. That may not be the case for their
older brothers and sisters who fought in World War II. Robert John
Slaughter, 73, a World War II combat veteran from Roanoke, Va.,
visited the Korean memorial recently. ``They have their memorial,''
he said of Korean War veterans, ``and we're still waiting for
ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Slaughter worries that the year 2000 groundbreaking for the $100
million National World War II Memorial will come too late. ``There
won't be many of us left, and that's a shame,'' he says with a hint
of ire.
</P>
<P>
   World War II veterans are dying at a rate of 34,000 a month.
It's estimated only 7 million of 16 million men and women who
served in the war will be alive in two years, and 5 million by the
time their memorial opens on Veterans Day in 2002, assuming all the
money is raised in time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are losing in one year as many as the 406,000 who died in
World War II,'' says Mike Conley, spokesman for group raising money
for the WWII memorial.
</P>
<P>
   Korean War veterans don't have an advocacy group tracking their
death rates, but being about five years behind the WWII vets, the
actuarial math isn't too hard to figure. Give or take, Wednesday
will be the last Veterans Day for maybe a half-million of the World
War II-Korean War generation of veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans Day was originally called ``Armistice Day'' for the day
World War I ended on Nov. 11, 1918. For years, speeches and large,
military-style parades highlighted the day in cities and towns
around the country. Those practices continued in the years
following World War II, when the holiday was renamed to honor
veterans of all American wars.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, however, Veterans Day has become less of a major public
event. From 1971 to 1977, at the height of the nation's angst over
Vietnam, it was relegated to a floating Monday holiday, to give
government workers a three-day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans succeeded in restoring the holiday's original timing.
Still, complains civil rights leader Hosea Williams of Atlanta, who
was severely wounded in Germany in 1945, Veterans Day has become
one of the least-observed American holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 73, will mark it with some of his 17 grandchildren at
Atlanta's Veterans Day parade, he said. ``I want them to know this
is an important day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Used to be Veterans Day was celebrated, respected, but it's
not anymore,'' Williams said. ``The average person in the streets
of America no longer shows any admiration for the suffering, the
dying, that went on to make this country what it is today.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I think of the way we died and struggled, many of my
friends, and the lack of respect, and that a generation of heroes
is disappearing so fast, it makes me sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Slaughter says there was a ceremony recently in Bedford, Va., at
a reunion of the 29th Infantry Division, the first to hit the
Normandy beaches on D-Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bells toll for every man who has died in the past year,''
he says. ``It seems like the bell was tolling for half an hour this
year. Our job is to educate the public so this memorial will get
built in Washington, and to make the public remember the
sacrifices.''
</P>
<P>
   Slaughter is philosophical about the fact that the Vietnam
Veterans Memorial, near the Korean memorial and not far from the
planned location for the World War II Memorial, is still the most
visited in the capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a different kind of war,'' Slaughter said. ``It's
freshest in everyone's minds.''
</P>
<P>
   But while hundreds of mementos are left each day at The Wall,
only a few flags and wreaths are lain at the Korean memorial (which
also has a wall, not inscribed with names but with 2,000 haunting
images of ordinary GIs, real photographs sandblasted into the stone
and staring forever out of polished black granite).
</P>
<P>
   Because of demographics _ the aging and deaths of World War II
and Korean War veterans _ Veterans Day will attract the most people
to the Vietnam memorial, says National Park Service ranger Loren
Goering.
</P>
<P>
   ``People still come at all hours, in the middle of the night,''
he said. ``Many leave personal items. And every evening, we pick it
all up to save it.''
</P>
<P>
   Articles are often poignant _ old photographs, floppy jungle
caps, medals, birthday cards, letters, dogtags, newspaper articles.
On a recent night, several soft-bellied, gray-haired men wept as
they looked at a faded photo of two GIs that had been taken in
Vietnam. Another choked up as his young son touched the name of a
pal who'd died 29 years before.
</P>
<P>
   Still, 23 years after the fall of Saigon, even that ritual is
beginning to fall off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vietnam veterans are getting older too,'' Goering said. ``It's
getting to be less and less of them coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hendrick writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
