the end these are merely words, and the nation will stand together.
 &HT;     (Eliot A. Cohen is professor of strategic studies at the Paul
H. Nitze School of Advanced International Studies at The Johns
Hopkins University.) 
 &HT;    (slugged: BC-ISRAEL-TODAY-PROFILE-NYTSF)
 &HT;    
 THE IMF DID NOT PLAY RUSSIAN ROULETTE  
 By David D. Hale  
 &HT;    (1,400 words) Critics charge that the IMF's loans to Russia were
imprudent and wasteful. But the IMF failed to stem the Russian
collapse not because its reform package was flawed but because
Russia's domestic woes _ combined with its sensitivity to the
global slump in oil and commodity prices _ were too severe to
prevent market panic. Had the $22 billion IMF package for Russia
been as large as its $40 billion bailout of Mexico in 1995, it
might have helped.
 &HT;     (David D. Hale is the global chief economist for the Zurich
Group and a consultant to the U.S. Defense Department.) 
 &HT;    (slugged: BC-IMF-RUSSIA-MESS-NYTSF)
 &HT;    
 GEORGE BUSH PUBLISHES MEMOIRS of HISTORIC ERA  
 By Michael Howard  
 &HT;    (1,300 words) No one is under oath when writing their memoirs,
but the joint account by former President George Bush and his
national security adviser, Brent Scowcroft, has better credentials
than most. By the summer of 1989, events in Europe were moving so
fast that ``the vision thing'' became largely irrelevant. All the
United States could do, in Bush's words, was encourage, guide and
manage change. This required seat-of-the-pants planning, not a
vision of a new world order.
 &HT;     (Michael Howard is Emeritus Professor of History at Oxford and
Yale Universities.) 
 &HT;    (slugged: BC-BUSH-MEMOIRS-COLD-WAR-NYTSF)
 &HT;    
 NATIONS HATE TO SAY `SORRY'  
 By Nicholas D. Kristof  
 &HT;    (1,500 words) Japanese people are famously polite, apologizing
at the start and end of every conversation and many times in
between _ which makes the reluctance to apologize for the war even
more remarkable. If the Japanese regularly apologize for being a
nuisance, even when they are not, why will they not show regret for
the slaughter of millions?
 &HT;     (Nicholas D. Kristof is Tokyo Bureau Chief for The New York
Times and co-author of ``China Wakes: The Struggle for the Soul of
a Rising Power.'')
 &HT;    (slugged: BC-APOLOGIZE-JAPAN-KOREA-U.S.-NYTSF)
 &HT;    
 EUROBASHING IS COUNTERPRODUCTIVE  
 By William Wallace and Jan Zielonka  
 c.1998 Foreign Affairs Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (1,450 words) The United States was built by immigrants who
shook off the disappointments of the old world for the hope of the
new. Businessmen and politicians in late-19th-century America
believed they represented the vigorous future, Europe the enfeebled
past. By now, this attitude should be history, but it's not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (William Wallace is a reader in international relations at the
London School of Economics and the Liberal Democrat spokesman on
defense in the British House of Lords. Jan Zielonka is professor of
political science at the European University Institute in Florence
and author of ``Explaining Euro-Paralysis.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (slugged: BC-EUROBASHING-STOP-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE INTELLIGENCE ROLE IN PREVENTING CATASTROPHIC TERRORISM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Ashton Carter, John Deutch and Philip Zelikow &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   (1,500 words) Terrorism is not a new phenomenon. But today's
terrorists, be they international cults like Aum Shinrikyo or
individual nihilists like the Unabomber, act on a greater variety
of motives than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Ashton Carter is Ford Foundation Professor of Science and
International Affairs at Harvard University's John F. Kennedy
School of Government and a former assistant secretary of defense. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (John Deutch is Institute Professor of Chemistry at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology and a former director of
Central Intelligence and deputy secretary of defense. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Philip Zelikow, a former member of the National Security
Council staff, is White Burkett Miller Professor of History and
director of the Miller Center of Public Affairs at the University
of Virginia.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (slugged: BC-TERRORISM-CATASTROPHIC-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE TESTING of AMERICAN FOREIGN POLICY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; Part I: RULES of the ROAD FOR AMERICAN FOREIGN POLICY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To most Americans, the success or failure of U.S. foreign policy
no longer seems a matter of life and death. We invest fewer
resources in defense, diplomacy and development. But the demands
upon us have not lessened. The patterns of world affairs shift with
each spin of the globe. Rising dangers replace receding ones; old
problems reemerge. (slugged: BC-GOALS-ALBRIGHT-ONE-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Part II: SANCTIONS ARE JUST ONE TOOL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Neither China nor Burma is democratic, and both take a dim view
of dissent. Yet we are engaged in a strategic dialogue with China
while maintaining far tougher sanctions, including an investment
ban, against Burma. Some accuse us of having a double standard. But
that's not true. (slugged: BC-SANCTIONS-ALBRIGHT-TWO-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Part III: FIVE MAJOR TESTS OF AMERICAN LEADERSHIP &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nations must unite in the struggle against terror. The U.N.
Security Council must deal firmly with Saddam Hussein's game of
threats and defiance. We must be resolute in our dealings with
North Korea. We must stand firmly behind implementation of the
Dayton Accords. The global community must redouble its efforts to
prevent the spread of weapons of mass destruction. (slugged:
BC-TERROR-NUKES-ALBRIGHT-THREE-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Part IV: FREEDOM IS AMERICA'S PURPOSE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We are the No. 1 debtor to the United Nations and the
multilateral development banks. We have been cutting foreign-policy
positions, closing diplomatic posts and shutting U.S. Agency for
International Development and U.S. Information Agency missions. We
lack the funds to provide full security for Americans overseas. Yet
we want our foreign policy to reflect our status as the globe's
leading champion of freedom. (slugged:
BC-MONEY-NEEDED-ALBRIGHT-FOUR-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   .................................................
</P>
<P>
   __ The following op-ed and full-length articles are also
available from the September/October '98 issue of Foreign Affairs:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TODAY'S KOSOVO CRISIS IS HARDLY A SURPRISE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Warren Bass &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Documents relating to diplomacy in Bosnia _ including Richard
Holbrooke's memoir ``To End a War'' and the State Department's 1996
official study of the process leading to the Dayton Accords of
November 1995 _ show that American officials were painfully aware
of the shortcomings of U.S. policy. Dayton's lessons are grimly
appropriate when considering the current violence in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   (slugged: BC-KOSOVO-BOSNIA-DAYTON-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TACKLING INTERNATIONAL CORRUPTION &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By John Brademas and Fritz Heimann &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   (1,300 words) After years of being tolerated with a mixture of
apathy, cynicism and denial, corruption is becoming a target of
serious international action. Today corruption is harder to hide,
as the wave of bribery scandals involving high-level officials in
Europe, Asia and South America demonstrates. (slugged:
BC-BRIBERY-CORRUPT-GLOBAL-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHAT IF WOMEN RAN THE WORLD? &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Francis Fukuyama &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   (1,400 words) Male tendencies to band together for competitive
purposes, seek to dominate status hierarchies, and act out
aggressive fantasies toward one another can be rechanneled but
never eliminated. The world scene will always be populated by
states led by the occasional Mobutu, Milosevic or Saddam. Even if
the democratic, feminized, postindustrial world has evolved into a
zone of peace where struggles are more economic than military, it
will still have to deal with those parts of the world run by young,
ambitious, unconstrained men.
</P>
<P>
   (slugged: BC-WOMEN-RUN-THE-WORLD-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE GREAT TECHNOLOGY GIVEAWAY? &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Michael Hirsh &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Today, quietly, without most Americans noticing, a revolution
has turned the U.S. defense industry upside down. The idea that
every time you sell a satellite overseas, you make a profit but
lose a little bit of your military edge _ harks back to a time when
CIA bean counters worried over every uptick in Soviet technology,
and when the U.S. defense industry was sequestered in top-secret
grandeur, spending untold billions on weapons designed exclusively
for the Pentagon, with older-generation models going to America's
Cold War allies.
</P>
<P>
   (slugged: BC-SATELLITE-COMMERCIAL-MILITARY-NYTSF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ...............................
</P>
