<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 12:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2819 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-ILLUSTRATOR-AZR &LR;      11-10 1440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-ILLUSTRATOR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTIST ILLUSTRATING MOST INTIMIDATING CLASSIC OF THEM ALL: THE
BIBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One afternoon more than a decade ago, illustrator and
book-artist Barry Moser paid a visit to Eudora Welty at her family
home in Jackson, Miss. Moser had never met the writer, so he took
along a mutual friend to make introductions, and a bottle of
something special to ease the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miss Welty,'' he said when they had been ushered into the
front parlor, ``I understand that you like bourbon whiskey.''
</P>
<P>
   Welty was frail with age, but she rubbed her hands together and
said, ``Oh, indeed I do!''
</P>
<P>
   They drank and talked for a while, their rich, Southern voices
stirring the air. Welty had spent her entire life in Mississippi,
and Moser had grown up in Tennessee, so there was common ground to
cover. Finally, the purpose of his visit came up: He proposed to do
woodcut engravings for a new edition of one of Welty's books.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' she said. ``Of all the things I've done, what are you
most interested in?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Robber Bridegroom,'' Moser told her, and she clapped her
hands and said, ``Oh, I'm so glad you said that!''
</P>
<P>
   ``So we agreed that's what we'd do,'' Moser says today from his
home in Massachusetts. ``And then I said, `Miss Welty, how much
input do you want on this? Do you want to see galleys, do you want
to see my sketches or what?' And she said, `Why no, Barry, I don't
want to see a thing. It's your book now.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most remarkable thing. Lesser writers want to tell
me what the images should be, what type to use, how big to make my
margins. But this was Eudora Welty, and she was turning her book
entirely over to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Welty was easy with him because she was already a fan of his
work. Moser, 58, has acquired many well-known admirers over the
course of his career, mostly because of the daring, intricate
engravings he has created for some of the most wonderful books in
all of literature. Even a partial list is exhilarating: He has
illustrated editions of ``Moby-Dick,'' ``The Scarlet Letter,''
Lewis Carroll's Alice books, ``Frankenstein,'' ``The Odyssey,''
``The Red Badge of Courage,'' ``Adventures of Huckleberry Finn,''
``The Call of the Wild'' and Norman Maclean's ``A River Runs
Through It.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of these were designed and published by Moser in limited
editions through his own Pennyroyal Press. Handmade books, they
sold for more than $1,000 each, and ended up in museums and special
collections across the country. Most also were published in
moderately priced trade editions that are available today through
mainstream book stores (Moser's ``Moby-Dick'' is even in
paperback).
</P>
<P>
   Now, after four years of work, Moser is about to finish the
biggest project of his life _ a new edition of the most
intimidating classic of them all, the Bible. The Pennyroyal Caxton
Bible will appear next year with about 235 engravings, meticulous
production details and a heady price tag. A main edition of 400
copies will sell for $10,000 apiece. Moser will not talk about the
price of a ``special'' edition of 50 copies printed on handmade
paper for serious collectors. He hopes to see the Bible
mass-produced at a reasonable price for general consumers.
</P>
<P>
   It will be the first illustrated by a single artist since 1865.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a nice letter from John Updike once,'' Moser says. ``He
wrote, `I'm glad to see that nothing daunts you.' But I think I'm
just not smart enough to be daunted. I know if I think about it,
I'll get real nervous. I had to accept this thing _ and this is
hard for me to say _ as simply another project. I know it's more
than that. Without even getting into the theological implications,
the Bible is the most important influence on the English language
as we know it. But I designed it, got a good printer and a good
typographer, and treated it as just another book.''
</P>
<P>
   Which does not, by any standard, indicate neglect. In addition
to the physical characteristics of his books _ the art of the book,
about which Moser speaks with something approaching rapture _ he is
known for the idiosyncrasies that mark many of his projects. Among
them:
</P>
<P>
   _He puts his own face into each of his books, ``either directly
or metaphorically,'' he says. ``I've done two editions of `The
Odyssey,' and in the first one I was Odysseus. It can be that
straightforward, or it can be something as small as the face on a
brooch on a woman's bodice.''
</P>
<P>
   _He cribs from the real world. His Jesus Christ is based on the
face of a New York City waiter. But the most flamboyant example is
``The Wonderful Wizard of Oz,'' in which Moser serves up a rogues'
gallery from the presidency of Ronald Reagan. Nancy Reagan is the
Wicked Witch, her husband is the Wizard, Caspar Weinberger guards
the gates of Emerald City, and Alexander Haig is a soldier of Oz.
Moser did this because of his distaste for Nancy Reagan's public
persona, and besides, he says, ``I thought it would be fun.'' He
enjoyed it so much that he went on to use Lee Iacocca as the
disembodied head of Oz, and Lillian Carter as the Witch of the
North.
</P>
<P>
   _Moser persuaded Maclean to let him illustrate ``A River Runs
Through It'' by proposing to space his engravings _ a repeating
order of three small images followed by one larger one _ so that
they mimicked a line from the book about the cadence of fly
fishing: ``It is an art that is performed on a four-count rhythm
between 10 and 2 o'clock.'' Maclean, who was known to be a
curmudgeon, was less than welcoming at first, but, Moser says, ``he
was so impressed that I knew that line, and when he understood that
I wanted to achieve that same four-count beat, he said `OK, you can
do it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   _Moser will deny that he has a favorite among his books, but he
dwells with obvious emotion on one of his least successful
projects, Mary Shelley's ``Frankenstein, or the Modern
Prometheus.'' He does not admire the illustrations as much as the
book itself _ ``the images and the type,'' he says, ``work together
as well as anything I've ever done.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more, he is drawn to the story. Moser was brought up in a
Tennessee family that he describes as ``rabidly racist,'' and when
he first read ``Frankenstein'' he found a moral message in its
pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a profound sympathy for the monster,'' he says.
``Whether his story is a metaphor of power or a metaphor of racism,
he is persecuted because he is different, because of his size and
looks. With my background, I found real meaning in that.''
</P>
<P>
   He works in a rarefied atmosphere, surrounded by the smell of
ink and the cachet of thousand-dollar books, but Moser's life is
anchored in reality. A phone conversation with him is carried on
against an odd background _ opera music at first, and then what
sounds like the bleating of goats. He lives in a farmhouse and has
creatures to feed, which is why he has taken on more projects than
he can count, many of them children's books for which he makes
watercolors. He has been chided, on occasion, for being too
prolific.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a mortgage and I've got dogs and I've got daughters
and I've got granddaughters and God Almighty there's a birthday
every month, it seems like,'' he says. ``I've got to make a living.
There are very few things that have been presented to me that I
felt I simply couldn't do. I would not agree to do a text that was,
in my sense of the universe, immoral. I wouldn't do `Mein Kampf' .
. . or something that was racist.''
</P>
<P>
   Has he ever regretted taking on a project?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, several times,'' he says. ``Inevitably the ones I've had
that feeling about are the ones that make money. Those that are
least appealing to me are the ones that the public . . . finds most
interesting. What that says, I do not want to know.''
</P>
<P>
   He is sure of this: Barry Moser has been a lucky man. He almost
abandoned woodcuts a while back because of a worldwide shortage of
boxwood, the best material for engraving blocks. The invention of a
resin that produces similar results saved the day. Even more
remarkable was his fortune in finding a patron for his Bible. Bruce
Kovner, a New York investor and collector of books, has put up the
money for the project.
</P>
<P>
   The irony of it is not lost on Moser.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been keeping a journal while I worked on the Bible,'' he
says, ``and I constantly come back to asking this question: Is it
possible? Is it possible that a reprobate like myself, a miscreant,
could possibly live in a state of grace? And the answer, it seems,
is yes. It's possible. Because I do.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-10-98 1218EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
