<HEADER>
A2824 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-MOODY-AZR &LR;      11-10 0440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MOODY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN LOOPY WAY, `MOODY' SOLVES THE MYSTERY  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
MOODY FOREVER 
by Steve Oliver (St. Martin's Press, $22.95) 
 
 By CHARLES KELLY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you've had your fill of iron-jawed private eyes who solve
most problems by whacking somebody in the chops, perhaps
angst-ridden investigator Scott Moody will be more to your liking.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, ex-mental patient Moody (who first appeared in Oliver's
mystery, ``Moody Gets the Blus''), earns a living driving a cab in
a suburb of Spokane, Wash., and working as a reporter for a small
paper.
</P>
<P>
   As if those careers weren't enough in themselves to make him
depressed, he's suffering from an obsession with death and regret
over his broken marriage and not spending as much time as he'd like
with his little daughter, Allison.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he does have a rich girlfriend, Xanthia, and his life is
going about as well as could be expected until he happens to be the
cabby who ferries Xanthia's father home from the airport one rainy
night, only to see the father stabbed to death.
</P>
<P>
   Moody is a suspect in the murder, although the case against him
seems weak. Then, Xanthia finds out her father had been worth $70
million. She didn't know her father had had that much loot and
wonders where the money came from. She hires Moody to backtrack on
her father to find out.
</P>
<P>
   Moody isn't exactly a clever gumshoe. He just wanders around,
follows up strikingly unpromising leads, pulls surveillance on
suspects when he can't think of anything else to do and is lucky
enough to run into people who can help him figure out what he wants
to know.
</P>
<P>
   He also periodically buys guns through Ira Sugarman, a dowdy
private eye who helps him out. Sometimes, Moody arms himself as
protection against possible violence. Sometimes, he does so with an
eye toward exacting revenge on those who have wronged him. In
either case, given Moody's unstable mental status, this desire to
stock up on armament is a bit unsettling if you take the story
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Moody's hit-and-miss searching leads him to an
institution known as the Longevity Institute near Palm Springs,
Calif., and the solution of the mystery about Xanthia's father.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time, ``Moody Forever'' is a pleasantly loopy
mystery, although things work out in ways that are far too pat.
This probably won't trouble readers who see the story as a romp.
Those readers will no doubt react favorably to Moody's amiability.
Others may find him too passive. At any rate, ``Moody Forever''
offers an interesting excursion into the offbeat. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-10-98 1219EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981110.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 12:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2826 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR &LR;      11-10 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FALL OF THE PHANTOM LORD &QL; 
 &UR; Andrew Todhunter (Anchor, $23.95)
</P>
<P>
   The man on the cover is rock climber Dan Osman, and he is
hanging by his fingertips over a whole lot of nothing. What's more,
he's happy about it. Osman is known for leaping from a 700-foot
bridge in Northern California, to be stopped 660 feet below by a
slender rope attached to his body harness. Is he frightened when he
does this? He is terrified, but that's the point. Climbers of
Osman's caliber are smitten by their own panic. They face it,
examine it, push through it and in the end return to prove
themselves again and again. In that sense, this is an introspective
and sometimes disturbing book, especially for those of us who
prefer to keep our feet on the ground and cannot understand the
urge to do otherwise. But Todhunter's elegant, understated style is
very effective in profiling this unique breed of people. Elite
climbers, as he portrays them, are incredibly skilled but not
necessarily heroic. Osman is a father and is sometimes conflicted
about risking his life again and again. He even admits that he
admires people who are not driven to put themselves at risk, ``who
are secure enough in themselves to be able to say, `You're not
getting me out there. I'm fine right here.' '' This book, which
began as an article for ``Atlantic Monthly,'' is a look at a way of
life that is built around the pursuit of fear. You don't have to
join Osman on the bridge to be fascinated. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; RUSTIC STYLE &QL; 
 &UR; Ralph Kylloe (Abrams, $39.95)
</P>
<P>
   Let's call this one ``Decorating With Twigs.'' We've received a
rash of similar books lately, the most noteworthy being Ann
Stillman O'Leary's ``Adirondack Style'' or, as we like to call it,
``Decorating with Bark and Moose Heads.'' These volumes feature a
veritable orgy of forest-related interior design ideas, including
the strategic placement of deceased animals, canoes suspended from
the ceiling, fishing tackle and snowshoes displayed Matisse-like on
walls, and complex chairs made out of branches and antlers. The
latter look so vastly uncomfortable _ the word ``impale'' comes to
mind _ that we wondered for a while if this might be a parody. No
such luck. It's for real, even the preserved-animal umbrella stand,
the banister of burled lodgepole pine (imagine a goiter epidemic),
the cowboy boots utilized as display objects. And more moose heads
than we care to count. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; MY YEAR OFF &QL; 
 &UR; Robert McCrum (Norton, $23.95)
</P>
<P>
   McCrum was 42 and editor-in-chief at the British publishing firm
of Faber &AMP; Faber when he woke up one morning and could not get out
of bed. His wife was away, and McCrum was forced to roll onto the
floor and drag himself commando-style across the bedroom and down
the stairs to a phone on the living room floor, where he summoned
help. The process took hours, and McCrum's description of it and of
the odd thoughts that ran through his head make vivid an experience
that is only abstract to most of us: McCrum had suffered a stroke.
``I had crossed by night from what Susan Sontag calls `the kingdom
of the well' to `the kingdom of the sick,' '' he writes, ``and,
though I still had no name for this new country I was in, it was
dawning on me that I was no longer the person I'd been 24 hours
ago.'' Through diary entries, literary ruminations, droll
observations and plain-spoken medical passages, he traces his
illness and his convalescence, acknowledging periods of despair,
frustration and self-pity. What saved him, he says, was the
extraordinary help of his wife and family. ``In my more melancholy
moments,'' he writes, ``I felt that the lesson in love I was
getting perhaps justified the appalling physical cost.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; DINING OUT &QL; 
 &UR; Andrew Dornenburg and Karen Page (Wiley, $29.95)
</P>
<P>
   That's ``New York Times'' restaurant critic Ruth Reichl on the
cover. As you can see, she is incognito. But look closely. Is she
enjoying that coq au vin? Is she leaning forward in pleasure or in
disgust? Is she gearing up for the kill or the coronation? There
are all kinds of power in the world, but one of the most curious is
that of the restaurant critic, who can make or break an
establishment with a single review. Dornenburg and Page have
interviewed critics, chefs and restaurateurs across the country to
get a feel for what most people view as one of the most enviable
jobs in the world. The book reads, at times, like an oral history,
with quote after quote served up without much in between. That's
laziness on the part of the authors and makes for some babbling on
the part of the interviewees. But the subject matter is
irresistible. How do critics conceal their identities when they're
on the job? What are their pet peeves? How much weight does a
critic give to food, ambience, service? What do the best critics
think of each other? What are their backgrounds? And our favorite:
What are the weirdest things they have ever eaten? A partial list:
ant eggs, alligator, fried grasshoppers, unborn calf ravioli,
stingray burritos, snake bile wine and roast duckling brains.
Dinner, anyone? &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Correspondent Anne Stephenson can be reached at
amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
