<DOCNO> NYT19981110.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 12:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2845 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOURNAL-HAITI-1111-CO     11-10 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-HAITI-1111-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JOURNAL: HAITI'S GRIDLOCK INSPIRES BOTH FRUSTRATION, ADMIRATION
 &HT;    EDs: Contains optional trims.
 &HT;    With photos, including a mug of Emling, available in the
International folder on the Cox Server.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti _ I thought that nothing could sap energy
or test patience like being the mother of two very small children.
</P>
<P>
   Then I came here.
</P>
<P>
   This squalid city, less than two hours from Miami by plane, is
the gridlock capital of the Western Hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent five-day trip, I saw potholes so deep that, as one
driver put it, ``you have to turn the headlights on to make your
way out.''
</P>
<P>
   Even worse, the narrow streets of crumbling concrete are choked
with rusting cars and trucks that barely move from dawn until dusk.
</P>
<P>
   Here, there are no traffic laws. No traffic signs. No traffic
lights. Well, none that function. There aren't even central
dividers or lines down the middle of the streets.
</P>
<P>
   In general, chaos is king, with most drivers acting like they're
the only ones on the road.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is simple: a population explosion, especially in
urban areas, has resulted in too many cars traveling on roads never
intended to handle such heavy traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, the number of vehicles here has skyrocketed from
about 35,000 to nearly 120,000.
</P>
<P>
   Haiti's population is now 8 million, surpassing projections made
in 1980 for the year 2003.
</P>
<P>
   If current trends continue, the population will be almost 10
million by the year 2010 and 20 million by 2040, according to the
United Nations. The number of people living in Port-au-Prince will
be nearly 4 million by the year 2010, more than twice the number
today.
</P>
<P>
   As such, it appears traffic will only get worse before it gets
better.
</P>
<P>
   It's gotten so bad that some Haitians voice a longing for the
days of the embargo between 1991 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the United Nations imposed a cut-off of trade designed to
force out a repressive regime.
</P>
<P>
   But the scarcity and expense of fuel smuggled in and sold for up
to $12 a gallon sure decreased traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The scene in this crowded city is made to seem even more jumbled
by the plethora of vendors sitting on the ground alongside major
thoroughfares with their merchandise spread out before them.
</P>
<P>
   With an unemployment rate of more than 60 percent, people are
eager to hawk whatever they've got.
</P>
<P>
   They run alongside cars, tapping on windows, trying to persuade
those inside to make a purchase.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the streets here are more like obstacle courses,
with drivers maneuvering their way around these salespeople, as
well as small animals, cavernous potholes, and broken-down trucks
and buses.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim follows.)
</P>
<P>
   There's also a strange mix of traffic outside the capital, with
the United Nations' beige peacekeeping vehicles zipping by farmers
pulling mules toting sugar cane.
</P>
<P>
   There is some talk about finding a solution to the traffic
problem -- one suggestion has been to build a train that would
circle the city -- but little can be resolved without a working
government.
</P>
<P>
   Haiti has been without a prime minister since June 1997, when
Prime Minister Rosny Smarth resigned following an election dispute.
</P>
<P>
   But, certainly, traffic is just the tip of a titanic iceberg
when it comes to irritations.
</P>
<P>
   The infrastructure that Americans take for granted -- safe
water, garbage disposal, and reliable electricity -- is a luxury in
Haiti, the hemisphere's poorest country.
</P>
<P>
   Many residents live in mud huts and are forced to haul water in
buckets on their heads for miles.
</P>
<P>
   Their children clutch ragged clothes around them that appear to
be at least four sizes too big.
</P>
<P>
   Even their pigs are skinny.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim ends here.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet never before have I encountered a people so unfailingly
optimistic in the face of mind-numbing adversity.
</P>
<P>
   Despite enduring years of vicious dictators and devastating
natural disasters -- the latest being Hurricane Georges -- most
Haitians are kind, proud, pleasant, and willing to share all that
they have with a stranger.
</P>
<P>
   When there's no garbage pickup -- and there rarely is --
business owners simply sweep trash into piles along the street,
where it is burned.
</P>
<P>
   Even in rural areas, appearances are so important that peasants
sweep their yards until the packed soil is smooth as a paved
parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, too, pride and resilience abound.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Haitians cheerfully balance two or three riders on
a bicycle when they don't own cars.
</P>
<P>
   At the airport, visitors are greeted on the tarmac by a lively,
smiling four-man troubadour band.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Most notable, though, are the beat-up trucks known here as
``tap-taps'' that are painted with colors so bright they're almost
blinding.
</P>
<P>
   Above the windshields are slogans such as ``Merci Jesus'' and
``Assurance en Christ'' or various other exuberant expressions of
thankfulness.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the drivers who are truly awe-inspiring. Even in
hours-long traffic jams they rarely display even a hint of anger or
impatience.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim ends here.)
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, Haitians have learned to maintain their composure even
when dealing with conditions that would surely send any American
over the edge in a few days' time.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers say that Haiti's proud history drives the
population, pointing to the fact that, in 1804, the slaves brought
in to work the sugar plantations revolted and established the first
free black republic.
</P>
<P>
   Others say that the Haitian people's indomitable spirit is
grounded on a foundation of strong religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   I only know that this country inspires both admiration and
frustration better than any other place I've known.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here lose their children to preventable diseases every
day, yet somehow they keep up their spirits,'' said one American
who lives here. ``Then, you have people in the United States, where
everyone has so much, who get depressed over a hangnail.''
</P>
<P>
   Try explaining that to small children. Talk about a lesson in
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
