<HEADER>
A2863 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPRINGSTEEN-ALBUM-HNS     11-10 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINGSTEEN-ALBUM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINGSTEEN SPINS AN INTOXICATING, LIVELY ALBUM IN `TRACKS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CRAIG MARINE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe the only way to judge Bruce Springsteen's new four-CD box
set of studio gems is to see if it stands up to his own sense of
what constitutes a good song.
</P>
<P>
   In Springsteen's new package, ``Tracks,'' he more than lives up
to his own exacting standards. The set contains 66 songs, spanning
Springsteen's 25 year career _ from the first recording he ever did
at Columbia, ``Mary Queen of Arkansas,'' on May 3, 1972, to ``Give
It a Name,'' a beautiful song he wrote in August. It is an
intoxicating collection, populated with living, breathing human
beings.
</P>
<P>
   The set includes 56 previously unreleased master recordings,
largely from Springsteen's ``The River'' and ``Born in the U.S.A.''
period, with 10 other masters that were featured as B-sides of
singles, some released only in Europe. Many of the songs will be
familiar to Springsteen devotees from live performances. Others
just seem to come out of nowhere, and their discovery is worth
sifting through the more than four hours of music.
</P>
<P>
   Springsteen's gift has always been his ability to stay grounded
in the real world _ a conscious decision made following his rapid
rise to fame with ``Born to Run.'' He saw the path others had
chosen before him _ Elvis, Dylan _ and figured he wasn't going to
isolate himself or implode.
</P>
<P>
   He brings a sensitivity to writing about issues that affect the
working class, without being patronizing or preachy. His admitted
admiration for Chuck Berry makes him strive to find the perfect
detail that brings a song to life, the way Berry could conjure up
``coffee-colored Cadillac'' to draw a listener into a song.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to name every good effort on the 66-song package would be
impossible; better to focus on a few. Take for instance, the
original track of ``Born in the U.S.A.'' Recorded during the
``Nebraska'' sessions _ which consisted mainly of Bruce, an
acoustic guitar and a tape recorder _ this version is stripped so
bare of the musical embellishments of the album version that there
is no way in the world a Republican politician would mistakenly use
this as a campaign slogan. Presented in its original form, the
pain, anger and frustration of a nation's self-betrayal is stark
and brutal. Sometimes less is more.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Born in the U.S.A.'' is not the strongest anti-war song in
the set. That honor goes to ``Shut Out the Light,'' an agonizing
tale of a hero's return to his small town home and the difficulty
he faces, knowing things will never be the same for him after what
he has seen and done. It's like ``A Farewell to Arms'' in less than
four minutes _ and you can hum it.
</P>
<P>
   But fear not _ this is not four hours worth of major bummer. The
cars and the characters and the adventures are all in evidence.
It's amazing that some of these tracks never made the earlier cut.
</P>
<P>
   The songs are not presented strictly chronologically, so there's
no real need to listen to them sequentially. It's fun to just put
on the CDs and listen at random, waiting to strike gold and knowing
you will.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the best song on the set is ``Cynthia,'' an infectious
little pop tune from 1983 that may be the most perfect recorded
expression of how a beautiful woman can change the lives of those
around her, for no other reason than that she exists.
</P>
<P>
   It's a nonthreatening, nonsexist admiration that celebrates the
simple joys that can be found every day. Ultimately, this is what a
listener gathers from Springsteen, and that is a tremendous gift.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-10-98 1249EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
