<DOCNO> NYT19981110.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 12:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2866 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROOT-CELLARS-HNS &LR;      11-10 0451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROOT-CELLARS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK TO BASICS: ROOT CELLARS ARE IDEAL FOR FOOD STORAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Although refrigerators are good for day-to-day
and even week-to-week storage, they can't accommodate vast
quantities of produce in bulk.
</P>
<P>
   If you are having a storage problem, you just might look at the
natural refrigeration of a cellar. A root cellar is used for
storage of many fresh, raw, whole vegetables and fruits for several
months after their normal harvest in a cold, moist atmosphere. Most
fruits and vegetables require storage in about 35 to 40 Fahrenheit
and a relative humidity level of between 65 and 95 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a newer home, you might want to partition off a
section on the north or east corner of the basement, one with no
heating ducts or oil or water pipes, to create a root cellar, or
else dig one next to an existing cellar wall.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, a root cellar was dug into the earth for food
storage. It was a common practice in America between the 17th and
19th centuries to locate the root cellar right under the house.
This was convenient: Early kitchens were often located in the
basement level and this permitted easy access to the produce
without having to go outside through the snow to fetch items that
were put up for the winter.
</P>
<P>
   But some root cellars were dug into a hillside several feet from
houses.
</P>
<P>
   The natural insulating properties of earth would keep food
products at the right temperature without freezing during winter
and keep them cool during the warm months. Root cellars also
provided proper ventilation, which helps control humidity and ward
off odors.
</P>
<P>
   Root cellars, like pantries and storerooms, keep light to a
minimum, unlike today's kitchen cabinets and refrigerators, where
food is constantly being exposed to light, which accelerates the
ripening process.
</P>
<P>
   Root cellars were created in various sizes, depending on the
amount of food to be stored. Some are just closet-like in shape,
with shelving on the upper part and a larger space on the bottom
for bushels of produce; others are the size of a room, with shelves
for canned goods and squash, and beams for hanging onions.There
also may be a work table in the center for gathering produce. Large
open spaces also would accommodate slated bushels and bins for
items such as potatoes and apples. Other crops, including carrots,
beets and celery, were often stored under the dirt floor.
</P>
<P>
   In a root cellar, celery can last between two to three months,
onions from five to eight months, carrots from three to five months
and potatoes from five to eight months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-10-98 1250EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981110.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 12:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2867 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASIA-QUOTES-$ADV15-CO     11-10 0364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIA-QUOTES-$ADV15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE FACES OF THE ASIAN ECONOMIC CRISIS
 &HT;    With ASIA-SUMMIT-$ADV15; Photos placed in the International
folder on the Cox Server.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Nov. 15 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    EDs. NOTE: These quotes, each accompanied by headshots, can
either be run in a quotebox, or can be dropped in as individual
illustrations to match the stories.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Japan's Machiko Sekido, 46, a divorced mother and manager of a
Tokyo art gallery: ``In the bubble era,' people bought whomever was
the popular artist. They would pay a billion Yen and not think
about it. But compared to then, the number who buy is declining.
People don't need art.''
</P>
<P>
   South Korea's Lee Du-Ho, 27, a caretaker in Seoul's Sosomun
Park, where 150-200 homeless have been living in tents: ``It's very
hard to see these people outside living so badly. I'm trying to
tighten my own belt because my salary has been cut, but this makes
me realize I have to save money so I won't ever live like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Malaysia's Liza Dhatta, 24, an office-worker in Kuala Lumpur who
has taken a 10-percent pay cut and been downgraded to a less
interesting job: ``This recession is interfering with people's
ability to get married. It costs too much money to have a family.''
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's Ahmad, 15, a ninth-grade student in the Tangerang
region, who says he's afraid his parents may be forced to pull him
out of school to save $1 a month in school fees:
</P>
<P>
   ``My father lost his job driving a pedicycle taxi. My mother
tries to make up by selling traditional medicines, but it's hard.
The last time we had meat was nine months ago, at the time of a
Muslim festival.''
</P>
<P>
   China's Li Yong, 25, a recent college graduate looking for a job
in Beijing: ``Our economy is a little more chaotic than we are
accustomed to. The rate of unemployment has risen. For me, it means
that the authorities did not assign me to a work unit after my
graduation. Even so, I'm sure there will be a position, if I try
hard enough.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
