<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 12:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2873 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-ASIA-$ADV15-C     11-10 1810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ASIA-$ADV15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ANALYSIS: APEC SUMMIT, ASIA TRIP HIGHLIGHT CLINTON'S ROLE AS
'CRISIS MANAGER'
 &HT;    With ASIA-SUMMIT-$ADV15.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Nov. 15 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When the world dials 911 these days, it's
increasingly the president of the United States who answers the
call.
</P>
<P>
   In an extraordinary year of global crisis management, President
Clinton has helped broker agreements aimed at ending bloodshed in
Northern Ireland, Kosovo and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   He's struggled, with mixed results, to counter efforts to build
weapons of mass destruction in Iraq and Iran, worked to hold
together a scheme that keeps in check North Korea's atomic
ambitions, and urged India and Pakistan to step back from their own
unnerving game of nuclear saber-rattling.
</P>
<P>
   Just this month he dispatched emergency aid to the victims of
flooding in Central America.
</P>
<P>
   And on Sunday he arrives in the Malaysian capital of Kuala
Lumpur, where, meeting with his counterparts in the 21-nation Asia
Pacific Economic Cooperation forum, or APEC, he'll try to help
guide the region out of its economic malaise before the financial
contagion afflicting East Asia and Russia cripples growth and
undermines wealth at home.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, whether it's a measure of the man and the limits of his
office, a testament to the times or simply the complexities of the
issues he's bound to address, not even the president of the United
States can claim to have brought peace to troubled lands, stability
to roiling markets or comfort to a world still menaced by powerful
weapons in dangerous hands.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, even as the White House has become the global crisis
center, the more intractable challenges of the late 20th Century
have become as much a reminder of the boundaries of American power
as of its possibilities. For Americans, and the growing number of
others who depend on them, the sobering truth is that not all of
these problems can be solved: some must simply be managed.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the nature of things in the world today,'' Clinton
said in a press conference last month. ''Not everything we have to
do is easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout most of what historians have labeled ''The American
Century,'' the White House has confronted its share, and often
more, of the world's problems.
</P>
<P>
   In the decade since the Cold War ended, though, the pace of the
global challenges set before American presidents has quickened,
even as the variety of those tasks has grown.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons have to do with technology, global integration and
the epic realignment of power and influence resulting from the
collapse of the Soviet empire.
</P>
<P>
   The first two trends have broadened the scope and lowered the
threshold of what constitutes a global crisis, even as the third
has made world problems breaking out virtually anywhere a uniquely
American concern.
</P>
<P>
   With other countries routinely looking to the last remaining
superpower before committing their own resources to address a
problem, the United States is often pivotal, if not, as U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright likes to say,
''indispensable.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, the ability of the United States, or any one nation, to
fully resolve complex global crises is being diminished.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't long ago, for example, that the United States and half
a dozen other industrialized democratic countries could control
most of what mattered in the world economy.
</P>
<P>
   That's no longer true.
</P>
<P>
   Improvements in air travel, computers and telecommunications
have helped make possible the emergence of a truly global economy,
while the collapse of the Soviet empire, and the failings of world
communism more broadly, have led dozens of formerly
centrally-controlled states to harness their workers and enterprise
to the border-less marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   There are now perhaps 60 countries, that are important
participants in world investment and commerce.
</P>
<P>
   That's presented enormous opportunities to the United States,
which will do some $2 trillion worth of two-way trade in goods and
services this year.
</P>
<P>
   Economic problems in far away lands, however, can have
unprecedented impact on jobs and wealth in this country, presenting
the White House with new headaches in uncertain times.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's more complicated in the sense that a lot more countries
are really important,'' said Fred Bergsten, director of the
Institute of International Economics, a Washington think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, instead of convening a meeting of the Group of Seven
finance ministers to fine-tune world growth, ''You have to worry
about what happens to a Thailand or an Indonesia,'' Bergsten said.
</P>
<P>
   Not every participant in the global economy, moreover, plays by
the same rules.
</P>
<P>
   Rampant corruption rotted the foundations of Indonesia's growth,
while organized crime has undermined Russia. Cozy links between
money and politics meant easy credit for a generation of
well-connected Japanese companies until the bubble of instability
that system created popped a decade ago, plunging Japan into
recession. Malaysia is retreating from the global economy, imposing
currency and investment restrictions meant to limit its exposure to
the risks of unbridled markets.
</P>
<P>
   All of that makes it difficult for the United States to repair
the damage done to each country's economy, or mitigate the threats
posed to Americans, by policies and practices Washington opposes
but has a finite ability to change.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the rise of free-market economics has put the
management of much of the world economy, by design, outside of the
domain of public policymakers and increasingly in the hands of
investment bankers, currency traders and even shareholders of
global corporate empires.
</P>
<P>
   ''The non-state actors, the private interests, play a larger
role,'' said Paul Papayoanou, assistant professor of political
science at the University of California at San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're not really controlling the economy, they're acting on
market forces,'' he said. ''But a lot of their actions affect the
international economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Hand-in-glove with those developments has been the emergence of
a truly global community linked by television, telephone and
computer communications.
</P>
<P>
   That's expanded the realm of crisis. In the global media
village, it's harder than ever to turn a blind eye to the suffering
of others, whether the cause of the trauma is genocide in Rwanda,
political violence in Yugoslavia or the death and devastation
caused by floods in Central America.
</P>
<P>
   That's particularly true for Americans, who, in winning the Cold
War, picked up global responsibilities not yet fully grasped.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim follows.)
</P>
<P>
   No sooner did the Soviet Union break up at the end of 1991, for
example, than its collapse triggered the eruption of ethnic and
civil conflicts, such as those that tore apart the former
Yugoslavia, once a Soviet satellite.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago the United States led a massive NATO
peacekeeping force into the former Yugoslav province of Bosnia to
stop Europe's worst bloodshed since World War II. The United States
has yet to knit back together the social and legal order, however,
that permitted Serbs and non-Serbs to coexist and cooperate as they
did under the old Soviet-backed system.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, White House officials admit that U.S. troops could
remain in Bosnia for years to prevent the outbreak of renewed
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   During the Cold War, Soviet and American responsibilities were
understood as clearly as their respective areas of control; there
was seldom any question over whether it was Moscow's job or
Washington's to take care of a given crisis, or to simply let it
drift.
</P>
<P>
   ''That tended to calm things, to make them easier to understand
and manage,'' said Ed Haley, professor of international relations
at Claremont-McKenna College, in Claremont, Calif. ''What's changed
is now Russia isn't a player at all.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Russia may have lost its ability to help deal with global
problems, but it has retained some capacity for preventing
solutions, or at least muddying the chances for their success.
</P>
<P>
   For months, in 1995, the United States and its NATO allies put
off decisive, and ultimately necessary, military action against
Serb atrocities in Bosnia, out of deference to Russia's historical
ties to the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Russian sentiment had had similar effects in the Yugoslav
province of Kosovo, where Serb troops have waged a year-long
campaign of terror against the ethnic Albanian majority; and in
Iraq, which has spent much of the year in violation of its 1991
pledge to grant United Nations inspectors access to alleged
nuclear, biological and chemical weapons sites.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who pulled back from the brink of threatened strikes
against Iraq in the face of Russian objections last winter, is once
again weighing such attacks. And, once again, his strategic
calculus must include the sort of Russian opposition that can make
it hard for the United States to use the tools of its own choosing
to act on clear-cut policy aims.
</P>
<P>
   ''It means the United States has to engage in threats and side
payments,'' said Papayoanou. ''There's sort of a bargaining process
that goes on with countries like Russia and China to get them to
follow a line of some other policy.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim ends here.)
</P>
<P>
   As crisis management increasingly involves other nations or
entire regions, or resources beyond the means of the United States
alone, it has become the president's job to try to muster global
support, through the use of multilateral institutions such as the
United Nations, the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), the
International Monetary Fund or the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   While the United States has the dominant voice in each of those
institutions, it must often compromise its aims or its methods to
build needed support among other member-nations.
</P>
<P>
   For a country that still defines success as total victory -- on
budget and on time -- the process of negotiating global consensus
can seem endlessly, painfully ponderous.
</P>
<P>
   ''We, rightly I think, constantly try to avoid unilateral
action, constantly try to build a group,'' said Haley. ''It's both
hard-headed and decent. It just gets horrifying sometimes before
the good can be done.''
</P>
<P>
   In an increasingly integrated world of growing complexity and
evolving risks, the White House finds itself managing crisis upon
crisis in hopes of reducing trauma and tragedy, even when it cannot
do away with them altogether.
</P>
<P>
   That's not all the world hopes for when it dials 911, but there
are times when that's as good as it gets.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
