<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2879 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARDROBE-STORAGE-HNS &LR;      11-10 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARDROBE-STORAGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEP YOUR CLOTHING SAFE, HAPPY DURING THE WINTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The season has changed and with it our wardrobes.
</P>
<P>
   Today's active lifestyles dictate that we have clothes for every
function for work and play. We put a great deal of money into
clothing and therefore must go to great lengths to take care of it,
especially vintage clothing or that one-of-a-kind piece, such as a
wedding gown.
</P>
<P>
   Wardrobes call for safe and proper storage.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Barber, president of Closet Crafters in Albany, said the
most important thing to keep in mind when storing clothes is to
eliminate what you won't put on anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should you take up and waste valuable space with clothes
you never wear?'' Barber said. ``Then you should think about what
you are going to store and where. Many times, people will store
files in their bedroom closet, as well as winter coats. You have to
make the proper room to store clothing properly and functionally.''
</P>
<P>
   Barber said that the layout of the closet will also depend on
whether it's to be male- or female-oriented.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too often, the actual architectural constraints of the
structure are an afterthought,'' Barber added. ``You should work
with the architecture rather than against it.''
</P>
<P>
   A moderate-sized closet can be transformed into a functional
closet without actually increasing its size by using various
storage systems, from portable organizers to built-ins.
</P>
<P>
   Barber noted that laminated storage systems take up more space,
and therefore ventilated steel units should be used for small
closets of 48 inches or less.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ventilated steel is also the least expensive of the three
storage options of laminated, ventilated steel or ventilated wood,
which is beautiful and warm-looking,'' Barber said. ``Ventilated
systems are not adjustable, like the laminated systems. But then
again, how many times do people adjust the shelves in their closets
once they are installed?''
</P>
<P>
   Within these modular systems, there are all kinds of storage
options, such as tie and scarf racks; drawers with dividers to keep
small items, such as socks, organized; acrylic shelf dividers to
keep folded clothes from toppling over; and laundry hamper, jewelry
drawers and various level hanging compartments to accommodate
dresses, trousers, and skirts and coats.
</P>
<P>
   There are also several different options when it comes to
storing shoes, each depending on the amount of space you have.
Shelves and racks are popular, where shoes are stored side-by-side,
but it's the shoe cubbies that save on space.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a 3-to-1 ratio in space savings, when it comes to
using shoe cubbies,'' Barber said. ``In a shoe cubbie, you store
your shoes toe-to-heel, like in a shoe box, except that unlike a
box, your shoes are all visible.''
</P>
<P>
   Another consideration is the closet door. Do you want a bifold
door or a swinging or sliding pocket door? Should the door swing in
or out? Also remember that a solid swinging door offers an
opportunity to use it for extra hanging space for ties, belts,
jewelry or hats.
</P>
<P>
   A well-organized closet can range in cost from as little as $150
to more than $6,000, depending on the size, materials, bells and
whistles.
</P>
<P>
   Some other helpful hints:
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep the closet clean and use sealable bags and storage boxes
to deter moths. Use cedar scent for proper protection and make sure
the container or plastic bag is airtight, with no rips or holes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Always dry clean or wash any item to be stored to rid it of
mildew spores or insect eggs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't leave clothing in plastic dry cleaner bags for long-term
storage because they can discolor garments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
