<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HYDE STILL DOESN'T GET IT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (k and w coding.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- The big guy from Woodale, Ill., could really use
some help. Anybody with a way out of the impeachment quagmire
should give him a buzz at 1-800-HYDE.
</P>
<P>
   Post-election and post-Gingrich, the chairman of the House
Judiciary Committee has more freedom but also more responsibility.
So far, though, Henry Hyde is acting more like he's trying to duck
and temporize. Talk about not getting it.
</P>
<P>
   It's said there was an election recently, in which strong
signals about priorities were supposedly sent here. So what do the
ostriches in the nation's capital plan to focus on for the next two
months? House Republican squabble politics and impeachment. They
are, without a doubt, related.
</P>
<P>
   Post-election, for starters, there are five fewer Republicans,
and most incoming freshman Republicans got elected by running away
from impeachment and expect their lame-duck colleagues to dump this
evidentiary and political mess by Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Post-Gingrich, Hyde no longer has a rabid GOP leadership on his
back, and the distractions of the succession struggle only increase
his running room. The trouble is that Hyde's name keeps popping up
in this struggle _ both as a possible draftee for a leadership job
and as a broker. So far, however, all Hyde has done with his
running room is run in place.
</P>
<P>
   Holding action No. 1 was his dispatch of 81 foolish yes-or-no
questions to the White House. He may eventually get some replies,
but even Hyde knows the silly demand for monosyllables will not and
should not be met.
</P>
<P>
   Holding action No. 2 was the scheduling for Nov. 19 of testimony
from his only planned ``fact'' witness _ the controversial
prosecutor who developed the case under suspicious circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it is true, as some winking Republicans suggest, that Hyde
is setting Ken Starr up for a fall or a swan song. But for those
trying to take this seriously, the idea that an impeachment case
can be made solely on the testimony of its leading advocate based
on uncross-examined testimony from conflicting witnesses is absurd.
</P>
<P>
   Underneath all this is a simple fact, partisan in nature because
it is partisan in reality: The Republicans don't have the votes in
the House to impeach on this case, but they can't stop themselves
yet; and some leading Republicans confide that they may not have
the votes in the super-partisan Judiciary Committee, either. In
military strategy patois, the GOP has no exit strategy.
</P>
<P>
   And the inclination at the very top of the White House for the
moment is not to provide them with something they are unwilling to
provide for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the president has a more than convenient hook for
holding back, the repeated statements of big-shot Republicans
before and even after the election that formal censure or any other
extra-constitutional maneuver is not an option. The idea is simply
to take them up on it.
</P>
<P>
   The leading proponent of this GOP line on the inside has been
Majority Whip Tom Delay of Texas. On the outside, it has been
former Vice President Dan Quayle. This position had its origins
back in the silly days when the conventional wisdom among press and
pols alike was that impeachment was ``inevitable,'' that any deals
or plea bargains should come at the virtually certain ``trial''
stage in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But the truth is that nothing was ever inevitable, not before
the election and certainly not now.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the election, there was nothing approaching a
two-thirds majority in the Senate for tossing Clinton out of
office. With the substitution of such GOP freshmen as Jim Bunning,
Peter Fitzgerald, and George Voinovich for experienced
Clinton-bashers Al D'Amato, Lauch Faircloth, and Dan Coates, that
fact of life is only underlined. Already, GOP veterans like Senate
Judiciary Committee chairman Orrin Hatch are saying more or less
publicly that the facts of evidentiary and political life in the
Senate ought to affect the facts of life in the House.
</P>
<P>
   But the absurdity instead grinds on. Hyde has himself rejected
stopping the madness, which threatens to become his madness, by
saying the issue of a punishment deal is above his pay grade. Not
anymore. Hyde has also said he does not want to bring impeachment
articles to the House floor that cannot attract bipartisan support.
The truth is they can't without major new evidence.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, when the votes on the inquiry were taken to
position members for the election Gingrich thought the GOP would
win, the highwater mark was 226 Republicans and 10 Democrats (five
of whom were against any inquiry) opposing the Democrats' limited
resolution, which Hyde has now in effect accepted post-election.
</P>
<P>
   But actual impeachment based on the Lewinsky case wouldn't come
close to attracting that number. Some true believers on the right
want to take the vote anyway, but no sane Republican leader would
expose members who may be vulnerable two years hence to a vote that
would have no purpose beyond spite.
</P>
<P>
   In this chaotic conundrum, there is little the White House can
do to help beyond not gloating about the election and staying
low-key on impeachment process issues _ in short, waiting for
sanity to emerge. It may take a while. Meantime, nobody named
Clinton is going to ``get away'' with anything. The ``public
rebuke'' of which Democratic Senator Joe Lieberman of Connecticut
spoke in August still waits in the wings.
</P>
<P>
   It would help, though, if the bitter, battling Republicans could
show at least a tad more negotiating maturity in this new
environment than Paula Jones has.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
