<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEET'S STRATEGY ON FUNDS PAYS OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sales practices at BankBoston Corp.'s mutual fund operation
are being investigated by the Massachusetts Securities Division.
The bank has yet to name a replacement for the unit's chief, who
left in August. The director of sales quit last month.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, literally a stone's throw away, Robert L. Ash, who
heads Fleet Financial Group Inc.'s growing mutual fund business,
says Fidelity and Putnam and Merrill Lynch are the competition, not
BankBoston. Still, the contrast is stark these days.
</P>
<P>
   While BankBoston dawdles, Fleet is putting up big numbers. In
the first nine months of this year, sales of Fleet's Galaxy Funds
family were up 120 percent over a year earlier to $649 million, or
more than for all of 1997. Monthly retail sales of Galaxy funds to
retail customers are averaging $72 million compared with $32
million a year ago. Fleet opened 70,000 new Galaxy accounts in the
first nine months of the year compared with 30,000 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the irony: BankBoston is being investigated for allegedly
goosing fees by moving customers out of its no-load funds and into
Fidelity and Putnam funds that charge higher fees, while Fleet has
built its success on just the opposite strategy. Fleet has waived
the load, or sales charge, on its Galaxy funds for retirement
accounts, thus encouraging customers to switch into them.
</P>
<P>
   The move has cost Fleet substantial fee income in the short
term, but has created a remarkable turnaround for the Galaxy funds.
Before waiving the loads, 90 percent of all of the new mutual fund
dollars brought in by Fleet went into third-party load funds like
Fidelity and Putnam. Now 85 percent of that money is going into
Galaxy funds.
</P>
<P>
   The pricing strategy has been the key, though the investment
performance hasn't hurt. Of Fleet's 29 Galaxy funds, most rank in
the top quartile or half of their peers over the last one to three
years, according to Lipper Analytical Services, which tracks fund
performance. The largest Fleet fund, the all-purpose Galaxy Asset
Allocation, ranks 50th of 191 such funds over the last year and
38th of 143 funds over three years.
</P>
<P>
   The architect of the Fleet strategy is Bob Ash, who had to
convince his bosses, Fleet chairman Terry Murray and vice chairman
Gunnar Overstrom, to forgo the short-term fees for the promise of
getting the long-term assets under management. Those inside Fleet
say this was no easy sell. The reason: Waiving the fees has cost
Fleet about $4 million this year alone.
</P>
<P>
   But Ash came with strong credentials _ built outside the bank
and outside of banking. He had been chief executive of AIG Asset
Management Services, where he worked for one of the toughest
executives in financial services, AIG chief executive Maurice
Greenberg. He had also headed mutual fund sales for Kemper
Financial Services. He was a man who had retired early because of
prostate cancer, but who was all too glad to have Murray talk him
back into a job 14 months ago after he had recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Ash's bet is essentially that Fleet will be better off waiving
the 3.75 percent load if it can get, and retain, the assets and
annual management fees. Ash argues that retirement money, unlike
taxable accounts, is not going to be chasing the latest hot fund.
In addition, bank customers themselves are more likely to remain
with Fleet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Retirement money stays put,'' Ash says.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Bathon, president of Financial Research Corp. in Boston,
says Fleet has prospered because it brought in people like Ash and
his deputy, Linda Goodwin, with solid mutual fund experience
outside the banking world and let them do their jobs. Bathon offers
high praise for Fleet: ``They can actually be compared to other
mutual fund groups,'' not other bank funds.
</P>
<P>
   Of BankBoston, he says: ``Their retail efforts are not in the
same league.''
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, the mutual fund business is just a tiny piece of
what either of these banks do. BankBoston has put most of its
energy into building its widely admired Latin America franchise and
the recent acquisition of investment banking heavyweight Robertson
Stephens.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston acknowledges that Fleet is ahead in the mutual fund
business. Fleet has about $16 billion in mutual fund assets,
BankBoston has $9.5 billion. BankBoston saw 15 percent sales growth
in the last year; Fleet is growing at 100 percent-plus. BankBoston
has 50 brokers in branches; Fleet has 275 and plans to move that to
1,100 in two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This business is at the top of our list we intend to grow,''
says Kathleen McGillycuddy, BankBoston's head of global treasury
who oversees the business. She says the bank hopes to fill both
vacancies at the top soon.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Guillette, a consultant with Cerulli Associates in
Boston, says both Fleet and BankBoston still have the same problem
plaguing most banks in their mutual fund operations: too much money
in low-fee money market accounts and too little in equity funds,
which have higher fees.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty percent of all the Fleet money was in money market
accounts at the end of September and just 33 percent was in
equities, the bank says. BankBoston was even worse: 69 percent was
in money markets and just 18 percent in equities. By comparison,
Fidelity has just 19 percent of retail assets in money markets,
Cerulli says.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, says Cerulli, Fleet has just $6 billion in equity and
bond assets, but that is good enough to rank number nine among all
banks. BankBoston has just $2.8 billion. (Reality check: A nice
midsize Fidelity fund like Dividend Growth has $7 billion in assets
alone.)
</P>
<P>
   As the state Securities Division pushes its inquiry of
BankBoston, it is reportedly looking into a change in the
compensation system in 1997 that may have encouraged its sales
people to push third-party funds over the bank's own 1784 Funds.
Ash, the Fleet executive, says he isn't worried about his own sales
reps.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no incentive for them to do what was happening at
BankBoston,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston, on the other hand, says it can't comment. There is a
pending inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another sign of a revived stock market: deals to buy money
management shops seem to be making a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Affiliated Managers Group of Boston struck its second deal in
three weeks Monday, agreeing to buy a majority interest in Rorer
Asset Management of Philadelphia for about $65 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Rorer manages $3.7 billion for institutions and wealthy
individuals. Affiliated will purchase 65 percent of the firm and
Rorer managers will keep the rest. It will join 12 other Affiliated
investment firms that manage a combined $53 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Affiliated agreed last month to buy a controlling interest in
Davis Hamilton Jackson &AMP; Associates of Houston, manager of about $3
billion, for an undisclosed amount of cash.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
