<HEADER>
A2929 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-VICTIMS-BOS &LR;      11-10 1409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-VICTIMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILIES FIND FULL DISCLOSURE DOESN'T HEAL ALL WOUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BEN BRADLEE JR.  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; GUGULETU, South Africa _ In the wrenching healing process from
the legacy of apartheid, the case of the so-called Guguletu 7
accomplishes as much as can be hoped for in this country.
</P>
<P>
   On March 3, 1986, seven young men were shot to death by police
in this black township outside of Cape Town. The case got
international attention and soon took its place alongside the
Sharpeville massacre, the murder of Steven Biko, and other
upheavals as another ugly milestone of the apartheid era.
</P>
<P>
   Two inquests in 1986 and 1989 absolved the police of any
wrongdoing and concluded that the killings were part of a
legitimate ``anti-terrorist operation.'' But two-years ago, the
Truth and Reconciliation Commission _ charged by President Nelson
Mandela to uncover what really happened under apartheid _ developed
new evidence that the Guguletu 7 had actually been lured to their
deaths and ambushed in an operation ordered by security forces in
Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
   The commission has touted the case as a centerpiece of its
efforts to learn how killings actually took place, to bring closure
to families of the victims, and where possible, to achieve a
measure of reconciliation between the families and those who
committed the crimes.
</P>
<P>
   But there are many kinds of victims in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with limited time and resources, the commission knew from
the start that it could not hope to solve, or even investigate, all
the murders of the apartheid years. So it concentrated on a limited
number of cases _ some high profile, others less so _ that told
larger stories.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, many of the 22,000 people whom the commission
decided were victims of gross rights violations, and thus eligible
for limited reparations, never learned what happened to their loved
ones. Others missed the deadlines imposed by the commission to
apply for victim status, thereby losing the opportunity for
compensation and closure.
</P>
<P>
   Still others, most notably the Biko family, learned a lot about
what happened to their relatives when the killers confessed while
applying for amnesty. But they found the notion of setting admitted
killers free intolerable, and they demanded that the perpetrators
be denied amnesty and prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like the other mothers, Eunice Miye remembers exactly how she
learned that her son, Jabulane, had been killed 12 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was watching TV that night and they said `seven guerrillas
from Russia were killed in Guguletu,''' Miye said in an interview
here. ``When the pictures came on, I saw my son lying dead. I saw
he had on the same clothes he had on that morning.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Truth Commission started to investigate, an important
early lead involved the tracing of a license plate on a police van
used at the Guguletu shootings to Vlakplaas, the notorious security
forces base outside of Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
   But the key discovery, found inside a cabinet at police
headquarters in Cape Town, was a video taken by police during and
after the killings. It showed close-ups of the bullet-riddled
bodies, and a dramatic scene where one of those killed, Christopher
Piet, was attached to a rope and dragged away.
</P>
<P>
   Then a black policeman from Vlakplaas, Sergeant Thapelo Mbelo,
confessed his pivotal role in the operation to investigators: He
had posed as an African National Congress commander sent to train
the seven men to fight in the resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Mbelo and others prepared them for their first operation:
a plot to ambush a bus that ferried police through Guguletu. But of
course Mbelo and others had told police of the plan, and when the
seven men were dropped off, about 25 officers were laying in wait
and opened fire on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a slaughter,'' said Zenzile Khoisan, the Truth
Commission investigator who led the probe of the case.
</P>
<P>
   The video was played at a hearing on the Guguletu 7 case at
which relatives of the victims testified. ``They asked us if we
wanted to see it and we said yes,'' said Irene Mxinwa, whose son
Simon was killed in Guguletu. ``But we didn't know how bad it
was.''
</P>
<P>
   When Cynthia Ngewu, Piet's mother, saw a close-up shot of her
son, she threw her shoe at one of the 23 officers who have been
implicated in the case.
</P>
<P>
   After she and Mxinwa composed themslves, they agreed to meet
with Mbelo. ``He asked forgiveness,'' said Mxinwa. ``He said he did
all these things, but he couldn't help it, and we must forgive him.
We did forgive. We hugged him.''
</P>
<P>
   But Miye refused to meet Mbelo. ``I can't forgive him,'' she
said. ``It's a wound you can never cover.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Helping to deal with families whose cases were either not
investigated as thoroughly as the Guguletu 7's or not investigated
at all, is Khulumani, a Johannesburg-based victim-support group.
Officials there say the commission promised more than it could
deliver.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm the director of a company and I can't finish the job,
I've got to hire people and work overtime,'' said Maggie Friedman,
an American whose South African lover, David Webster, was shot and
killed by security forces in 1989. ``Expectations were raised too
high from the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Khulumani official, Duma Khumalo, has been trying,
unsuccessfully, to obtain help from the commission for people like
Elizabeth Mkhwanz, of Evaton, a township south of Johannesburg. She
said her son Steven was beaten, tortured, and finally shot to death
by police in 1992. In an interview, Mkhwanz said she stopped
reading the newspapers or watching television after her son was
killed, and hadn't heard about the Truth Commission. As a result,
she missed the deadline to apply for victim status.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the majority in South Africa, life goes on,'' said
Khumalo. ``Those who've suffered will suffer some more.''
</P>
<P>
   Other families who lost relatives in the apartheid years have
learned much from the Truth Commission, but say they are not
prepared to forgive those who have confessed to the killings, and
they strongly oppose amnesty for them.
</P>
<P>
   A case in point is that of Stanza Bopape, a 27-year-old activist
from Mamelodi, a township on the outskirts of Pretoria. In June
1988, he was arrested in Johannesburg and taken to John Vorster
Square police headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Police said at the time that Bopape had escaped while being
driven to another location, but he never contacted family members,
and he was never found.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in December 1996, after receiving subpoenas from
investigators and as the deadline for seeking amnesty approached,
10 police officers, including then commissioner Johannes van der
Merwe, applied for amnesty and admitted that Bopape had died while
being interrogated.
</P>
<P>
   They said because Bopape was uncooperative, that he needed to be
given ``a little fright.'' So he was strapped to a chair and given
electric shock treatments. But he soon slumped over, dead. They
claimed that he was given only two or three jolts at levels that
should not have been fatal, so they suspected he may have suffered
from a heart ailment.
</P>
<P>
   Afraid that reaction to the death-in-detention might have caused
further unrest at a particularly unstable time, the police said
they took Bopape's body to the northeastern part of the country and
dumped it in the Komati River. The body has never been recovered.
</P>
<P>
   The Truth Commission considers the Bopape case to be one of the
most important it investigated because of the top-to-bottom
involvement of the Security Police in his death and its subsequent
coverup. But Bopape's familiy is opposing amnesty for the 10 police
officials in the belief they are still not telling the whole truth.
They say Bopape had no history of heart problems and suspect that
he was beaten and tortured to death. They believe his body was then
exploded, not dumped in the river, to conceal evidence of a beating
or torture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel very sad because there's not been full disclosure,''
said Michael Bopape, Stanza's brother. ``They've admitted they
killed him, but they haven't told us how they killed him. These
guys should be arrested to serve as an example for people holding
top positions in government. So it can't happen again. So my
father's soul will rest in peace.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Johannesburg correspondent Kurt Shillinger contributed to
this article.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
