<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SKI-FASHION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEECE IS THE WORD, KILLY IS THE NAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIE HATFIELD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One word can almost sum up the trend in 1998/99 skiwear: fleece.
</P>
<P>
   That soft fuzzy stuff that used to come only on teddy bears now
covers the skier inside and out, and not just because it's cute and
comes in bright colors and feels like you're wearing your jammies.
Fleece, made as ski equipment, say in the women's jacket of
Polartec 300 made by The North Face, is warmer than many other
natural materials. It comes in all weights and is used to make
everything except ski boots: hoods, headbands, neck warmers, inner
jackets, outer jackets, vests, gloves, liner gloves, one-piece
underlayers.
</P>
<P>
   And if your whole ski jacket isn't fleece, portions of it may
be. This is the season of kaleidoscopic fabrications on single
garments; i.e. fleece in the places where you most need softness
and warmth such as around the neck, rubberized fabric at the elbows
where you most need stretch, ventilated breathable fabric under the
arms, and, for fashion alone, leather or fur trims at some
necklines and wrists.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to parkas and pants, Jean-Claude Killy is the name
to remember. While hordes of athletes throw their names onto
clothing lines, Killy backs his up with a promise: You will be
warm. Known for his three gold medals at the '68 winter Olympics,
Killy was familiar with that bone-chilling cold that can hit a
skier during the not-so-great conditions that sometimes exist in
ski country, and he has put plenty of study and technology into his
fabrics to keep out that nasty cold. Notable are the
diagonally-placed synthetic down fibers inside his parkas for men
and women, that led Randy Bisson, assistant manager of the Ski
Market on Commonwealth Avenue, to promise that Killy parkas are the
warmest in the store this year _ and the most popular.
</P>
<P>
   ``Killy is flying out of the store,'' says Bisson, and when one
looks at the color splashed on the walls and hangers, one
understands the appeal to that sense, too. With black as the basic
jacket, and black practically the required color for pants and
accessories, brights in new tones are on the parkas. Surprisingly,
for the women, an acidic lime green is one of the more popular
shades, followed by a strong marigold yellow that Killy calls
``chrome.'' There's red, and blue, and the women's parkas, puffy
but not gigantic and slimmed down from past seasons but covered in
hardware such as giant zippers, are $174.99, while the man's, most
often in black, with ``pit'' zippers for ventilation even under the
arms, and heat-taped seams, which provide superior water
resistance, are $588. The big difference in price is not just
because the men's jackets are bigger. They're more technical, with
different sections of the parka in different technical
fabrications, some more water-resistant or stronger or warmer than
others.
</P>
<P>
   The North Face has a man's jacket with a powder shirt in one
garment for $395 at the Ski Market, which features a double storm
flap under the arms and a velcroed articulating hood that contours
to the head, so that when you turn your head, your face is not
facing the inside of your hood.
</P>
<P>
   Marmot makes vests that can be zipped right into the jacket by
means of a second zipper under the first. This is layering taken to
the extreme.
</P>
<P>
   The best value in the Ski Market is the Columbia parka. If you
buy one jacket for $183, you're actually getting two, because there
is a removable nylon and fleece shell under the jacket.
</P>
<P>
   A black waterproof, breathable, high-backed, double suspender
Gore Tex pant for men is $180 and actually has a drop seat, Dr.
Denton-style, for faster bathroom visits with all those clothes on,
and Bisson notes that this has been an extremely good selling
feature.
</P>
<P>
   The regular fleece gloves are $29 at the Ski Market, but this
year there is a North Face Windstopper fleece glove with Gore Tex
layer for $47, or a thicker fleece glove for $55.
</P>
<P>
   Bisson urges people who can't keep warm on the slopes to come in
for a total body lesson, which starts with the underwear dictum:
never cotton. ``It sits, soggy and cold, next to your skin when
wet,'' he says as he leads you over to the Lycra poly blend tops
and bottoms in sleeveless, tank or long-sleeved styles, all of
which constantly wick the moisture from your body. With ``Wick &AMP;
Dry'' ski socks, at $12 per pair, he dares you to come back and say
you were cold this winter on the slopes. Snowboarders, by the way,
can this season find plenty of socks and gloves, in addition to
parkas and pants, made just for their sport.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest news at Bogner is the hugely popular ``Fire &AMP; Ice''
line of snowboard and skiwear for the college-aged and younger
skier. This line is slimmed down from the formerly oversized
styles, especially in snowboard clothing, and it's a technical line
with bonded seams and very warm and thin water- repellant fabrics.
The prices are not as shocking as the adult Bogner, either: A parka
in the Fire &AMP; Ice line is $228. Colors are ecru, cornflower blue,
navy and white, and sometimes all of these colors or several of
them are blocked into one garment, as in the $158 Italian fleece
jackets (yes, Bogner is as committed to fleece as the others; their
fleece, however, is even more luxurious to the hand than most). The
pant in this line is lined but not bulky, with nylon polymide and
is waterproof and insulated. It has a flat front like a jean and a
straight leg with a boot cut, for $198. Sleek zippered black cable
sweaters with fleece sections are popular, as are the
black-and-white color blocked parkas and the chenille and wool
fabric blocked sweaters. Wool sweaters with stripes across the
chest are $128 at Bogner. A snowboard pant, big but not oversized,
with a white stripe piped down the black legs, is $178.
</P>
<P>
   Big Ice is, ironically, the littlest Bogner in the place. It's a
whole line for the littlest skier, sized for the 3-12-year-old, and
its trim just hints of Bogner classic style, with a snowflake or a
reindeer embroidered here or there rather than splashed all over.
Matching fleece mittens, gloves, and hats are part of the parka and
pant and sweater Big Ice line, and it follows the same baby
blue/ecru/white shades as the Fire &AMP; Ice line for big brothers and
sisters.
</P>
<P>
   You can still get your high style at Bogner and its
corresponding price, if that's your thing on the slopes. The adult
``Burnout'' pattern is flocked velvet or floral jacquard Ultrasuede
in the same cornflower blue and ecru as the younger lines. As with
the other lines, there are matching fleece pieces for these parkas
and pants and one-piece suits. ``Sonia'' is a smooth black
microfiber jacket of polyurethane with a tunnel drawstring at the
waist for a fitted look. It's $758 unless you want a huge brown fox
fur detachable collar and cuffs; then it's $1,098. There's a White
Buffalo theme from New Mexico, with stars and a buffalo embroidered
on the parkas and a huge ``Legends of the White Buffalo'' logo on
the back. The equivalent of fur trim for men who wish to make a
fashion statement is leather, and there is plenty of it at Bogner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
