<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SKI-UTAH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR AREAS FROM THE NEXT OLYMPIC STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Looking back at the Olympics I have covered as a skiwriter, from
Lake Placid to Nagano, only a couple _ Lillehamer and Albertville _
were not preceeded by much anxiety over snow conditions. And often,
the worries were justified.
</P>
<P>
   From the warm Chinook winds that threatened to melt the Calgary
ski runs to the monsoon weather that tried to wash away last year's
Nagano games, no area seemed without threat. Even Europe during
World Cup season sometimes has snow droughts that force venue
shifts and postponements.
</P>
<P>
   But even before the Olympic Committee picked Utah as the site of
the 2002 Winter Games, nearly everyone on the scene had the same
thought: ``What a perfect venue Salt Lake City would be!''
Especially for skiing.
</P>
<P>
   Questions of transportation (airports right downtown) to
infrastructure (much of it already built) aside, the Rockies in
general, and Utah particularly, have the most predictably perfect
snow of anywhere in ski country. Anywhere you can get to without a
band of Sherpas, that is.
</P>
<P>
   It has been called ``champagne powder'' and ``cold smoke,'' but
whatever its name, the snow that falls on the Utah Rockies is as
close to perfect as ski snow gets. The occasional drawback is that
it snows so much so fast that skiers can't reach the areas. Roads
closed; snow falling too fast to plow _ that kind of thing.
</P>
<P>
   True, Colorado, from Vail to Aspen to Steamboat to Arapahoe, is
usually credited with having cornered the most truly great ski
areas in the United States, nor is Colorado (Montana, Idaho, New
Mexico) shabby in the snow department.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact that Utah is considered a near perfect
international ski venue should be instructive to skiers making the
annual trek west for a Rocky Mountain vacation. Even within all
that perfection are a couple of polar opposites: Indeed, Utah
skiing seems to divide between the relentlessly rough Alta and
Snowbird and the terminally suave Deer Valley.
</P>
<P>
   If readers' surveys are any measure of how aging boomers, who
dominate the ski travel business, like their skiing, think smooth,
think plush, think rich. Deer Valley, where ski checking valets
greet you at every doorway, comes up near the top of most lists.
</P>
<P>
   Attendants fairly flock to your group and all its gear when you
arrive, and the place treats you like a celebrity from that moment
on. Which is also how the resort approaches its snow, grooming it
to a smoothness rarely matched in Utah or any other state. Top
service and grooming, whatever it costs, have been Deer Valley's
plan from the start, and the plan works. Few skiers who go away
having spent rigorously complain. They know what the area is all
about and they want some.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that there's anything namby-pamby about the
skiing. Yes, it's groomed to a fault so that skiers on the long
blue cruisers can achieve sensations of flight. But this mountain
has some oomph to it as well. Steep and deep bowls of powder,
bumps, and steep chutes are also features to keep the top-level
skiers challenged for a week's vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is Deer Valley in any way small or limited. With 1,750 acres
and a 3,000-foot vertical drop, the area has as much variety for
mixed ability groups as any area in or outside the Rockies with the
exception of Vail and Whistler. This season, two new areas _ Deer
Crest and Empire Canyon _ open up over 500 acres of new terrain
ranging from moderate blue cruising to steep glades and chutes.
</P>
<P>
   The food is exactly what you'd expect from Deer Valley _
exquisite, expensive, and in the estimation of loyalists worth
every penny. The lodging is top drawer as well.
</P>
<P>
   If banning snowboards seems snobbishly backward in this age of
detente, so be it. Deer Valley is unashamed of its position, and
misplaced boarders will be given free ski rentals for the day.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Park City's great advantage as an Olympic venue is its
proximity _ via good roads _ to the Salt Lake City airport. This
hometown of the US Ski Team boasts a fine ski area _ especially
with this year's additions _ in an area that has an off-slope buzz
to it. With much of the state's skiing still rather spartan in
terms of restaurants and shopping opportunities, Park City has all
above amenities and will most certianly continue to develop with
the Olympic games just 38 months away.
</P>
<P>
   About six miles out of town, at an place once called Park City
West, then Wolf Mountain, is a remarkable ski area. The Canyons is
typical of Les Otten's American Skiing Co. approach to such
projects: The stated aim was to create not just the biggest ski
area in Utah, but the biggest in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   While The Canyons currently falls just short of that goal, its
2,700 acres of varied terrain unfolds only when skiers lift above
the rather unimpressive front face of the lower slopes, which is
all one sees from the road.
</P>
<P>
   But even here, the first phase of an ambitious base village is
in place, and ASC this season has added two high-speed quads and a
triple chair, as well as Sun Lodge at mid-mountain.
</P>
<P>
   As the gondola lifts above the lower face, the Canyons spreads
out in a spectacular array of peaks, chutes, and open bowls that
will give skiers the entire smorgasbord of experiences, from the
blue cruisers of Snow Canyons to some dense gladed skiing through
Escapade Woods. And, by the way, the Canyons not only allows
snowboards but has built a terrain park. The Canyons, which
averages 325 inches of snow anually, is an easy 30-mile trek from a
national airport.
</P>
<P>
   Many skiers in the advanced range count Alta among their
favorite areas on Planet Ski. In terms of buff conditions and
service _ or even night life _ Alta is the alter ego of Deer
Valley. In fact, the infrastructure at Alta reminds one of a trip
back in time, and the grooming is barely noticeable. But the snow
is as near perfect as snow can be, and grooming matters little.
Alta is deep and steep, with natural chutes and bowls. It is for
good solid skiers who can do powder and broken snow skiing, or are
serious about learning them. This is the area where photos are shot
of skiers wearing bandanas over their mouths to keep them from
drowning in powder, or so the legend goes.
</P>
<P>
   The downside to Alta, aside from a lack of grooming and modern
lifts, is that snow is sometimes so abundant the road up Little
Cottonwood Canyon is inaccessible. Skiers put up with some
deprivation to ski Alta, but as Chris Holbrook puts it: ``All the
better to focus on what you go there for _ serious skiing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
