<HEADLINE>
A RETURN TO WORLD WAR II SITES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Historic Tours, one of the companies that offer tours to World
War II battle sites, is planning tours on the 55th anniversary of
the D-Day invasion of France's Normandy Beach next year. Another
such company is Galaxy Tours, which has seen an increase in
inquiries about its World War II programs.
</P>
<P>
   Some 90 percent of Galaxy's tour participants are veterans, but
Hal Ryder, president of the company, said, ``In recent years, we
have had an increase in nephews of veterans; now the veterans are
calling, asking to take their grandchildren.''
</P>
<P>
   In Honolulu, perhaps the most famous symbol of the war's ending
is about to open to the public. The Battleship Missouri Memorial
will open Jan. 29 on the 55th anniversary of the ship's launch.
</P>
<P>
   While the Missouri didn't enter service until near the war's
end, it secured its place in history on Sept. 2, 1945, when on its
deck the Japanese signed surrender papers. During the war, it
served in the battles of Iwo Jima and Okinawa and also as the
flagship for Admiral William ``Bull'' Halsey.
</P>
<P>
   Some have criticized having the Missouri in Pearl Harbor across
from the Arizona Memorial, which honors the thousands of military
who died within the Arizona and other ships during the Japanese
attack on Pearl Harbor on Dec. 7, 1941. But the USS Missouri
Memorial Association, caretaker of the battleship, has pledged to
preserve the solemnity of the Arizona Memorial.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri will be placed with its bow pointing toward the
Arizona, and all activities will be focused around the midsection
of the Missouri to minimize noise distractions to the Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   When the Missouri opens to the public, visitors will be able to
view historical displays, including the horse saddle Halsey kept in
his quarters. The quarterdeck where the surrender took place will
not be altered, nor will it have interpretive signs _ visitors will
be left to contemplate the significance of the site.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantis Adventures in Hawaii is now taking reservations for
tours of the battleship. Tours begin at $12 for adults to $49 for a
deluxe tour that includes transportation from Waikiki, services of
a guide, and lunch. For information, call toll-free 877-644-4896.
</P>
<P>
   For information on visiting World War II sites in Europe, call
Historic Tours in New Jersey at 877-WW2-TOUR, or Galaxy Tours in
Pennsylvania at 800-523-7287. Valor Tours of California is also
planning tours to Europe. For information, call 800-842-4504.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Helping others
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vacations used to mean escaping job stress and relaxing, but now
more and more Americans are using their vacation time to help
others. The number of volunteer vacationers has skyrocketed.
Cross-Cultural Solutions, a nonprofit organization that offers
short-term volunteer programs in India, is adding a Ghana program
for January. Volunteers will work for three weeks or more with
local social service programs in villages in the eastern plains of
Ghana, a region steeped in West Africa's vibrant traditional
culture. From fostering small-business programs for women to
teaching English in schools, volunteers can make substantial
contributions. Other areas of work include health care, the arts,
and recreation. No volunteer experience is necessary. The Ghana
program is $1,850 and covers all expenses. Air fare is additional.
The program fee and air fare are tax-deductible for US residents.
For more information, call 800-380-4777.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Colorful calendars
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's calendar season, and two of the best come from New
Hampshire publisher Kanin Press. The third edition of The 1999 New
England Lighthouse Calendar focuses on 12 island lighthouses. One
of the most useful calendars around is the New England Weekenders
Calendar, with information on fairs, festivals, and special events.
There's an easy, quick reference guide for planning weekend
getaways. The calendar includes 12 watercolor illustrations by New
England artist Pat Ryan Perkins. Also available is a Southeastern
Lighthouse Calendar and Mid-Atlantic Weekenders Calendar. Each
calendar is $12.95, and all are available in stores or from Kanin
Press, PO Box 1174, Portsmouth, NH 03802 (add $5 for shipping and
handling). For store locations, call 603-433-4775.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sweet Suites
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's Maxwell Hotel, an Art Deco masterpiece, is
offering a Sweet Suites Deal. Guests who book a junior suite for
three nights receive the fourth free. Current rates are $195 a
night. The hotel, located in Union Square, also features a lot of
shopping services, from maps to foot spas _ nice after a day of
shopping. From Nov. 15 to Dec. 30, the hotel will be giving one
guest a day a gift certificate for $25 to $100, good at area
stores. For information, call 888-734-6299.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Study in England
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An educational experience for all ages is being offered by the
University of Cambridge in England. The 15th annual study program
will be held July 18-31 and includes seminars ranging from Thomas
Hardy and the Crusades to politics today. Students live in private
rooms with baths, and all courses have field trips and are
available for credit. For information, write to Joann Painter,
Office of Cooperating Colleges, 714 Sassafras St., Erie, PA 16501;
or telephone 814-456-0757.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Irish castle stays
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Off-season is the time to live regally yet on a budget. CIE
Tours offers stays at two of Ireland's top hotels _ Ashford or
Dromoland castles. The $699, four-day/three-night package includes
round-trip air fare from Boston or New York, stays at one of the
castles, breakfasts, a rental car with unlimited mileage, and more.
Extra nights at $172 a person are available. For information, call
800-CIE TOUR.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Palace by night
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to Hampton Court Palace in London can tour the palace
by lantern light through Dec. 22. The tour ranges from the Tudor
kitchens to Henry VIII's State Apartments on to the Haunted
Gallery, where the ghost of Catherine Howard, Henry's fifth wife,
is said to run screaming along the corridor. Tours are offered
Tuesday, Saturday, and Sunday evenings. For information, call
800-806-7187.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
For men only
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A ``for men only'' spa program has opened at the Jalousie Hilton
Resort and Spa on St. Lucia. Male spa-goers now make up 30 percent
of all spa visitors, and the Hilton has developed special
treatments, from facials and sea slat body scrubs to sulfur mud
baths.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
You pick the time
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A nice feature of the Sheraton Center Toronto Hotel is its
``clean at your convenience'' program that lets guests choose when
they wish to have their room cleaned and refreshed. A doorknob card
allows guests to check off their desired cleaning time, with a
choice of four periods. Adding to the program is that mini-bar
staff will do their checking and restocking during the selected
period, rather than interrupting guests at another time.
</P>
