<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2946 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-DEKOCK-BOS &LR;      11-10 1263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-DEKOCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO AN EXECUTIONER, KILLING WAS PART OF THE WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BEN BRADLEE JR.  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ELIZABETH, South Africa _ Eugene de Kock was apartheid's
chief executioner, licensed to kill as the commander of an elite
death squad and terrorist unit based at Vlakplaas, a farm outside
Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
   Nicknamed ``Prime Evil'' by compatriots because of his lust for
violence, de Kock was once the most decorated member of the South
African Security Police. Before arriving at Vlakplaas in 1985, he
was a commando in the bush war against Rhodesia, now Zimbabwe. He
led the team that bombed the African National Congress's London
office in 1982 and commanded Pretoria's most notorious
counterinsurgency unit in Namibia.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, following a 21-month trial, de Kock was found guilty of
89 crimes, including six murders, one attempted murder, two counts
of conspiracy to commit murder, and 66 counts of fraud. He was
sentenced to 212 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is hoping to be freed, or face a greatly reduced
sentence, by applying for amnesty to the country's Truth and
Reconciliation Commission. The commission just finished a 2
1/2-year investigation into crimes of the apartheid era, but its
amnesty committee continues its work. It has the power to free
those it finds have testified truthfully about politically
motivated crimes.
</P>
<P>
   De Kock's amnesty application consumes 4,000 pages and covers
more than 120 ``incidents'' in which he was involved. Some
investigators have linked him and his men to well over 100
killings, but de Kock says the figure is closer to 65.
</P>
<P>
   In his trial, and in testimony at various amnesty hearings of
the Truth Commission, the 49-year-old de Kock has emerged as the
foremost symbol of the horrific excesses of the white-minority
regime. Wearing glasses with thick lenses, his straight dark hair
plastered on his head, de Kock speaks in a monotone that belies the
dastardly deeds he recounts.
</P>
<P>
   Among his sensational disclosures: naming more than 20 senior
military and police officials, and former presidents P.W. Botha and
F.W. de Klerk, all of whom he asserted either ordered or approved
of his operations.
</P>
<P>
   De Kock's defense that he was following orders echoes arguments
made by Nazi war criminals in Nuremberg, and even by American
soldiers at the My Lai massacre in Vietnam, which have been
rejected by the world community.
</P>
<P>
   But since the end of his trial, de Kock seems to have succeeded
in changing the initial perception of him as the psychopathic devil
incarnate. Now, even many blacks see him more as a sympathetic fall
guy.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of the shifting emotions about de Kock first surfaced
last year during a memorable amnesty hearing at a community center
in Port Elizabeth, an industrial city on the Indian Ocean that had
been a flashpoint in the anti-apartheid resistance.
</P>
<P>
   In a potentially incendiary setting, de Kock appeared before
hundreds of people amid tight security. But then a strange thing
happened. After listening to de Kock describe how he had committed
murder and mayhem on orders from those who had now abandoned him,
the crowd burst into applause.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were hearing the truth articulated for the first time
and it was like a breath of fresh air,'' said Dumisa Ntsebeza, a
commission member who served as head of the panel's investigative
unit.
</P>
<P>
   Added Denzil Potgieter, a mixed-race member of the commission
who sits on the amnesty committee that will pass judgment on de
Kock: ``He's been a very popular figure whenever he appears. He's
gotten applause and had people eating out of his hand. I would have
thought it unthinkable that people would not have wanted to kill
him on sight, so it's been quite amazing to see this reception.''
</P>
<P>
   In its final report issued in late October, the Truth Commission
praised de Kock for being the prod that forced other members of the
security forces to come forward and tell their stories in hope of
obtaining amnesty. ``The ironic truth is that what brought them to
the commission was the fullness of the disclosures made by an
individual often painted as the archvillian of the apartheid era _
Mr. Eugene de Kock,'' the report said. ``Whatever his motives, the
commission acknowledges that it was largely he who broke the code
of silence.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   De Kock, who stuttered as a child, was raised in the
Johannesburg suburb of Brits, the son of an ardent nationalist who
was a court magistrate. He was taught by his father and others that
``We were at war. We were taught that the man who shoots first will
win,'' he once testified. ``Shoot second and you're dead.''
</P>
<P>
   In court and before the commission, de Kock has described in
vivid detail some of the killings he carried out in his 15 years in
the security forces. He once helped murder a suspected informer
with a shovel, another with a pool cue; others he suffocated with
the inner-tubes of tires.
</P>
<P>
   In one 1988 incident, de Kock said he and a team of operatives
waited in ambush for a group of Pan Africanist Congress fighters to
cross the border into South Africa from Swaziland. When a van
appeared carrying those he assumed were the targets, de Kock
emptied his Uzi at the car, killing a man and two women, each of
whom was unarmed.
</P>
<P>
   A third woman, who survived the initial flurry but was wounded
and begging for her life, was finished off on the spot. But de Kock
and his team soon realized the wrong people had been shot. So they
returned to the same spot several nights later and killed four
more.
</P>
<P>
   De Kock said he and his men used James Bond-like gadgets such as
booby-trapped bombs hidden in radios, tape recorders, or pens, and
mailed the devices to ANC targets living in exile in neighboring
countries. Once they tested a booby-trapped set of earphones by
blowing off the head of a pig before sending another pair to an ANC
lawyer, who was decapitated by the exploding earphones.
</P>
<P>
   De Kock maintained he wasn't all bad. Describing a raid into
Lesotho in which he and his men killed a dozen ANC exiles, he told
how an infant belonging to a slain woman and her husband had
survived the attack. De Kock scooped up the baby boy, placed him in
an adjoining room, and called the police to have the child picked
up.
</P>
<P>
   And it wasn't all darkness and death at Vlakplaas, either. There
were also memorable braais, or barbecues, in which de Kock and his
men would unwind, get raunchy, and drink until they retched. ``We
had only the best at Vlakplaas,'' de Kock said, referring to the
liquor they consumed.
</P>
<P>
   The existence of Vlakplaas was exposed in 1989, but it was not
disbanded by President de Klerk until 1993. De Kock rails against
de Klerk: ``I regard him as one of the greatest cowards the country
has ever produced,'' he said at his trial. ``He sold out certain
members of the security forces to the ANC.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, referring to President Botha as well, de Kock added:
``They want to eat lamb, but they don't want to see the blood and
guts.''
</P>
<P>
   De Kock was arrested in 1994 as he tried to flee South Africa
for Portugal, where his wife and children were waiting for him. He
had sold his house, was carrying phony passports, and had already
opened several Swiss bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   In his application for amnesty, de Kock wrote: ``I am not a
psychopath, but merely a product of a certain kind of ... training
I received, which was mainly of a military nature, and which
flourished and developed in the apartheid milieu in which I found
myself at that time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
