<HEADER>
A2949 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISTRICT-MAYOR-BOS &LR;      11-10 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISTRICT-MAYOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D.C.'S NEW MAYOR: HE'S NO BARRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In his natty gray suit and signature bow tie,
Anthony A. Williams is as politely buttoned-up as they come,
distinctly and almost purposefully out of place in the rough and
tumble of the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the last week of his campaign here for mayor, he still
appeared uncomfortable in the role of political supplicant. ``I
need your support,'' he would mumble in a barely audible voice,
stiffly working the crowds.
</P>
<P>
   But they loved him anyway. They loved him because he is
unpolished, because he is as straight as the pinstripes in his
suit, because he is entirely lacking in the charisma and
flamboyance that sustained his predecessor, Marion Barry, through
years of political turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 47, is the un-Barry mayor-elect, a Harvard-trained
African-American lawyer and policy wonk, Washington's new hope for
a city that wants to regain the power to govern itself. With the
defeat of Senator Lauch Faircloth, a North Carolina Republican and
staunch opponent of home rule for Washington, political observers
say it is a realistic hope.
</P>
<P>
   Williams joins the growing ranks of a new generation of young,
highly educated, big city black mayors with a conservative edge
that includes Dennis Archer of Detroit, William Campbell of
Atlanta, and Michael R. White of Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was propelled to victory in all 140 voting precincts
over moderate Republican Carol Schwartz by collective exasperation
with potholes that aren't filled, schools that don't teach, and
police who don't patrol.
</P>
<P>
   But ironically, Williams &UR;  &LR;  was elected despite a shift in power
away from blacks, who lost their majority on the city council for
the first time. The black population has fallen by 20 percent in
the past decade, and now makes up only 60 percent of the District,
while white, Hispanic, and Asian populations are all rising.
</P>
<P>
   Williams's election marks the end of an era.
</P>
<P>
   Barry, who bowed out of the election after 16 years as mayor,
inspired enormous pride in the District, championing home rule,
thumbing his nose at a Republican Congress he believed to be racist
and dictatorial. He is credited with having opened local government
to disfranchised blacks for the first time, enlarging the middle
class, caring for the elderly and, at one time anyway, expanding
city services.
</P>
<P>
   But his is a mixed legacy. Known for his arrest while smoking
crack, his racially divisive rhetoric, and political rehabilitation
as a sinner redeemed, Barry also shamed the city. It was on his
watch that the District hit an all-time low two years ago with
hemorrhaging budgets and a dysfunctional bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   Fed up, Congress reduced Barry's role to one of ceremonial
ribbon-cutter, canceling his budgetary powers and creating a
financial control board _ with Williams as its chief financial
officer _ to manage the District.
</P>
<P>
   Williams quickly did what many thought was impossible: He reined
in spending, cleaned house, and put tax collectors to work. This
year, he returned a $184 million surplus, scoring big points with
Congress _ and District voters, who began a movement to draft him
into the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been more enthused about Tony than any other candidate
since 1968,'' said Max N. Berry, a fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   No one expected the newcomer tarred with the label of
``carpetbagger'' for recently moving into the district to beat the
home-grown politicians who had been waiting in the wings for years
to run when Barry stepped down. But, in a late entry into the
primary, Williams pulled a major upset by defeating six candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did my job, they didn't,'' was his mantra.
</P>
<P>
   Williams grew up in Los Angeles, the child of Postal Service
workers. Adopted at the age of 4, friends say he flourished with
the nurturing of his hard-working parents. He is an avid
birdwatcher and outdoorsman with his wife, Diane, and their
daughter, Asantewa, 24.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, where he worked for the city on affordable housing
after graduating from Harvard, his co-worker, John Huggins, said
Williams was known for his humor, brains, and devotion to serving
low-income communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a visionary,'' said Huggins. ``He doesn't just see the
bricks and mortar, he sees the buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams has three Ivy League degrees and is an experienced
public servant, having worked as executive director of the St.
Louis Community Development Agency, deputy state comptroller of
Connecticut, and chief financial officer of the US Agriculture
Department before running the control board. But does he have what
it takes to be more than a bean-counter?
</P>
<P>
   ``His vision is evolving. In some areas it's clear, but in
others he still needs work,'' said outgoing Mayor Barry. ``He is
going to have to get some charisma or he won't be around for long.
Also, courage and perseverance.''
</P>
<P>
   But Williams already has displayed his mettle with the control
board, doing what Barry never could, including firing city workers.
He didn't, however, help his cause by having police escort the
employees from their desks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't just be a technocrat mayor,'' noted Tom Sherwood,
author of ``Dream City,'' a Washington political history.
</P>
<P>
   Political observers point out that the District still has no
full congressional representation or control over its own budget
and judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have some real worries that he becomes the greatest colonial
governor ever,'' said Mark Plotkin, a political commentator on
Washington public radio. ``He's so accommodating and savvy about
knowing what the masters want in Congress ... that he doesn't fight
for what we want: an expansion of home rule.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Williams is counting on his good relations with the
Republican Congress to further the cause as he tries to turn the
city around.
</P>
<P>
   He has pledged to unite the city as he pushes for economic
development by streamlining and improving government services, the
tax code, and public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody in City Hall told Tony he could get anything done,
make any idea a success, if he learned to think Irish,'' remembered
Stephen Coyle, Williams's boss at the Boston Redevelopment
Authority. ``Maybe that's what Boston gave him, the appetite and
capacity to resolve community problems, and this long and secret
journey of his to learn to think Irish.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
