<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEN-AMBASSADORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIT WIRES YOUTHS FOR ACTION, WORLDWIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ It's a tough job, trying to create the
future.
</P>
<P>
   You have to do things like ride a small boat through flooded
villages in Bangladesh. Or get pulled off a train by authorities in
China, who confiscate your software because they're suspicious of
what it might contain. Or even have your equipment blown up by
terrorists when they bomb a US embassy in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The folks at MIT's Media Lab thought such efforts were worth it,
though. In the most ambitious undertaking of its kind, they have
connected 3,000 10- to 16-year-olds around the world _ some in
remote areas that had not even been wired for telephones before _
through a specialized computer network.
</P>
<P>
   The objectives, said Media Lab officials, were as ambitious as
the logistics: to promote international dialogue, develop ideas for
advancing technology, and, in incremental but demonstrable ways,
instigate programs that could change the world. Most pointedly, the
idea was to aim at those targets by empowering young people through
computers, especially in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
   The yearlong endeavor will culminate with a week of meetings at
MIT of about 90 participants, elected electronically by their
peers, beginning Sunday, Nov.15. They will discuss their results;
learn additional computer skills and other methods to pursue their
individual interests; and share their views with representatives of
various governments, educational institutions, and high-tech
industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is for this to be a wedge,'' said Justine Cassell,
assistant professor at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology
and director of the Media Lab's multimillion-dollar Junior Summit
project. ``We obviously can't reach every kid in every country ...
but the participants can, and already have, moved this into their
communities and beyond.''
</P>
<P>
   In Pune, India, for instance, 14-year-old Pooja Girish Aphale
used her international e-mail link to solicit ideas on how to
improve the lives of poverty-stricken ``rag pickers.'' Then she
started several local drives to get food and medicine to these poor
Indians, who derive their nickname from their search for food and
other necessities on trash-collection days in affluent
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Luca Avadani, a Bucharest, Romania, resident who was accepted
into the Junior Summit even though he is only 9, has a more global
and long-range pursuit. He has been working, along with his fellow
students on-line, to put together a proposal and solicit funding
for a Children's World Bank that would subsidize nutrition,
education, and other programs intended for kids.
</P>
<P>
   On a loftier level, sponsors said they hoped to starkly
illustrate how computers are causing national borders to blur, and
perhaps accelerate their disintegration by promoting dialogue among
disparate young people for whom this relatively new technology will
be an integral fact of life.
</P>
<P>
   Like most technology researchers, the MIT officials point out
that children are rarely brought into the creative process on
computer use or development, even though they are widely believed
to have a natural affinity that allows them to think in innovative
ways. Furthermore, the officials believe too little basic research
has been done into children's use of computers or into their
long-term effects, so both those issues are being tracked by
Cassell and her colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being the first digital generation, I believe we kids have a
lot to offer and show the world,'' Eduardo de Oliveira Rodrigues
Neto, a 15-year-old participant from Brazil, wrote in an e-mail
interview with the Globe last week. ``We are the base of the
future, it is today's kids that is going to shape tomorrow's
future. Our knowledge and experience will be crucial to further
development inside the informatics field.''
</P>
<P>
   Creating a process through which the participants could make
contact proved a daunting task in itself, but it has already led to
significant technological achievements. To begin with, not all the
nations' phone lines could handle the data flow for Internet
access, so a ``common denominator'' e-mail system was devised that
gives everyone a high-speed way to stay in touch.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the most important breakthrough, however, has been a
translation system by which participants can type messages in their
native languages, send them, and have them converted
automatically &UR;  &LR; into one of five languages (Chinese, Spanish,
French, English, or Portuguese) within 10 seconds. MIT officials
said the overwhelming majority of users know at least one of those
languages, but multilingual participants sometimes have to help
those who do not.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the officials said, more than 25,000 e-mail messages
have been transmitted during the life of the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has been able to crack the multi-language,
multicultural barrier like this before,'' said Annette Tonti, a
business consultant hired by the Media Lab to be executive producer
of the Youth Summit. ``Having a kid from China talking to someone
speaking Hindi in Bangladesh is pretty powerful ... and it
obviously has potential applications of all sorts.''
</P>
<P>
   While Tonti hailed the project for its pure research component,
as well as for its potential in furthering cross-cultural
communication, she also made it clear that she foresees rapid
applications in the business world. Indeed, she said she plans to
advise clients on how they can create better international
communications systems _ particularly by employing the Media Lab's
innovative translation technology.
</P>
<P>
   The Junior Summit was the brainchild of Isao Okawa, chairman of
the CSK Corp. in Japan, the parent company of Sega Enterprises Ltd.
Asserting that children's views about technology had not been
sufficiently considered, he launched a small-scale project in 1995
that ended with 41 kids from around the world meeting in Tokyo that
November.
</P>
<P>
   Last July, he asked Nicholas Negroponte, Media Lab director, to
embark on a far more ambitious effort, which Okawa's firm and
several others have helped to fund. Applications went out to
educational, governmental, and service organizations that deal with
children; by November, 8,000 responses had come in from 139
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Cassell said entries were judged on the basis of such criteria
as ``passion'' and ``strength of ideas,'' but not access to
computers. So 67 computers had to be shipped or hand-carried to
places where there were none at local schools or other
institutions, and other necessities like telephone lines had to be
arranged; at one site in rural China, a satellite phone was
provided because land lines were unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   While only 1,000 entries were accepted, that translated into
3,000 participants because some applications included several
friends or classmates. Moreover, all the computers in the system
were placed in schools or other community buildings, rather than
homes, so that other students and residents could use them or
contribute to the international dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Adult facilitators were provided, along with guidance on
discussion topics and technical questions, but the participants
were assured that all their communication would be confidential.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I have learnt the real meaning of sharing and caring,''
wrote Aphale, the Indian girl, in response to an e-mail asking what
she had learned from the project. ``I did not just send messages
and receive them, but I exchanged heartfelt ideas and feelings. The
Junior Summit is like a global family and not just usage of
advanced technology.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-10-98 1324EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
