<HEADER>
A2955 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPRING-FASHION-HNS &LR;      11-10 1195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRING-FASHION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINTER WHITES ARE BACK FOR SPRING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ During the fall season, Ralph Lauren's winter whites
didn't even make it to the selling floor, according to Mary
Hamilton, the boss lady at the San Francisco Polo Store.
</P>
<P>
   All those luxurious seven-ply hooded sweaters and elegant creamy
cargo pants were pre-sold. So it's a sure thing that the women who
bought them will absolutely love the paper-white pieces in Ralph's
new spring collection, which are basically the same stuff _
beautifully tailored cargo pants, T-shirts, military short jackets
_ done up in lighter, airier, season-appropriate fabrics.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren showed his collection in SoHo last week in a warehouse
kitted out all in black with padded, flax-linen benches for the
press and friends. It got people in the mood to see more pared-down
neutrals that are so easy on the eye and easy on the body. The
flax-colored linen skirts rippled away from the body, topped with
loosey-goosey tunics in the same hues but contrasting textures.
Linen herringbone pants, readaptations of last season's hipster
pants (some cargo pantss, some not) were worn with no belts.
</P>
<P>
   Then the color arrived. Bubble-gum pinks, lily-of-the-valley
leaf greens, vivid purple, marigold yellow, all worn with a
brightened up Army-issue green, which Ralph calls olive. Olive
cashmere and silk shells, silk tanks, cashmere hooded tops and a
ubiquitous poncho (the only misstep in the collection), which had
some hardened New Yorkers hooting at the thought of flipping on a
cashmere poncho. It probably would feel divine.
</P>
<P>
   This is a mistake-proof collection of wearable clothes with a
few outstanding pieces: the fabulous gray strapless cashmere dress
from the fall collection (the one that was photographed right and
left and cost $15,000) was redone in floaty, sheer, creamy-white
organza for spring; an ivory silk faille anorak worn over a white
silk roll-neck sweater and silk faille pants; a skimpy,
cling-to-the-body front-zip ``hoodie'' worn over an ivory cotton
gabardine skimmer dress and another hooded sweater, all done up in
candy-pink cashmere. Delicious.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kors, meanwhile, like Ralph, specializes in the American
uniform _ sportswear that is adaptable and collectible. However,
Kors' collection was tightly focused and limited to a few signature
pieces: classic Bermuda shorts (narrow, like a pair of pipe-stems
cut off to knee length), the camp shirt, the figure-loving sheath
and the anorak. What he did with them, however, was far from
ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Kors saves his best ideas for Celine, his pricey
French line, but here, he has translated some of the popular
qualities that have revived that house. For instance, the
juxtaposition of luxurious material with sportif shapes. He paired
a long white cashmere ``pull'' with a graphic, giraffe-printed calf
skirt and then turned the black undershirt into an accent piece
above a deep chocolate-mahogany pailette skirt. The prettiest
outfit? Another glitzy skirt of marble cream pailettes worn with a
heather gray cashmere undershirt.
</P>
<P>
   His pants were, in the main, rip-stop taffeta, which works up
like parachute nylon but has a luxuriously shimmery finish. One of
featured items was a black silk rip-stop taffeta anorak, worn like
a short, flippy dress on the runway.
</P>
<P>
   Kors' collection was deceptively simple _ his color palette was
playful and serious at the same time _ for instance, orange with
olive (a lot of olive), stone worn with white (the anorak done up
in stone suede is a real keeper) and a few pieces in cinnabar for
variation, like the anorak worn with silk hopsack shorts that could
go to lunch anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Turning from well-tailored casual to the glitz of Hollywood, old
and new ... namely, Bob Mackie, who is back with a very Texas
collection _ Easter egg colors weighted with beading and floating
panels of chiffon _ and Kevan Hall, who has created one of the most
beautiful collections seen thus far for Halston.
</P>
<P>
   The black-and-white Halston showroom was lined with a double row
of chairs on each side and populated with fans who gave Hall a
standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely does appreciative applause break out in the middle of a
show, but it did at Halston, where a classic white cotton man's
shirt atop a long platinum beaded skirt got gasps and claps. (One
wonders if Hall saw Sharon Stone at the Oscars in one of her
husband's white dress shirts and a lavender Vera Wang sarong?) The
collection started out with the sexy, clingy, bias-cut gowns that
the original Halston was so famous for. Matte jersey or cashmere
was shaped as if it had been created on the body to begin with.
With a color palette inspired by coral reef hues, Hall featured
aqua, shark (his name for the platinum), sand, coral (which was
ginger rather than orangey pink), black and white.
</P>
<P>
   A few of the dresses had laser-cut holes in them and were so
tight that only women _ like Ashley Judd, say _ with a penchant for
no underwear would be very comfortable wearing them. With the
exception of one slinky white job with teensy stars slicing through
to the skin, the idea didn't fly. It looked like a moth on speed
had gotten to the clothes.
</P>
<P>
   What did work were the show-stopping pave-sequin dresses and the
gowns strewn with luminous abalone pieces. A silver-satin evening
suit _ with a tube top so encrusted with abalone that it looked
like an abandoned wreck as seen underwater _ was an original spin
on gussied-up sportswear.
</P>
<P>
   Hall has definitely turned up the heat for Halston with one
sizzling bunch of neoclassic, collectible dresses.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wish I could say the same for Bob Mackie. His Vegas roots need a
touch-up. Some of his clothes were so predictable, they made
glitter look tired. A few dresses were a breath of fresh air: The
sexiest in the line is a little Marie Antoinette number with not a
sequin, rhinestone or bugle bead in sight. Instead, it is a
magnificent celadon faille gown with a flowered, brocaded corselet
bodice cut so low, I heard one woman say: ``No wonder they got in
so much trouble in 18th century France _ the neckline dumped their
poitrines right into the soup.''
</P>
<P>
   The black-and-white group looked best, with a flippy little
cocktail number _ black chiffon skirt with sewn-down hip pleats and
flouncy hem topped with a black-and-white beaded bodice _ scoring
the most points.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Mackie does tend to go off the deep end. A gray
chiffon off-the-shoulder top looks like it came right off the back
of Ann Panagulias when she sang ``Lulu'' 10 years ago. Mackie
adapted the Act I ``pierrot'' costume for commercial consumption,
pairing it with jeweled silver lace pants. Very Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, the entire first row of a prominent section at the
smallish Forum venue was taken up with Neiman Marcus buyers direct
from Texas. One of them _ all blond hair, teeth, headband and sable
coat _ never got off her cell phone. But then, nobody ever said you
can't be chic and gauche at the same time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-10-98 1326EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
