A2956 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      11-10 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW THE ENGLISH FELL FOR AUTUMN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Why is fall the only season we have two different words for?''
a friend asked recently. Good question, and whatever the answer, we
know this one can't be blamed on journalists: Fall may be a better
headline word than autumn, offering both brevity and punnability,
but both terms were around long before newspaper editors got their
grubby hands on them.
</P>
<P>
   Another way to put the question might be, Why don't we have two
words for every season? Given the mixed parentage of English, it
would be no surprise if the Norman conquerors had brought their Old
French versions of the other three seasons along with autompne (as
it was spelled then), just as they brought liberty and marriage to
a language that already had freedom and wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, though, if the English refused to Frenchify their winter,
spring, and summer, they seem to have embraced autumn warmly.
Chaucer uses autumn in 1374, but the Oxford English Dictionary
doesn't have an example of fall used to describe a season till 1545
_ and even then, it's still a phrase, faule of the leafe, rather
than a single word.
</P>
<P>
   Fall itself was, of course, an English word before the Norman
Conquest, and if it wasn't used to describe autumn in the years
before 1066, another word must have been current _ perhaps one that
proved less appealing to the Anglo-Saxon ear than the newly
imported autumn. (I'm hoping some generous medievalist will e-mail
with the answer.) In any case, the two words flourished side by
side for more than 400 years _ and then, on the way to the 20th
century, a funny thing befell fall.
</P>
<P>
   According to Bill Bryson, author of ``The Mother Tongue,''
England suddenly fell out of love with fall in the late 19th
century. Americans went on using it, but as autumn came to dominate
in England, the Brits forgot that fall had ever been their word,
and began to think of it yet another crude American aberration.
</P>
<P>
   Thus a letter to The Guardian in London, asking the same
question my friend posed, puts it this way: ``Why does autumn have
a separate American name, while the other three seasons don't?''
And a writer to The Financial Times, also in London, despairs at
finding the phrase ``later this fall'' in the London-based
newspaper: ``Later this what?'' he demands. ``Britain may be about
to surrender what's left of her democracy and independence, but to
see our version of the English language entering the autumn of its
days is sad indeed.'' After such an energetic display of ignorance,
it's surprising _ well, a little _ to find this linguistic
doomsayer identifying himself as the editor of a magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, poor fall. Admitted only reluctantly into its native land,
thrown overboard a few centuries later in favor of a French
arriviste, then dismissed as a colonial vulgarism. Now that is sad
indeed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Invitation to a hanging
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Diana Lamb of Brewster for letting us know _ just in
time for the holidays _ that festoon is no mere synonym for
decorate, but has a specific meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Lamb objected to a writer's description of a poster festooning a
wall: ``Festoon means `to hang or form a decorative chain or strip
in a curve between two points,' she writes, as in preparation for a
festive event. The dictionaries at hand concur, though they do
mention one less cheerful definition: In dentistry, festoon
describes the curve of the gum around the neck of the tooth.) So
festoon the halls with swags of greenery _ there's another word
with the same curvy connotations _ but stick to push-pinning when
it comes to posters.
</P>
<P>
   Another usage misdemeanor, this one in an advertisement, was
noted by Hal Appleton of Watertown: ``Without a family portrait, it
wasn't just their mantle that was empty,'' reads the copy. The
shelf in question _ the one above the fireplace _ is usually
spelled mantel. In the hierarchy of language crimes, this one ranks
low because mantle, meaning cloak and a host of other things, and
mantel, the fireplace ledge, are not truly different words, just
variant spellings. But most of the people who hang their stockings
by the chimney next month will hang them from the mantel. Santa may
or may not be checking his list for spelling errors, but cautious
celebrants should probably stick with the mantel majority.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (What's the word? Write or e-mail yours to Jan Freeman at The
Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378; freeman(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-10-98 1327EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
