<HEADER>
A2959 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLENN-MOSES-NYTSF &LR;      11-10 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN-MOSES-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESSONS FROM GLENN'S MISSION -- AND ECHOES OF THE BIBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York Times
Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative CONNIE
WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or fax
her at (816) 822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 By RABBI ELI HECHT  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    John Glenn has proven, once again, that he is capable of
extraordinary feats. In humble fashion he explained his recent trip
into space as a giant step for geriatric science.
 &HT;    Through his experiments aboard Discovery, scientists will gain a
better understanding of what happens to the body in zero gravity
and, hopefully, the results will provide a better understanding of
the aging process.
 &HT;    As a larger segment of society grows older, such geriatric
studies are increasingly needed.
 &HT;    In Judaism there is a proverb, ``As men age, their opinions
change.'' (Talmud Shabbat 152). For example, we have seen the
former president, George Bush, fulfill his wish to skydive. Glenn
got his wish to skydive in the other direction, upward into space.
 &HT;    These men, who have achieved stability and greatness,
nevertheless are still looking for challenges. Their opinions about
fulfillment change regularly.
 &HT;    One of the most important lessons we can learn from the Glenn
space mission is how to maintain integrity yet still get along with
younger and less-experienced people.
 &HT;    Imagine if Glenn had tried to pull rank on his fellow space
companions, saying,``I am a senator, a war hero and an experienced
space veteran. I will not listen to a younger commander. My age and
rank puts me way above you.'' The mission would have failed.
 &HT;    In acknowledging that regardless of his attributes he still must
listen to ground control and respect his fellow space companions,
he again proved to be a hero. He helped make the mission a success
by recognizing his limits and carrying out his role.
 &HT;    Society has long worshipped youth, often forgetting the older,
experienced and wise people. For many, the elderly represent a
burden on society. Too little respect has been given to this
growing sector.
 &HT;    But now things are changing. Glenn has raised the consciousness
of senior citizens by telling them to become vibrant and to demand
a part in this active world. He has shown the way for all citizens.
 &HT;    His message is to keep on having hopes and dreams.
 &HT;    I especially liked Glenn's answer regarding God and prayer.
Asked whether he prayed in space, Glenn replied:
 &HT;    ``I pray every day, and I think everybody should. I don't think
we can look at Earth every day -- to look out at this kind of
creation and not believe in God is, to me, impossible.''
 &HT;    In the Bible, Moses was 80 years old when he became a heroic
leader for his people. Legend has it that Moses went up to heaven
for 40 days and nights. He didn't even have a space suit and he did
fine in the zero gravity. His age caused no restrictions.
 &HT;    He led the Israelites into the desert and was a fearless
commander for 40 years.
 &HT;    It has been said that a good man, like fine wine, becomes better
as time goes by. Yes, it caused a great splash in 1962 when Glenn's
space capsule landed in the Atlantic. But last week he made an even
greater splash by returning safely again from space.
 &HT;    He has become an inspiration to those in the graying and
twilight age. He has shown there is no real gap between the young
and the elderly and that people are only as old as they feel.
 &HT;    Maybe the younger generation will learn a thing or two about the
capabilities and possibilities of their older generation.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    c.1998 Rabbi Eli Hecht
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Rabbi Eli Hecht is vice president of the Rabbinical Alliance of
America and past president of the Rabbinical Council of California.
He is the director of Chabad of South Bay in Lomita, Calif. and
writes a monthly Op-Ed column for the Long Beach Press-Telegeam.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
