<DOCNO> NYT19981110.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2965 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      11-10 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY'S EXPERIENCES ARE REAL PAGE-TURNERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is not the ``I'm Running For President'' manifesto, and not
just because he's already written it. Two years ago, Bill Bradley
wrote, ``Time Present, Time Past,'' a look back on his three terms
as a US Senator from New Jersey. That book should be a primer for
every would-be office-seeker in the land, because it is a
distinctly nonideological treatise that has resonance for everyone
from a staunch Christian far right winger to a Trotskyite.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to know why Bradley should be president, read that
book.
</P>
<P>
   And if you want to know whether he will run for the office, hang
on a little longer. He says he will let us know by the end of the
year, and it will be dependent on two factors.
</P>
<P>
   ``One,'' he explains, ``with whatever ability and experience I
have, am I the person who can do the most to improve the quality of
life for Americans at this time? Does the man match the moment?
Number two, do my wife and daughter want to join me in a jump off a
50-story building?''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Time Present, Time Past'' he makes it clear that he has
profound reservations about subjecting himself and his family to
the type of intense personal scrutiny running for a modern-day
presidency requires _ not that he, unlike some high-ranking
officials we can name, really has anything to hide.
</P>
<P>
   The once and perhaps future politician remains a private citizen
for the time being, and now he comes before us wearing a different
hat. Bill Bradley, Princeton '65, Olympic gold medal winner, Rhodes
scholar, possessor of two NBA championship rings (1970, 1973), and
1982 Hall of Fame inductee, has written a love letter to basketball
titled, ``Values of the Game,'' (Artisan Press, New York City), and
it is every bit as prescient, thoughtful, and just plain valuable a
work as you'd expect from a man who never approaches any task
without a full commitment.
</P>
<P>
   There is irony in the timing. The book comes out while NBA
owners and players squabble over how to whack up billions (plural)
of dollars in revenue, even as the game in question is sadly
deteriorating on an annual basis. Once that inane dispute is
settled, both sides will be left facing the brutal reality that
their game stinks, at least in comparison to what it could, and
should be. The plain truth is that neither the generic modern
player nor the generic modern owner will read ``Values of the
Game'' and understand what Bradley is getting so worked up about.
</P>
<P>
   The chapter titles alone indicate how gloriously utopian
Bradley's basketball vision is: ``Passion,'' ``Discipline,''
``Selflessness,'' ``Respect,'' ``Perspective,'' ``Courage,''
``Leadership,'' ``Responsibility,'' ``Resilience,'' and
``Imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   His first thought was to link the basketball to the politics and
then to real life. ``Then I realized I didn't need the politics,''
he explains. ``The basketball stood on its own.''
</P>
<P>
   A Bill Bradley book is a Bill Bradley book. There is no ``as
told to.'' During his final season with the Knicks, he wrote,
``Life on the Run,'' which ranks with Jim Brosnan's ``The Long
Season,'' and Ken Dryden's ``The Game'' as the best inside-out
examinations we've ever been given of what team dynamics are all
about and what it (itals)really(unitals) means to be a professional
athlete. That was 22 years ago, and who among us is the same as he
was 22 years ago?
</P>
<P>
   ``Writing this was great fun for me,'' Bradley says. ``I'm 22
years older. There are things in this book I couldn't have
understood 22 years ago. I could have written about discipline and
selflessness, but I could not have properly addressed resilience,
inspiration, perspective, and passion. This book reawakened some
things in me that had been dormant for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   As a freshman senator, Bradley felt it was vital to distance
himself from his basketball past. Fully cognizant that his great
name recognition made it possible for him to get elected to such a
high office at a very young political age, he likewise realized
that, once in office, knowing how to come off a screen wasn't going
to be of much value in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't initiate any basketball conversations for at least
two or three years,'' he reveals. ``I don't think I was defensive
about it, but I wasn't going to trade on it. After four or five
years, I reverted to my natural instincts.''
</P>
<P>
   His most recent connection to the game took place during the
last two years, during his residency as Stanford's visiting ``Payne
Professor.'' He renewed an old affinity for the college game,
becoming a friend and unofficial adviser to both the men's and
women's teams. He says that two of the men's players _ sharpshooter
Ryan Mendez and banging forward Pete Sauer _ ``remind me a little
bit of me'' and he maintains that All-American Katy Starbird ``is
the closest thing to John Havlicek I've ever seen, right down to
the upright run.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Values of the Game'' is a spectacularly illustrated book, and
any questions about where the Boston Celtics as an institution fit
in the Bradley scheme of things can be answered by enumerating the
number of photos in which a Celtic, or the Celtics, are placed in a
favorable light (14). Of course, we are now talking about the
Celtics that were, not the ones that are, and it is entirely in
keeping with Mr. Bradley's gentlemanly demeanor that he allows the
reader to make this deduction.
</P>
<P>
   At age 55, Bradley is very much at peace with himself. He has
been an athlete, he has been a public servant, and he has been a
private citizen. He is not remotely conflicted. If he ever does
wind up living at 1600 Pennsylvania Avenue, it will be as
athlete-husband-father-Hall of
Famer-politician-negotiator-diplomat-fan-normal human being. He
will not find it necessary to apologize for having been a jock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am comfortable with the duality of my life,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Read ``Time Present, Time Past'' to see if you like what the
senator has to say. Read ``Values of the Game'' to see if you like
what the Hall of Famer has to say.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
