<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTING THE SPOONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So the Republican Party is going to try pragmatism. Get ready
for plenty more tears. The party surely will find a way to
recapture its soul, but first its next generation of leaders is
going to have to run off a generation of nuts and hustlers who
attempted to hijack it.
</P>
<P>
   While they are at it, party leaders might take a lesson from
Masssachusetts, where the GOP just sold a governor and a lieutenant
governor to the electorate in an overwhelmingly Democratic state.
They would have had three of the four top statewide offices if
Treasurer Joe Malone hadn't decided to challenge the victorious
Paul Cellucci to a primary battle. To what should we ascribe the
local GOP's success?
</P>
<P>
   The taste for divided government is only part of the answer.
Like any competitor, a political party must differentiate its
product. Republicans historically have positioned themselves as
being more market-oriented, more vigilant, and, well, more
(itals)disinterested(unitals) than the Democrats _ the party of
good housekeeping vs. the party of social progress. With
Republicans, you're not supposed to have to count the spoons (so
often).
</P>
<P>
   Bill Weld was himself an exemplar of this sort of honest,
competent Republican, and his administration had more than its
share of others. They were successes and failures, long-tenured and
short: administration and finance secretaries Peter Nesson, Mark
Robinson, Charles Baker, economic development Secretary Dan
Gregory, to name only some of the most prominent.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Weld himself, though, you couldn't find a better
example than Mitchell Adams, who announced last week he would step
down after eight years as commissioner of revenue. He is joining a
firm, Healthwatch Technologies, that scouts Medicare payments for
fraud and abuse.
</P>
<P>
   No agency of state government is more tender than the Department
of Revenue. It has awesome power to know the income and wealth of
every citizen of the Commonwealth, to rule on the metaphysical
distinctions of the tax laws, and to demand compliance to its
interpretations. Like any police force, the DOR attracts its share
of zealots, trimmers, and would-be crooks. Michael Dukakis had Ira
Jackson, but twice in the previous 20 years, major housecleanings
had been required.
</P>
<P>
   So how did it do under Adams? ``Excellent,'' says Harold
Hestnes, a senior tax attorney at Hale and Dorr. There was no
breath of scandal during his eight years. His senior deputy,
Frederick Laskey, has advanced to become secretary of
administration and finance. And in terms of operations, ``which is
what he concentrated on, it probably became the model for the
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, the work force declined steadily through attrition
under Adams, _ from nearly 2,000 persons in 1992 to fewer than
1,500 today. Meanwhile, revenues soared 50 percent thanks to
economic growth, and so did assessments and collections of
delinquent taxes. Meanwhile, staffers pushed aggressively into new
technologies: telephone filing, electronic funds transfer, and
imaging. Revenue productivity more than doubled to $9.5 million per
employee this year.
</P>
<P>
   What about the politics underneath? That's another matter.
Massachusetts gained a black eye nationally in 1996, when a survey
of top tax accountants and large corporations by CFO magazine rated
the state 49th among the states in terms of fair and predictable
tax administration, ahead of only Louisiana. The next year it
dropped to last.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Outdated legislative check-reins account for most of the
turmoil, says Adams. Massachusetts is the only state in the nation
where tax officials lack the authority to settle bills without the
attorney general's review, and corporations must pay their tax
bills upfront before appealing them. A certain aggressive culture
of enforcement is part of the problem as well, as the Globe's Brian
Mooney documented in an investigation last year.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Adams repeatedly lobbied the Legislature to change
the law. And he hired a leading maven of corporate law, Donald
Evans, as first deputy commissioner and general counsel, to develop
a more global view. Did he succeed in changing the culture? Only
time will tell. But there were at least as many spoons in the
drawer as when he came.
</P>
<P>
   Weld chose Adams because he knew and trusted him; they had been
friends since Harvard College. Adams in turn was willing to put his
reputation on the line. It helped in his job that Adams went home
at night to his partner of 18 years, Kevin Smith. Mitchell Adams
was not a Republican _ ``hell, I raised money for McGovern.'' He
simply worked and lived like one.
</P>
<P>
   And no appointment that Paul Cellucci makes will signal more
about his administration than the choice he makes to replace Adams
at the Department of Revenue.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh writes about economics for the Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)nws.globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
