</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS COACH HAS FEW OPTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The call is out now. From Portland to
Providence, the good people of New England sound like George III.
They are calling for the heads of the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   They want Willie Clay out. They want Bruce Armstrong and Max
Lane and Todd Rucci and Zefross Moss out. They want Chris Canty
out. They want a dozen guys out of the tub and onto the club.
</P>
<P>
   As the new millennium and the Buffalo Bills both approach, the
people of New England want only one thing of their Patriots today.
They want them to go to war or go to hell. But is a troop change
before battle the answer to the problems that have beset and
bedeviled these Patriots?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but more to the point is this: Does General Pete
Carroll have enough troops to effect such changes?
</P>
<P>
   The answer to the first question is that reinforcements
certainly would help, but the answer to the latter negates that
because the answer to the latter question is simpler.
</P>
<P>
   The answer is that there are no reinforcements.
</P>
<P>
   For better or worse _ and lately it's been worse _ Carroll is
playing the best players he has. Sunday in Buffalo, he will replace
Canty with Steve Israel at right corner, and that may help, but
Canty is far from the only problem Carroll is facing.
</P>
<P>
   His troops have lost three of their last four battles and barely
escaped a skirmish in Indianapolis with their scalps intact. They
have not played well in a long time, and that applies to nearly
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, those troops have suffered enough casualties to keep Alan
Alda's ``MASH'' unit in reruns for five years. As of this morning,
more than a dozen Patriots are in the infirmary: Vincent Brisby
(finger), Troy Brown (ankle), Terry Glenn (hamstring), Shawn
Jefferson (ribs), Tony Carter (knee), Chad Eaton (thigh, back),
Chris Slade (knee, ankle), Brandon Mitchell (broken foot), Henry
Thomas (ankle), Willie McGinest (groin), Mark Wheeler (knee), Larry
Whigham (knee), and Todd Collins (groin), to be exact.
</P>
<P>
   There was once a coach here who said, ``In football season,
football players play football.'' This was the same coach whose
injury reports were always shorter than a haiku. But he is gone,
and the infirmary is full again, just as it used to be when the
Patriots regularly went 6-10.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Carroll either has been unlucky in this matter or
needs to have the whirlpool drained, but either way nothing he said
Monday indicated that much is likely to change on the medical
front.
</P>
<P>
   ``The list is long,'' Carroll said. ``I haven't got a whole lot
of good reports.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll met with his band of weary warriors the morning after
Sunday's 41-10 rout because, he said, ``Today was a day to
challenge our players individually.'' He went on to say, ``That
challenge has been issued.''
</P>
<P>
   One hopes that didn't mean the announcement of a Scrabble
challenge Wednesday night after practice, followed by ice cream and
cake, but whatever it means, it isn't likely to mean that many
heads will roll, because other than Israel for Canty, what is
Carroll supposed to do?
</P>
<P>
   Replace Bruce Armstrong with Ed Ellis? Not if he wants Drew
Bledsoe to stay off the injured list.
</P>
<P>
   Replace Max Lane with Damon Denson or Todd Rucci with Heath
Irwin or Zefross Moss with Scott Rehberg? Not unless he wants to
replace Robert Edwards with Sedrick Shaw _ permanently.
</P>
<P>
   Replace Willie Clay with Chris Carter or the long absent Tebucky
Jones? Not unless he wants to bet the over this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   So what is Gen. Carroll to do when he challenges his troops?
What can he really say? With what can he threaten them? No more
Dairy Queen after practice?
</P>
<P>
   There is, frankly, little he can do but hope his troops have
pride enough to fight harder and heart enough for the lame and
infirm to take their cue from Jefferson, Slade, Thomas, and Eaton,
who are all playing with injuries that would have the common man on
disability for a month.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, he can do nothing. It is too late for the general
or his lieutenants to rally the troops. The troops have to rally
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest pitfall we can get into as players is to say,
`It's not our fault,''' said Bledsoe. ``We're being prepared. It
falls on us to go execute.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we fall into that trap (of blaming the coaches), it
snowballs because the minute you shift that blame you have an
excuse to let yourself off the hook. If you do that, you won't do
what you have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   What the troops have to do is obvious. They have to do their
jobs, earn their money, and fight back even if their groin aches or
their hamstring is tighter than a violin string.
</P>
<P>
   They have to fight back, because there are no reinforcements
coming to bail them out. Either they fight now with what they have
or they end up like Custer's troops. And, as Carroll knows all too
well, Custer's troops weren't the only ones who went down at Little
Big Horn.
</P>
<P>
   The troops took the general with them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
