<HEADLINE>
FIORENTINA PAYS PRICE FOR FAN INTERFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Florence's soccer fans had a bittersweet Sunday. Fiorentina
regained first place in Italy's Serie A with a 4-1 victory over
Venezia, but a disciplinary committee ruling eliminated the club
from the UEFA Cup competition.
</P>
<P>
   Fiorentina appeared to be on the way to the Round of 16 after
defeating Grasshoppers, 2-0, in Zurich and taking a 2-0 halftime
lead in the second leg, which was being played in Salerno. But a
fan tossed an explosive device _ called a ``bomba di Maradona''
after the former Napoli star _ which injured an official.
</P>
<P>
   The match was abandoned, and the committee ruled Fiorentina the
loser, 3-0, reasoning that the home team was responsible for the
behavior of its fans at the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But the fans who caused problems were supporters of neither
competitor. In fact, they were suspected ``tifosi Salernitani'' who
had declared themselves enemies of Fiorentina because of the
Florentines' relations with a Salernitana rival. The ``bomb''
apparently was meant for Fiorentina players, a mitigating factor
that led the committee not to further penalize the team.
</P>
<P>
   Almost lost in the Machiavellian manifestation of city state
clashes and intrigue is the fact that the match was being played in
Salerno to provide aid to flood victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would choose Lo Stadio Arechi again,'' Fiorentina president
Vittorio Cecchi Gori said. ``Certainly, the act of one person
cannot place a black mark on a region so rich and beautiful. It was
an isolated act by someone crazy that does not have anything to do
with sport.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Opponents needed
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bruce Arena's  &LR; US national team debut was conducted in a
low-profile setting, before 15,074 spectators at Spartan Stadium in
San Jose Friday night. There was no television coverage of the 0-0
draw with Australia, though the match will be shown today by ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Arena has won only once in his last four games, including losses
to Columbus in the MLS playoffs and Chicago in the MLS Cup final
with D.C. United. He will juggle his duties by guiding D.C. United
against Vasco da Gama of Brazil in the InterAmericana Cup at RFK
Stadium Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But with the likely postponing of the Confederations Cup,
scheduled Jan. 8-20 in Guadalajara and Mexico City, Arena and the
US could be scrambling for games. Mexico has proposed delaying the
tournament until August, since France was withdrawn, to avoid
conflicting with European club schedules.
</P>
<P>
   Likely foes for the US in coming months could be Belgium and
Holland, who are exempt from qualifying as co-hosts of the Euro
2000 Championships.
</P>
<P>
   US Soccer Federation officials also could consider the example
of clubs in the Spanish Liga, which have collected millions of
pesetas from gate receipts for victims of Hurricane Mitch, and
Peru, which will send its national team to San Salvador for a Nov.
27 friendly at Estadio Cuscatlan.
</P>
<P>
   A tournament involving Central American nations would go far in
promoting the national team image. Or the MLS could organize a
tournament involving Central American clubs. This would keep MLS
teams active and encourage interaction between the league and
Central America.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution's leading scorer,  &UR; Raul Diaz Arce &LR; , &UR;  &LR; has returned
to El Salvador and likely will play for the national team against
Peru.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Valuable properties
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boca Juniors president  &UR; Mauricio Macri  &LR; has said he will not
transfer  &UR; Guillermo Barros Schelotto  &LR; or  &UR; Martin Palermo &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who
have been attracting attention from Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But Macri likely will be unable to prevent Palermo from
departing, since the striker's pass has been valued at $25 million
_ a rec-ord for an Argentine player.
</P>
<P>
   Palermo, who was purchased from Estudiantes de La Plata for $4
million, has scored 34 goals in 45 games for Boca Juniors. He leads
Argentina's Primera Division with 14 goals, two off the record set
by  &UR; Roberto Sosa  &LR; of Gimnasia y Esgrima de La Plata before
departing for Udinese in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa converted a last-minute goal for Udinese in a 2-2 tie with
Juventus Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Salas doubles up
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's Chilean striker,  &UR; Marcelo Salas &LR; , &UR;  &LR; has decided not to be
governed by his principles regarding citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   Salas was praised during the World Cup for having refused to
apply for Spanish citizenship because he considered himself a
Mapuche Indian, a group that had been victimized by the
Conquistadores.
</P>
<P>
   But Salas has now adopted a pragmatic policy. He plans to obtain
a double passport, canceling his foreign status in European Union
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a problem for me, as I am not renouncing my Chilean
nationality,'' Salas said. ``If having a double passport, Italian
or Spanish, helps me and Lazio, I will not object. And why would I
renounce Spanish citizenship? For historical reasons? Certain
things even now are passing. And should we say that a Spaniard
should be treated badly in Chile, because many centuries ago
certain things happened? No, it doesn't really seem right to think
like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Salas, who was transferred for $21.5 million to Lazio this year,
certainly has made an impression on coach  &UR; Sven Goran Eriksson &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   ``I compare him to  &UR; Gerd Muller &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the great German striker of
the '70s,'' Eriksson said. ``But Salas is technically and
tactically more complete.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The pain in Spain
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Real Betis's problems continue in Spain. Betis is
third from the bottom of the Liga after losing, 1-0, to Espanyol.
Betis president  &UR; Ruiz de Lopera  &LR; invested more than $65 million
into players, including $35 million for Brazilian midfielder
 &UR; Denilson  &LR; and nearly $20 million for  &UR; Benjamin &LR; , &UR;  &LR; making him the
most expensive Spanish player ever.
</P>
<P>
   But Betis struggled this season, winning only once under its
first three coaches, two of which were fired.  &UR; Vicente Cantatore
 &LR; resigned after starting the season with a 1-4-1 record.  &UR; Javier
Clemente &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the national team coach in the 1994 and '98 World Cup
finals, changed the Seville club's alignment, placing Denilson
behind lone striker  &UR; Oli &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and won in his debut before falling to
Espanyol.
</P>
<P>
   Mallorca leads the league by a point over Real Madrid. Mallorca
took a 1-0 victory over Villareal; Real Madrid tied, 1-1, at
Alaves; and Barcelona squandered  &UR; Rivaldo's  &LR; 35th-minute goal,
surrendering the equalizer to  &UR; Fabio Pinto  &LR; in the 87th minute and
the deciding goal to  &UR; Petar Dubovski  &LR; in the 93d.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Purse of the Bambino
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since 1938, Bolivia has had 15 national team coaches, all
foreigners. The latest is  &UR; Hector  &LR; `` &UR; Bambino &LR; ''  &UR; Veira &LR; , &UR;  &LR; 52, who
coached River Plate, San Lorenzo, and Boca Juniors in Argentina.
Veira's contract is worth about $500,000 annually for four years,
and if Bolivia qualifies for the 2002 World Cup, he could obtain a
bonus of $1 million. These are incredible numbers for one of the
hemisphere's poorest nations ... The MLS does not appear interested
in pursuing many African players, which could be a mistake, judging
by the success of  &UR; Sean Bartlett &LR; . In the MLS's first season,
former Colorado Rapids coach  &UR; Bob Houghton  &LR; recruited Bartlett from
the African Nations Cup tournament in South Africa. The MLS
profited by selling Bartlett for $1 million to FC Zurich, the
highest price the Swiss club ever has paid for a player. Bartlett
leads the UEFA Cup in scoring with six goals, going into a Nov. 24
visit to AS Roma ... While the NBA's Celtics remain locked out, the
original Celtic is going strong. Celtic overcame Glasgow rival
Rangers' nine-year hold on the Scottish Premier League championship
last year. After a slow start this season, Celtic appears
rejuvenated after taking a 6-1 victory over Dundee FC. Dutchman
 &UR; Wim Jansen  &LR; guided Celtic to the title last season, then resigned.
General manager  &UR; Jock Brown  &LR; eventually hired a replacement, the
Slovakian Dr.  &UR; Jozsef Venglos &LR; , &UR;  &LR; but Celtic struggled in Scotland
and was eliminated from both the Champions League and UEFA Cup.
Brown resigned after Celtic fell to FC Zurich. Now, Canadian
 &UR; Fergus McCann &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the club chairman who helped launch Celtic into
the modern world of finance and television, also plans to leave.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
