<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2994 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-SKI-NENGLAND-B     11-10 1380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SKI-NENGLAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NEW ENGLAND, THE CHOICE IS YOURS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite the widespread shifting of corporate plates beneath the
surface of Planet Ski in recent years, three truths ever shine: No
grouping of properties in a corporate portfolio stamp stamps any
ski area with an imprimatur of the parent company _ personalities
are just too different _ nor could skiers care less who owns the
snow on which they are sliding.
</P>
<P>
   Also, despite the fact that American Skiing Co., Intrawest, and
Booth Creek hold most of the major cards in New England, there are
plenty of quality independent areas, some of which have formed
marketing alliances.
</P>
<P>
   In the neighborhood of Mount Snow, not far from Killington, and
close enough to be a competitor of Sugarbush, for example, Okemo is
now a long-running success story. Despite all the ballyhoo about
tough terrain, the truth about skiers is that blue cruising is by
far the most popular dish on the menu, and that's what Okemo
serves.
</P>
<P>
   Overlooked until the '80s as a sleeping giant, Okemo has built
its popularity on maximizing all that blueness with superb grooming
and lifts, and with a strong family ambience that most skiers like.
This year, the mountain has added 60 slopeside condos that will
enhance the village atmosphere. As Okemo has grown in popularity,
the town of Ludlow has also become a pleasant ski town with some
night life and good restaurants that cover the range form
cheeseburgers to gourmet.
</P>
<P>
   An extreme opposite yet thrives up the road in Vermont where Mad
River Glen still sports the most recognizable bumper sticker in ski
country: ``Mad River Glen _ Ski It If You Can'' _ though you still
find the odd VW bus that rattles up the valley with a message
against short skis emblazoned on its rusty bumper.
</P>
<P>
   Mad River knows how to turn a vice (hardly any snowmaking or
grooming) and turn it to a virtue of minimalism. Redolent of the
good old days before machinery got in the way of skiing, devotees
of this area even sing the praises of an ancient single chair on
grounds that it keeps skier density low on the terrain above that
it serves.
</P>
<P>
   And the terrain is superb at Mad River Glen, though don't come
here looking for bluecruisy skiing. That dish is not on the menu
here, nor is there much for beginners, even low intermediates
looking to put notches on their belts.
</P>
<P>
   And snowboarders? Don't even show up in shredder clothes. Boards
haven't been allowed here since owner Betsy Pratt kicked them off
in 1991. When she sold the area to a cooperative of shareholders
four years later, the ban went with the deed, and is not about to
be relaxed anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Sensitive terrain? Non-accommodating lifts? Snow too fragile and
too light for boards? These are some theories advanced about the
area's position, but more likely is the ambient old-timer snobbery.
Those who love this area _ and they are legion _ like it just the
way it is.
</P>
<P>
   Across the valley, Sugarbush may be Mad River's alter ego, but
you can still sit at the Blue Tooth bar quaffing brewskies while
the Allman Brothers bang out country blues, the whole scene
reminding boomers of skiing in their college years.
</P>
<P>
   But make no mistake about Sugarbush. With some of the finest
terrain in New England _ and a good variety _ this area is
seriously on the move. At one time the snowmaking was so bad it was
a rare year that its expert piece de resistance _ Castle Rock _
could open for more than a few weeks in the year.
</P>
<P>
   But what a difference 20 million little dollars make! New
snowmaking and lifts, much arising from Les Otten's hard-fought
battles with Vermont's rabid no-growthers, have transformed
Sugarbush into a thoroughly modern ski area, and with plenty of
room to develop. This, of course, strikes locals and devotees as a
mixed message. But this area once touted in the Stein Erikson era
as ``Zurmat of New England,'' will continue to develop and grow as
a rival to its own corporate cousins in the Green Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, two old rivals in the White Mountain National
Forest _ Loon and Waterville Valley, now under the corporate
blanket of George Gillett's Booth Creek _ are still, well, old
rivals. At about two hours up Route 95, they share the claimed
distinction of being the closest serious skiing to Boston, and
indeed, Boston is largely who skis at both.
</P>
<P>
   Loon, which suffers from bottlenecks of the 13,000 who hit the
town every weekend, badly needs the permit to install a new quad
that would connect a newly cut trial system between the mountain
and downtown Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   Loon's skiing is buffed and varied, though without any really
hairball trails to rubberize your knees. Still, the blue cruisers
are groomed for smooth rides that reflect the area's recent
committment to new snow production system. With Lincoln at its
base, Loon has plenty of apres ski life and a few excellent
restaurants. After skiing some clear day, drive a few miles up New
England's most spectacular highway, the Kancamagus. Take your
camera.
</P>
<P>
   An exit before Lincoln, but with a six-mile access off
Interstate 93, Waterville Valley has started to pour on the
snowmaking, bringing it into the modern ski world by providing some
of that buff stuff. Also, Waterville may be the only area in
history to have improved itself by shortening a major lift _ its
high-speed summit quad, which used to pick up a useless and
annoying 300 yards to the very top. About all this did is give you
such a blast of cold wind as to put you in mind of the spectacular
mountaintop restaurant, the Shcwindi Hut a short ski away with its
wonderful hot homemade food.
</P>
<P>
   Those who love Waterville for its cranky old New England trails
with their bumps, and multiple fall lines _ just like Tom Corcoran
designed them _ find little change under the new George Gillett
ownership. Waterville still boasts a couple of leg burners _ Ciaou
and Gemma _ on the south side, and some of the best novice terrain
anywhere. The blue terrain is also terrific.
</P>
<P>
   Though the village is a shuttle ride away, there is a nice sense
of community, apres ski, and alternative activities such as
cross-country skiing, in-town ice skating, sleigh rides, and the
like. The inns around the valley _ all served by shuttle to the
slopes _ range from fair to great.
</P>
<P>
   Across the forest rising across Pinkham Notch from Mount
Washington is another of those areas, Wildcat, that dates to the
early days of New England skiing and has as loyal a following as a
ski area is fortunate to have. There just seems some aura about the
place that makes aficionados want to brand themselves ``Wildcat
Skiers.''
</P>
<P>
   No, it's no Mad River in terms of spartan challenge, nor is it
even remarkably tough to ski. But Wildcat's terrain is varied with
some nice old-style narrow twisters mixed in with those that have
been retrofit over the years into broader straighter runs. Wildcat
Trial itself is a terrific blue trail that must be skied with
focus.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from a dozen solid runs top to bottom, Wildcat's proximity
to Mount Washington gives it the most beautiful views in New
England, occasionally hellacious winds and weather, but just as
often blankets of new snow that no one else ever saw.
</P>
<P>
   Maine's two fiercest rivals, Sugarloaf and Sunday River, also
both fit underneath the ASC roof, and continue to expand and
refine, Sunday River holding onto the number two spot for
popularity in New England behind Killington.
</P>
<P>
   But one local area, Shawnee Peak in Bridgeton, a suburb of
Portland, is also on the move. Built in 1938, this area's skiing
may not be in the White Heat or Snowfields league, but Shawnee Peak
delivers some first-rate snow and grooming, and still has a feel of
old New England to the cut of many of its trails.
</P>
<P>
   Many years ago, Sunday River began tapping into the beehive of
North Conway, but this year Shawnee, about a half-hour away on
Route 302, goes one better than merely advertising. Several free
shuttle trips daily conect Shawnee with North Conway, which is a
fair rival for Cranmore and Black. Shawnee has also added an inn to
its base area, expanding the apres-ski choices, which was not too
hard, after all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
