<HEADLINE>
BEANIE BABIES ARE HITTING THE SLOPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   And there go the Beanie Babies in their bobsleds! This riotous
race is just one way youngsters learn while having fun at the new
Winter Science Program at Smugglers' Notch, Vt. The program, part
of the ski and snowboard all-day camps held from Dec. 4 through
April 11, aims to give age-appropriate lessons about weather, snow,
equipment technology, and physics. (But whatever you do, don't tell
the youngsters they'll learn something _ kids just want to have
fun.) Some of the events:
</P>
<P>
   _The Beanie Baby Bobsled Races. Children design and make
bobsleds for these oh-so-popular dolls to ride and race. That
teaches youngsters a bit about gravity and motion.
</P>
<P>
   _The Big Air Dummy Contest. Children get a similar lesson when
they make a dummy and send him or her downhill on skis or a
snowboard.
</P>
<P>
   _Snowflake Catch &AMP; Keep. Snowflakes are captured on black felt.
The kids then memorize their favorite flake (no, not Uncle Harry)
and re-create it by cutting the pattern on paper.
</P>
<P>
   And what a grand science classroom: The woods, mountains, ski
slopes, room are all part of it, as are the pumphouse, the
snowmaking center computer, snowguns, hoses, and snowcats. Learning
scenarios are set up for ages 3-17. For more information and a free
video, call 800-451-8752 or visit www.smuggs.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Travel Trivia:  &LR; Which of the following places are (or is) in
Switzerland: Chamonix, Lausanne, Garmisch, or all three? (Answer at
end of column.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Skiing the Web:  &LR; The new Winter Center at
www.accuweather.com. &UR;  &LR; contains forecasts for and information about
hundreds of ski resorts across the United States. There are
long-range snow and ice forecasts, and as reports from each resort
become available, the site will present snow depth and slope
conditions, hours of operation, and the number of trails and lifts
available.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; In a name: &LR;  The Vail area was once known as Gore Creek Valley.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; McSki: &LR;  The first ski-through McDonald's has opened on the slopes
in Lindvallen, Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Freebie:  &LR; The Berkshires of Western Massachusetts are lovely in
winter. And there's lots to do, with six downhill ski areas, eight
cross-country ski areas, museums, inns, restaurants, and shopping
galore. For the ``Official Guide to the Berkshires'' with
information on activities plus a calendar of events, a map, and
cultural brochure, call 800-237-5747. You can visit the Berkshire
Visitors Bureau Web site at www.berkshires.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Did you guess it? &LR;  Travel Trivia answer: Lausanne is in
Switzerland. (Chamonix is in France and Garmisch is in Germany).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
