<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TYNER-MUSIC-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER JAZZ REBEL SHOWS MELLOW SIDE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICK MITCHELL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ It's an old story, in art as well as in politics: The
fiery young radical matures into a proud keeper of the traditional
flame.
</P>
<P>
   That would certainly seem to be the case with pianist McCoy
Tyner, who performed a jazz concert Friday night in the Cullen
Theater at Wortham Center in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   There's no question that Tyner has mellowed considerably since
his percussive, keyboard-pummeling days with John Coltrane's
mind-expanding quartet of the early '60s. His virtuosic range now
encompasses the entire jazz piano repertoire, from easy-swinging
blues and vintage stride to delicate ballads.
</P>
<P>
   Tyner also has suffered of late from occasional lapses of taste.
His current album is an ill-fitting salute to the pop songs of Burt
Bacharach, complete with saccharine string arrangements that clash
with the intense improvisations that have been the hallmark of his
style.
</P>
<P>
   But it's too simple to say that Tyner has undergone a complete
pendulum swing, from bomb-tossing revolutionary to
spirit-constricted reactionary.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, he was always the relative traditionalist within
Coltrane's group. When the latter's music pushed beyond the final
frontiers of conventional harmonic structure, Tyner departed.
</P>
<P>
   For another thing, he remains quite capable of unleashing a
torrential, soul-cleansing shower of notes when the inspiration
strikes, as it inevitably will.
</P>
<P>
   Tyner's solo appearance _ his first Houston visit in seven years
_ was dubbed a ``Soliloquy,'' after the title of one of his early
'90s albums. And indeed, it appeared at times as if Tyner was
carrying on a conversation with himself at the piano, in dramatic
fashion. The program opened with a toe-tapping, stride-right
reading of the standard ``How Deep Is the Ocean,'' followed by the
ballad ``For All We Know.'' ``The Greeting,'' a Tyner original,
displayed the dense note-clusters and knuckle-busting runs that
have made him one of the most influential pianists of the past 30
years, while ``You Taught My Heart'' to Sing poured forth sheer
lyricism.
</P>
<P>
   The Cullen Theater's pristine acoustics, which have in the past
presented problems of balance for larger jazz groups, splendidly
revealed the tonal contrast between Tyner's powerful left-hand
rhythms and dazzling right-hand filigrees.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half of the program, Tyner dispensed with the
gracious introductions to get down to serious business at the
keyboard. The only title he announced was ``Miss B,'' written for
his mother, which shifted from a lullabylike melody into a rolling
gospel rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   As with fellow jazz piano legends Art Tatum and Oscar Peterson,
Tyner's technique has become so prodigious that it at times
threatens to overshadow the deep feeling in his playing. To put it
bluntly, this never happened when he was with Coltrane or in the
early years of his solo career.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, would we really want him to still be playing
bombastic, 40-minute modal vamps when he can make just as much if
not more musical sense with a four-minute blues variation? Tyner's
thoroughly personalized approach to the vintage stride style makes
young neo-traditionalists such as Marcus Roberts sound like
schoolkids by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   The encore was, fittingly, Coltrane's ``Giant Steps.'' Jazz has
been widely criticized in the last two decades for turning away
from the relentless evolutionary process of the 1920s through the
'70s in favor of formalistic retrenchment. Some have gone so far as
to proclaim the music creatively moribund, best relegated to the
historical realm alongside all those dead European composers.
</P>
<P>
   But as long as true giants such as Tyner are still alive and
stepping, the flame will continue to burn. Not as wild and free as
it once did, perhaps, but with no less integrity and clarity of
vision. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
