<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SELECTIVE-MUTISM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDREN WHO ARE SILENT IN SCHOOL AREN'T ALONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Sandra Williams has a bright and talented
10-year-old daughter. The only problem is she won't talk in school
_ not to teachers or friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``The common reaction is, `What's wrong with that kid?''' said
Williams, who lives in the Albany suburb of Colonie.
</P>
<P>
   The answer is a rare and little understood behavioral disorder
known as selective mutism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a form of social anxiety,'' said R. Lindsey Bergman, a
researcher from the Division of Child and Adolescent Psychiatry at
the University of California at Los Angeles. ``It's kids who are
extremely, extremely shy.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of us don't like speaking in public. But this condition
goes beyond butterflies in the stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Hugh Johnston, a psychiatrist at the University of
Wisconsin, likens it to being asked to stand up before a strange
crowd and sing the national anthem.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us likes to come under the scrutiny of others,'' he
said. ``These kids have this very normal phenomena but they have
too much of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams didn't realize her daughter, Samantha, had a problem
until she started getting phone calls from teachers telling her
that Samantha wasn't talking. Initially, she thought it was normal
anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our daughter did speak in day care and minimally in
kindergarten,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Samantha speaks perfectly at home, but at school, she writes
notes to friends, who often speak on her behalf. That's the typical
pattern for children with selective mutism, Johnston said. By
definition, they are silent at school and verbal at home, where
they feel comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   It is uncertain how many children are affected by selective
mutism or what causes it. Researchers believe there may be a
genetic link, passed on by shy or phobic parents. In many cases,
there's no explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically nobody has heard of this and everybody thinks
there's something terrible wrong with the child,'' Bergman said.
</P>
<P>
   Some children are misdiagnosed with autism or their parents are
put under scrutiny for abuse. In other cases, well-meaning teachers
and therapists can cause more harm by singling out the children,
humiliating them, or pressuring them.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the problem gets more complicated with time, as the
children develop a reputation in school for not talking. That makes
them even more reluctant to speak because they know everybody will
be listening.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, there's no quick fix.
</P>
<P>
   ``What works for one kid won't necessarily work for another,''
Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Treatment varies, from therapy to medication, to a combination
of both.
</P>
<P>
   Studies have shown that children treated with a class of
anti-anxiety drugs, including Prozac, Luvox and Zoloft, often show
the fastest improvement. The theory is the medications help
diminish the child's fear of speaking.
</P>
<P>
   Other children grow out of the condition, usually at puberty.
``They realize at some point that not talking draws more scrutiny
than talking a little bit,'' Johnston said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who was shy herself as a child, no longer dwells on
why her daughter developed selective mutism. Instead, she's
focusing her efforts on starting a selective mutism support group
in the Albany area so parents can share information and overcome
the isolation that comes with disorder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe Samantha is the only child who suffers from
this,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, she's grateful her daughter, now a
fifth-grader, is making some progress after 18 months of medication
and therapy. Though Samantha still won't speak in school, she will
talk to friends on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a baby step, but at least it's a start,'' Williams said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
