<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMERON-FILM-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TITANIC' DIRECTOR SAILS ON WITH PROJECTS THAT MAY INCLUDE `APES'
REDO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  EDITORS: Photo of James Cameron available on New York Times photo
service. 
 
By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ When James Cameron made his first visit to Houston
last week, he came as conquering hero: as director of Hollywood's
top money-maker, ``Titanic,'' and as self-proclaimed ``king of the
world'' when it cleaned up on Oscar night.
</P>
<P>
   But Cameron didn't come here as a director. He came here as an
actor _ and a humble one at that.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron did his acting as part of TheatreVision, a new process
that enables blind persons to hear audio descriptions of films via
wireless earpieces as they're shown in theaters.
</P>
<P>
   For ``Titanic,'' Cameron split reading duties with actress Angie
Dickinson, recording his lines in a Los Angeles studio.
</P>
<P>
   He became the first director to read for his own film in the 4
{-year history of TheatreVision, which ventured beyond Los Angeles
for the first time with last week's Houston screening of
``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting and challenging,'' Cameron said before
screening his acting debut. (Well, he did appear briefly in
``Titanic's'' steerage dance scene and played himself once on ``Mad
About You.'')
</P>
<P>
   But Cameron, 44, thrives behind the camera. He has written,
directed, produced, edited and worked as a camera operator and art
director on films since he broke into the business in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   As director, he's had a nonstop string of hits: ``The
Terminator,'' ``Aliens,'' ``The Abyss,'' ``Terminator 2: Judgment
Day,'' ``True Lies'' and ``Titanic,'' winning Oscars for the last
as director, producer and editor.
</P>
<P>
   Long active in his films' video campaigns, he's unveiled added
footage for ``Aliens'' and ``The Abyss'' on laserdisc and may do
the same for ``Titanic.'' Cameron also has taped optional audio
tracks for laserdisc, offering his analyses as his movie plays.
</P>
<P>
   But his TheatreVision reading was different.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only voice work, but it's still acting, and you have to
put something into it,'' he said. ``You have to try to conjure up
the drama of the narrative.''
</P>
<P>
   Though blind people can glean much from a film's music, dialogue
and sound effects, ``a lot of the mood also comes from the way you
say the words,'' Cameron said. ``You can't just read them in a
monotone.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the script supplied by TheatreVision is written with
artistry in mind.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Titanic's'' opening scenes of a deep-sea dive, Cameron is
heard ominously saying, ``The sonar screen sketches the ocean's
terrain in bright colors. A man peers through a porthole searching
the watery darkness.''
</P>
<P>
   After the screening, he fretted that his voice sometimes
overlapped the dialogue _ which TheatreVision tries to avoid _ but
said, ``That can't be helped sometimes. It can take longer to
describe something than it takes to happen on screen.''
</P>
<P>
   His only real problem, he said self-deprecatingly, ``was that I
got tired of hearing my own boring voice drone on and on.''
</P>
<P>
   Cameron still hasn't chosen his follow-up to ``Titanic.'' He's
been linked to a possible remake of ``Planet of the Apes'' and a
lavish big-screen treatment of comics hero Spider-Man.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect the latter anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spider-Man is all tangled up,'' Cameron said, with a quip the
web-slinger's fans can appreciate.
</P>
<P>
   As for ``Apes,'' ``It's a possibility,'' he said. Yet Cameron
may just produce the film, not also direct, yielding that job (if
rumors are right) to Michael Bay of ``Armageddon.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, he's still riding high on the success of ``Titanic,''
which includes enjoying a new friendship with the cast's Gloria
Stuart, 88.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gloria's great,'' Cameron said. ``We have dinner about once a
month and just hang out. She cracks me up, and she's gotten to be
good friends with my girlfriend'' (Suzy Amis, who played Stuart's
granddaughter in the film).
</P>
<P>
   To date, ``Titanic'' has grossed more than $1.8 billion
worldwide and is selling millions of copies on video.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount hasn't set a date yet for its release on the
sophisticated and burgeoning new DVD format. Paramount officials
will only say that ``Titanic's'' DVD release is ``inevitable.''
</P>
<P>
   Cameron already is exploring that avenue anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're just scratching the surface on what you can do
with DVD, in terms of additional functions,'' Cameron said. ``But
DVD's capacity is not unlimited.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've sort of run up against a wall on `Titanic.' I want to
try to get it onto one disc. To me it kind of defeats the purpose
to have two discs'' (since the film has no intermission).
</P>
<P>
   Yet two discs may be needed for the 194-minute ``Titanic'' on
DVD, just as two tapes are needed for VHS.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron is enthusiastic, however, about DVD's option of
switching between a widescreen image and the ``pan and scan''
format normally seen on TV and video.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's one of the cool things about DVD, getting the
widescreen and pan-and-scan versions on the same disc,'' he said.
``That way, you don't have to make that decision at the point of
purchase. You can sample both later.''
</P>
<P>
   This would apply especially to ``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   Due to the nature of the film Cameron used, Super 35mm, the
picture is larger at the top and bottom for pan-and-scan than it is
for widescreen. So each format offers visual information that the
other does not.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron tries to serve both formats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even with today's widescreen consciousness on video, I'd say
less than 20 percent of people buy widescreen as a choice. And you
can't tool all your thinking for 20 percent of your audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Cameron thinks DVD also ``could very easily'' accommodate an
optional audio track for TheatreVision, enabling blind people to
enjoy such films at home, too.
</P>
<P>
   For theaters, the studios still need cooperation from movie
exhibitors, ``and that's the next big challenge,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Theater owners generally will resist something new because it
means expenses for the equipment,'' Cameron said. ``I don't know
what it would cost them, but for the studios the cost is relatively
inconsequential in the grand scheme of things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Movies are for everybody, and I would love for people who are
visually impaired or blind to enjoy my films as much as everybody
else.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
