<HEADLINE>
DESIRE, DISCIPLINE AND DRIVE: AUTHOR ANITA BUNKLEY LAYS OUT THE
GROUND RULES FOR SUCCESS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  EDITORS: Photo moving on the New York Times photo service. 
 
By BARBARA KARKABI 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Confident and poised, Anita Bunkley sits on a white sofa in the
comfortable living room of her Alief home. With five novels and,
most recently, a nonfiction book under her belt, she is the picture
of success.
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't always been the case. Back in the 1980s, Bunkley was
a divorced single mom balancing two jobs and raising two preteen
daughters. It was not, she says, a high point in her creative life.
But hidden deep inside her was a dream _ to write historical novels
aimed at African-American women.
</P>
<P>
   One night she found herself at a party attended by a well-known
Hollywood filmmaker. Bunkley timidly told him she was a teacher,
but really wanted to write novels someday.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you waiting for?'' the director asked her. ``Call
yourself a writer. How else are you ever going to become one?''
</P>
<P>
   Bunkley took his advice and stopped putting off her dream. Her
experiences and those of other successful women who often took
risks to achieve their goals are the basis of Bunkley's latest
book, ``Steppin' Out With Attitude: Sister, Sell Your Dream!''
(HarperCollins, $12.50).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's written from my perspective as an African-American
woman,'' Bunkley said. ``But it is also multicultural, because I
talked to all kinds of women doing research. I don't think it's a
self-esteem problem so much as the fact that women are very
concerned about looking and acting appropriately. They don't want
to look pushy, aggressive or vain. But I think you can get out
there and speak, as long as you have the attitude that `I'm
grateful for my talents.' ''
</P>
<P>
   After Bunkley decided to stop dreaming and start her writing
life, she joined a writer's group and began researching a story.
Originally from Ohio, she was intrigued by the tale of the
beautiful mulatto Emily, who according to legend was the ``Yellow
Rose of Texas'' in the song of the same name. Bunkley went to the
library to look for a book about her and found there was none. So,
she decided Emily`s mysterious story would become her first book.
</P>
<P>
   Like many aspiring writers, Bunkley researched and wrote at
night and on weekends. After taking a course in self-publishing,
she eventually decided to publish ``Emily'' herself. She originally
printed 1,000 copies to see if there was any interest and then
printed another 10,000. Bunkley still has one of the first copies
tucked away on a living room bookshelf. Pulling it out, she thumbed
through it nostalgically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Publishing my own book was one of the hardest things I have
ever done,'' Bunkley said. ``I had to get in the car and drive
around with the book to all the bookstores. I had to fly places and
talk to people. I spent a lot of money, but it was worth it. I
scraped a lot and drove an old car when people were buying new
cars. But I wanted to do it, so I never grumbled.''
</P>
<P>
   It was, she emphasizes in ``Steppin' Out With Attitude,'' part
of a well-thought-out plan. Bunkley broke even and maybe made a few
thousand on ``Emily,'' but it got her name out. The next book she
started researching was ``Black Gold,'' set in 1920s Texas. Bunkley
sent the first 50 pages to a competition at the University of
Texas/Dallas and won first place. An agent saw it and suggested
Bunkley send it to her when she was finished.
</P>
<P>
   Bunkley did just that, and the agent got her a six-figure,
two-book contract with Penguin USA. That was in 1992, and Bunkley
was able to devote herself to full-time writing. Bunkley, who loves
to talk to readers at bookstores and enjoys making speeches, also
started lecturing and doing workshops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would talk to the women while selling my books, and I met a
lot of people who wanted to find out how to market books,'' Bunkley
said. ``I did a workshop called `Don't Be Shy,' because I really
think you are selling yourself when you are selling books. Books
are very personal, and I think if you know the author you are more
likely to buy the book. That has been my experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Some women also were asking her how to promote themselves or get
more visibility in their companies. Others would talk about their
dreams of opening a business. So Bunkley decided to put together a
``Steppin' Out With Attitude'' workshop that eventually led to the
book _ a collection of success stories as well as practical tips,
worksheets and a step-by-step program for achieving goals.
</P>
<P>
   In the process of gathering her material, Bunkley interviewed
125 women around the country about their experiences. She
ultimately ended up using about 52 stories _ including those of
Houston City Councilwoman Martha Wong, African-American historian
Patricia Smith Prather, Realtor Beth Wolff and fashion designer
Toni Whittaker. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get the stories of women who had a dream, and
their attitudes,'' Bunkley said. ``I wanted to know what they
thought was important to them, how they started out, what they did
when they ran into problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Bunkley's book starts with the premise that everyone has good
things going for them. She advises building on your assets and
making a list of skills _ are you organized, patient, good with
ideas? Her guide is then divided into what she calls the ``three
D's'' _ desire, discipline and drive.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with ``desire,'' she says it's important to embrace
your dream, whatever it is, then draft your personal mission
statement and find a new angle to make your product or talent stand
out.
</P>
<P>
   Then you need some ``discipline'' to make things happen. Stick
with your dream, she says. Don't create excuses to lose. Distance
yourself from negative feelings. And never burn bridges.
</P>
<P>
   The third element is ``drive.'' Don't turn and run when faced
with a problem, be mentally prepared, plan for wealth, learn the 10
commandments of networking, stay informed and embrace the applause.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting when I ask people what keeps them going.
Someone might say: `I wanted to prove to my father I could be a
city council person' or `I've been trying to write this book for 10
years, and I am going to do it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   During a recent signing at a Washington, D.C., bookstore,
Bunkley met a woman who was employed as a computer programmer but
mentioned that she was really a massage therapist. Her dream was to
open a massage center. Bunkley told her: `` `You are exactly what
I'm talking about. Give me your card. I'm on the road all the time
and always need a massage.' Sometimes I think people are afraid of
success, often because they are afraid of change.''
</P>
<P>
   Bunkley emphasizes that she doesn't want to make anything _
career changes, writing books, opening a business _ sound easy. It
takes a lot of hard work, combined with a business plan. But she
does believe dreams can be achieved, if you go about it in a
rational way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day people publish books and open businesses,'' she
said. ``It goes back to desire, discipline and drive. Do you really
want it? Think it through carefully, and don't leave your job 'til
you have a plan. It took me two years of planning and studying
before I published `Emily.' But I also found that once people know
what your dream is, they are ready to help you.''
</P>
<P>
   These days Bunkley's life is exactly the way she wants it. She's
been married to businessman Crawford Bunkley for 11 years, her
children are grown, and she is enjoying her first grandchild.
Bunkley loves being able to combine lecturing, traveling and
writing, and enjoys the variety of women and men that she meets
while selling her books. On the wall of her upstairs study are
framed letters from Dan Rather and the late Alex Haley. Behind her
desk are shelves holding copies of her six books. It's an exciting
time, she said, to be talking about books.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Steppin' Out' was my first nonfiction. I'm glad I took a
break and did it,'' she said. ``But I will probably go back to
fiction. For my next project, I would like to rework and republish
`Emily, the Yellow Rose.' That was my first book, and it's been out
of print now for four years.''
</P>
<P>
   Bunkley is, she says, very grateful for her life and gifts. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
