<HEADLINE>
IN CANADA, TREMBLANT IS TOPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone who has spent much midwinter time in Quebec's St.
Lawrence country knows the meaning of cold. It can be bitter,
especially for those who have not made with some extraordinary
preparations.
</P>
<P>
   We get that out of the way first because its proximity to the
Arctic Circle is about the worst thing one can find to say about
Tremblant, one of the top-ranked ski areas in North America.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't always that way. After its early glory days half a
century ago, Mont Tremblant (new owners have since dropped the
``Mont'') began a long slide into ordinariness.
</P>
<P>
   Those returning to the area after an absence of a few years are
struck by the transformation. When the Canadian-based Intrawest
bought the area, it poured on the investment capital for such a
thorough make-over that few recognize the old Mont Tremblant.
</P>
<P>
   The retrofit on the mountain included new trails and on-mountain
facilities, a state-of-the-art snowmaking system, and new
high-speed lifts.
</P>
<P>
   But the most astounding reformation has been the village that
has brought Tremblant back to its former status as a premier
destination resort. Seeking more than a mere instant ski theme
park, Intrawest designers created their concept of the new
Tremblant based on the European style of the old Quebec city.
</P>
<P>
   Narrow streets, multicolored and styled condos _ all quaint in a
Tyrolean sort of way _ fabulous restaurants and shops, and all the
modern facilities such as pools and health clubs lift the new
Tremblant village to a solid leap above anything else in the East.
Beneath all that village quaintness is the modern convenience of a
large underground garage servicing the hotels, condos, and
shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   Tremblant, a two-sided mountain, is varied enough so that groups
of varying ability can travel there together and find plenty of
decent terrain. On the south side, beginners start on the Flying
Mile lift and work at a number of runs just above the ken of
absolute newcomers. La Passe and Nansen, La Crete and Roy Scott are
some terrific runs for newer skiers and boarders.
</P>
<P>
   There is a rope tow and the Cabriolet lift that serves as a fine
first-timer slope where lessons are underway constantly. The best
thing about this area is how isolated it is from the main traffic
flow, alowing the new skiers freedom from hotshots whizzing past.
</P>
<P>
   From advanced beginner to solid intermediate, Tremblant is at
its best. Most skiers in this range like the broad open blue
cruisers, and that is what they get with runs like Grand Prix and
Alpine. Some of the mogul runs are gentle enough, and some of the
steep areas groomed well enough so that low-end intermediates can
cut their teeth to new alternatives to the paved boulevard approach
to terminal intermediacy.
</P>
<P>
   While the double black diamonds are rightly marked _ they are
challenging _ the single blacks offer a whole range of advanced
intermediate terrain, including an oddity, Cure Deslauriers, which
is a rhythmic, wavy descent that feels as close to a snowboard park
as anyone riding two boards is likely to get. Le Tunnel and Banzi
are good challenging advanced terrain, while other blacks fail to
live up to that rating.
</P>
<P>
   Again, the double blacks do live up to their billing. The area
called the Edge on the North side of the mountain is served by a
quad chair that has no bailout below the level of strong
intermediate skiing. Aside from one cut trail, the rest of the
skiing here is ungroomed glades, some of them dropping straight
down the fall lines in dense woods. Also on this side are some
steep bump trails like Dynamite and Expo.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Tremblant has 11 lifts _ five high-speed quads _
servicing 500 acres, all of it open to boarders as well as skiers.
For information, call 800-461-8711.
</P>
</TEXT>
