<HEADLINE>
STICK WITH STOCKS FOR THE LONG HAUL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA YIP 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I don't have to say, ``I told you so.''
</P>
<P>
   I'll let the numbers do that.
</P>
<P>
   When the stock market started its tumble in the summer, I and
investment professionals told jittery investors that they should
keep their eye on their long-term investment plan and not let daily
market gyrations cause them to vamoose from stocks. The market
would come back.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past month, it has. Stocks, as measured by the
bellwether Dow Jones industrial average, are just 3.9 percent below
their July 17 record close of 9,337.97.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow has recovered from a decline of almost 20 percent from
its July high in late August.
</P>
<P>
   After yanking their money out of stock mutual funds in October _
when the market was rallying _ investors have poured back in a big
way.
</P>
<P>
   Investors poured a net $4.51 billion into stock funds in the
week ended Wednesday, their largest inflow in four months,
according to AMG Data Services in Arcata, Calif., which tracks fund
flows. Most of the money went to growth funds and international
funds.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks of small companies, which were battered during the
market's swoon, gained an average 28.9 percent from Oct. 8 through
Nov. 5, according to Lipper Analytical Services in New York, which
tracks stock funds.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, small stocks wrapped up their best four weeks Friday in
at least 20 years, helping many money managers do what they haven't
done for five years: Beat their benchmark, the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 Index, a benchmark of small and
midcapitalization companies, surged 29 percent since Oct. 8 _ the
best four weeks for the index since it was created in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   In the same period, 75 percent of diversified equity mutual
funds outperformed the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bad timing abounds &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those who get in now missed a month when the average domestic
stock mutual fund gained an average 22.7 percent from Oct. 8
through Nov. 5, according to Lipper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Market timers are just doomed to failure,'' said Ivy McLemore,
spokesman for Aim Management Group in Houston, a mutual fund firm.
``It's kind of like juggling nitroglycerin; it's great to tell your
friends that you do it, but if you have one bad day, it hurts a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   This is how much it could hurt. If you invested $10,000 in the
Standard &AMP; Poor's index on Sept. 30, 1993, your $10,000 would have
grown to $24,785 by the end of this past September, according to
Aim. That's an average annual total return of 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But if you were out of the market during the 10 best days in
that five-year period, your return would have slid to 12.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people tend to chase recent performance, they tend to buy
in peaks and sell out at troughs, so they cost themselves money,''
said Scott Cooley, an analyst at Morningstar Mutual Funds in
Chicago, which tracks fund performance. ``It really does emphasize
the desirability of a disciplined investing plan.''
</P>
<P>
   This is called dollar cost averaging, which calls for you to
invest a fixed amount of dollars in securities at set intervals.
</P>
<P>
   That enables you to buy more shares when the price is low and
fewer shares when the price is high.
</P>
<P>
   ``Across all investment categories, the returns that investors
actually earned were lower than they would have been had they done
dollar-cost averaging, because they tend to buy hot areas and sell
them when they turn cold,'' Cooley said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Market's attitude changing &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The mindset of the market has started to change from the summer,
when gyrations in world financial markets caused investors to
shrink away from investments that had even the slightest risk and
go into safer U.S. Treasury securities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is as much uncertainty now,'' said Henry
Lartigue, chief investment officer of Chase Bank of Texas in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Your best move is to devise a disciplined investment plan that
enables you to invest a fixed amount of money consistently. Stick
to that, no matter what.
</P>
<P>
   Staying focused on what you want to accomplish with your money
in the long run will keep you from panicking.
</P>
<P>
   Cut out these rules, paste them in front of your personal
computer or telephone and refer to them when you feel the urge to
follow the pack:
</P>
<P>
   Don't let panic dictate your investment strategy because nobody
knows what the market will do.
</P>
<P>
   Don't presume that rushing into stocks now will make you rich,
because November won't guarantee more happy markets through the end
of the year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Send e-mail to pamela.yip at chron.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
