<HEADER>
A3031 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARE-MUSIC-REVIEW-HNS     11-10 0461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARE-MUSIC-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARENAKED LADIES PROVES TO BE DAZZLING IN CONCERT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE CRAWFORD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Let's get the obligatory Barenaked Ladies facts out of
the way.
</P>
<P>
   First, they're geeks. Many articles describe them as slightly
older versions of those nerdy Dungeons &AMP; Dragons players you sort
of acknowledged in high school. (Before you get riled up, yes, I
was one, too. I just forgot to become a pop star.)
</P>
<P>
   Second, they're Canadian. But they aren't like Canadian rock
gods Rush or Triumph. More like Bob and Doug McKenzie of ``Strange
Brew'' fame or the Kids in the Hall mixed with bits of Oingo Boingo
(who, by the way, were NOT Canadian) and a lot of common pop sense.
</P>
<P>
   On an album, this formula can be entertaining, though ultimately
a little stifling. Sometimes there's just too much going on _ too
much sunny melody, too much propulsiveness, way too much
cleverness.
</P>
<P>
   In the concert setting, though, it comes out as a heady brew. As
evidenced at the Aerial Theater in Houston on Sunday night,
Barenaked Ladies are one of the more entertaining live acts around
_ they certainly were a hit with the alarmingly youthful audience.
</P>
<P>
   The fun starts with their stage banter _ always genial,
lightning-quick and knife-sharp, and often gut-bustingly hilarious.
Some examples:
</P>
<P>
   The ``Meet the Security Guard'' segment, in which
guitarist/vocalist Ed Robertson coaxed a reluctant _ but gargantuan
_ guard named Andre to strum Robertson's guitar for an impromptu
reading of Lenny Kravitz's ``Are You Gonna Go My Way.''
</P>
<P>
   The risque ``Hello Houston'' rap involved pick-up trucks,
intimate behavior in said pickup trucks, the Johnson Space Center,
a Canadian astronaut and various scatological themes.
</P>
<P>
   Multitalented bassist Jim Creeggan's midshow bass solo _ upright
bass, that is _ which sounded like the Kronos Quartet playing a
mind-meld of ``Itsy Bitsy Spider'' and ``Hava Nagila.'' Seriously.
</P>
<P>
   While vastly entertaining, such elements would be pretty weak if
not backed by BNL's edgy and increasingly polished pop. These guys
know how to take a hook and dig all the way to China with it.
</P>
<P>
   The show, as expected, focused largely on the band's most recent
album, ``Stunt.'' The songs from that album translated well to the
live setting, particularly the manic ``Who Needs Sleep'' and
``Alcohol,'' and the plaintive ``I'll Be That Girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, the band delivered a rather lackluster rendition of
their cranial parasite of a smash-hit song, ``One Week.'' It lacked
the irresistible sparkle of the studio version. Maybe they're a
little sick of it. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steve Crawford is a free-lance writer based in Houston. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
