<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, Nov. 11:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (Moving in ``i'' news file.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-TOLL (Miami) _ An examination of the staggering
economic toll of Hurricane Mitch: It may take Honduras and
Nicaragua decades to recover from the destruction. By Larry Rohter.
With locator map.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.S. (Washington) _ Iraq developments; Clinton meets with
advisers. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TIBET (Lhasa) _ China's economic boom is the newest threat
to Tibet's culture as the long battle between Chinese modernity and
Tibetan tradition goes on. By Seth Faison. With photo and locator
map.
</P>
<P>
   DALAI-LAMA (Washington) _ Dalai Lama meets with President
Clinton and Vice President Gore amid new warnings from China. By
Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-RIGHTS (Beijing) _ Human rights group says 140 Protestants
have been arrested in central China. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-KOSOVO (Pristina) _ Interview with top rebel commander;
fears are growing that rebels are killing Serbs in numbers that
would make it difficult for truce to hold. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-ELECT (Jerusalem) _ The Arab politics of voting and not
voting in East Jerusalem; winners of Jerusalem and Tel Aviv
elections. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-FUTURE (Jakarta) _ People's Assembly meets to chart
country's political future. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-INAUG (Berlin) _ Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, in
inaugural address, pledges jobs and optimism. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-PHILIP (Dublin) _ Pushing peace and paving the way for
visit by Queen Elizabeth, Prince Philip visits Ireland and Northern
Ireland. By James F. Clarity.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-ECON (Rio de Janeiro) _ Government proposes new budget,
slashing billions for schools and hospitals. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (Moving in ``w'' news file.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS (Washington) _ Court ruling on inventors and patent
rights. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-LIVINGSTON (Washington ) _ Interview with Rep. Robert
Livingston of Louisiana, who has locked up the votes to become the
new speaker of the House; his day, Capitol developments on Rep.
Jennifer Dunn's candidacy for majority leader. By Katharine Q.
Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   ELECT-PERSPECTIVE (Washington) _ Political Memo. Republicans
suffered a defeat a week ago, but their hand-wringing and turmoil
and upheavals since have made it look like a rout. By Richard L.
Berke.
</P>
