   &UR; NATIONAL (Moving in ``a'' news file.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ORGAN-BANK (Boston) _ Just as scientists announced that someday
they may be able to grow livers and hearts outside the body,
recipients and donors from around the world gather for the 30th
anniversary of the country's oldest organ bank. They talk about how
the fight over who gets organs is tearing apart organizations and
recipients. By Carey Goldberg. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS-TRAIL-TOWN (St. Marys, Kan.) _ St. Marys, once the last
``civilized'' stop on the Oregon trail, is now a crossroads of a
different sort, where passionately held and often contradictory
visions of American life at the end of the 20th century are being
lived out at close quarters. By Jo Thomas. With photos.
</P>
<P>
   BAPTISTS (undated) _ The Texas Baptist convention, the biggest
Baptist group in the U.S., may be splitting, with conservatives
fleeing an organization that is dominated by moderates. Meanwhile,
the national Baptists are dominated by conservatives. By Gustav
Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (Moving in ``f'' news file) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-TRIAL (Washington) _ Justice Department lawyers
continue questioning Steve McGeady, an Intel executive, and then
Microsoft's lawyers will cross-examine him. By Steve Lohr and Joel
Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   CARGILL-GRAIN (Dallas) _ Cargill, the world's largest crop
trader, agrees to buy the grain unit of its closest American rival,
Continental Grain, expanding its share of the $51 billion market
for domestic corn, wheat and soybeans. By Allen R. Myerson.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TRADE (Washington) _ President Clinton and other
officials speak on trade, emphasizing that despite the economic
crisis, the United States cannot be the ``importer of only
resort,'' a reflection of growing political pressure on them from
unions and businesses. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-BANANAS (Washington) _ The trade dispute over bananas is
breaking out again with the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   BRISTOL-MYERS (Undated) _ Bristol-Myers Squibb, lambasted by
analysts for being the drug industry's slow player, is shuffling
its top management. By David J. Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   COMPAQ (San Francisco) _ Stepping into the middle of a bitter
international trade dispute between the United States and Japan,
Compaq Computer has agreed to make a three-year loan of a parallel
supercomputer to a federally financed weather research laboratory
that had been denied in its effort to buy a Japanese supercomputer.
By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At midday, the industrial average was off 21
points, or 0.2 percent, and the Nasdaq index was down 5.6 points,
or 0.3 percent. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE-HEALTH (Moving in 'a' news file) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PAIN-RELIEF (San Diego) _ A new class of drugs seems to be
living up to its promise of relieving pain and inflammation for
millions of arthritis sufferers but without the gastrointestinal
side effects of current drugs, according to new data presented at
the annual meeting of the American College of Rheumatalogy in San
Diego. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   ALTERNATIVE-MEDICINE (Washington) _ The influential Journal of
the American Medical Association publishes an issue focusing on
various alternative medicine treatments. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   MIR-STATION (Washington) _ The Russian space agency proposes
changing the orbit of the future international space station to
match the orbit of Mir. The stated reason is to transfer elements
from Mir to the station, but some Russian nationalist leaders are
also arguing that Mir should be kept alive as Russia's own symbol
in space. By Warren Leary.
</P>
<P>
   BLIND-ANTIBIOTIC (Undated) _ The leading cause of preventable
blindness worldwide can effectively be treated by a single dose of
an antibiotic once a year, health workers said Tuesday, and they
announced a major push to distribute the drug in five African
countries. The disease, trachoma, is caused by a strain of the
chlamydia bacterium. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
