<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BAY STATE DOUGHBOY'S DIARY OF WAR _ AND PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: For Wednesday A.M. release)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eighty years ago today, a Massachusetts soldier wrote home from
the front line in France. He'd never seen a party like it,
celebrating the end of World War I.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the wildest of wild nights, and the noisiest night
before the (July) 4th in Worcester cannot be compared to what is
going on here right now ... What a place this, tonight, the first
night of peace. Turn a town of absolute darkness and solitude and
misery into a town all lit-up, with 2,000 French and 500 American
soldiers running around, 90 percent of them drunk and singing, and
blowing bugles ... There is a big chateau situated on the side of
the hill here decorated with jack o'lanterns.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter came from Joe Rodier, 24, with one year's enlistment
under his belt, a Worcester Polytechnic student who'd signed up
with the 24th Engineers, writing to his sister Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   He kept a detailed diary, beginning with a late-February trip
across the North Atlantic in a troop ship carrying ``9,100 men and
big cargo.'' It was ``very hot'' in the hold; ``two men died, 30
cases of scarlet fever and 100 cases of measles on board.'' The
troops kept watch for German submarines. A Wisconsin soldier who
died of diphtheria was buried at sea. ``Many men sick and epidemic
feared.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe avoided the ``hot rat-hole'' where he had to sleep as much
as possible, staying on deck despite ``a sore foot, a bad stomach,
a tooth-ache, and a nose-bleed. Otherwise feeling fine. Very poor
eats.'' The men worried after word that a transport 40 miles ahead
had been sunk. One drill called to practice evacuating ``the rat
hole'' took Joe's cohort 25 minutes to file on deck. ``Every man
lost 10 pounds as he pictured himself going down ...'' March 3:
``Torpedo crossed our bow in the dark. Another sub nearly ran into
us ... The darkest night I ever saw in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Landing at Brest, his outfit hiked six hours with full packs to
``a swell-looking `rest camp' built by Napoleon in 1810 for his
soldiers ... nothing in the barracks except boards ... very cold
and damp in the barracks. Napoleon walked in about 10, followed by
Lafayette and Joan d'Arc about 11 p.m.''
</P>
<P>
   July 1 found his outfit at Nancy, for their first view of gutted
buildings and hostile artillery fire. His unit was the first
American outfit to arrive. ``Greeted and cheered royally
everywhere. Quite a bit of shooting going on.''
</P>
<P>
   As the action gets hotter, his handwriting becomes less precise.
July 4: ``Big doings this evening with searchlights, bombs, shells,
etc.'' July 18 he clocked ``train after train, every 15 minutes''
rushing allied reinforcements to the front.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turning point of war'' is a bold phrase he underlines four
times, drawing an American flag for emphasis.
</P>
<P>
   Joe's daughter, Ruth Gilmartin of East Falmouth, sent a copy of
some of his diary pages. One of his lucky days was Friday the 13th
of September. In neat handwriting it begins: ``American offensive
started here at 4:30 a.m. Counted 34 Allied planes in sky at one
time. Big Advance made.'' Then, an exuberant scrawl: ``RED SOX WIN
WORLD SERIES.''
</P>
<P>
   The entry for the 14th reverts to the grim business of war:
``Capture of 8,000 prisoners and much materiel. Big success all
along this front. St. Mihiel retaken after four years of German
rule. Confession to a French priest. Heavy artillery all night.''
</P>
<P>
   By Oct. 2, with peace less than six weeks off, Joe's diary
entries start to run diagonally across the page. With a renewed
Allied offensive spanning a 150-mile segment of the front, Joe
allows himself to speculate on when the war will end. ``Public
opinion is that fighting will cease before winter. I think not. He
(the German foe) has got to be licked.''
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 9: Cold and disease take their toll. ``More deaths from
Spanish Grippe.'' Making the rounds of civilian houses to pay
laborers, ``found things there in a most filthy condition and
everybody sick. Foggy night. Boche (artillery fire) overhead for an
hour but could not find me.'' The next Sunday, it's ``Mass, 9:15
a.m. Rain. Work.'' But he allows himself a dollop of hope: ``Looks
like an early peace.''
</P>
<P>
   By Nov. 4, his writing explodes off the diary page: ``Armistice
signed with Austria. Takes effect at 3 p.m. today. Hurrah.
Everybody drunk. Germany wants peace. Good health. Raining weather.
Artillery fire ...'' Next day, it's ``artillery duels all day and
night.''
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 10, Joe begins his day with confession. ``The day of
days,'' he writes. ``Kaiser abdicates. Revolution and defeat in
Germany. The war is won. Greatest of rejoicing ... Germany is done
forever ... Artillery fire all night. Heavy.''
</P>
<P>
   On the fateful day of Armistice, at the 11th hour of the 11th
day of the 11th month, the war finally ends. ``Another day of
days,'' commences Joe. ``Armistice signed with Germany to take
effect at 11 a.m. this date. Great manifestations. Towns lighted up
at night. Everybody drunk, even to the dog. Moonlight, cool night
and not a shot heard ... Everybody happy, and another good feed.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Rodier was lucky, like millions of other American soldiers,
sailors, and airmen we salute today for having won and rewon the
freedoms we enjoy today. They made the free world what it has
become, the triumph of civilization to this juncture. But there
were so many who never came home like Joe did. He was discharged in
1919, married in '21, worked at the Registry of Motor Vehicles,
raised eight kids. He died at 53.
</P>
<P>
   In the century's major conflicts, this many Yanks perished:
</P>
<P>
   World War I 116,500
</P>
<P>
   World War II 405,399
</P>
<P>
   Korea 54,246
</P>
<P>
   Vietnam 58,000
</P>
<P>
   So many lives sacrificed. Which is why this tribute ends the way
Joe signed his Armistice Day letter to his sister: ``Your loving
and living brother, Joe.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
