<SLUG> BC-PIE-THROWING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO LEADERS CONDEMN PIE ATTACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RACHEL GORDON  
 c.1998 San Francisco  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Members of the Board of Supervisors have
condemned two recent pie-throwing attacks on the mayor and a
supervisor, allegedly carried out by members of an environmental
organization that want to draw attention to their cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a laughing matter,'' Supervisor Michael Yaki said
Monday. ``It's an assault on people. It's an assault on public
officials. It's an assault on government.''
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Gavin Newsom was struck in the face on election
night, and Mayor Willie Brown was hit a few days later. Four
people, who belong to a group that calls itself the Biotic Baking
Brigade, have been arrested for attacking the mayor. The group
throws baked goods at famous people to draw attention to
environmental and social causes.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Amos Brown introduced a resolution on Monday's
declaring that the city ``will not tolerate assaults on public
officials.'' He also called for stepped-up police security for the
mayor.
</P>
<P>
   The act of throwing a pie, he said, may seem harmless enough,
but the consequences of someone charging at an elected leader could
have been devastating.
</P>
<P>
   ``What if that person had a gun or a knife?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Newsom, hit outside his victory party on election night, called
the incident ``unnerving.'' At first he wasn't going to press
charges against the assailants, but changed his mind when the mayor
was attacked.
</P>
<P>
   ``In hindsight, I regret (not filing charges), only because,
obviously, of the incident that happened a few days later to the
mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Biotic Baking Brigade said they targeted Brown
because of his policies on homeless people. They also have claimed
responsibility for hitting Newsom with pies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
