   BBO-MEETINGS (Nashville) _ The general manager meetings, where
trades are made and free agents are signed, continue. By Murray
Chass.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-METS (Undated) _ Latest developments in the Steve Phillips
situation. By Jason Diamos.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKEES (Undated) _ Latest Yankee free-agency and trade
developments, including the approach of still one more deadline for
David Cone, who has to decide whether to accept a one-year deal
from the Yankees or perhaps look elsewhere. By Buster Olney.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-KEITH-JACKSON (Ann Arbor, Mich.) _ Keith Jackson is retiring
when he's still at the top of his game, after three decades as the
bourbon-smooth, amusing, cantankerous voice of college football. He
wants to be with Turi Ann, his wife of 46 years, to garden, fish,
and ``get up in the morning, then decide what we want to do.'' By
Richard Sandomir.
</P>
<P>
   HKN-ISLES-PENGUINS (Pittsburgh) _ Islanders at Pittsburgh. By
Tarik El-Bashir.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDUCATION (Moving in 'a' news file) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EDUC-ACCREDITATION (Undated) _ A growing chorus says the
accreditation process has gone out of control, tying up college
administrators for weeks on end, answering the hundreds of
questions posed by visiting inspection teams. These critics also
raise the concern that many accrediting agencies have become
lobbyists for the academic disciplines they are supposed to
regulate. By William H. Honan.
</P>
<P>
   EDUC-PHD'S (Undated) _ Responding to charges that universities
are producing too many Ph.D.'s who are unable to find jobs, a
committee of the Association of American Universities, a group of
elite research universities, Tuesday defended their production of
Ph.D.'s as being useful for society, but called on its members to
make sure their programs were meeting student needs and preparing
them for careers. By Karen Arenson. Wih photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DINING (Moving in 'd' news file) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-RICE (Marysville, Calif.) _ In a six-week blitzkrieg each
fall, California farmers harvest about half a million acres of
rice, almost all of it the sticky short-grain and medium-grain
varieties grown in Japan. It might as well be a secret military
operation. Most Americans do not realize that California grows rice
at all, although it accounts for a quarter of the national crop,
and diners eat it every time they set foot into a sushi restaurant
or bite into a rice cake; with recipes. By William Grimes. With
photos.
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT-CARD-FRAUD (Undated) _ How common is credit card fraud in
restaurants? A look at how risky it is to hand over the card. By
Timothy J. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   ZAGAT-GUIDES (Undated) _ Twenty years ago this week, Tim Zagat
published the first of his populist restaurant guides and changed
the way Americans assess restaurants _ a look at the man, and his
sometimes-criticized methodology. By R.W. Apple Jr.. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   MASTER-CHEF (New York) _ Apple pound cake; with recipe. By
Francois Payard and Dorie Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-COOKING (Undated) _ Most chefs jazz gravlax up with
sauces and side dishes _ how else could they charge $12 a plate?
But this salt-cured fish dish, with its intense orange color and
meltingly tender texture, is brilliant on its own or with just a
few drops of lemon or mild vinegar. And even a kitchen novice can
make it at home; with recipes. By Mark Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   WINETALK (Undated) _ Comparing American Viticultural Areas, our
system of naming wines by regions, to the French way of doing the
same thing, the appellation system. By Frank J. Prial.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TASTINGS (Undated) _ Wine of the Week: Chassagne-Montrachet
Rouge, Jean Noel Gagnard, 1996, Burgundy, France. About $20.
</P>
<P>
   POMEGRANATES (Undated) _ While some cooks may experiment with
sprinkling the jewel-like pomegranate seeds over desserts, most
have not discovered the wealth of delicious dishes that can be made
when cooking with pomegranates, which are in season now until
January. By Barbara Kafka.
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-GUIDES (Undated) _ The annual holiday mail order guide.
By Marian Burros. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Food questions and answers. By Melissa
Clark.
</P>
