<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 15:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3208 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX     11-10 0455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS THERE A DR. SEMMELWEIS IN THE HOUSE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: A few years ago, a movie came out about a Dr. Suleman in
Germany, the doctor who discovered and developed the method of
sterilizing surgical instruments. Do you know the name of this
movie?
</P>
<P>
   _ D.L.B., Weatherford, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: It sounds like you're referring to Dr. Ignaz Semmelweis, a
Hungarian physician who reduced the number of postpartum infections
by insisting that doctors wash their hands between patients.
</P>
<P>
   Several movies have featured Semmelweis, who lived from 1818 to
1865. The 1938 short film ``That Mothers Might Live'' won the Oscar
for best one-reel short subject presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Three foreign films have been produced about the doctor.
``Semmelweis'' was the title of Hungarian films released in 1940
and 1952. More recently, the French made-for-TV movie ``Docteur
Semmelweis'' aired in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   While working at a Vienna hospital, Semmelweis urged staff to
thoroughly wash their hands before delivering children, causing
immediate reduction in a mortality rate that was as high as 18
percent. He died 35 years before his findings became accepted
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My daughter loves some British children's books we found that
are about characters called the Dinobabies. I can't find any other
ones at bookstores. Where are they available?
</P>
<P>
   _ F.S., Lynchburg, Va.
</P>
<P>
   A: BBC Children's Books has published at least 12 ``Dinobabies''
books, but they're not currently being marketed in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The U.K. affiliate of Amazon.Com, which is on the World Wide Web
at www.amazon.co.uk, sells all 12.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Dinobabies'' animated TV series by Fred Wolf Films is
syndicated in the United States, but not in all markets.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'd like to get Engelbert Humperdinck's address for a
birthday coming up in February. Where can I write to him?
</P>
<P>
   _ C.Y., Hurst, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to Engelbert Humperdinck, 7101 Smoke Ranch Road, No.
1086, Las Vegas, NV 89109, or visit his official Web site at
www.engelbert.com.
</P>
<P>
   The singer, who was born Arnold George Dorsey on either May 2 or
May 3, 1936, has sold more than 122 million records and has a fan
club claiming 8 million members.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 27, Interhit Records released ``The Dance Album,'' a
re-recording of Humperdinck songs such as ``Release Me,'' ``Quando
Quando Quando'' and ``After the Lovin'.''
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
