<DOCNO> NYT19981110.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3249 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINETALK-NYT &LR;      11-10 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINETALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MATTER OF YARDS FROM GOOD TO GREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   To the French, where a wine comes from is more important than
what's in it. That a wine comes from Burgundy means more than that
it's made from pinot noir grapes.
</P>
<P>
   It was on this premise that the French created the remarkable
concept of controlled appellations, or place names, more than half
a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   Under this system, known as Appellations d'Origine Controllee,
strict rules determine not only the precise place where a wine can
be made, but also the kinds of grapes to be used, how much of them
can be picked and exactly how much wine can be made from them.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, a wine made from a specific Bordeaux commune, like
Pauillac, must conform to the criteria for quality laid down
expressly for Pauillac by the National Institute of Controlled
Appellations. So important are the designations to wine producers
that major political battles have been fought by wine-producing
regions to obtain them.
</P>
<P>
   Today, such laws cover about a third of French wine production,
with the proportion growing. These laws, Alexis Lichine once wrote,
``have required growers to match soils and microclimates with the
most promising vines until the nearest thing to a perfect marriage
is achieved.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States has long had geographic laws covering
winemaking, but they have been much less demanding. For example, a
wine can't be called a California wine unless all the grapes in it
come from that state, while a wine can't be called a Napa Valley
wine unless 75 percent of its grapes come from the Napa Valley.
</P>
<P>
   A wine cannot be called a varietal, like cabernet sauvignon or
chardonnay, unless 75 percent of it is made from the named grape.
Oregon has its own rule, which makes the minimum 95 percent.
</P>
<P>
   There are subregions in American wine country, too, but they
have little to do with setting or maintaining standards. Only
recently have American winemakers come to agree with their European
counterparts that specific terrains produce specific kinds of wine.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, they believed, particularly in California, that
most of their soil was good and that what mattered was climate.
</P>
<P>
   Americans have now seen the light. The winemakers, noting that
subregions within a region like the Napa Valley produce wines with
a specific style and taste, wanted controlled areas based on
geography.
</P>
<P>
   To express a real or imagined diversity, the winemakers got the
Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, the federal agency that
oversees wine regulations, to create American Viticultural Areas.
</P>
<P>
   The Napa Valley now has a dozen subregions so labeled, including
Stag's Leap, Howell Mountain, Mount Veeder, Rutherford and
Carneros. At least half a dozen more locales in the valley are
waiting for federal approval as viticultural areas.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these subregions were created for a single winery: the
only winery in the Atlas Peak viticultural area is Atlas Peak. Wild
Horse Valley, another Napa subregion, has no wineries, just a
vineyard. A recently approved area designation in Mendocino County
includes three mountains, but only their tops.
</P>
<P>
   But where the French appellation system was created only after
hundreds of years' experience and is governed by strict rules that
are toughly enforced, the American system is often seen as little
more than a marketing tool.
</P>
<P>
   A viticultural area is defined as ``a delimited grape growing
area distinguished by geographic features, the boundaries of which
have been recognized and defined.''
</P>
<P>
   For wine quality, that definition means nothing. Its inclusion
on a wine bottle label would mean about as much. Which is why some
winemakers use not only the viticultural area on their labels but
also the name of the vineyard that grew the grapes and occasionally
a specific plot of vines within the vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   Once a viticultural area is created, nothing more is required of
the wineries and growers within it. There is nothing to prevent an
indifferent winemaker from hiding behind the name of his
viticultural area, should his winery be in one, and producing
indifferent wines.
</P>
<P>
   If he is not in a designated area, he can petition the
government to create one for him.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, viticultural areas are a good idea. They
emphasize the importance of site, of seeking out and developing not
only regional differences but also minute, vineyard-to-vineyard
character changes.
</P>
<P>
   In Bordeaux, a distance of a few yards can mean the difference
between a good wine and a great wine. This comes from years of
trial and error, sometimes centuries. I haven't the slightest doubt
that American vineyards and the wines they produce will one day
show the same diversity.
</P>
<P>
   It may take a while, but it can only benefit those of us who
delight in drinking the stuff.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-10-98 1555EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
