<HEADER>
A3256 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CREDIT-CARD-FRAUD-2TA     11-10 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-CARD-FRAUD-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRAUD'S RARE, BUT CHECK THE TAB ANYWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Texas)   (af)  
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Last week, when a well-known New York chef was
charged with falsifying the tips on receipts submitted to credit
card companies, an alarm might have sounded for diners who don't
think twice about the precise amount scrawled on the bottom of the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Some might even admit that, after a a few glasses of wine and a
couple hours of conviviality, they barely think once about it.
</P>
<P>
   And few could say that, weeks later, they check their receipts
against the billing statement.
</P>
<P>
   But how much of this sort of fraud is going on? And just how
difficult is it to accomplish?
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials charged David Ruggerio _ the chef and
owner of the restaurant David Ruggerio and the star of a newly
minted television show _ with stealing $190,000 by submitting
fraudulent restaurant receipts to the credit card companies of 26
of his customers.
</P>
<P>
   Ruggerio's lawyers dispute the charges, but whatever the outcome
of this particular case it is instructive: unscrupulous waiters and
others in a restaurant can alter figures by small or large amounts,
a fact that suggests it's always wise to check personal receipts
against the credit card company's bill when it arrives.
</P>
<P>
   The credit card companies say restaurant-bill fraud is rare and
getting rarer. Moreover, the charges against Ruggerio, if proved,
would go beyond the uncommon to the outrageous: the disputed
transactions range from $5,000 to $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time I ever saw this done this
systematically,'' said David Robertson, president of The Nilson
Report, a credit card industry newsletter. ``In other cases, you
might have a waiter or someone else on the staff doing this, but it
doesn't add up to much.''
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing complicated about what Ruggerio is accused of.
Investigators say that he tacked huge _ and bogus _ tips onto
charges, and that his restaurant then received the full amount from
its credit card processor, Paymentech Merchant Services.
</P>
<P>
   Because it often takes 30 to 40 days for such charges to show up
on diners' statements, Ruggerio would have had at least a month to
use the money before customers discovered the discrepancies.
</P>
<P>
   According to Paymentech, the company caught on to the
overcharges, but only after it had paid Ruggerio about $190,000 _
showing that even card processors with sophisticated electronic
safeguards can briefly be duped.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson said that as recently as five years ago it might have
been possible for such padding to go completely undetected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fraud is lower than a snake's belly in the credit card
industry right now, because they're able to analyze millions of
transactions and find patterns of fraud fairly quickly,'' he said.
``It's quite a success story, actually.''
</P>
<P>
   But the safety net is designed to catch large numbers. If bills
were falsified only occasionally, and only small amounts of money
were involved, the transactions could slip through.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, the statistics on restaurant fraud don't reflect
the times when a tip or some other part of the bill is inflated and
the error isn't caught and disputed by the customer. (Such disputed
transactions, in credit card parlance, are called ``charge
backs.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``There have to be some losses that are undetected and not
captured by the numbers,'' Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, restaurants have one of the lowest levels of fraud in
the credit card industry, because most transactions occur face to
face and diners typically examine their checks and credit card
bills before signing.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And unlike jewelry stores and consumer electronics outlets,
which are victims of credit card fraud more frequently because it
is easy to fence the products they sell, restaurants are protected
because dining out can't be hocked on the black market.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an industry, we've seen a dramatic reduction in charge-back
rates over the last eight years,'' said David Richey, vice
president for card operations at Visa USA. Richey said that about
0.06 percent of all transactions are charged back now, as against
0.28 percent in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Several New York restaurateurs said that credit card fraud _
whether grand or petty _ is not a big concern for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has not been an issue here,'' said Ben Benson, owner of the
midtown Manhattan steakhouse that bears his name. ``During the era
when there was more cash floating around, waiters could overcharge
customers. But that doesn't happen much any more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes waiters will change the numbers on a credit card
tip, like making a $37 tip look like an $89 tip. But when we see a
20 percent tip become a 50 percent tip, that obviously makes us
take a closer look. And then we'll bring it up with the waiter and
sometimes even with the customer.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some restaurants are still concerned that they will
be defrauded in a bogus credit card transaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're worried,'' said Sarah Polansky, office manager for the
Cupping Room Cafe in SoHo. ``Sometimes we get charge-backs from
customers who say they forgot they ate here. Very few of them are
authentic.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodney Bell, a spokesman for Paymentech, a Dallas company that
is one of the biggest credit card processors in the country, said
it can help restaurant owners create ``electronic parameters''
around its accounts to protect them.
</P>
<P>
   If a credit transaction is too large or a restaurant an
unusually large number of charges, those parameters can be
breached, prompting a warning that the transactions may be suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Large credit and charge card companies like Mastercard, Visa and
American Express all have similar systems, creating a sophisticated
electronic web designed to snare scam artists.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, it is always possible for problems to slip through
the cracks, and there are some common-sense steps that diners and
restaurateurs can use to protect themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Although diners once had to worry that their names and credit
card numbers might be lifted from carbons that were thrown out
after a charge slip was signed, most transactions now are
carbonless. But diners should still keep their receipts and check
them against their credit card statements when the monthly bill
arrives.
</P>
<P>
   Life is a bit more complicated for restaurant owners. First, a
couple of rules of the road. A restaurant is on the hook for a
charge-back only if a processor or a credit card issuer can prove
that the restaurant did not monitor the validity of a transaction
by making sure, for example, that the signature on a card matches
the signature on the bill.
</P>
<P>
   If a restaurant follows the correct procedures for handling the
card, then the processor or card company has to absorb any losses.
</P>
<P>
   Card companies like Visa recommend that restaurants set up a
process for recording disputed charges and tracking them according
to the employee involved as one way of protecting themselves from
in-house theft.
</P>
<P>
   Some restaurants have their own controls in place. For example,
at the Hard Rock Cafe, a midtown tourist mecca, a service charge is
not included in a bill unless the party has six or more diners. And
credit card charges for such big parties require the authorization
of a manager, who is also required to swipe the card through the
terminal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
