</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TED AND SYLVIA: FOREVER LINKED IN LIFE, DEATH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is gratifying for me to have been in England, quite by
chance, when Ted Hughes died last week. The London press _ both the
quality dailies and the sleazy tabloids _ was filled with distended
feature articles and other glowing tributes to their poet laureate.
</P>
<P>
   Poets rate higher station with the British people than with our
own. That St. Louis-born, Princeton-educated defector, T.S. Eliot,
was claimed by both countries, but his death in the first week of
1965 was somehow a matter of greater importance in the United
Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   Even when a poet so fully American as Robert Frost passed on,
soon after his participation in John Kennedy's inauguration, the
British outmourned us in the public print and perhaps in their
hearts as well.
</P>
<P>
   No complaint this time. Because I was there rather than here, I
read the obituaries and pallbearing testimonials and learned more
about Ted Hughes than I would ever have known otherwise. On my
return, I reread some of his poems, read others for the first time,
and refined what had been a tentative appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   In our country, the name Ted Hughes has been mainly a footnote
to the life and career of Sylvia Plath, the American poet whose
suicide in 1963 at age 30 occurred soon after the collapse of their
six-year marriage. Perhaps especially in the American imagination,
Hughes has been etched as a villain, even a murderer, for having
left Sylvia Plath for another woman, at least ostensibly.
</P>
<P>
   When they first met at a poetry gathering in 1955, Hughes was 25
and Plath was 23. They married a year later, and soon afterward
Hughes was on his way to being famous. His debut volume, ``The Hawk
in the Rain'' (1957) introduced a poet with a remarkable sense of
the beauty and violence of the natural world.
</P>
<P>
   They lived briefly in the United States while Plath taught at
her alma mater, Smith College; but then they settled in England,
where the Hughes star continued its rise. Plath was in his shadow
throughout their married years, which produced two children.
</P>
<P>
   Her first collection, ``The Colossus'' (1962), was politely
received; but it was the publication of ``Ariel'' three years after
her death that set the legend of Sylvia Plath in motion. Over three
posthumous decades, she has risen steadily on the fame graph and
now is among the best-known poets of our history.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Ted Hughes stunned the literary world by breaking his
long silence about Plath and their life together _ not in talk-show
interviews but with a volume of poems titled ``Birthday Letters,''
most of whose individual components were as if spoken to his dead
wife. The poems, consciously cathartic and rather apart from his
characteristically brutal nature verse, were accepted as ``his side
of the story.''
</P>
<P>
   And his side surely has some validity. Sylvia Plath certainly
possessed genius, probably ``too much'' genius, and to have lived
with her would conceivably have been a cruel challenge. As a senior
at Smith in 1953, she suffered a nervous breakdown and attempted
suicide. Her only novel, ``The Bell Jar'' _ published under a
pseudonym in the year of her death and under her own name in 1971 _
is an elaborate explanation of her collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes, in the now-well-read ``The Minotaur'' and other
``Birthday Letters'' entries, attributes Plath's neurosis to a
Freudian struggle with the dead father whom he could not replace.
He cites her father as inspiration for the ``Ariel'' poems that
remain the cornerstone of her reputation, although two other poetry
volumes are in the posthumous haul _ along with Plath's collected
prose and her journals and correspondence. Her ``Collected Poems''
took the Pulitzer Prize 18 years after her death.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Hughes' death at 68 was unexpected; his cancer had been in
remission, and he was ceremonially honored by Queen Elizabeth II
only two weeks before. He had been Britain's poet laureate for 14
years.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is books editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7731. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
