<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMELESS-POLICY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO PLANS NEW APPROACH TO HOMELESSNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GREGORY LEWIS and RACHEL GORDON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Homeless people who are arrested repeatedly for
public drunkenness would have to choose between a detoxification
program or jail under a new push to find a solution to San
Francisco's chronic vagrancy problem.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for the homeless quickly criticized the proposed
initiative, saying that the administration of Mayor Willie Brown is
trying to make homelessness a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the mayor's staff, however, said they were looking to
see how other cities deal with the seemingly intractable homeless
problem. The policy would be a humane attempt to end the
``revolving door'' of substance abuse, they said. The
administration has reviewed the homeless policies in Boston,
Chicago, Los Angeles, New York, Portland, Ore., and Santa Monica,
Calif., some of which have strict law against vagrancy.
</P>
<P>
   The new plan would target those arrested for public drunkenness
three times within a 60-day period. Upon conviction, they would be
offered a slot in a substance abuse program or a 60-day jail
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The policy, however, would rely on space being available at
detoxification centers. If there were no space, the city would
revert to the current policy of citing and releasing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city recognizes that there's a problem with people being
severely intoxicated day in and day out on city streets,'' said
Bevan Dufty, the mayor's director of neighborhood services. ``This
is about chronic offenders, people who are belligerent and cause a
threat to themselves and to others. This is not about
incarceration, but about helping people.''
</P>
<P>
   The policy, he said, also would help residents and merchants
affected by the scofflaws.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is clearly we have a problem with a revolving door of
people who are cited continuously and released,'' said Kandace
Bender, the mayor's spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Those who provide services for the homeless referred to a
revolving door of a different kind. This one, they said, would spin
the homeless through the criminal justice system and forced
treatment, but send them back on the streets to begin the cycle
over again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Police officers will force certain individuals of their
choosing into treatment inside jails, but the city is not going to
expand treatment _ current beds that already have long waiting
lists will be used,'' said Marykate Connor of Caduceus Outreach
Services, which provides treatment for mental illness and
addiction.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, whose administration has wrestled with homelessness for
three years, is searching for a new policy with an eye toward his
November 1999 re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's plan, called San Francisco Cares, is in
draft form. It proposes ``a range of solutions, both short-term and
long-term,'' said Terry Hill, the mayor's homeless services
coordinator. ``The mayor is not interested in more and more
shelter. He wants to find concrete long-term solutions for folks
who are in dire straits.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill denied there would be any sweep of homeless people by the
police.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything punitive or police-led was rejected by the mayor. The
mayor wants us to treat people where they are whether it's mental
illness or substance abuse,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One member of the city's Board of Supervisors, Amos Brown, said
the city must crack down on public drunkenness, urinating and
defecating in public, and using and selling drugs. He said some
people use homelessness as an excuse to break the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no excuse for bad behavior,'' he said. ``Just because
you're homeless doesn't mean you have the right to go out there and
be unkind to someone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
