<SLUG> BC-WEB-INITIATIVE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDUCATION INITIATIVE MAY BE SHAPED ON THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Web site is CQ; will not be accessible until Wednesday.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIAN GUTHRIE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A Silicon Valley venture capitalist is asking
Internet users to help craft a school-choice ballot initiative and
then sign it on-line, a test of cyberspace democracy that may be
ahead of its time.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Draper, calling public education in California a disaster,
said he would launch a cyber initiative Wednesday to get it on the
ballot in 2000. Through a Web site to be located at
www.localchoice.com, on-line users will have a say in how Draper's
initiative is worded.
</P>
<P>
   Draper has three fundamental goals: to give parents tax dollars
to send their children to the school of their choice; reward or
sanction principals based on student performance; and redefine the
state's role in education.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to give California parents the opportunity to choose
the best school for their child,'' said Draper, a father of four
and a founder Draper Fisher Associates of Redwood City, Calif. He
also was named to the state Board of Education by retiring Gov.
Pete Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Avoiding the word voucher because ``it scares people,'' Draper
said it would be left to the Internet community to determine
whether, through his initiative, public tax dollars should be used
to send children to public schools, or to public, private and
religious institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through on-line polls, people will be able to write to us and
tell us where we're right and wrong,'' Draper said. ``We need to
break up the education bureaucracy by creating a market system. The
money should follow the child to the school of choice.''
</P>
<P>
   School choice, an umbrella term for everything from home
schooling, education tax credits and public and private
scholarships, is getting more attention across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court on Monday let stand a Wisconsin court
ruling expanding Milwaukee's voucher program to allow parents to
send their children to religious schools.
</P>
<P>
   Large-scale state-run voucher programs are in place in Cleveland
and Milwaukee, and programs are being debated in Vermont and
Pennsylvania. In California, voucher systems face vehement
opposition from the powerful state teachers unions and ambivalence
among voters.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, California voters defeated a proposition that would
have given students from poor families a voucher worth 50 percent
of the annual cost of public schooling.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Draper is proposing giving the entire annual
per-pupil spending _ more than $5,500 per child _ to the public or
private school of the family's choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to do away with a lot of the education bureaucracy,''
he said. ``Why do we even need county offices of education?''
</P>
<P>
   Although the California secretary of state has identified
technology that could be used for gathering and validating
electronic signatures, there are political and legislative hurdles
to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would need time to develop an electronic database of
electronic voters, complete with signatures that counties would be
able to verify,'' said Alfie Charles, spokesman for the secretary
of state.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Alexander, president of the California Voter Foundation, a
nonprofit organization that promotes the Internet as a tool for
voter education, called Draper's on-line campaign a good idea, but
premature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know whether the secretary of state would accept
digital signatures,'' Alexander said. ``But this will attract
people who are deeply interested in the issue of school reform.
Maybe this initiative will be the catalyst that gets the digital
signature process in place.''
</P>
<P>
   For Draper, the initiative is a chance to fuse his interests in
the Internet and overhauling the education system.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went into my daughter's classroom and saw her using the
same textbooks I'd used 25 years ago, in a classroom that was
falling apart, I realized there had been no change in education
over 25 years,'' said Draper, who moved his children from public to
private schools. ``I have always believed that market systems work.
We need competition for our education bureaucracy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
