<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MET-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. METROPOLITAN MUSEUM OF ART NAMES 2 LEADERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Tenn., R.I.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ James Houghton, the former chairman of Corning Inc.,
was named chairman of the Metropolitan Museum of Art on Tuesday.
Houghton, a member of the Met's board for 16 years and its vice
chairman since 1984, succeeds Arthur Ochs Sulzberger, who announced
his retirement from the post in September.
</P>
<P>
   The museum also announced the appointment of David McKinney as
the next president of the Met. McKinney will succeed William Luers,
who is stepping down after 12 years. McKinney, who spent 36 years
with IBM, is the executive secretary of the Thomas J. Watson
Foundation and the director of the Thomas J. Watson Fellowship.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement signals a major change in the power structure
of the Met, the largest art museum in the country, with more than
two million objects and more than five million visitors last year.
Unlike Luers, who reported directly to the board, McKinney will be
responsible to Philippe de Montebello. De Montebello, who has been
the museum's director for 21 years, has been named to the new
position of chief executive officer, putting him in charge of all
museum operations.
</P>
<P>
   In McKinney, who turns 64 this month, the Met has chosen a man
with a strong business background. ``We looked at many people of
all ages and sexes in all different worlds from academic to
nonprofit,'' de Montebello said Tuesday. ``Dave best fit the
cumulative qualities we were looking for. When you look to the
future, he brings a tremendous amount of wisdom and experience.''
</P>
<P>
   De Montebello added that at a moment when the museum is facing
larger challenges than ever _ with its building renovations, cuts
in the operating funds it receives from Reader's Digest, and its
aim to move forward technologically _ McKinney's experience in
strategic planning, technology and international relations would
make him a great asset. McKinney served as executive officer of the
IBM World Trade Europe/Middle East/Africa Corp., retiring in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will work in smooth partnership,'' de Montebello said. It
is well known in the art world that de Montebello has had a
strained relationship with Luers.
</P>
<P>
   The passing of the chairmanship from Sulzberger, the chairman
emeritus of The New York Times Co., to Houghton signals a new era
for the Met. Sulzberger's tenure as Met chairman was a time of
expansion. The museum's attendance grew to 5.2 million visitors
from 4.8 million; its membership grew to 111,594 from 96,531, and
its budget nearly doubled, to $116.6 million from $64 million.
</P>
<P>
   The new chairman will be following in the footsteps of his
cousin Arthur Houghton, chairman of the Met from 1969 to 1972.
James Houghton, a Harvard-educated executive who became chairman of
Corning in 1983, retiring 13 years later, is a director of
Metropolitan Life Insurance Co., J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co. and Exxon Corp.
He is also a trustee of the Pierpont Morgan Library, the Corning
Museum of Glass and the Corning Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be an interesting time at the Met,'' Houghton
said. ``We have a new president and a new management structure. As
far as the direction of the museum goes, I'd say we're on a pretty
good track.''
</P>
<P>
   As its new president McKinney, a native of Tennessee, comes to
the museum with little background in art other than taking art
classes and visiting museums. But as an executive at the
International Business Machines Corporation he has filled several
major positions, among them executive assistant to the chairman of
IBM, vice president of personnel and president of IBM World Trade
Americas/Far East Corp. He also served as head of the IBM corporate
operations staff and was a member of the corporate management
board.
</P>
<P>
   McKinney is also a trustee of Brown University and a director of
the New York Philharmonic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's premature to have a plan in mind,'' he said Tuesday. ``I
need to learn more about the Met first.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
