<HEADER>
A3373 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRACHOMA11-11-COX     11-10 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRACHOMA11-11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CAMPAIGN MOUNTED AGAINST INFECTION THAT BLINDS MILLIONS
 &HT;    545 words
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With a drug company's donation of several million
doses of antibiotics, a private foundation has launched a campaign
against a common eye infection that blinds millions of people in
tropical countries.
</P>
<P>
   The infection, known as trachoma, causes blindness the hard way,
said Dr. Joseph Cook, director of tropical disease research for the
Edna McConnell Clark Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   After repeated infections over a period of years, the victim's
upper eyelids slowly turn inward because of scars. This causes the
eyelashes to scrape against the cornea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a slow and painful way to become blind,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a preventable way, even though the World Health
Organization estimates more than 150 million people worldwide have
trachoma infections and more than 5 million are blind because of
the disease.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, river blindness, a disease spread by a biting
fly, has blinded an estimated 250,000 people. Only cataracts cause
more cases of blindness than trachoma, Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   Clark Foundation officials announced Tuesday that using public
health measures, village-based surgery and approximately 4 million
doses of zithromycin donated by Pfizer Inc., the foundation will
launch a campaign against the disease in five countries, probably
Vietnam and the African countries of Morocco, Mali, Ghana and
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer officials said the donation is valued at roughly $60
million, based on the price the company charges pharmaceutical
wholesalers. In addition, the company has agreed to donate $3.2
million in cash to the campaign, Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   Trachoma is most common in countries where poverty, poor access
to water and poor hygiene are pervasive. In addition to Africa and
Asia, the disease is prevalent in parts of Australia and Central
and South America.
</P>
<P>
   The bacteria that cause trachoma are spread from person to
person through physical contact, especially among children, by
items such as towels that are shared within families and by flies,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   A single capsule of zithromycin, which Pfizer markets as
Zithromax, can keep a person free of trachoma for up to a year,
Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the campaign, seeking to eliminate the factors that
spread the disease, will attempt to teach people the importance of
face washing, even in arid areas, and the use of clean water.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within a single community, when you reduce the total number of
cases, you cut down on the 'force of infection' and inhibit the
spread of the disease,'' Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   For people whose eyelids already have been damaged, a 15-minute
operation, which can be performed in a village setting by a public
health nurse, can prevent scraping of the cornea, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy of surgery, antibiotics and health training was
developed by the foundation over the past 12 years, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Good hygiene, good water and health education have eliminated
trachoma in developed countries, including the United States, Cook
said. However, most eye hospitals in the United States were first
built to treat trachoma, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Edna McConnell Clark Foundation was established by Edna
McConnell Clark and her husband, Van Alan Clark. Mrs. Clark was the
daughter of David McConnell, founder of Avon Products Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-10-98 1647EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
