<SLUG> BC-CALIF-RICE-STICKY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO COOK `STICKY' RICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By WILLIAM GRIMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Almost all the rice grown in California is ``sticky rice,'' the
mostly short-or medium-grain varieties that clump together when
cooked. Besides being the appropriate rice for sushi and other
Japanese dishes, sticky rices make ideal rice cakes and add a
heftier texture to rice salads.
</P>
<P>
   Like all members of the subspecies japonica, these rices contain
high levels of the starch amylopectin and low levels of amylose,
the other starch in rice. Rices like Basmati or Southern-style
long-grains, also known as indica rices because they originated in
India, have low levels of amylopectin and high levels of amylose,
meaning they cook up drier.
</P>
<P>
   In their cookbook ``Seductions of Rice'' (Artisan, 1998),
Jeffrey Alford and Naomi Duguid offer instructions for making
Japanese-style rice. First, rinse the rice with cold water several
times before cooking to remove excess starch; otherwise the rice
will be too sticky. When the water runs clear, let the rice sit in
a sieve for 20 to 30 minutes, absorbing the water that clings to
it.
</P>
<P>
   Using one and a sixth cups water for each cup of rice, put the
rice and water in a heavy medium-size pot, uncovered, and turn the
heat to high. When the water reaches a vigorous boil, cover and
reduce the heat to medium-low. Cook for 5 minutes, then reduce the
heat to very low and cook 10 more minutes. Remove from the heat,
and let stand for 10 minutes before serving. Do not uncover or stir
the rice at any point before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Sticky rice should feel tacky _ that is, adhesive enough to form
a convenient clump when herded by a pair of chopsticks, but not
gooey or mushy. Each grain should be plump, shiny and distinct.
``It should be toothsome,'' said Rocco DiSpirito, executive chef at
Union Pacific in Manhattan. ``You want it slightly chewy, with a
little springiness in it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
