<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ECONOMY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO ATTEND PACIFIC RIM MEETING, BOLSTER ASIAN ECONOMIES
THROUGH TRADE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton said Tuesday he and other Pacific
Rim leaders will work to bolster Asian economies when they meet
next week to discuss broad trade agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will attend the Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation forum
in Malaysia despite the crisis over Iraq's defiance of
international arms inspectors, spokesman Joe Lockhart said.
Clinton's attendance had been in doubt as the United States
contemplates military strikes against Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   The president, talking trade to students and experts gathered at
the massive Ronald Reagan Building, provided a broad overview of
the upcoming APEC session and economic issues facing the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll work on speeding the economic recovery in Asia,
strengthening the social safety net, helping companies there to
restructure their debt so they can emerge from the crushing burdens
they face and once again employ people and pay them wages,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The administration fears the Asian economic collapse, which
already has helped push Russia into a meltdown, could work its way
through Latin America and eventually disrupt the United States
growing economy.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton again pointed to Japan as the key to reviving the
Pacific Rim markets. The president plans to stop in Tokyo, as well
as South Korea, after the APEC meeting next week in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The restoration of growth in Japan, which has been stalled now
for more than five years, is absolutely essential to the
restoration of growth in the remainder of Asia,'' Clinton said.
``The rest of us look to Japan to move quickly to implement the
good banking reforms which have been passed, to spur demand for
goods and services in the home market, to reduce unnecessary
regulations and to open its markets.''
</P>
<P>
   The goal of APEC is to bring down all tariff barriers and
promote free trade throughout the region. The United States has a
similar goal with the nations in Central and South America.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said his administration would again ``find common
ground'' with Congress to pass the so-called fast-track negotiating
authority that would allow him to negotiate trade pacts free of
amendment by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The president also warned nations that are dumping their steel
products into the United States. ``We are committed to a full and
timely enforcement of our trade laws to address unfair trade
practices affecting this industry, and we will insist that our key
trading partners play by the rules,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton earlier signed into law a measure agreeing with other
nations to crackdown on international bribery. The international
agreement requires nations that sign it to enact laws outlawing
their citizens from bribing foreign officials to win business
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   He said the United States has had such laws for 20 years and the
international pact will help level the playing field for U.S.
companies. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
