A3542 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT &LR;      11-10 0451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brother Acts
</P>
<P>
   For the Marsalis brothers, it's quite a week. Thursday night in
New York at Carnegie Hall, the Grammy Award-winning saxophonist
Branford Marsalis joins the Carnegie Hall Jazz Band for a salute to
two great swing-era band leaders, Jimmie Lunceford and Tommy
Dorsey. Friday, in Weill Recital Hall, the Orion String Quartet
will perform the Pulitzer Prize-winning composer Wynton Marsalis'
first string quartet, ``At the Octoroon Balls.'' Inspired by
Marsalis' early life in New Orleans, its motifs include Creole
dances and runaway trains.
</P>
<P>
   Immortals
</P>
<P>
   Paul McCartney and Bruce Springsteen were among the stars named
Tuesday for induction next year into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame
in Cleveland. Also named were Del Shannon, Curtis Mayfield, Dusty
Springfield, Billy Joel, the Staples Singers, Charles Brown and Bob
Wills and the Texas Playboys. With George Martin, the British
record producer who offered the Beatles their first contract, they
are to be inducted in March in a ceremony in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In Character
</P>
<P>
   George Romney (1734-1802), the popular English portraitist,
often turned to Shakespeare's plays for inspiration. The Folger
Shakespeare Library in Washington has nearly 500 of his drawings,
most never exhibited. Tuesday 116 went on view in `` `Designs From
Fancy': George Romney's Shakespearean Drawings.''
</P>
<P>
   Worse Half
</P>
<P>
   Ellis Island is a National Monument, and on the north side, its
famous Main Immigration Building, restored and renovated in the
1980s, is a prime tourist attraction. But on the south side, two
dozen historic buildings, smothered in shrubs and vines, stand
abandoned. Between 1900 and 1937, this was a hospital complex where
some 10 percent of the 12 million immigrants who reached the island
were detained before they could enter the country. Starting
Thursday, this complex will be the focus of ``Forgotten Gateway:
The Abandoned Buildings of Ellis Island,'' at the National Building
Museum in Washington. The 37 large-format photographs by Larry
Racioppo capture the intimacy and ghostly emptiness of the complex.
</P>
<P>
   Weill Doings
</P>
<P>
   The Eastman School of Music at the University of Rochester is
celebrating the arrival in the United States of manuscripts of all
original music composed by Kurt Weill when he lived in Germany,
including ``The Threepenny Opera.'' Weill's Viennese publisher,
Universal Edition AG, has turned them over to the Sibley Music
Library at the Eastman School, where a Weill festival begins
Wednesday and ends Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
