<HEADLINE>
TV NOTES: ELECTION AND HURRICANE COVERAGE; FOX VS. NBC; '60 MINUTES
II' 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: bylines at end of articles)  
 (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Elections Vs. Hurricane Mitch
</P>
<P>
   More than 10,000 people died in floods or mudslides brought on
by Hurricane Mitch in Central America, and the infrastructures of
Nicaragua and Honduras were virtually destroyed. Big news story,
right?
</P>
<P>
   Yet the network evening news broadcasts devoted a total of only
53 minutes to it in the two weeks that ended with Friday's
broadcasts _ roughly half the coverage given earlier this year to
two much less damaging hurricanes, Bonnie (104 minutes) and Georges
(94).
</P>
<P>
   Was this because Mitch's devastation became news at the height
of election coverage or because Mitch did not threaten the United
States?
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to say it's isolationism and xenophobia, there's no
way around it,'' said Andrew Tyndall, publisher of the Tyndall
Report, a weekly newsletter that tracks coverage on the major
networks' evening news broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   But logistics played some role. Networks have fewer reporters in
Central America, and the devastation restricted reporting further.
</P>
<P>
   ``All news organizations were caught off guard by the amount of
destruction down there,'' said David Doss, executive producer of
NBC's ``Nightly News,'' which led its broadcast with Mitch stories
two nights last week while CBS and ABC led with it only once.
``Once the real gravity of it filtered out, we moved in very
quickly.'' Doss also pointed out that two other major news events
were happening then: John Glenn's space flight and the midterm
elections.
</P>
<P>
   At ABC News, the two men who run ``Nightline'' _ anchor Ted
Koppel and executive producer Tom Bettag _ talked Saturday and
decided to spend four consecutive programs this week (starting
Tuesday night) examining Mitch's devastation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all covering the election, and I don't think we were
paying proper attention to the storm,'' Koppel said Tuesday,
speaking by cellular phone from a riverbank in Choluteca, Honduras,
where he was waiting for a helicopter to take him to his next stop.
``There was until two weeks ago a huge bridge over this river,'' he
added. ``It was built by the Japanese as a gift to Honduras. Now
one end of it is in the middle of the river.''
</P>
<P>
   By LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
<P>
   Fox on NBC's Tail
</P>
<P>
   Now maybe it's time for NBC to get worried. Far from dominating,
as usual, a ratings sweep month, those all-important ratings
competitions, NBC finds itself in an all-out struggle with Fox
among viewers between 18 and 49 _ the only race those two networks
count _ and with CBS among viewers of any age.
</P>
<P>
   The news from two weeks ago surely raised some eyebrows, if not
hackles, at NBC. That week Fox beat NBC among those precious
18-to-49-year-olds, and last week the competition for that group,
was, to steal a quote from Dan Rather's election-night Bartlett's,
``tighter than last year's bathing suit.'' NBC edged Fox by
one-tenth of a rating point.
</P>
<P>
   For the November sweep, NBC's lead over Fox has dwindled to
four-tenths of a point.
</P>
<P>
   Most ominous is the news from Thursday, the night NBC has owned
like a birthright. Last week, Fox, relying on one of those
down-and-dirty video specials it pulls out of its crypt every sweep
month (``Shocking Moments Caught on Tape!'' _ including courtroom
brawls and a mudslide wiping out a street), drew huge numbers of
male viewers away from NBC.
</P>
<P>
   That was never possible when ``Seinfeld'' ruled the night,
because male viewers were devoted to that comedy. The same is
clearly not true for ``Frasier'' and certainly not for ``Veronica's
Closet,'' NBC's latest disappointing beneficiary of the best time
period on television.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of the other disappointments, ``Suddenly Susan'' and
``Caroline in the City,'' are now on Monday, where this week they
all but collapsed under the growing strength of CBS's comedies.
</P>
<P>
   Even though it has already merited one magazine cover
(Entertainment Weekly), ``Will and Grace'' was drubbed Monday night
by CBS's new comedy, ``Becker,'' now teamed with the emerging hit
``Everybody Loves Raymond'' as the real comedy deal on Mondays.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, ``Frasier'' and ``Veronica'' will have to contend with
perhaps the most potently lurid Fox special yet _ and certainly the
one with the best title: ``When Good Pets Go Bad.'' It features
such moments as a man with his whole head squashed in the jaws of
his ``pet'' alligator.
</P>
<P>
   Next week Fox will be back with ``Busted on the Job 3,'' with
such sights as a hotel maid trying on a guest's lingerie and a
disgruntled baker spraying pies with window cleaner.
</P>
<P>
   Fox had its own disastrous start to the season but has come back
thanks largely to the return of ``The X-Files'' on Sunday, which
easily dominated all three competitors among young adults,
especially young men.
</P>
<P>
   The ``X-Files'' did fall off sharply from its premiere rating
from a year ago _ down 27 percent _ but still beat last year's
average rating, suggesting there is still life in the show.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   A Plus: Rose's Rolodex
</P>
<P>
   ``60 Minutes II'' is the name it was given, but there is nothing
second-string about the on-air team assembled for the latest CBS
News magazine program.
</P>
<P>
   With the announcement Tuesday that Vicki Mabrey and Charlie Rose
have signed contracts, the four correspondents for ``60 II'' are in
place.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Rather, anchor of ``The CBS Evening News,'' chief
correspondent on ``48 Hours,'' author, radio commentator and former
correspondent for the original ``60 Minutes,''_ is the marquee
name.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Bob Simon, CBS News' Tel Aviv-based roving
reporter, widely regarded as one of the world's top correspondents,
and Ms. Mabrey, who joined CBS News in 1992 and has been a
correspondent in London for the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   Rose is the odd duck in that he comes not from CBS News but from
public television, where his talk show is a late-night institution
with a devoted following among intellectuals, artists, policy wonks
and newshounds. Rose will keep his show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlie Rose is one of the best interviewers out there,'' Jeff
Fager, the executive producer of ``60 II,'' said Tuesday. ``He
brings an amazing hunger for stories, which all four have in
common; he also brings an amazing Rolodex.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mabrey brings a ``fresh face,'' Fager said, while at the
same time being ``a classic `60 Minutes' choice'' because the
magazine's original correspondents all came up through the ranks of
CBS News.
</P>
<P>
   Simon is even more classic; he has done so many reports for ``60
Minutes'' that he could be mistaken for a regular correspondent
there. As for Rather, the main issue is how he will manage to fit
more work into his schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan is a workhorse like no other,'' Fager said. ``He just
doesn't stop. He's unsleeping in terms of his desire to report
stories.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-10-98 1737EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
