<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3592 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOCH-STAGE-LADN     11-10 1310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOCH-STAGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRETTY FLY FOR A WHITE GUY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; When Danny Hoch talks about ``my generation,'' as
he often does, he doesn't stammer the ``g'' the way Roger Daltrey
did on the Who's 1965 pop anthem of that name.
</P>
<P>
   Hoch, you see, doesn't put much stock in antiquated baby-boomer
references, nor could his demeanor be described in any way as
``faltering.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My generation,'' Hoch declares emphatically, ``is getting
criminalized for profit.'' His generation can get a jail sentence
easier than it can get a job. His generation doesn't go to
mainstream theater because it doesn't see itself represented there.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what my generation is up against, as a hip-hop
generation, as a hip-hop culture of resistance,'' says the
27-year-old Queens native, in Los Angeles recently to promote his
new solo show, ``Jails, Hospitals &AMP; Hip-Hop,'' which opens tonight
at the Actors' Gang in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Hoch (rhymes with rock) can talk this kind of talk all day long,
as sharp-edged and smoothly syncopated as a rap single. But it's
not just another case of gangsta-envy afflicting a Long Island
homeboy.
</P>
<P>
   A performer of multiple, ever-shifting identities, Hoch summons
characters across a wide ethnic, sexual and socioeconomic spectrum,
sampling different syntaxes like a hip-hop DJ and flipping
characterizations with the speed of an Internet Web browser.
</P>
<P>
   In his highly praised 1995 show, ``Some People,'' which ran at
the Mark Taper Forum, Hoch portrayed (among others) an
English-challenged Polish handyman, a Bronx-Jamaican dance-club
performer, a straight-outta-Jersey pseudo-yuppie and a 50-ish
Jewish matron whose rhetoric doesn't always match her liberal good
intentions.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Jails, Hospitals &AMP; Hip-Hop'' he segues from a Riker's
Island prison inmate to an Old Havana student street vendor
obsessed with American pop culture to a frustrated, disenfranchised
white Montana teen-ager and his black rapper alter-ego, Flip-Dogg.
</P>
<P>
   How did Hoch acquire his gift of tongues? You could start with
his mom, who worked as a speech pathologist at a Bronx hospital,
helping victims of car accidents and gunshot wounds reclaim their
voices. She also used to take her son to see live theater both on
and off Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Hoch continued honing his skills while training in North
Carolina and New York City, studying everything from Shakespeare to
Tennessee Williams to Sam Shepard. Somewhere along the way, he was
influenced by performance-monologist Eric Bogosian, whose wife, Jo
Bonney, is directing ``Jails, Hospitals &AMP; Hip-Hop.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoch also spent a good part of the early 1990s teaching conflict
resolution through drama to adolescents in New York City's jails
and alternative high schools with New York University's Creative
Arts Team.
</P>
<P>
   ``My director/mentor was an ex-Black Panther, and she saw
theater in a totally politicized way. And she changed my life _ I
wouldn't say just her, but this (kind of) theater changed my
life,'' he says of the experience.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the best explanation for his dexterity is that Hoch,
a fourth-generation New Yorker, spent his formative years and all
his other years in an outer-borough Babel where every day he heard
people conversing in everything from Polish- and Italian-accented
English to Trinidadian and Jamaican patois.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sort of the foundation of my upbringing and my life is based
on diversity,'' he says. Even so, Hoch still is sometimes suspected
of being a pop anthropologist, making forays into America's
cultural back streets and hauling away linguistic booty.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, a lot of people say, `Oh, where'd you get these
characters?' `How'd you start doing this?' as if I came from a
`traditional,' quote-unquote, theater background, you know, a North
American theater background, then, like, decided to delve into
ghetto storytelling, or delve into marginalized societies. This is
my generation _ these are my communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Wearing the obligatory hip-hop uniform of Mets warmup jacket and
sneakers (he also favors baseball caps worn backward or forward),
Hoch is a good-natured sort who grins and laughs easily. His one
concession to his growing celebrity seems to be a cellular phone,
which he puts aside during the 50-minute interview. Occasionally,
while mulling over a point, he rubs his ring from New York City's
High School of Performing Arts, Class of '88.
</P>
<P>
   Quick-thinking and not prone to self-censorship, he'll tell you
pretty much whatever you want to know. Some of these anecdotes, in
fact, have furnished fodder for ``Jails, Hospitals &AMP; Hip-Hop.''
</P>
<P>
   Why did he drop out of Quentin Tarantino's latest film?
</P>
<P>
   The movie, Hoch says, ``is really about nothing _ it's just sort
of glorifying everything negative about society.'' Hoch also
disliked the script's inclusion of a scene that referred to a bar
``filled with dirty greasy Mexican whores.''
</P>
<P>
   Was he disillusioned by his aborted guest-star appearance on
``Seinfeld''? (Hoch dropped out after refusing to portray a pool
attendant at Jerry's health club as a crazy Spanish-speaking guy
named Ramon.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little disillusioning,'' Hoch begins.
</P>
<P>
   Then he checks himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't disillusioning _ I take that back _ it was
liberating. Because I knew what Hollywood thinking was. I knew in
1995, before I had this `Seinfeld' episode in my life, when I was
having Hollywood meetings and I was meeting executives at Paramount
and Universal and Fox, and I was sitting down with them and they
were saying, `What do you want to do? We love you, we think you're
a great talent, what kind of movie do you want to make?' I would
tell them, and they would say, `Look, America's mostly white
people, they don't want to listen to that'.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoch immediately adds that his policy isn't to turn down
everything Hollywood offers. After all, he appears in a cameo in
Terrence Malick's soon-to-be-released World War II feature film
``The Thin Red Line,'' and just completed starring in his own movie
``White Boys,'' directed by Marc Levin. ``Jails, Hospitals &AMP;
Hip-Hop'' is also being made into a film.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal was never to get discovered and be a movie star,'' he
explains. ``My goal was to create catharsis in a theater with my
generation and my community, with stories center-stage that come
from my community and my generation.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, how's he going to get his generation into the Actors' Gang
this month?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Hoch's been working on that in conjunction with the
show's presenter, the Mark Taper Forum. Tickets are being priced at
$25, but with $10 student tickets available for all
performances. &UR;  &LR; Hoch also decided to eschew the usual high-cost
newspaper ads in favor of hiring South Central-based ``street
teams'' to pass out handbills promoting the show in areas
frequented by teen-agers and young adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a control freak,'' Hoch says. ``I just find that, at
the end of the day, if you want something done right politically,
socially and morally, you gotta do it yourself. I can't rely on the
Mark Taper Forum to do it, I can't rely on Quentin Tarantino to do
it, I can't rely on my agents.''
</P>
<P>
   Like hip-hop itself, Hoch knows he easily could turn into
another Madison Avenue commodity. He's turned down offers to make
soft-drink commercials and is confident he'll be able to resist
whatever future temptations come his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather have a kid come up to me in the street and say, `Oh
(expletive), I saw you when you came to Riker's Island. You really
made me think. That was really wow what you did, 'cause we didn't
expect to see that. It made me think about my life,' rather than
some kid come up to me and be like, `Oh, you were the guy that blew
up the token booth on `Money Train' _ that was phat`!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-10-98 1741EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981110.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3597 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEMA11-11-COX     11-10 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEMA11-11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FEMA CHIEF: HOLD HOMEOWNERS IN HIGH-RISK AREAS MORE ACCOUNTABLE
 &HT;    430 words
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By NICHOLE MONROE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Homeowners who choose to live in areas plagued by
floods and other natural disasters should be held more accountable
if they refuse to take steps toward disaster prevention, the
director of the Federal Emergency Management Agency said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   James Witt said the agency may propose to Congress a law that
would deny federal flood insurance to homeowners who have filed two
or more claims totaling more than the value of their home and who
refuse to elevate their home or accept a buyout.
</P>
<P>
   The national flood insurance program spends more than $200
million each year on properties that have been repetitively
flooded. Currently, no limit is set on the number of such claims a
homeowner can make, a FEMA spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People need to accept the responsibility and consequences of
their choice to live in high-risk areas,'' Witt said.
</P>
<P>
   He also proposed that residents in high-risk areas be charged
the fair market rate for insurance instead of the lower, subsidized
federal flood insurance rate.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Hunter of the Consumer Federation of America was critical of
that proposal. He said the government subsidizes insurance rates
for older homes, and in exchange, cities agree to control new
construction in high-risk areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that would be sort of reneging on your half of the
bargain,'' said Hunter, director of insurance for the consumer
advocacy group. ``It's not appropriate for the government to
promise something, then renege on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Witt also proposed that flood plains and wetlands be protected
from development. In the next two years, Witt proposed, cities
should strive to make sure such public buildings as city halls and
fire stations are insured for 80 percent of their replacement
value.
</P>
<P>
   Witt urged businesses, politicians, flood plain managers and
environmental groups to work together to develop strategies to
prepare for and reduce the effects of natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the know-how to reduce risks, but it means we must
change the way we think and plan and budget,'' Witt said. ``It
means instead of responding to disasters, we must do more in
prevention. It means that instead of waiting to react, we prepare
now for the next flood, the next hurricane, fire or earthquake.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal government expects to spend more than $59 million
this year on disaster assistance to Floridians affected by
hurricanes Earl and Georges, according to the FEMA office of
financial management.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, the agency expects to spend more than $74 million in
the wake of tropical storms Charley and Frances.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
