<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONDURAS-RELIEF-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MITCH STORM VICTIMS NEED MONEY, AID 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARTY RACINE 
and JEANNIE KEVER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Residents are turning out in force to donate tons of
food and medical supplies for the Central American survivors of
Hurricane Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   But the devastation is so great that the need for relief aid
will continue for months.
</P>
<P>
   Former President Bush was in Tegucigalpa, the Honduran capital,
as more than 60,000 pounds of aid from the U.S. relief group
AmeriCares arrived Sunday. He said much more would be needed for
months _ maybe years _ to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell the American people and the people of the world
that the devastation is appalling,'' Bush said after viewing the
damage.
</P>
<P>
   While many local groups are still collecting food and medicine,
national and international relief agencies are accepting only money
to buy what is needed in bulk, rather than trying to process and
ship material aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all practical purposes, the best way people can help is
through monetary donations,'' said Russell Hubbard, a spokesman for
the Greater Houston Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   People may donate through the American Red Cross International
Response Fund by calling 800-HELP-NOW (800-435-7669) or, for
Spanish speakers, 800-257-7575.
</P>
<P>
   Make checks payable to the American Red Cross International
Response Fund, earmarked for Hurricane Mitch relief.
</P>
<P>
   Other agencies requesting money:
</P>
<P>
   AmeriCares is seeking money to cover medicine and food for
people in Honduras and Nicaragua. The private, nonprofit disaster
relief and humanitarian aid organization has already sent $20
million in supplies to the area since since Hurricane Mitch hit.
</P>
<P>
   Checks marked Hurricane Mitch Relief can be sent to AmeriCares
Foundation, 161 Cherry St., New Canaan, Conn. 06840. Credit card
donations made be made by calling 800-486-HELP.
</P>
<P>
   Checks may be sent to the Salvation Army, 1500 Austin St.,
Houston 77002.
</P>
<P>
   CARE is receiving checks at 151 Ellis St. NE, Atlanta, Ga.
30303-2426, or by phone, 800-521-2273.
</P>
<P>
   Quest for Peace, a national nonprofit organization that has been
sending humanitarian aid to Nicaragua for 15 years, is accepting
checks marked Hurricane Relief at Quest for Peace, P.O. Box 5206,
Hyattsville, Md. 20782. Credit card donations can be made by
calling 301-699-0042.
</P>
<P>
   Other organizations still are collecting supplies. Many also
need volunteers to help with the work:
</P>
<P>
   The Honduran Consulate of Houston is accepting both money and
supplies, especially medications, canned goods, bottled water,
powdered milk and disposable diapers.
</P>
<P>
   Checks or money orders, payable to the Honduran Relief Fund, can
be sent to the Consulate General of Honduras, 4151 Southwest
Freeway, Suite 700, Houston 77027.
</P>
<P>
   Donations will be accepted through November and probably through
December, said spokeswoman Ludan Majia.
</P>
<P>
   The Guatemalan consulate has a collection site at 11528
Bellaire, Houston. Volunteers are needed for packing and carrying
boxes of supplies to the airport and Port of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Money donations can be deposited at Sterling Bank under account
number 021-030205, or checks marked ``Ayuda Guatamala Por Huracan''
may be mailed to the Guatemalan consulate, 3600 S. Gessner, Suite
200, Houston 77063. Consulate number: 713-953-9531.
</P>
<P>
   Before accepting any more clothing, the Nicaraguan consulate
needs additional warehouse space _ preferably at least 2,000 square
feet and accessible to volunteers on nights and weekends.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're swamped,'' volunteer Barbara Thompson said. ``We thank
everybody for what they're doing, but right now we've got a
backlog.''
</P>
<P>
   Medical supplies are desperately needed. Most needed are medical
rubber gloves, salves, ointment, adhesive bandages, Ace bandages,
anti-diarrhea medicine, antibiotics, hydrogen peroxide, burn
medicine, packaged needles, dried milk, canned formula, can openers
and baby bottles.
</P>
<P>
   Checks can be made out to the Nicaraguan Relief Fund/American
Red Cross and sent to the consulate at 6300 Hillcroft, Suite 250,
Houston, Texas 77081.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers are needed to process the donations that have poured
in to the Christian Alliance for Humanitarian Aid, which is
preparing to send help aboard the Spirit of Grace, a ship that
routinely sails mercy missions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We desperately need labor,'' volunteer Bill Warren said. ``Big
shipments (of donations) are hitting us. We have about seven
semi-trailer trucks, and about that many people to unload them.
It's just impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers can work four-hour shifts between 8 a.m. and 6 p.m.
at least through Saturday. For more information, call the alliance
at 281-412-2285.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Alliance is an ecumenical coalition of churches
and volunteers. It is working out of a warehouse at 4401 Rice Dryer
Road in Pearland, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance also is accepting donations of nonperishable food,
baby clothes, cotton diapers with pins, personal hygiene items,
drinking water, dish towels, blankets, nonprescription medicines,
sleeping bags, tents, household items and hand tools. Donations may
be dropped off at most Houston Fire Stations and the Nicaraguan
consulate at 6300 Hillcroft, Houston.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
