<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-CHARLES _ LONDON _ Britain's Prince Charles,
ever-mindful of looking like a normal guy to his subjects, launched
his own Internet Web site on Tuesday. The page, as colorful as it
is tasteful, is also interactive -- allowing for questions. It
contains everything you'd want to know about the immediate heir to
the throne. OK, well, almost everything. (Roughton, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving by 3 p.m. EST in the (i) International and (l)
Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   JOURNAL-HAITI _ PORT AU PRINCE, Haiti _ When reporters mention
Haiti, they invariably mention that it's the poorest country in the
Western Hemisphere. But what does that mean? It means that
bone-thin children play in the open sewers that twist through the
slums here. It means that most babies are born without a doctor
present. And, for this reporter, it means it's a place that's hard
to get out of your head after returning to the world's richest
country. (Emling, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Photo mug of Emling available.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving by 1 p.m. EST in the (i) International and (k)
Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   FEMA _ WASHINGTON _ James Lee Witt, director of the Federal
Emergency Management Agency, speaks at a Press Club luncheon
Tuesday to ``unveil the new face of FEMA and announce new
initiatives on repetitive losses, damage reduction and coastal
building.'' (Monroe, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-LEADERS _ WASHINGTON _ As House Republicans declare
their candidacies for leadership positions, here's a rundown on
what those jobs actually are all about: speaker, majority leader,
whip, conference chairman, policy committee chairman and campaign
committee chairman. (Malone, Cox News Service 750).
</P>
<P>
   TRACHOMA _ WASHINGTON _ Officials of the pharmaceutical firm
Pfizer Inc. announced Tuesday that they will donate millions of
doses of the drug Zithromax to treat the blinding disease trachoma
in five countries, Morocco, Mali, Ghana, Tanzania and Vietnam. The
bacterial infection causes millions of cases of blindness annually,
most of them among children. (Nesmith, Cox News Service 300)
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-REHAB _ WASHINGTON _ A group called Physician Leadership on
National Drug Policy releases results of a study on the
effectiveness of various kinds of intervention programs against
illicit drug use. (Nesmith, Cox News Service 300)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ Continuing spot coverage of the
Microsoft antitrust trial. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   VETERAN _ The macabre vision is 80 years old but remains
shockingly alive in James Lindsey's brain. On the edge of a bomb
crater, a legless German soldier sits upright in death, staring
ahead like he awaits for Lindsey's unit. The dead man's pack is
still strapped to his back, propping him up. In his pack, the
soldier carries a rotten loaf of bread and three photos: one with
three proud mustashioed men in uniform. Another has one of those
men posing with a woman and a small boy. The third has the woman
alone with the boy. ``I think it was his wife and baby,'' said
Lindsey, a reed-thin, 102-year-old Jonesboro resident who in 1918
was an artillery gunner with American Expeditionary Forces as the
Yanks blasted through a tough but sagging German Army. Feature on
Lindsey, one of a dwindling number of World War I vets, tied to
Veterans Day on Wednesday, which was originally Armistice Day,
celebrating the end of World War I. (Torpy, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   MEMORIAL _ The year was 1967. The place was the highlands of
South Vietnam. Sweating and nervous, Richard Cruz and 15 other U.S.
soldiers sat near an open field, waiting under the clear, bright 2
a.m. sky, straining for the slightest sound or sight of the enemy.
When the machine gunners who were supposed to keep watch fell
asleep, four or five Viet Cong crept up slowly on the men and began
hurling grenades into the blackness. Seconds later, shrapnel
pierced Cruz' legs, back, knees and eyes. Cruz was one of the lucky
ones _ he lost no limbs and eventually regained sight in his right
eye. But many Hays County residents lost their lives in Vietnam and
other 20th- century wars. Now, more than 30 years later, Cruz does
not want their lives forgotten. A Veteran's War Memorial in San
Marcos will list their names. His plan is to sell personalized
bricks to people and raise the money for the monument. (Rodriguez,
Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   DDN-VETERAN _ On Veterans Day, John Whitt of Springboro is
asking for help. The Air Force veteran was exposed to radiation
during above-ground nuclear testing in Nevada in the early 1950s.
As a serviceman he watched the explosions and, when on leave with
buddies, explored the mountains near Nellis Air Force Base that he
says were contaminated by radioactive fallout. Now he wants the
Veterans Administration to certify him for disability benefits but
the VA has refused three times. He says that vets like him, called
downwinders, were closer to the test explosions than American POWs
were in Japan when the U.S. dropped two atomic bombs in 1945 yet
the ex-POWs are granted disability benefits. The VA stands by its
rule that only the American prisoners of war and not other soldiers
exposed to radiation who came after them are eligible for veterans
disability benefits. (Smith, Dayton Daily News). 20. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   TALL-TX-CAPITOL_ Reports that Texas' Capitol is taller than the
dome in Washington, D.C. have been pure Texas braggadocio. Now,
Texas plans to back up its bragging rights. The State Preservation
Board is planning to measure the dome to put the matter to rest
once and for all. (Ward, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   BAXTER-COLUMN _ National political commentary by Tom Baxter of
the Atlanta Journal-Constitution. This week's subject is the
vacancy Newt Gingrich's departure leaves in Congress, and in
Georgia's 6th District. (Baxter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   DELRAY-DRUGS _ DELRAY BEACH, Fla. _ Central House, located on
the Delray Beach-Boynton Beach border, is an Alcoholics Anonymous
clubhouse. It is home to dozens of AA meetings each week _ for
women, men, beginners, alcoholics only _ and recently has become
the site of a monthly ``rave'' modeled after the ones at big-city
all-night dance clubs. Central House is also a focal point of an
unusual and vital community in southern Palm Beach County _ a
community of recovering alcoholics and drug abusers that by
experts' accounts is surprisingly large for the area's size and
suburban character. (Mnookin, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-LYNN-UNIV _ BOCA RATON, Fla. _ Donald E. Ross, president of
Lynn University, is one of the highest paid college presidents in
the nation _ and deservedly so, in the opinion of Lynn's board of
trustees. But the trustees are concerned the Internal Revenue
Service may not agree. Ross' $320,965 salary in 1996-97 _ the last
year reported _ was higher than that of the presidents of Harvard,
Massachusetts Institute of Technology and other larger, more
prestigious private universities. (Horine, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
