<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOD NOTES: THE NEW ABC FOOD HALL; DINING WITH THE ASTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It has taken six years to evolve, but ABC Food, the
new food hall at ABC Carpet and Home, 888 Broadway (19th Street),
is finally up and running. The complex, comprising nearly 14,000
square feet on three levels of the Old World knicknack-laden store,
includes a new food retail area on the lower level adjacent to the
existing Parlour Cafe, which is now a bit smaller.
</P>
<P>
   Candies and packaged sweets are on the main floor of the store,
and there is a well-stocked department for kitchenware and table
accessories a short flight above, with everything from wire whisks
to sterling silver berry spoons.
</P>
<P>
   The food hall has attracted some big-name purveyors. Murray's
Sturgeon Shop on the Upper West Side has opened a branch there,
selling excellent smoked fish and delicious pickled salmon, with
caviar supplied by Caviar Russe. There is a counter with breads
from many fine sources, including Eli's, Amy's and Sullivan Street.
</P>
<P>
   Ceriello of Williston Park, N.Y., is handling aged prime beef,
cured meats like prosciutto and mortadella, and Italian sausage,
including a delicious fresh variety made with mozzarella and
broccoli rape. Negotiations are under way for the first retail
outlet of D'Artagnan, the wild game company in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The prepared-food department is being run by Mitchel London.
There is also a well-stocked cheese department that emphasizes
imports, especially French. These departments are surrounded by
shelves that are stocked with olive oils, vinegars, condiments,
pasta and other packaged ingredients. A fresh flower stand will be
added in about a week.
</P>
<P>
   A restaurant, the decor of which was shipped in parts from
Brazil and is now being reassembled, is to open in about two months
on the lower level. It will have its own entrance on East 18th
Street, in addition to access directly from the store. Evan Cole,
ABC's president, is planning to have Jeff Salaway, an owner of the
Nick &AMP; Toni's restaurants in East Hampton, N.Y., and near Lincoln
Center, to run the restaurant and the Parlour Cafe. Salaway said
the restaurant, as yet unnamed, will feature rustic Italian and
Mediterranean food. John DeLucie is to be the chef, and Jonathan
Waxman the consultant.
</P>
<P>
   New York Food History
</P>
<P>
   In the year that celebrates the 100th anniversary of the
incorporation of New York City's boroughs, it is fitting that ``On
the Town in New York: The Landmark History of Eating, Drinking and
Entertainments From the American Revolution to the Food
Revolution,'' by Michael and Ariane Batterberry (Routledge, $30),
has been reissued. The authors added a 15-page afterword to bring
it up to date.
</P>
<P>
   The original was published in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is food documented in the book, but also restaurants,
dining practices and the movers and shakers of the city's social
scene. Its lively prose deserves a more attractive typeface and
design, and the authors do a better job covering the city's dining
and entertainment scene of 100 years ago than they do with all that
has happened in the last 25 years, an important era. But for those
who want to know how the Astors entertained or what it was like to
dine at the original Delmonico's, the book is a must.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-10-98 1801EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981110.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3635 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURT-AIRLINES-HNS &LR;      11-10 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-AIRLINES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT EXAMINES TREATY PROTECTING AIRLINES FROM LAWSUITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An Israeli airline's search of a woman and her
luggage was so intrusive and traumatic that she should be able to
sue the carrier, El Al, for $5 million for the mental anguish she
suffered, her lawyer told the Supreme Court Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   No, her illness simply resulted from an accident stemming from a
routine check, an event that barring her from seeking big damages,
airline lawyers replied during oral arguments before the justices.
</P>
<P>
   How the court decides the case could have major implications for
a 69-year-old treaty known as the Warsaw Convention, which protects
the aviation industry from massive lawsuits after airline
disasters.
</P>
<P>
   Under the 1929 Convention, passengers suffering bodily injuries
from ``accidents'' occurring during ``international air
operations'' are limited in the damages they can seek from an
airline. That cap is now about $145,000.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the aviation industry has always maintained that if
a passenger's claim falls under the Convention's criteria, that
person's case must be decided according to Convention rules.
</P>
<P>
   During Tuesday's arguments, Justice Antonin Scalia criticized
what he called the Convention's ``vague'' language _ contained in
Article 17 of the treaty _ on when an airline is liable for
damages. He asked sarcastically, ``How many smart people from how
many countries came up with this article?''
</P>
<P>
   The case stems from a May 22, 1993, incident in which Tsui Yuan
Tseng, a clinical technician in New York City, went to the John F.
Kennedy International Airport there and checked in for an El Al
flight to Tel Aviv, Israel. After asking Tseng routine questions
about the reason for her flight, El Al's security guards decided
that she was a high-risk passenger. They took her to a private room
to search for explosives.
</P>
<P>
   During the search, the guards went through Tseng's luggage in
another room. After that, they told her to remove her jacket,
sweater, shoes and belt and to loosen her blue jeans to mid-hip
level. A female guard searched Tseng's body outside her clothing
for 15 minutes and finally searched her with an electric security
wand.
</P>
<P>
   Determining that Tseng was not a security risk for the flight,
the guards escorted her to the waiting plane.
</P>
<P>
   Though she suffered no physical injury because of the search,
Tseng said she became ``really sick and very upset'' during the
flight and was ``emotionally traumatized and disturbed'' throughout
her trip to Israel and later back in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Tseng sued El Al, saying she needed the $5 million in damages to
compensate for her mental stress.
</P>
<P>
   At the U.S. District Court trial of the case in 1994, lawyers
for El Al said that if Tseng suffered any mental anguish, it was an
accident resulting from a routine security check and therefore
covered under the Warsaw Convention. This meant that she could sue
only for a maximum of $145,000.
</P>
<P>
   The airline lawyers also contended that the airline was not to
blame for the psychological trauma and not liable for any damages.
</P>
<P>
   The federal court agreed with both El Al arguments and dismissed
the case.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1997, the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit
overturned the district court's decision, ruling that the security
search could not be defined as an ``accident'' and that the
Convention did not apply to Tseng's case.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, the appeals court said, Tseng could sue El Al in a
federal court without regard to the Convention's $145,000 cap.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court did not rule on whether Tseng's mental anguish
resulted from El Al's security search.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Diane Wilson, representing El Al, told the Supreme
Court that the drafters of the Convention intended for the treaty
to cover all instances of bodily harm, including psychological
distress, occurring during international airline operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This court must follow the drafters' original intention and
overturn the appeals court's ruling,'' she insisted.
</P>
<P>
   However, Robert Silk, representing Tseng, argued that a security
search was ``certainly not an accident'' and, therefore, Tseng's
resulting mental anguish did not fall under the Convention.
</P>
<P>
   He contended that she should be allowed to pursue her case under
U.S. law allowing higher compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Silk told the justices that it would be ``absurd'' if the
Convention were to ``grant to airlines a freedom to imprison,
assault and batter their passengers, immunizing them (the airlines)
from local law requirements that they compensate their victims.''
</P>
<P>
   The case is expected to be decided this spring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
