<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCCER-CHICKEN-NEWSPAPER-LATINTRADE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW RULES FOR BRAZILIAN SOCCER; RECIPE FOR FRIED CHICKEN SUCCESS;
ANOTHER DAILY NEWSPAPER FOR MEXICO
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-996-0075 or fax at 310-996-0089; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 By KEEFE BORDEN in Rio de Janeiro; FIONA ORTIZ in Guatemala City;
and CLAIRE POOLE in Mexico City 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    NEW RULES FOR BRAZILIAN SOCCER
 &HT;    RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ Brazil's most popular pastime and
passion, soccer, now has a new governing law designed to clean up
the sport and give it a more professional image. The South American
country has dozens of professional teams in several leagues, some
of which have been caught up in scandals over the millions of
dollars the sport moves every month. With allegations that some
team executives were buying referees, gambling, laundering money,
and skimming profits, many Brazilians felt a change was in order.
The biggest proponent of the new law was Edson Arantes do
Nascimento, the former minister of sports who is more commonly
known as the great soccer legend Pele, for whom the new law was
named.
 &HT;    As originally envisioned, the new law would have enforced a
series of strict new rules governing the conduct of referees and
team executives and would have removed some disputes from the
Brazilian Football Confederation, soccer's governing body in
Brazil. The proposal, like soccer itself, raised so many
deep-seated feelings that a congressional debate on the subject
evolved into a shoving match in Congress. ``It demonstrates how
much passion soccer causes in our country,'' says Mario Drummond
Coelho, a spokesman for the sports ministry. ``From the poor to the
rich man, everybody has an opinion about soccer.''
 &HT;    Eventually, a version of the law was passed before Brazil's
national team went to defend its World Cup championship in France
earlier this summer.
 &HT;    The new law gives players in all sports protections they never
before enjoyed. While official statistics are hard to get, Drummond
says there are between 12,000 and 15,000 professional athletes in
all sports who are affected by the new law. Only a handful of those
athletes enjoy the multimillion dollar contracts that the flashiest
soccer stars have. One of the most important clauses of the new law
gives players limited rights to transfer to other clubs, something
they didn't have under old law. ``What we had in the past was like
slavery,'' he says. But the free-agency clause doesn't take effect
until February 2001, and many critics say teams are already trying
to sign long-term agreements with players before they have the
right to transfer to other teams. A second major change in the new
law gives players minimum insurance protection when they step out
onto the field to play, something only the best and highest-paid
athletes enjoyed in the past. The new law also gives players
protection from clubs that can't _ or won't _ pay them. ``Players
sometimes went for months without pay,'' Drummond says.
 &HT;    Probably the most controversial clause of the new law requires
sports clubs, as the soccer teams are known, to register as private
businesses. This clause forces clubs to adopt professional
accounting procedures to keep track of the income from ticket
sales, broadcast rights, clothing sales, and promotional fees _ and
pay taxes on them. Previously, the clubs were registered as
private, non-profit organizations, despite the huge sums of money
they took in. ``That was the biggest lie in Brazilian sports,''
Drummond says.
 &HT;    It remains to be seen how many of Brazil's soccer clubs will
respect the new law.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    RECIPE FOR FRIED CHICKEN SUCCESS
 &HT;    GUATEMALA CITY _ The smell of extra-crispy fried chicken fills
the air in the departure lounges at Guatemala's international
airport. Almost every traveler seems to be carrying a bright yellow
fast-food box decorated with a smiling chicken.
 &HT;    ``There's nothing like this in the U.S.,'' says one Guatemalan
passenger, who wrinkles his nose at the suggestion that Kentucky
Fried could be a reasonable substitute and who says his family in
the United States demands he take them Campero fried chicken when
he travels.
 &HT;    With an aggressive expansion campaign that picked up pace in the
1990s, Campero has installed 108 of its bright, clean and friendly
restaurants in the region. The Gutierrez family, which founded the
company in 1971 as an extension of the family poultry farm, owns 58
in Guatemala, 31 in El Salvador and six in Honduras. In December
the first Campero franchise opened in Panama and now there are 3
franchises in that country, five in Costa Rica, two in Nicaragua
and three in Ecuador.
 &HT;    Intense quality control and a training institute for employees,
who can achieve high school diplomas while employed by Campero, are
the top reasons for the company's success, according to executives.
 &HT;    ``We have put a lot of time, effort and money into the quality
control program, to develop a system that tells us what is
happening week to week in every restaurant,'' says Roberto Denegri,
manager of Campero's international division.
 &HT;    After an unsuccessful attempt to expand to Miami in the late
1980s, Campero plotted its new franchise expansion with great care.
Since 1992 Campero has changed its logo, redesigned its
restaurants, expanded its menu to include breakfasts and spicy
chicken sandwiches and added playgrounds and kiddie theme parties.
 &HT;    Fried chicken might not have much competition in Guatemala, but
in other countries Guatemala is up against the big guys. Profits
have been ``stupendous'' in all seven countries in recent years,
says Denegri, who declined to release specific figures.
 &HT;    ``You can measure our success by how full the restaurants are.
We're the only world class Latino chain, with table service,'' says
Denegri. ``One of the beauties of Campero is that it attracts all
type of people, from executives in ties to laborers.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ANOTHER DAILY NEWSPAPER FOR MEXICO
 &HT;    MEXICO CITY _ Hoy made quite a splash when it hit Mexico City
newsstands earlier this year.
 &HT;    The 48-page, full-color tabloid has set out to appeal to
middle-class Mexicans who are turned off by Mexico's best-selling
newspaper, the sensational La Prensa, but find Reforma, published
by the same family that produces El Norte in Monterrey, too
elitist. To do that, the new publication has hired 20 staffers away
from Reforma with double the salaries.
 &HT;    It has also plowed around $34 million into state-of-the-art
equipment and facilities, including an entire city block on Mexico
City's south side for its headquarters.
 &HT;    At first glance, the newspaper is refreshing. One of its first
issues included a story about how a man was dealing with his
friends' machismo when he lost his job and had to take care of the
house and kids while his wife went to work. A more recent issue
profiled the lives of some of the city's firefighters, exploring
the risks they face. The paper also has hands-on sections on how
economic news affects everyday citizens and reports on crime and
how citizens can safeguard themselves.
 &HT;    But after just a few months, the newspaper has failed to find
its readership. ``It's a newspaper without a personality,'' says
Raymundo Riva Palacio, an editor at Mexico City financial newspaper
El Financiero and an expert on the Mexican media.
 &HT;    Director General Miguel Canton Zetina and his editorial
director, Cruz Ulin Hernandez, didn't return calls from LATIN TRADE
seeking comment. But other officials have said that their goal is
to boost the newspaper's circulation from 50,000 at launch to
100,000 in the short term to 250,000 in the long term, putting it
in the same league as La Prensa. In a city teeming with 30-plus
newspapers, it'll be an uphill climb.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</TEXT>
