<SLUG> BC-WORKING-WOMEN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVING FOR RETIREMENT MEANS HAVING A PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILLIAN MINCER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Congratulations. You graduated in June, landed a job in
July and have by now discovered numerous ways to spend your
hard-earned paycheck.  &LR; txr:There are the basics such as rent,
clothes and food, not to mention car payments and student loans.
</P>
<P>
   With that kind of list, the last thing in the world you're
thinking about is saving for retirement, even if the people in
human resources encouraged you to sign-up for the company 401(k)
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Well think again _ especially if you're a woman.
</P>
<P>
   The national debate and recent national meetings on Social
Security, including one at Penn Valley Community College, remind us
how inadequately most of us have prepared for retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is that your pension correlates to your
salary. American women traditionally earn lower wages than men and
are less likely to be covered by an employment-based pension plan.
</P>
<P>
   Women also are less likely to participate in a 401(k) plan if it
is available. That's because the rate of employee participation
also correlates to earnings. Only 39 percent of workers earning
less than $15,000 per year participate, while 90 percent of those
earning $75,000 or more take part.
</P>
<P>
   No problem, you're thinking. There's Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes and no.
</P>
<P>
   Elderly women receive less Social Security than elderly men
because most earned less and worked fewer years.
</P>
<P>
   But even with Social Security and a pension, if you want to
retire with the same standard of living you now have, you have to
start saving early, warns Sandi Weaver, a certified financial
planner.
</P>
<P>
   Most people wait until they are in their 40s and 50s to start
planning for retirement, she said. That leaves many of them with
inadequate resources, so they are forced to work longer or cut
their standard of living when they retire.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver's solution is simple, but may not be well-received by a
society that's used to immediate gratification.
</P>
<P>
   She recommends that everyone start saving as soon as possible,
preferably from the beginning. Begin by taking advantage of the
401(k) plan at work. Start with even $25 or $50 a month and try to
increase it every year as you get a raise.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not enough. People also need to save in addition to a
401(k) plan. Often that means cutting other expenses. One of the
least painful places to cut is entertainment, Weaver said. She also
encouraged people to consider whether they should be driving a
less-expensive car and whether they should refinance their
mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver thinks people don't plan because they don't have the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Take the time before it's too late.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
