<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAIL-BREAK-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE OF SIX CAUGHT AFTER JAILBREAK AS CITY WONDERS: WHAT
HAPPENED? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN T. DAUNER and ANNE LAMOY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Kan. _ In a manhunt that straddled the state line,
three Wyandotte County, Kan., Detention Center escapees were caught
in Kansas City, Mo., on Monday afternoon, but two _ including a
convicted murderer _ remained at large.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, people throughout Wyandotte County were
wondering what had happened to pave the way for the biggest jail
break in the history of the 8-year-old facility. They were also
wondering how or why jail officials failed to act for nearly two
and a half hours after receiving a report that a prisoner might be
loose on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Wyandotte County Sheriff's supervisors suspended
three deputies for violating regulations and procedures. Sheriff
Mike Dailey refused to identify the men.
</P>
<P>
   The escapees still being sought Monday were Cleveland Henderson,
24, a convicted felon who is charged with six counts of aggravated
robbery, and Carsey Littlewood, 21, who is charged with capital
murder. Both men are Kansas City, Kan., residents.
</P>
<P>
   Captured Monday afternoon were James Crume Jr., 39, a convicted
murderer; Steven A. Ford, 17, facing sexual assault charges; and
Michael J. Enriquez, 20, charged with possession of cocaine on a
Jackson County warrant.
</P>
<P>
   The sixth escapee, James Wedlow, 16, was apprehended Sunday in
an apartment building in Kansas City, Kan. He is charged with
aggravated robbery and auto theft.
</P>
<P>
   The six inmates apparently escaped about 11 p.m. Saturday.
Dailey said the prisoners, acting at about the same time, somehow
manipulated the locks on their fifth- and sixth-floor cells and
then broke through two doors or manipulated those locks while
making their way out of the building.
</P>
<P>
   Dailey said he had found no evidence that jail personnel had
aided the inmates in their escape. By late Monday, authorities had
not been able to replicate how the prisoners manipulated the cell
and fire-door locks, the sheriff said.
</P>
<P>
   The escape left many people, including Wyandotte County District
Attorney Nick Tomasic, uneasy. ``I hope they don't hurt someone,''
Tomasic said.
</P>
<P>
   Unified Government Commissioner Bill Young, chairman of the
government's Public Safety Standing Committee, said he had faith
that Dailey would get to the bottom of the escape.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make any sense that they got through two locked
doors,'' Young said. ``It sounds like a big problem to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Manuel Palacio, the father of a young man whom Littlewood is
charged with killing, said Monday that he was considering sending
his wife and daughters to sleep with relatives. ``I fear for my
family,'' Palacio said.
</P>
<P>
   Littlewood is one of two men charged with capital murder in the
Oct. 3 slayings of Michael J. Palacio, 20, and Aldo Davila, 15,
both of Kansas City, Mo. Palacio and Davila were shot to death in
the Rosedale area of Kansas City, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Monday, police on both sides of the state line
followed up on tips from callers.
</P>
<P>
   About 6:30 a.m., someone reported that Littlewood and Henderson
were at an apartment complex in Kansas City, Kan. Officers
surrounded the complex, but the search was fruitless and ended
about 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in a cold drizzle, some apartment-complex residents
said they were frightened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just said last night, `What if they were up here?' '' said
Felicia Carson, standing outside with two small children.
</P>
<P>
   Police speculated that Littlewood may have been at the complex
because a former girlfriend lives there.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, someone informed police that Crume, Ford and Enriquez
were holed up in a house.
</P>
<P>
   They were arrested without incident inside a green, wood-frame
house. Once inside a police van, the three men could be heard
yelling. Ford, one of the last to be handcuffed, was wearing white
socks but no shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the three would remain in the custody in Kansas
City, Mo., to await extradition to Kansas City, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really, really frightening,'' said Juanita Kelton, who
lives across the street. ``I never dreamed they'd be over there.''
</P>
<P>
   About 4 p.m. Monday, a tipster reported seeing Henderson in a
Pontiac Trans Am in Kansas City, Kan. The car was painted with grey
primer and had Missouri plates, authorities said. After a short
chase, by car and on foot, the man police believed was Henderson
got away. So did the car, which another man was driving.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the escape, a normal complement of 15 to 16
deputies and supervisors was on duty. Dailey said about 11 staff
members were working on an overtime basis.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that the jail was not being run according to
regulations Saturday night. For one thing, mandatory hourly head
counts apparently were not made, the sheriff said.
</P>
<P>
   The jail is supposed to be locked down at 9 p.m. The escapees
and 38 other prisoners were in individual cells in one of two
maximum-security pods. But jail logs showed that some prisoners in
the pod were let out of their cells after lock-down to make
telephone calls, J.B. Hopkins, jail administrator, said. The
prisoners were returned to their cells after the calls, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dailey said authorities believe the escapees may have stopped
their cell doors from locking, possibly by slipping something
between the lock bolt the door jam. There also is a striker bolt on
each door that would have to be opened, and prisoners don't have
access to either lock from inside the cells, Dailey said.
</P>
<P>
   Any lock bolt that did not seat should have activated a warning
light in the jail control room but apparently did not, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Once out of their cells, the inmates jimmied the lock on a fire
door leading from the pod into an interior fire escape stairwell,
went down the stairs and broke through the lock on another fire
door to gain freedom on the north side of the building. Both fire
doors had cell type locks but were not alarmed, Dailey said.
</P>
<P>
   Dailey said jail officials recently heard that inmates were
using combs to try to manipulate locks. Deputies then went through
the jail and picked up all the combs they could find.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1992, there have been at least three incidents involving
inmates walking away or breaking out of the jail.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1992, five inmates used a smuggled hacksaw to cut steel
window bars on a fifth-floor, maximum-security cell and slid down a
makeshift rope of bed sheets. They came down on the ground-floor
roof of the district attorney's office and got away. They were
recaptured within a few days.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1996, a prisoner using a key provided by a jailer
escaped from a jail van but was shot in the back and apprehended
before he got more than 100 yards. The prisoner, a convicted rapist
named Charles Holmes, lived but was paralyzed from the waist down.
</P>
<P>
   In September, the key witness in Crume's murder case walked out
of the jail before he was officially booked in. His absence was not
discovered for about three weeks. He turned himself in the day
after his absence came to light.
</P>
<P>
   Dailey, a former major on the Kansas City, Kan., Police
Department, has been sheriff since 1995. He was appointed to
succeed a former sheriff who resigned. Dailey was elected to a
four-year term in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
