<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILTON-PAYMENT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE GAMING OFFICIALS EXAMINING $3 MILLION PAYOUT TO HILTON
DIRECTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE STEPHENS  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A director of the Hilton Hotels Corp. who
resigned during a scandal over its Kansas City casino was paid more
than $3 million after leaving the company.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri regulators plan to scrutinize the payments to Raymond
C. Avansino Jr. as part of a continuing examination of the Flamingo
Hilton casino and its relationship with the Kansas City Port
Authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a precaution, we are going to re-examine the transaction,''
said Mel Fisher, executive director of the Missouri Gaming
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson County Prosecutor Claire McCaskill also is investigating
dealings between Hilton and the Port Authority, which controls the
site of the Flamingo Hilton riverboat. She would not say Monday
whether her office would also look into the payments to Avansino.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our investigation will be as broad as it needs to be,''
McCaskill said.
</P>
<P>
   A Hilton spokeswoman confirmed the payment to Avansino. She
declined to provide details, however, and would not say whether two
Hilton executives who resigned with Avansino received similar
payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really don't comment on compensation issues,'' said the
spokeswoman, Kathy Shepherd.
</P>
<P>
   Avansino could not be reached for comment Monday. He resigned in
1996 after disclosing that he approved paying $250,000 to a company
linked to Kansas City Port Authority Chairman Elbert Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Anderson has been convicted of unrelated charges of
bribing a City Council member and a chairman of the Jackson County
Legislature. Anderson is now cooperating with federal
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Hilton and its subsidiaries agreed to pay the federal
government $655,000 to avoid criminal charges that their $250,000
grant was designed to reward Anderson for his support for the
casino. Federal prosecutors contend a Hilton employee, whom they
have not named, agreed to a total payment of $1.25 million to
secure Anderson's vote.
</P>
<P>
   McCaskill began investigating this fall, at the request of the
gaming commission. She said Monday she was looking into whether
bribery charges should be filed under state law.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press has reported that Hilton documents
described the payments to Avansino as compensation for ``unvested
stock options.'' The company also allowed Avansino to keep a
company car and unspecified ``other equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   Shepherd declined to elaborate on the report, but said Hilton
disclosed the payments to its stockholders more than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Steve Hill Jr. has said prosecutors did not pursue
charges against individual Hilton employees because none of them
benefited personally and because none still worked for Hilton.
</P>
<P>
   Hilton's agreement with federal prosecutors shows that in 1993,
Anderson arranged for Hilton to pay $250,000 to K.C. Perspectives.
The company was owned by an Anderson business associate, Michelle
Lathan.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors called the payments a ``reward'' to Anderson,
designed to ``influence his future support as Port Authority
chairman.''
</P>
<P>
   An attorney for Anderson declined to comment. A lawyer for
Hilton has said the corporation did nothing wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Gaming Commission officials said Monday that they knew
Avansino held stock options when he resigned. But they were unaware
when he cashed them in, or how much he received.
</P>
<P>
   Avansino is a former casino regulator from Nevada and, until
November 1995, was president of Hilton.
</P>
<P>
   F. Michael O'Brien, who resigned about the same time, was
executive vice president of Hilton Gaming Corp. and was the Hilton
executive who appeared to have had the most contact with Anderson
about the grant. The third Hilton official who resigned was Mark
Rousseau, senior vice president for development at Hilton Gaming
Corp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-10-98 1813EST &QL; 
