A3687 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPOSTERSON-840(2Take     11-10 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPOSTERSON-840(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPOSTOR TURNS MOM'S JOY AT SEEING SON TO ANGUISH
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Canada points note) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GABRIELLE CRIST 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The mother walked nervously toward Gate 42
at Dallas/Fort Worth Airport, her eyes scanning the crowd for the
son she had not seen in 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   She had not held him in her arms since he was a baby, and had
had only sporadic contact with him over the years. Hoping that a
reunion would erase the emptiness she felt, she'd hired a private
investigator in Canada to contact the boy and arrange a meeting.
</P>
<P>
   There he is, she thought, spotting a teen who was looking her
way. But as she drew closer, her heart started racing.
</P>
<P>
   This was not the boy Sheila Powell had seen in the photographs.
He wasn't tall and skinny. He didn't have big ears.
</P>
<P>
   Still, they hugged and she kissed his cheek, then invited him to
her home in Fort Worth. She had to know who he really was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put on an act that would have won an Oscar,'' Powell said.
``I had to because I had to find out what these people were up
to.''
</P>
<P>
   She finally learned the boy's true identity, and a story of
deception, desperation and a mother's fragile hopes of reuniting
with her son unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   It is a story so bizarre that it's hardly believable.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Powell was 22 and living in North Carolina when she met her
husband-to-be, Generoso Moccia, in 1979 through an ad in the
National Examiner tabloid. Within months, they were married and
living in Chatham, Ont.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was as sweet as he could be,'' Powell recalled, seated in
the living room of her small home on McCart Avenue. Within a year,
they had a son, Salvatore Moccia.
</P>
<P>
   Thumbing through her wedding album, she told how marital bliss
quickly turned to bitterness. Within three years, the couple were
getting divorced.
</P>
<P>
   Custody documents filed Aug. 6, 1981, by Generoso Moccia refer
to testimony by Powell that she had been hospitalized after a
beating by her husband and had undergone psychiatric treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to reach Generoso Moccia for this article were
unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband was seeking temporary custody of their son, and on
June 29, 1981, during a visit, Powell took Sal and fled to North
Carolina. Two months later, a Canadian court ordered that Powell
return her son to her ex-husband in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could not afford to go back and fight him,'' said Powell,
42, who stays at home to care for another son who is 14. ``I didn't
know how to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell went on with her life, had another son and, in 1986, got
married and moved to Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, when Sal was 12, Powell called to tell her son that his
maternal grandmother had died. She said she wanted to have a
relationship with him, and he seemed amenable.
</P>
<P>
   Sal wrote to her, told her about his friends and his favorite
subjects in school. He signed his name and drew a big heart around
it.
</P>
<P>
   Within weeks, he wrote again, but this letter was different.
</P>
<P>
   ``You said anything I wanted you would buy it and send it to me
by airmail. Well, here's what I want and you better send it to me
or I won't come to Texas,'' states the letter, which Powell keeps
in a cardboard box filled with her life's mementos.
</P>
<P>
   He then listed his demands: a jackknife, two brass knuckles, two
slingshots, two Swiss Army knives, a pair of nunchaku, a
basketball, a wallet, a watch, a big squirt gun and a BB gun, to
name only a few.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would make up for all the birthdays you missed if you buy
me this stuff,'' the letter says. ``I won't talk to you on the
phone until I get the stuff I want in the mail. I mean it.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell wrote her son a letter and told him not to expect any
airmail packages.
</P>
<P>
   Their contact ended.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Powell received an anonymous letter from Canada with
several recent pictures of her son. It told Powell where her son
was living and going to school.
</P>
<P>
   ``You must not let anyone know we are helping you,'' stated the
letter, signed ``your guardian angel.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell called the school and asked the vice principal how her
son was doing. He sent Sal's most recent photograph.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
