</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSWEEK-EDITOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITAKER NAMED EDITOR OF NEWSWEEK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mark Whitaker, who was penciled in as Newsweek editor even
before the death of the legendary Maynard Parker last month, was
formally _ and predictably _ named to the post Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Though the 41-year-old Whitaker will be the first black editor
of a major national newsweekly, that distinction was downplayed
both by media observers and by Whitaker himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud and honored about all that,'' said Whitaker, who
began at the magazine as a student intern in 1977. ``But my goal is
to be the best possible editor of Newsweek, not just the best
possible black editor.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker had handled day-to-day editing duties along with
chairman and editor in chief Richard Smith since Parker was
hospitalized earlier this year with leukemia, which led to his
death from complications from pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
   So Whitaker clearly had the inside track in a field of
candidates that included Washington bureau chief Ann McDaniel,
international editions editor Michael Elliott, and assistant
managing editor Evan Thomas. McDaniel and national affairs editor
Jon Meacham were both named managing editors Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not a surprise within the building,'' said Jonathan
Alter, a Newsweek senior editor and columnist who has known
Whitaker since their days on the daily Crimson at Harvard, where
Whitaker graduated summa cum laude in 1979 and won a Marshall
Scholarship to Oxford. ``People were very happy that it was made
official. There was a big round of applause.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker, who had been managing editor since January 1996, is a
classic insider at a magazine that values loyalty. He had his
ticket punched at all the requisite stops _ six years as an
international writer, four years as business editor, five as
assistant managing editor, and two as managing editor.
</P>
<P>
   He directed the magazine's coverage of the 1987 Wall Street
crash, Princess Diana's death, and the Monica Lewinsky scandal and
also wrote occasional essays on race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark clearly has the experience, drive, character, and good
judgment to lead Newsweek into a very successful future,'' said
Smith, who will work with Whitaker on strategic issues and
long-range editorial planning.
</P>
<P>
   Newsweek, which trails archrival Time by nearly a million copies
(3.2 million to 4.1 million) in the subscription war, has been
trying to close the gap in recent years by jumping on big stories
and writing edgy pieces on both pop and computer culture.
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker, who launched the magazine's monthly Focus on
Technology section and its weekly Cyberscope page, said that he
wanted to expand Newsweek's emphasis on science, the global
ecnonomy, personal finance, and family issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll continue to cover the major stories as aggressively as
possible,'' said Whitaker. ``We'll continue to scramble the jets in
the Maynard Parker tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Scrambling the jets'' was Parker's term for his willingness to
tear the magazine apart near deadline and order up a fresh cover
story to stay abreast of the news.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when the newsweeklies are struggling to compete in the
24-hour world of cable news and the Internet, Whitaker said
Newsweek needs to find ways to remain timely and relevant,
especially to younger readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want our readers to have an emotional attachment to the
magazine,'' Whitaker said. ``I don't want it to sit on a coffee
table or a nightstand as homework.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
