<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3704 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      11-10 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE'LL BE MISSED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When they come down out of the clouds,
congressional Democrats will be sorry they crowed about the
precipitous downfall of incendiary House Speaker Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   They are going to miss him like crazy.
</P>
<P>
   Who else can raise money for the Democrats by the truckload? Who
else's name, enunciated with proper scorn, is guaranteed to inflame
Democratic audiences the way Sen. Edward Kennedy's name arouses
Republican crowds?
</P>
<P>
   Who else drives voters to the polls to support Democrats just to
keep his offensive noise level down? Who else is so low in the
polls he makes even used car salesmen seem like pristine pillars of
society?
</P>
<P>
   Who else indeed, except Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly not that pragmatic, careful and until now nationally
obscure fellow, Rep. Bob Livingston, R-La., the prospective new
House speaker. Lacking Gingrich's perpetually Mephistophelian
smile, the Livingston visage is tightly controlled and absent of
political mischief.
</P>
<P>
   It might take ages to build Livingston into a worthwhile villain
capable of producing Democratic campaign contributions, and indeed
it may never be possible if he proves to be as responsible as he is
currently portrayed.
</P>
<P>
   Former Speaker Jim Wright can now gloat. He's the Texas Democrat
hounded from office by ethics charges leveled primarily by
then-minority-backbencher Gingrich that were similar to charges
later leveled against Gingrich himself. A Gingrich who lives by the
partisan sword deserves political death by the partisan sword.
</P>
<P>
   But other Democrats should think twice about what losing
Gingrich means in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   He will never again be the provocative powerhouse he was as
speaker _ despite the fanciful theory that he may now run for
president since he is free to be himself without the burdensome
accountability of public office. Being himself helped to produce a
conservative congressional revolution four years ago, but both he
and the revolution are exhausted, and it won't work twice.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich insists that although momentarily jobless he will
remain publicly visible and active in politics. He has long hinted
that he envisions himself in the White House. Fortunately, not many
other people have that vision.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich as recycled gadfly will pop up in our consciousness
from time to time, mostly when he indulges his most outrageous
ideas. But it is difficult to imagine that he will ever be taken
seriously again. He had the ultimate power to make public policy
and lost it. He is just another political face, scaring no one.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich is not comparable to defeated GOP presidential
candidate Bob Dole, who earned the national approval of his party
if not the country. Gingrich was a product of an elite, closed GOP
circle in the House, with narrow interests and a narrow perspective
not necessarily reflective of the country.
</P>
<P>
   But we knew he was on his way out when he pushed his second
book, ``Lessons Learned the Hard Way,'' with a cover photograph in
which he looked oddly cozy and lean in jeans and a leather jacket.
He was trading the old fire for a more conventional pose. The book,
and his makeover, didn't find a market. We knew too much about the
old Newt, whom we considered the real Newt.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, whose relationship with
Gingrich ranged from poor to poorest, will be more at home with a
fellow pragmatist like Livingston. But the partisan contrast
necessary to win elections may be more difficult to draw with
Gingrich out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   If Gephardt and Livingston are happily cutting backroom deals
all day, how are voters to know the winners from the losers? Oh,
dear.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich was a wonderful symbol of everything Republicans loved
and Democrats loathed.
</P>
<P>
   But we in the media will miss him too. Journalists thought he
was a terrific story, no matter what else we thought of him.
Actually, we helped to do him in.
</P>
<P>
   Americans like to personalize politics, and so when we see an
individual who is erratic, colorful, fearless _ and interesting _
we overexpose him or her. The shelf life of political shockers is
not very long, as Minnesota Gov.-elect Jesse Ventura may soon
discover.
</P>
<P>
   We voters say we want our politicians to be outspoken and frank
and totally independent. But we don't really. We like them to be
comfortable, safe, in the middle of the road where they can't roll
off into the ditch and take us with them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-10-98 1826EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
