<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3749 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPOSTERSON-2ndTake-T     11-10 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPOSTERSON-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
FORT WORTH, Texas: most recent photograph. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Then Powell recruited the help of private investigator Gary
Cummings, who had been referred to her by the Chatham-Kent Police
Department in Ontario. She was broke, so Cummings allowed her to
set up a payment plan and started searching for Sal without any
money upfront.
</P>
<P>
   Cummings said he quickly found Sal and persuaded him to go to
Texas and meet his mom.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring his work was worthy of a little publicity, Cummings
contacted the local newspaper and pitched the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teen Reunites with Mom,'' read the headline in the Chatham
Daily News. There, on page 6 of the Aug. 17 paper, was a picture of
the private eye and a teen-ager shaking hands with the town's
police chief. The photo was taken just before the trip to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, Powell waited anxiously.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I wanted to do was just take care of him and love him and
get him to stay in Texas,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But when she saw the boy and a friend sitting at the gate, her
hopes sank.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said it was nice to meet me after all these years,'' Powell
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   At her house, she tried to get the boy alone, hoping she could
somehow trick him into confessing that he was not Sal.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Powell dropped off the teens and an investigator
who had accompanied them in downtown Fort Worth, where they said
they wanted to hang out. While they were gone, she looked at the
boys' plane tickets: Neither had been issued to a Salvatore Moccia.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours, the investigator called to say that he and the
teens were cutting their trip short. Still, when the trio returned
for the boys' backpacks, Powell didn't confront them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have just told them right then and there, but I
didn't,'' she said. ``I don't know why I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, Powell called Sal's school. Someone told her
they had seen the article _ and the picture _ in the local
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   But the boy identified as Sal Moccia in the picture was actually
Dan Laflamme, 17, a friend of Sal's who had been kicked out of
school.
</P>
<P>
   Laflamme, who has a criminal history that includes armed
robbery, said that he and Sal had planned to go to Texas but that
Sal changed his mind the day before they were supposed to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Laflamme said Cummings asked him to step in for Sal. Powell
would never know the difference, Laflamme said he was told.
</P>
<P>
   Cummings offered $1,000 for the job, Laflamme said.
</P>
<P>
   The plan seemed easy enough, Laflamme said, and it included a
free trip to Texas. But as he waited at the gate for Powell to
arrive, Laflamme started getting nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking: `I don't want to do this. I want to go
home,''' Laflamme said.
</P>
<P>
   Laflamme, now a busboy and dishwasher at a Chinese restaurant,
said he hopes he can someday apologize to Powell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to say that I didn't realize that it would affect her
like that,'' he said. ``I'm young. It just seemed like fun at
first.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Cummings said it is he who has been conned. He
said Laflamme learned that he was looking for Sal and began posing
as Sal from the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I paid him nothing,'' said Cummings, who says Powell owes him
$1,800 for his services. ``I am not happy with the fact this
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   After being reached by phone, Sal Moccia would not comment for
this article. Before he hung up, he said he does not want to see
his mother.
</P>
<P>
   Powell said she is convinced that her ex-husband has
``brainwashed'' Sal and said she won't give up trying to see him.
</P>
<P>
   She repeatedly calls the police chief, the Chatham newspaper,
Sal's school and her son. She has also called TV talk shows to see
whether any are interested in her story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want somebody to look at me and tell me they are
sorry,'' Powell said. ``It all started because I placed an ad for a
husband.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Gilbert, the vice principal at Sal's school, said Powell
should leave her son _ and any hope of a reunion _ alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's doing herself more harm than good.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
