<HEADER>
A3767 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MITCH-WARNING-HNS &LR;      11-10 1493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MITCH-WARNING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MITCH EXPLODES MYTHS ABOUT HURRICANES, SHOWS NEED TO RE-EVALUATE
WARNING SYSTEMS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By EDWARD HEGSTROM 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PESPIRE, Honduras _ With a major mountain range and 150 miles
lying between them and the Caribbean Sea, the people of this quaint
colonial village never thought they would be hit by Hurricane
Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   They were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Torrential rains carried by Mitch swelled the Pespire River and
swept away an entire neighborhood of 300 homes in the lower part of
town.
</P>
<P>
   At least 15 people died in the hamlets that lie in the hills
outside town, where warnings of the storm couldn't get through.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we were too far away to have all this damage,''
said Pedro Martel, a native of Pespire, a town with tidy
cobblestone streets, adobe homes and a gleaming white church.
``We're close to the Pacific, not the Caribbean'' where Mitch
stalled for days just off the Honduras coast.
</P>
<P>
   The people of Pespire weren't the only ones caught off-guard. By
reaching at least 200 miles inland and wreaking havoc in the
mountains of southern Honduras and northern Nicaragua, Mitch
exploded a number of myths about hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom suggests that hurricanes do most of their
damage when heavy winds attack the coastline. But Mitch and a
number of other recent hurricanes show that storm systems can
sometimes be more deadly when heavy rains fall in mountains
hundreds of miles inland.
</P>
<P>
   After watching the devastation from Mitch, even some of the
world's top hurricane experts acknowledge they may need to
re-evaluate how they go about warning people of potential
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still a little anchored to this idea that the first
thing is to get people away from the coast,'' said Jerry Jarrell,
the director of the National Hurricane Center in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The potential for massive death in the highlands is ``probably
an issue that gets overlooked,'' he said, noting that after
watching the effect of Mitch he will begin think of possible
changes to the way the service warns about hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Mitch cause most of its damage after it had been
downgraded from a hurricane to a tropical storm, but it also killed
more than 4,000 people in neighboring Nicaragua, a country that
received little direct warning of the catastrophic flooding coming
its way. ``We didn't think it was going to come to Nicaragua,''
said Mauricio Rosales, the head of the Nicaraguan government's
meteorology department. ``They U.S. hurricane officials didn't warn
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrell acknowledges that Nicaragua might not have received
enough attention. ``I'm not sure we did that much for them,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no one can say that the National Hurricane Center ignored
the potential for problems in the hills.
</P>
<P>
   While predicting that the storm would likely move northwest
toward Belize or Mexico, the service also gave ample warning about
possible problems in the hills.
</P>
<P>
   One early warning from Oct. 27 noted that heavy rains in the
mountains of Honduras and other parts of Central American ``could
cause life-threatening flash floods and mud slides.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, U.S. hurricane experts note that each nation has
responsibility to warn its own citizens, and weather experts within
the country need to study how a storm might affect their own
territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things vary depending on the country,'' said Chris
Landsea, a hurricane researcher at the National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Association. ``The individual weather services need to
tailor their advisories based on their own terrain.''
</P>
<P>
   Though it is funded entirely by U.S. taxpayers, the National
Hurricane Center provides storm-warning services to all of the
Caribbean and Latin America under an international system.
</P>
<P>
   In other parts of the world, Japan, Australia, India and other
countries share in paying for the monitoring system.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrell said the system was established under U.S. leadership
because other countries simply couldn't afford the sophisticated
satellites and airborne reconnaissance required to predict
hurricane movements.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is required to give the other countries
three-day forecasts of a storm's potential movements. When a
hurricane seems likely to hit, the U.S. advises that the target
country to issue a hurricane warning.
</P>
<P>
   The system generally works, but there are problems.
</P>
<P>
   Few people at the National Hurricane Center speak Spanish, and
the forecasters from Central America often do not speak English.
</P>
<P>
   At times, the hurricane center has trouble even making contact.
In one crucial period, hurricane center meteorologists were unable
to reach weather officials in Honduras for nine hours, according to
Jarrell.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that we had trouble contacting them suggests they are
not very well equipped,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hector Flores, the director of the Honduran National
Meteorological Service, denies that he was ever out of contact with
the hurricane experts in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the hurricane disaster response system is
based on a fairly basic principal: Predict where the storm will hit
and evacuate people from the coastline.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane center's warnings have worked remarkably well,
particularly in the case of Hurricane Andrew, which hit South
Florida in October of 1992. Evacuations from greater Miami probably
saved thousands of lives, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom says that a hurricane is most deadly right
along the lowlands of the coast. The powerful winds at the center
of the tempest push the ocean forward into a bulge, causing the sea
level to rise by up to 15 feet _ a phenomenon known as a ``storm
surge.''
</P>
<P>
   When the storm surge hits the coast, lowland areas are entirely
submerged under the pounding surf and the driving wind, a lethal
combination.
</P>
<P>
   Most the deaths in the more powerful hurricanes, such as the one
that devastated Galveston in 1900, occur when the storm surge hits
the coast.
</P>
<P>
   But the traditional system of evacuating the coastline is not
enough in the Caribbean and Central America, where rugged mountains
rise almost at the edge of the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   When hurricanes collide against those mountains, heavy rains can
cause catastrophes hundreds of miles from the storm center. Even
the way scientists measure the strength of a hurricane can be
deceptive when it comes to predicting impacts in the Caribbean
basin.
</P>
<P>
   The strength of a storm is measured by its winds, a crucial
factor in lowland areas like Florida. But the system doesn't
measure the potential for rain, which is the key factor in
mountainous regions.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most deadly storms in recent Caribbean history were
not ranked as particularly strong tempests by the hurricane
center's measurement system.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrell offers the example of Hurricane Gordon, a relatively
minor storm that hit Haiti in 1994. Yet the storm took 1,500 lives
in the highlands of the country.
</P>
<P>
   A minor tropical storm moved in to southernmost Mexico just last
summer. The storm caused little fuss until it passed over the
mountains of Chiapas, causing floods that killed more than 200
people.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Mitch is the deadliest recent example by far. At one
point, the storm ranked as class 5 hurricane on a scale of 1 to 5.
Though the storm hovered off Honduras, the National Hurricane
Center predicted that it was likely to move northwest, hitting
Belize or Yucatan.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the storm camped along the coast off Honduras, where it
lost most of the force of its winds. Much of the damage came from
flooding and mudslides after the downgraded storm moved slowly over
the mountains. Mitch's track meandered into El Salvador and
Guatemala before circling once again over the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all of the damage in Honduras and Nicaragua was caused
by rain rather than wind. In some parts of mountainous Honduras,
the storm dumped more than 20 inches of rain in six hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect that when the storm started to weaken, people put
their guard down,'' said Jarrell.
</P>
<P>
   But he noted that his office warned Honduran officials to stay
alert. By the time the storm reached southern Honduras, local
political leaders only had limited time to warn the people.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Pespire, officials heard radio reports of impending
floods and evacuated the lower part of town before the river swept
away the homes.
</P>
<P>
   But in other parts, people weren't quite so lucky. A few miles
upstream in the hamlet of La Rampa, the people only learned of the
flooding by watching the river rise.
</P>
<P>
   When the river swelled up over its banks in a matter of a few
hours on Oct. 30, the people ran out of their homes and headed for
the hills, with no protection from the pouring rains.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't take anything out of our homes,'' said Fredy
Ortez, who lived in one of 30 homes swept away. ``There wasn't
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The river left us poor.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
