<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DRUG COURTS REDUCE RE-ARREST RATES, STUDIES SAY
 &HT;    525 words
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Drug-use intervention initiatives in which arrested
offenders are ``coerced'' or guided into treatment programs
significantly reduce re-arrest rates, according to a series of
studies released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Drug arrests in America more than doubled between 1980 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Studies commissioned by an organization known as Physician
Leadership on National Drug Policy concluded that ``drug courts''
and structured treatment programs for prison inmates, teen-age
offenders and parolees dramatically reduce prison recidivism and
drug-abuse relapses.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation-funded organization is made up of 37 physicians,
including former Health and Human Services Secretary Louis Sullivan
of Atlanta, former Food and Drug Administration Commissioner David
Kessler and Antonia Novello, surgeon general during the Bush
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``This field is in an evolving stage,'' said Lonnie Bristow,
vice chair of the physicians' group and a former president of the
American Medical Association. ``We need more serious research and
ongoing evaluations of existing programs to determine which
programs work best for whom and how to sustain them.''
</P>
<P>
   The studies were conducted by researchers from universities and
private study institutes, including Columbia University in New
York, Texas Christian University in Fort Worth, the Rand Corp. and
the University of California, Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers presented results of the commissioned studies at a
daylong meeting Tuesday in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   TCU researchers D. Dwayne Simpson and Kevin Knight said a
comparison of former prison inmates enrolled in long-term
residential treatment centers showed drug-use rates declined by 67
percent for cocaine users, 65 percent among heroin users and 53
percent among heavy drinkers.
</P>
<P>
   Simpson and Knight also concluded that 27 percent of former
inmates who complete the ``after-care'' programs are arrested
again, compared with more than 75 percent of formerly incarcerated
drug offenders who receive no treatment.
</P>
<P>
   A Rand Corp. study of drug courts in Multnomah County, Calif.,
concluded the alternative courts produced savings of $10.2 million
in avoided criminal justice system expenses, theft reduction,
public assistance and medical claims.
</P>
<P>
   The ``drug court'' concept, in which defenders, prosecutors and
judges work together to coerce offenders into treatment programs,
has spread rapidly in recent years as local and state governments
search for ways to reduce the cost of dealing with drug offenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is that, when drug treatment is available in the
criminal justice system, it works,'' said David C. Lewis, director
of the Center for Alcohol and Addiction Studies at Brown University
in Rhode Island and project director of the physicians' group.
``The bad news is that it's usually not available.''
</P>
<P>
   Physician Leadership on National Drug Policy is funded by the
John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation and the Robert Wood
Johnson Foundation. It is chaired by June Osborn, president of the
Josiah Macy Jr. Foundation and former chair of the National AIDS
Commission during the Bush administration.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
