<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The 21-nation Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation
forum will meet from Nov. 17-18 in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia to
discuss major trade issues. But what will be foremost on the minds
of many is how to bring the region -- and Russia -- out of a the
malaise that it has been in for 17 months, and is threatening the
global economy.
</P>
<P>
   Following are thumbnail economic profiles of all of the
countries:
</P>
<P>
   UNITED STATES
</P>
<P>
   Geography: Area, 3.5 million sq. mi.; Capital, Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 266.5 million
</P>
<P>
   Government: Democratic republic
</P>
<P>
   Economy: GDP, $7.576 trillion (1996)
</P>
<P>
   Trade: Exports, $855.2 billion; Imports, $953.9 billion (1996)
</P>
<P>
   Currency: American dollar
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRALIA
</P>
<P>
   Geography: Area, 3 million sq. mi., about the size of the 48
continental U.S.; Capital, Canberra.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 18.7 million
</P>
<P>
   Government: Democratic, federal-state system recognizing British
monarch as sovereign.
</P>
<P>
   Economy: GDP $350 billion
</P>
<P>
   Trade: Exports, $56 billion (1997); Imports, $59 billion (1998)
</P>
<P>
   Currency: Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
   BRUNEI DARUSSALAM
</P>
