<SLUG> BC-THIRD-BLIND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PFIZER SAYS DRUG CAN HALT DISEASE THAT BLINDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A major US pharmaceutical manufacturer and a New York foundation
Tuesday initiated a $66 million effort to attack a bacterial
disease virtually unheard of in developed countries that has left
nearly 6 million Third World residents blind and 146 million others
infected.
</P>
<P>
   A one-gram dose of an antibiotic called Zithromax given just
once a year can treat the disease, trachoma, an infection of the
upper eyelid caused by the chlamydia bacterium. People infected
develop painful, running sores on their eyelids that leave crusty
deposits on the eyelashes that, over time, scratch away their
corneas and leave them blind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like having sand in your eye all the time,'' said Heather
Lauver, assistant manager of corporate philanthropy for drugmaker
Pfizer Inc., which is teaming with the Edna McConnell Clark
Foundation on the project.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the International Trachoma Initiative will seek to
eradicate trachoma in five countries, most likely Ghana, Mali,
Morocco, Tanzania, and Vietnam, identified by Harvard School of
Public Health researcher Michael Reisch as the most promising
candidates for a nationwide medical program.
</P>
<P>
   Trachoma has been found in dozens of countries, particularly in
sub-Saharan Africa, Indochina, and Iran, as well as parts of
Mexico, Brazil, and Australia. An estimated 540 million people are
at risk of developing trachoma.
</P>
<P>
   To support the program, Pfizer is donating $58 million worth of
Zithromax, and the company and the foundation are each putting in
more than $3 million to manage a comprehensive plan to eradicate
the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Besides administering the antibiotic to hundreds of thousands of
people, the project will also fund eyelid repair surgery for people
with advanced trachoma, improved access to clean water and health
education, and campaigns to get people to wash their faces daily to
reduce the risk of transmission. Insects attracted to running eye
sores also spread it from person to person.
</P>
<P>
   ``Concerted efforts using this strategy could readily eradicate
the world's leading cause of preventable blindness,'' said Dr.
Alfred Sommer, dean of the Johns Hopkins University School of
Hygiene and Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   The effectiveness of Zithromax, which was introduced in 1992 and
has become the leading antimicrobial medicine in the United States,
as a cure for trachoma was shown in a 1996 study involving 10,000
Moroccans.
</P>
<P>
   The standard treatment for trachoma has involved a six-week
cycle of two daily applications of ointment. ``It's painful, and
there are a lot of problems with noncompliance,'' said Dr. Mike
Magee, Pfizer's senior medical adviser.
</P>
</TEXT>
