<HEADLINE>
AIG EXECUTIVE CHOSEN TO HEAD MASSMUTUAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In a change that portends more than a shift in
executive positions, Massachusetts Mutual Life Insurance Co.
Tuesday named a senior official from competitor American
International Group Inc. to its top post.
</P>
<P>
   Robert J. O'Connell, who headed AIG's US life insurance
business, will succeed Thomas B. Wheeler as chief executive of the
Springfield, Mass. insurer. Wheeler, who is retiring, said the
shift was designed to allow MassMutual, the nation's 11th largest
life insurer, to undertake a host of strategic initiatives,
including acquisitions and possible conversion to a new corporate
form.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob isn't going to do anything at the moment,'' Wheeler, 62,
said. ``He's going to sit and learn about the company and then make
some changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler said O'Connell, 55, would seek to grow MassMutual by
buying companies, possibly overseas, and to decide whether the
firm, nominally owned by its policyholders, should convert to a
mutual holding company, issue stock, or remain as it is. O'Connell
would also consider how to grow MassMutual's asset management
business, also through acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to look at external growth as well as internal
growth,'' said Wheeler, who is staying on as board chairman.
O'Connell also bears the title of president. He was traveling and
unavailable to comment.
</P>
<P>
   MassMutual also said that president and chief operating officer
John J. Pajak, 63, was stepping down after 41 years of service. The
chief operating post will remain vacant.
</P>
<P>
   MassMutual, the second largest insurer in Massachusetts after
John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co., has considered taking its
$88.5 billion OppenheimerFunds Inc. mutual funds unit public. It
considered a merger with Milwaukee's Northwestern Mutual Life
Insurance Co. earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   The life insurance industry on which MassMutual focuses has seen
slumping sales and grown more competitive. But MassMutual is one of
few mutually owned firms to have a triple A rating from Standard &AMP;
Poor's, the ratings agency.
</P>
<P>
   MassMutual, with a total $160 billion in assets under
management, including $63 billion of its own, is the parent of
David L. Babson Co. &AMP; Inc., a Cambridge, Mass.money management
firm, and Cornerstone Real Estate Advisers Inc., of Hartford, Conn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
