<SLUG> BC-CHINA-RIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA CRACKS DOWN ON UNREGISTERED CHURCHES, RIGHTS GROUP SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Chinese authorities have detained 140 Protestants and
severely beaten more than a dozen church leaders in the last few
weeks, a New York-based human rights organization said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The incidents occurred in Henan province in an area known to
have many ``house churches.'' These are often run by evangelical
Protestant groups that have refused to register with the
government, so members worship furtively in homes rather than in
state-sponsored churches.
</P>
<P>
   David Zhang, identified as a spokesman for China's house
churches, has sent a letter protesting the arrests to a number of
leaders and groups both in the West and in China, the group Human
Rights in China said in releasing the letter.
</P>
<P>
   Zhang, who was born in China but now lives in the United States,
said he knew some of those detained. ``The situation is very
dangerous for these people,'' he said in a telephone interview from
California.
</P>
<P>
   Zhang said that 40 worshipers at a house church were arrested
Oct. 26 in the city of Wugang and that more than 100 were detained
Nov. 5 in Nanyang. In both cases, the leaders of the house churches
were beaten and tortured and are still being held, he said. Other
worshipers were detained and released.
</P>
<P>
   ``These two acts are not isolated,'' Zhang wrote in the letter
he sent to President Clinton, Amnesty International and China's
Cabinet, among others. ``In the next two months there will be more
acts of religious persecution throughout the country.''
</P>
<P>
   China requires that all churches register with the government,
and in the last few years has stepped up its efforts to ensure
compliance. Once their congregations accept this constraint,
mainstream Protestants have relative freedom to worship.
</P>
<P>
   But the unregistered house churches, which tend to be relatively
small with a variety of beliefs, are under surveillance and suffer
frequent harassment, particularly at the hands of local officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Officially, policies on religion are fairly enlightened,''
said a religion expert who spoke on condition of anonymity, ``but
you also have instances all over China where at a local level there
are abuses or policies don't get followed.''
</P>
<P>
   Scholars estimate that there are at least 20 million Protestants
in China, including those who worship in house churches. A small
number of house church leaders are serving prison terms, but more
commonly their meetings are broken up by the local police,
sometimes followed by short detentions.
</P>
<P>
   A police official in Wugang, who gave his family name, Wang,
told The Associated Press that police there broke up an illegal
meeting Oct. 26 but started arresting people only when the
worshipers resisted, even firing homemade rifles at the officers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
