u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALTERNATE-MEDICINE-BO     11-10 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALTERNATE-MEDICINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVEY SHOWS SURGE IN USE OF ALTERNATIVE HEALING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new survey shows that the use of alternative medicine has
surged in the 1990s and Americans are now making more visits to
alternative healers than to primary care medical doctors.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 4 in 10 Americans used at least one alternative, or
``complementary,'' remedy in 1997, and among people 35 to 49 it was
5 in 10. Visits to alternative practitioners in 1997 jumped by 47
percent from 1991, to a total of 629 million _ exceeding all visits
to primary care medical doctors, said the study.
</P>
<P>
   The report from Dr. David M. Eisenberg and collegues at Beth
Israel Deaconess Medical Center in Boston and the Harvard Medical
School updates a similar survey carried out in 1990 and published
in 1993, which found that 3 in 10 Americans used alternative
therapies.
</P>
<P>
   Most people who saw an alternative practitioner for a serious
condition also saw a medical doctor, Eisenberg reported.
</P>
<P>
   The updated survey is the lead article in the Journal of the
American Medical Association, whose current issue is wholly devoted
to the alternative medicine phenomenon. Two JAMA editors call it
``deeply troubling'' that billions of health care dollars are being
spent on an array of practices and products with little proof of
safety or efficacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uncritical acceptance of untested and unproven alternative
therapies must stop,'' write Dr. Phil B. Fontanarosa, a senior
editor, and Dr. George D. Lundberg, the editor of JAMA. And
therapies that have been shown not to work or to be harmful
``should be abandoned immediately,'' they add.
</P>
<P>
   It is the second sharp critique of alternative medicine to come
from a leading medical journal in the past two months. In
September, the New England Journal of Medicine published several
reports documenting harm from herbal remedies, and editorialized
that alternative medicine has been getting a ``free ride'' from the
scientific community, which it said has failed to subject such
therapies to the same rigorous tests as it does conventional
treatments.
</P>
<P>
   The most-used alternative therapies, according to the new
survey, are relaxation techniques, herbal medicine, massage,
chiropractic and spiritual healing by others. About half of the
total alternative practitioner visits were for two therapies _
massage and chiropractic.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the NEJM, the JAMA issue contains some reports of
alternative therapies that proved effective, along with ones that
failed to show benefit. Nine other medical journals affiliated with
JAMA are also carrying reports on alternative medicine this week.
</P>
<P>
   Among the results published in the special JAMA issue:
</P>
<P>
   _ Irritable bowel syndrome, a common set of symptoms that
include abdominal pain, bloating, constipation and diarrhea,
responded to chinese herbal formulations in an Australian study.
</P>
<P>
   _ Spinal manipulation by a chiropractor failed to alleviate
tension-type headaches, according to a Danish study.
</P>
<P>
   _ Acupuncture proved ineffective in treating nerve pain due to
infection with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV), but no other
treatment has been shown to work either, said researchers from
Denver, the University of Minnesota and the National Institutes of
Health.
</P>
<P>
   _ Patients with carpal tunnel syndrome who participated in an
8-week yoga program improved more than patients who only received a
wrist splint, said a report from the University of Pennsylvania
School of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   _ Researchers from Italy and China tested an ancient Chinese
practice, moxibustion, which has been used to reposition fetuses
incorrectly oriented in the womb before birth. Moxibustion involves
burning an herb near the body so that the smoke stimulates
particular acupuncture points. The report said that moxibustion
increased fetal movements and was effective in repositioning a
significant number of fetuses who had been in a breech (feet-first)
presentation in the womb.
</P>
<P>
   _ Overweight patients who took an herbal remedy, Garcinia
cambogia, which is found in many commercial weight-loss products,
were no more successful at shedding pounds than were those who took
a placebo, according to a report from the obesity research center
at Columbia University College of Physicians and Surgeons.
</P>
<P>
   _ Saw palmetto, a popular herbal remedy for symptoms caused by
an enlarged prostate, is about as effective as the drug Proscar in
relieving symptoms and increasing urine flow, and had fewer adverse
effects than the drug, said researchers at the Minneapolis Veterans
Affairs Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   The updated survey from Eisenberg and colleagues estimated that
Americans in 1997 spent $12.2 billion of their own money on visits
to alternative therapists (most are not covered by insurance) and
an additional $5.1 billion on herbal remedies, $3.3 billion on
high-dose vitamins, $1.7 billion on diet products and $4.7 billion
on books, classes or equipment related to alternative therapy.
</P>
<P>
   This total of about $27 billion is comparable to the $29.3
billion in out-of-pocket expenses paid for all US physicians'
services in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The study also found that about 15 million Americans are taking
herbal remedies or high-dose vitamins at the same time that they
are using prescription drugs, putting them at risk for drug-herb
and drug-vitamin adverse interreactions, Eisenberg warned.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Tom Delbanco, chief of general medicine and primary care at
Beth Israel Deaconess and co-author with Eisenberg of the original
survey, predicted Tuesday that 95 percent of alternative remedies
won't withstand scientific scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   He labeled the current interest in alternative medicine a fad,
fueled by a nostalgia for quieter times, natural products and the
days when doctors could spend a lot of time listening to their
patients' troubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 10 years, it will be something else,'' said Delbanco,
adding that ``scientific medicine'' will come up with a variety of
new treatments for common, chronic problems that alternative
medicine won't be able to compete with.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
