<HEADLINE>
COURT REJECTS DALLAS INVENTOR'S BID FOR PATENT PROTECTION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A unanimous Supreme Court on Tuesday rejected a
Dallas area inventor's bid for patent protection, ruling that he
waited too long after marketing his product to qualify.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling shortens the time an inventor has to perfect an
invention before applying for a patent.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Pfaff waited so long after selling his product _ a socket
to hold computer microchips during testing _ that he missed the
one-year deadline for applying for a patent, the high court ruled.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law says a patent cannot be obtained if an invention has
been on sale in this country for more than one year before the
application is filed.
</P>
<P>
   Pfaff had argued that the clock should have begun ticking later
_ after he'd perfected a working version of the device. While he
had detailed drawings of the device when he sold it to Dallas-based
Texas Instruments in April 1981 _ it took months to create a
working prototype. He didn't apply for the patent until April 1982.
</P>
<P>
   The high court rejected Pfaff's argument, saying the year begins
before an invention has been completed. In their 9-0 decision, the
justices said the clock starts when a pending invention is placed
on the market and its blueprints are sufficiently clear to enable a
skilled technician to build the product.
</P>
<P>
   Patent attorney Jay Alexander of Washington said the court's
ruling should serve as a warning to small inventors to pay
attention to patent questions before the work is done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apply for a patent as soon as possible. That way you eliminate
the risk,'' said Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   Large companies, by contrast, are generally well-versed in
patent law, Alexander said. Most have policies in place to ensure
they do not miss the one-year deadline for filing their
applications, he added.
</P>
<P>
   In their ruling, the justices upheld a federal appeals court
decision that stripped Pfaff of his patent. The U.S. Court of
Appeals for the Federal Circuit had ruled that Pfaff's April 8,
1981, agreement to sell 30,100 of his sockets to Texas Instruments
for $91,155 rendered his April 19, 1982, patent application invalid
due to the one-year time limit.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court's decision marked a victory for Wells
Electronics of South Bend, Ind., which makes competing socket that
had challenged Pfaff's patent in court.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. District Court for Northern Texas upheld the validity
of Pfaff's patent, prompting Wells Electronics to appeal to the
Federal Circuit, which hears patent cases.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court for the Federal Circuit said the clock began
when Pfaff signed the contract because his invention was
``substantially complete'' at the time of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The high court interpreted the Patent Act even more broadly,
saying the year begins when inventions that are sufficiently
described on paper are put on the market.
</P>
<P>
   The justices compared Pfaff's situation to that of Alexander
Graham Bell, who more than 100 years ago applied for his patent
before he had constructed a working telephone. The Supreme Court in
1888 upheld Bell's patent, ruling that he had described a telephone
with ``sufficient clearness and precision'' to merit the
protection.
</P>
<P>
   In a similar vein, the high court noted that the plans Pfaff
delivered to Texas Instruments before signing the contract were
identical to those he submitted with his patent application more
than a year later. Therefore, the court concluded, Pfaff's proposed
socket product was ``ready to be patented'' at the time he reached
the agreement with Texas Instruments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The primary meaning of the word `invention' in the Patent Act
unquestionably refers to the inventor's conception rather than to a
physical embodiment of that idea,'' Stevens wrote. ``The statute
does not contain any express requirement that an invention must be
completed before it can be patented.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
