<HEADER>
A3811 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITISH-TV-2TAKES-$AD     11-10 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITISH-TV-2TAKES-$ADV15-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN'S FLIES-ON-THE-WALL DOCUSOAPS TRANSFIX A NATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For releae Sunday, Nov. 15)  
 (bl)  
 By SARAH LYALL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ In the last year or so, British television viewers have
been introduced to a traffic warden who sadistically sings
``Another One Bites the Dust'' when he finds an illegally parked
car. They have met a middle-aged woman who, having failed her
driving test six times, spreads terror among the local populace as
she doggedly continues with her driving lessons.
</P>
<P>
   And they have watched as an airline steward, asked by a
passenger why you can't smoke the duty-free cigarettes you purchase
on the plane, replies: ``You can buy condoms in Boots. Need I say
more?''
</P>
<P>
   These are some of the most memorable characters to emerge from
Britain's latest television fad, fly-on-the-wall documentaries that
profess to show the unvarnished truth about various institutions,
from health spas to veterinarians' offices to supermarkets. Their
quality varies widely, but the shows seem to have so captured a
public mood that at times they can draw as many as 10 million
viewers, or about half the national viewing audience on a given
night.
</P>
<P>
   While the shows are boons for the networks _ they cost half as
much as the average sitcom and are often more than twice as popular
_ their weedlike proliferation has provoked a furious debate in
Britain about the possible exploitation of their subjects, the
debasement of Britain's proud documentary tradition and the
always-thin line between reality and entertainment in the genre.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the country's most respected documentary filmmakers
believe that such shows, called observational documentaries or
docusoaps in the industry, condescend to their subjects to provoke
an easy laugh or fleeting emotional response from the lazy
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with many of the new soaps is that they don't
enrich or inform our lives,'' said Paul Watson, who in 1974 made
``The Family,'' a fly-on-the-wall documentary about a working-class
family in Reading that is now considered both the precursor to and
the model for the genre. ``All we have is a bunch of middle-class
people going in and sneering at other people, laughing at them
because they're so stupid. The filmmaker finds someone who can't
drive very well, for instance, and laughs at them.''
</P>
<P>
   In its time, ``The Family'' was considered almost breathtakingly
daring, in that it took seriously the concerns of a working-class
family, the sort of family rarely seen on television outside of
sitcoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that was wrong in their lives was wrong with the
vast majority of working-class lives, but they were trying to do
something about it,'' said Watson in an interview, explaining the
show's appeal. And viewers were electrified by the unflinching
portrayal of a family that many found much like their own, and by
the way television could so illuminate some of the basic social
issues of the day.
</P>
<P>
   That was 24 years ago. The more recent fashion for fly-on-the
wall series probably dates back to early 1996 and ``The House,'' a
six-part BBC documentary that followed the Royal Opera House
through a series of riveting financial, political and artistic
crises.
</P>
<P>
   While that series set the stage for its more recent offshoots in
that it was high entertainment with recognizable heroes and
villains, it was in a class above many of the new shows, because it
represented a serious effort to look at a serious institution. The
show set off an impassioned discussion about the role of the opera
and the elite arts in general in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely, however, that viewers of a show like ``Health
Farm,'' which detailed the glitch-plagued $14 million opening of
the Forest Mere countryside retreat, tuned in by the millions
because they were seriously interested in the societal issues
underlying the operation of a health spa. Instead, they enjoyed
watching as the stressed-out general manager scarfed down doughnuts
on the sly, the aerobics instructor confessed that he was a closet
smoker and that he ``hadn't had sex in ages,'' and the pudgy guests
were herded en masse into the aquatherapy pool like cows to the
slaughterhouse.
</P>
<P>
   And viewers of ``Airline,'' which followed the ups and downs of
Britannia Airways, which specializes in cut-rate package vacations,
were probably less interested in the politics of the airline
industry than they were in the personal dramas that lay behind the
scenes. These included the problem of an elderly gentleman who
happened to be falling-down drunk (he was barred from his flight),
a woman who began to cry because she hadn't been given a seat with
extra legroom and a man who grew apoplectic when his tea arrived
long after his sandwiches and scones. ``This is a debacle,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Grant Mansfield, the controller of features and arts
documentaries at the ITV network and the man responsible for
scheduling many such shows, said that they had touched a nerve in
people, allowing the audience members to be the voyeurs in a series
of ``Truman Shows'' with one difference: all the protagonists know
they are being watched.
</P>
<P>
   ``At their heart, these shows are about contemporary British
life,'' he said. ``The successful ones are, first and foremost,
about the concerns and preoccupations of people in Britain, and
they have warm and empathetic characters which draw sympathy from
the audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many of the characters on the docusoaps have gone on to
new-found fame. Maureen Rees, the hapless star of ``Driving
School,'' was, at last sighting, recording a driving instruction
video. Jane McDonald, the bravura nightclub singer of a certain age
featured on ``The Cruise,'' made a CD that instantly jumped to the
top of Britain's music charts, and she is currently performing to
sold-out crowds around Britain.
</P>
<P>
   And the Adelphi Hotel in Liverpool, the subject of the series
``Hotel,'' suddenly found itself deluged with reservations, even
though it was portrayed as being about as efficiently run as Fawlty
Towers, the fictional hotel in the old John Cleese farce.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the shows have a point of view, a narrative angle. But
others just seem to meander aimlessly along.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find some of them very watchable,'' said Michael Waldman,
who directed ``The House.'' ``But I do think that quite often there
is a tendency to just press the camera and see what happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're commissioning great wodges of these things, and there
is a danger that all you get is lazy television for lazy viewers,
programs that have a superficial attractiveness, get high ratings
and then are instantly forgettable.''
</P>
<P>
   With so many shows having been broadcast or in the works, it is
hard to know what can possibly be left to make a series about.
``All of the obvious lines of work have been covered _ vets,
doctors, police, nurses, midwives, sailing crews, traffic
wardens,'' wrote Alan Hay in the daily newspaper The Scotsman.
``You name it, they've trivialized it.'' The joke in the industry
is that the next fly-on-the-wall documentary commissioned will be
about the making of a fly-on-the-wall documentary.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, if you get a few successes in a particular genre,
the great danger is that they're copied _ you become a production
line and just push out more and more of the same, rather like a
sausage machine,'' said Chris Terrill, who produced the mega-rated
show ``The Cruise'' and is now making a series about life inside a
women's prison. ``But the idea that we've exhausted all those areas
where we can make another observational documentary is a dangerous
one. The ones that really work are those that concentrate on
people, and allow them to take us to events, rather than the other
way around.''
</P>
<P>
   Another problem, critics say, is how the shows treat their
subjects. In its last annual report, the Broadcasting Standards
Commission, which administers the television industry's code of
practice, said it had received a number of complaints from viewers
upset at ``what they have seen as unacceptable treatment of a
vulnerable individual.'' Do the participants in docudramas, the
commission asked, understand what they are taking on and what the
consequences might be?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think these programs intend to be unfair, but in the
end the control of the program belongs to the producer and the
editor,'' said John Eldridge, a professor of sociology at Glasgow
University and a founder of the Glasgow Media Group. ``People
hardly know what they're in for unless they're involved in the
world of the media. They may think they know, and feel something of
the glamour of it, but I don't think they can really know.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely that the luckless manager of Forest Mere in
``Health Farm'' knew that he would be yelled at by his boss, on
camera, in the last episode of the series. (He was dismissed two
days after filming stopped.) And it is unlikely that the sobered-up
version of the drunken man on ``Airline'' would have relished the
sight of himself reeling around, singing and swearing at the
airport staff, even if he did finally get on a plane 24 hours
later. But that is the price the subjects pay for their burst of
fame.
</P>
<P>
   And Mansfield said that the producers paid special attention to
the emotional needs of their subjects, even sometimes giving
participants the chance to view rough cuts of the shows and to make
a case for changing things they particularly object to.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may have covered something inaccurately or included
something hurtful or difficult, and we'd have to talk about it,''
he said. ``We've made dozens of these things now, but by and large
I can't remember a situation where we've reached loggerheads with a
subject. They know we're not doing it as a press release for
them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
