<SLUG> BC-CANADA-REMEMBRANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE FEAR NEW REMEMBRANCE DAY ABORTION SHOOTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ The opening shots fired in what have come be called
the Remembrance Day snipings cracked the early morning gloom of
Nov. 8, 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Garson Romalis, then 57, a British Columbia gynecologist who
performed abortions at his Vancouver clinic, was at the breakfast
table waiting for the bread to pop from the toaster when two
bullets pierced the window of his suburban home. The first 7.62mm
rifle slug slammed into the back of his chair, the second tore into
his thigh, shattering bone and severing an artery.
</P>
<P>
   He nearly bled to death on the kitchen floor.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, across Canada, the days of early November have
become a season of fear for those in the front ranks of the
abortion rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   For four years now, Canada's Remembrance Day _ the country's
somber Nov. 11 commemoration of its war dead _ has been overcast by
the shootings of three abortion doctors in British Columbia,
Manitoba and Ontario as well as two doctors in western New York,
just across the Ontario border.
</P>
<P>
   Strong similarities between the attacks suggest the work of a
single sniper, and police are scouring 50 states and 10 provinces
in search of a 44-year-old American, James Koop, a Vermont resident
wanted for questioning in last month's fatal shooting of Barnett
Slepian of Amherst, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``All victims were shot in the hours of darkness. All were
residing in a home that was somewhat secluded by trees or a
fence,'' said Inspector Keith McCaskill of the Winnipeg, Manitoba
police, spokesman for the US-Canada task force investigating the
shootings. ``All were shot in their residences through a window or
a glass door.''
</P>
<P>
   Police fear the sniper may strike again in Canada this year,
although there is hope the massive manhunt under way might deter
what has become an annual rite of anti-abortion violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very much on alert because someone could be struck
anywhere,'' said Anne Drennan of the Vancouver Police.
</P>
<P>
   Several abortion clinics in British Columbia and Alberta closed
their doors this week for fear of attack. Meanwhile, a package of
written materials described as ``militantly anti-abortion and very
threatening'' was received Tuesday by an Ontario newspaper, the
Hamilton Spectator, raising more alarm.
</P>
<P>
   Slepian, an outspoken defender of his abortion practice, was
killed by a rifle bullet fired through the window of his home on
the night of Oct. 23.
</P>
<P>
   Police in Canada and the United States suspect that the abortion
doctor was killed by the same gunman, or a close confederate,
responsible for the Remembrance Day shootings that started with the
wounding of Romalis in British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Many observers believe the sniper attacks are meant to make
Canada's Remembrance Day a symbolic date of mourning for aborted
fetuses.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there is no question that the shootings have made
Canadian doctors providing abortions fearful and anxious, and the
procedure is becoming less readily available in Canada because of
that fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Access to safe medical abortion is being threatened by
murderous attacks on doctors,''' said Henry Morgantaler, the
Canadian pro-abortion physician whose campaign led to legalization
of the procedure in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   In a show of defiance, Morgantaler, whose Toronto clinic was
heavily damaged by a bomb blast in 1992, announced he will open a
clinic offering abortions in New Brunswick on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The opening of such clinics has become a rarity in Canada as
many doctors and health centers are fearful of offering the service
to pregnant women in a country where the procedure remains nearly
as controversial as in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Many abortion clinics operate under a degree of security that is
highly unusual in a country whose violent crime rate is far lower
than in the United States. A number of abortion doctors wear
bulletproof vests and keep all windows at their homes covered with
blankets that conceal even the shadow of movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a sense of a reign of terror,'' said Marilyn Wilson,
executive director of the Canadian Abortion Rights Action League.
``There is a special concern that younger doctors won't want to do
this.''
</P>
<P>
   About 107,000 abortions are done in Canada each year, or one for
every 3.5 live births. Nearly all are paid for with tax dollars
under the country's national health system. Nontheless, the
procedure is generally available only in urban areas. One mostly
rural province, Prince Edward Island, bans doctors from terminating
pregnancies in general hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, anti-abortion protests are commonplace, clinics
providing the service are regularly picketed, and opponents argue
that doctors who perform the procedure are, in effect, setting
themselves up for attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Violence breeds violence, and I think there will be more
violence as long as they allow abortions,'' said Rev. James Whalen,
a Roman Catholic priest and anti-abortion activist in Ontario. ``If
you teach people in a country to accept abortion and euthanasia,
you are promoting violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1994 shooting, there have been four other attacks,
including the Slepian ambush:
</P>
<P>
   -- On Nov. 10, 1995, a sniper's bullet shattered the elbow of
Hugh Short, a gynecologist with an abortion practice, as he watched
television in the den of his home in Ancaster, Ontario. He has
retired from medicine as the result of the wound.
</P>
<P>
   -- On October 28, 1997, a gynecologist with an abortion practice
was wounded by a shot fired through a window of a home near
Rochester, N.Y. Police refuse to release the name of the victim.
</P>
<P>
   -- On November 11, 1997, Jack Fainman, 66, a Winnipeg
gynecologist, was struck in the shoulder by a bullet fired through
the window of his home. The wound forced him to abandon his
practice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
