<HEADER>
A3820 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PANTYHOSE-TEST-960(2T     11-10 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANTYHOSE-TEST-960(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANTY HOSE ARE EXPENSIVE, SCRATCHY, MISERABLE _ AND SALES ARE
SAGGING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thursday morning: Outspoken non-pantyhose wearer (me) begins The
Great Pantyhose Experiment. Goal: To determine whether the benefits
of wearing nylons _ i.e. look like Jamie Lee Curtis _ outweigh the
disadvantages _ i.e. feel like bratwurst.
</P>
<P>
   8:05 a.m. Search closet for hose-appropriate outfit. Find dusty
suit skirt unworn since last job interview. Rifle through dresser
drawers and locate unopened pair of ``nude'' pantyhose _
sandalfoot, light support. Attempt one-footed entry. Snag hose with
jagged edge of gnawed-on fingernail. Cuss. Begin sweating beneath
sheath of man-made material now vacuum-packed to thighs. Scowl at
husband after he admires legs for first time in months. Whine about
having to subject self to this merciless punishment.
</P>
<P>
   9:10 a.m. Politely tolerate curious stares from co-workers
demanding to know ``What's the occasion?'' Listen to every female
in office older than 45 invoke memories of garter belts and
stockings. Blah, blah, blah.
</P>
<P>
   2:30 p.m. Start feeling oddly grown-up. Clop down office hallway
in barely worn 3-year-old pumps exuding brassy confidence. Sit down
in cafeteria and cross legs, assuming ladylike demeanor. Consider
switching careers to marketing or law so would HAVE to shop at Ann
Taylor and dress like Ally McBeal.
</P>
<P>
   2:35 p.m. Realize above thought provoked by low-blood-sugar
delirium. Buy pack of M&AMP;Ms from vending machine. Yank up waistband.
</P>
<P>
   5:35 p.m. Peel off so-called second skin. Scratch legs like
flea-bitten dog. Cradle favorite jeans in arms and promise never to
betray again. Put pantyhose experiment on hold.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   There are a few women in the world who relish pantyhose. There
are a few more who don't mind them. There are millions upon
millions who would like to grab the guy who invented nylon by the
lapels and demand to know what the heck he was thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Pantyhose bind. They sag. They're hot in the summer and cold in
the winter. They itch.
</P>
<P>
   The slightest of rough edges _ on fingernails, on chairs, on
file cabinets _ can turn an $8 investment into nothing more than a
handy way to store onions.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, as soon as women saw it was safe to ditch
pantyhose, thanks to the acceptance of casual business attire and
bare-legged fashion trends, they did. Sales started sliding after
1994, when the industry sold 1.6 billion pairs of sheer hosiery. In
1997, the figure had fallen to 1.3 billion, according to the NPD
American Shoppers Panel.
</P>
<P>
   Here's where innovation becomes a crucial part of marketing. In
the past few years, manufacturers have introduced body shapers,
hose that target a specific ``problem'' area (thighs, bottom, hips)
and mush it into place. Three-D stretch gets rid of the
ring-around-the-calf look. And the new ``compression'' hosiery,
like Hanes Revitalizing Collection, claims to improve circulation
in the lower limbs. (The compression squeezes feet and ankles to
prompt blood flow upward.)
</P>
<P>
   Breakthroughs notwithstanding, it's all basically torturous,
according to 100 percent of the working women we talked to at the
Fort Worth Outlet Square during a recent lunch hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're hot, they're uncomfortable, and I rip them
regularly,'' groans Kaycee Shane, a law student and part-time
intern in the U.S. Attorney's office. ``I wear them once, and I
throw them away.''
</P>
<P>
   Browsing in the Hanes outlet store, Kristi Willis and Christina
Jackson, insurance company employees, expressed similar disdain.
``They don't last very long, and they cost too darn much,'' Willis
declared.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson admits to sometimes taking off her nylons while her boss
is at lunch. Women wear hose, she cracks, ``because it's a man's
world and they insist on it.'' She points to a pair of sheer black
thigh-highs. ``Like these. I buy these for my husband.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, 7:45 a.m. Rouse in cold sweat, rattled from nightmare
in which all slacks hanging in closet turned to heavy-support
nylons. Notice new package of pantyhose next to bed, purchased
yesterday from local department store. Pull covers over head.
</P>
<P>
   7:50 a.m. Give in, remembering job is on line.
</P>
<P>
   8:05 a.m. File nails. Lie supine on bed and attempt to pull on
new ``compression'' hose, the industry's latest technological
advance. Wriggle, squirm, jerk. Snag in half-dozen places despite
(yes, despite!) in-home manicure. Feel like a sausage in casing.
Feel prickly sensation all up and down legs. On the other hand,
skirt seems loose; compression seems to be taking effect. Slip into
black pumps (a record two times in one month!).
</P>
<P>
   11:30 a.m. Graciously accept compliment on ensemble from
newspaper's society writer. Momentarily revisit Ann Taylor fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   11:55 p.m. Endure embarrassing catcall on street by Neanderthal
in pickup truck. Think pantyhose may present safety concern.
</P>
<P>
   1:10 p.m. Realize trips to the ladies' room taking several
minutes longer than usual. Realize I am walking like toy soldier in
compression hose, which are supposed to invigorate gams and
``enhance overall leg health.''
</P>
<P>
   5:50 p.m. Can't tell if legs are more or less invigorated than
usual. Can tell I am more aggravated than usual.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Mary Alice Smith wears pantyhose with shorts in the summer. She
buys mass quantities from the Hanes catalog _ no control top, thank
you _ and favors the patterned styles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just looove pantyhose,'' says Smith, an associate professor
at Tarrant County Junior College. ``I think I was born wearing
them.'' But Smith grew up watching her mother put on makeup and
stockings every day, ``even if she was just going to sit around the
house.'' Her affection for nylons is kinda inbred.
</P>
<P>
   Not so for post-boomer women.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry has lost a whole generation of wearers,'' notes
NPD Group's Perry James. The company's research shows the average
age of sheer hosiery wearers has edged up to 46, from 42 in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a big pantyhose fan at all,'' says 26-year-old Amy
Hooper, owner of A. Hooper, one of Fort Worth's most
fashion-forward boutiques. ``The biggest plus to wearing pantyhose
is having that control top hold you in where you want to be held
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Hooper's customers, for the most part, don't want or don't need
``body shaping.'' And most twenty- or thirtysomething women grew up
wearing clothing much less constricting and less traditionally
feminine than the togs in their moms' closets. Plus, the look now
is barelegged. Even for winter, midlength skirts and tall boots are
far more runway-savvy than, say, black hose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't ever suggest wearing black hose,'' stresses Hooper.
</P>
<P>
   She does acknowledge that some businesswomen have no choice in
the matter when it comes to nylons. Hooper's advice: Pick a nude
hose (she prefers Donna Karan, The Nudes).
</P>
<P>
   ``Pantyhose are just not an essential piece in your wardrobe
anymore,'' she insists. For this season, at least.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday 8:30 a.m. Wake up late in midst of yet another
nightmare: This time, huge rip appears in $45 Austrian pantyhose
purchased at chic Dallas boutique. Oh, my _ realize I really did
buy $45 pantyhose yesterday at chic Dallas boutique in effort to
blow lid on myth that costly pantyhose are better than Target
brand. Don pair of white gloves and pull on ``Cosmetic'' color
nylons. Hmmmm. Try hard to deny noticeable difference between these
European hose and ones I've been suffering in. Admire legs.
Actually feel mobile. Actually feel comfortable. Spend next hour
searching for clothing to go with extravagant new leg wear.
</P>
<P>
   9:50 a.m. Set off to work _ very, very, very carefully.
</P>
<P>
   10:30 a.m. Wait for someone in office to notice stunning calves.
Reapply lipstick. Check hair. Wish nails were polished. Wish
earrings were bigger. Feel self being sucked into black hole of
Fashion Consciousness. Close eyes and try to picture favorite jeans
and sweat shirt.
</P>
<P>
   1:30 p.m. Can't stand it any longer. Announce to co-workers that
I am wearing $45 Austrian pantyhose soaked in lanolin for softness.
Allow lower leg to be stroked by numerous impressed women in office
who can ``sort of'' tell a difference. Insist they have GOT to try
these hose. Remember that no one I know, especially me, should be
spending $45 on a pair of nylons.
</P>
<P>
   4 p.m. Narrowly avoid running Euro hose on errant staple. Become
suddenly very tired of worrying more about pantyhose than important
things, like how to pay upcoming credit-card bill.
</P>
<P>
   6 p.m. Find self as eager to rid body of expensive pantyhose as
moderately priced ones due to overwhelming responsibility to avoid
snags. Make note to spend next available $45 on new pair of khakis.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
