<HEADER>
A3823 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUGHES-EXCERPTS-TEX     11-10 0257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUGHES-EXCERPTS-TEX </SLUG>
 
(EDS: Accompanies HUGHES-PLATH) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Excerpt from ``The Blue Flannel Suit'' by Ted Hughes in
``Birthday Letters'' (Farrar, Straus and Giroux, $20)
</P>
<P>
   ``You waited.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing yourself helpless in the tweezers
</P>
<P>
   Of the life that judged you, and I saw
</P>
<P>
   The flayed nerve, the unhealable face-wound
</P>
<P>
   Which was all you had for courage.
</P>
<P>
   I saw that what gripped you, as you sipped,
</P>
<P>
   Were terrors that had killed you once already.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I see, I saw, sitting, the lonely
</P>
<P>
   Girl who was going to die.
</P>
<P>
   That blue suit,
</P>
<P>
   A mad, execution uniform,
</P>
<P>
   Survived your sentence. But then I sat, stilled,
</P>
<P>
   Unable to fathom what had stilled you
</P>
<P>
   As I looked at you, as I am stilled
</P>
<P>
   Permanently now, permanently
</P>
<P>
   Bending so briefly at your open coffin.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Excerpt from ``Suttee,'' also included in ``Birthday Letters'':
</P>
<P>
   ``You were a child-bride
</P>
<P>
   On a pyre.
</P>
<P>
   Your flames fed on rage, on love
</P>
<P>
   And on your cries for help.
</P>
<P>
   Tears were a raw fuel.
</P>
<P>
   And I was your husband
</P>
<P>
   Performing the part of your father
</P>
<P>
   In our new myth _
</P>
<P>
   Both of us drenched in a petroleum
</P>
<P>
   Of ancient American sunlight,
</P>
<P>
   Both of us consumed
</P>
<P>
   By the old child in the new birth _
</P>
<P>
   Not the new babe of light but the old
</P>
<P>
   Babe of dark flames and screams
</P>
<P>
   That sucked the oxygen out of both of us.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
