<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMEY-TV-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS LAWMAKER SHUNS TV IN FIGHT TO KEEP JOB AS MAJORITY LEADER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an era when politicians live and die by
television, House Majority Leader Dick Armey has taken an unusual
approach in fighting to keep his job: No TV.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Republican, who faces two telegenic challengers, has
failed to make a single public appearance in the week since his
party took a drubbing at the polls. While his opponents have been
bashing him in live television interviews, Armey has been
campaigning the old-fashioned way in one-on-one telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   His low-key approach is a throwback to the days when leadership
contests were inside affairs, but the ability to perform well on
television is considered a key job requirement for House leaders in
the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an issue. It is something that all the members talk
about,'' said former Rep. Bob Walker, a confidant of retiring
Speaker Newt Gingrich. ``Dick has his moments on television, but
that is not one of his strengths.''
</P>
<P>
   Armey's opponents have made that point again and again, both by
their words and by their repeated television appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Communication is very key,'' Rep. Steve Largent of Oklahoma, a
Hall of Fame football star, said in his latest CNN interview
Tuesday. ``You can have a great message, but if you have a
messenger that people are afraid of or don't believe, you're not
going to connect.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone in the TV department, Rep. Jennifer Dunn of
Washington state declared her intention to run on CNN's Inside
Politics after hinting about it on a Sunday morning program.
</P>
<P>
   The TV-friendly pitch seems to be working with some Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a new spokesman,'' said Rep. Jay Dickey of Arkansas, a
Largent backer. ``I think Dick could adjust. But when he stands up
to speak, people remember the old approach. We have to start
worrying about being liked.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Armey and Largent claim that they are rapidly collecting
the commitments they need to declare victory in a contest that will
be decided on Nov. 18, when the 223 House Republicans select
leaders for the new Congress. Dunn, the last to enter the race,
said she is also picking up support.
</P>
<P>
   A potential challenger, Rep. Howard McKeon of California, bowed
out and endorsed Armey Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm counting and recounting, because that's how we do these
things. But I'm pretty confident right now,'' Armey said in a
written response to questions from the Star-Telegram. ``This is a
matter of 223 people who will vote. I think it's best that we talk
directly, and hash out our differences within the family.''
</P>
<P>
   But the majority leader has failed to win backing from two
pivotal players in the leadership scramble, Rep. Bob Livingston of
Louisiana, the man in line to become House speaker, and Republican
Whip Tom DeLay of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston, who locked up the speaker's race Monday, told Armey
that he will stay neutral, but the two men have had a strained
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes without saying that Livingston doesn't want to spend
every day looking over his shoulder,'' said Ken Johnson, spokesman
for Rep. Billy Tauzin of Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay's refusal to back his fellow Texan came as no surprise
because the two conservatives have clashed repeatedly over
legislative strategy. Their relationship hit a low point last year
when DeLay's allies accused Armey of duplicity during an aborted
attempt to oust Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   Although the plotters felt they had Armey's support, the coup
fizzled when Armey reported the plan to the speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no one counts Armey out. The blunt-talking Texan
campaigned in 120 congressional districts and contributed $1.4
million to Republican candidates and campaign organizations in this
year's election.
</P>
<P>
   Although some of Armey's advisers have urged him to be more
visible, Walker said the majority leader may be following the best
approach. The former Pennsylvania lawmaker has endorsed Dunn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the less experienced candidates are going to find that
some of the time they have spent lining up television interviews
would have been better spent lining up colleagues on the
telephone,'' Walker said. ``If you're not getting your commitments,
it doesn't matter how good you are on television.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
