<HEADLINE>
POOR SCHOOL DISTRICTS ASK COURT TO PLACE N.H. IN RECEIVERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH JIMENEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ A group of school districts Tuesday asked the
state Supreme Court to throw the state into receivership if the
governor and Legislature fail to replace an unconstitutional school
funding system that relies almost entirely on local property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The motion also asks the court to appoint a special mediator to
broker an agreement between struggling school districts and a state
government unwilling to alter its unique tax structure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The schools won't close. The receiver would temporarily make
sure the funds are available to them,'' said Andru Volinsky, lead
lawyer for the Claremont Coalition of property-poor school
districts. The districts filed suit in 1991 challenging the
legality of a system that allows property tax rates to vary as much
as 16-fold between communities.
</P>
<P>
   Last December the court ordered the state to act by April 1 to
ensure that taxes are levied proportionally and that all children
are provided equal access to an adequate education. After April 1,
the current system will become illegal and towns will no longer be
able to collect the school portion of property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers have agonized over how to comply with the order
without enacting a statewide sales, property, or income tax,
something Democratic Governor Jeanne Shaheen has sworn to veto.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the state asked the high court to allow the current
system to remain in place for two more years to give lawmakers more
time to craft a compromise and to win over legislators who feel
that the best response is to ignore the court order.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are those who feel, `Let's tell the court to pound
sand,''' said House Speaker Donna Sytek, a Republican who like
Shaheen opposes any broad-based tax.
</P>
<P>
   Shaheen does not believe the court has the authority to appoint
a receiver empowered to spend money that under the state
constitution must be raised and appropriated by the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think they don't,'' Shaheen said in a press conference late
Tuesday afternoon that set the stage for a head-to-head clash
between the two branches of government.
</P>
<P>
   The team of lawyers representing poor school districts
disagrees. When constitutional amendments conflict, for example, it
is up to the court, not the Legislature or governor to decide which
provision prevails, Volinsky said.
</P>
<P>
   The state's request for a two-year delay would provide Shaheen
and legislators the time needed to bring a constitutional amendment
before voters, the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do that, the optimal time for people to vote on the
ballot option would be at the same time as the February 2000
presidential primary,'' Shaheen said.
</P>
<P>
   Most observers find it unlikely that the court would grant a
lengthy extension, however, particularly since past amendment
proposals, including one backed by Shaheen, would have erased or
severely limited the court's authority over school funding issues.
</P>
<P>
   The school districts are asking that until the Legislature acts,
the state's entire $943 million general fund be used to finance
public education. Asked if doing that would mean that state
government would have to shut down, Volinsky replied, ``It would if
the Legislature doesn't act.''
</P>
</TEXT>
