<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3878 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENSUS-FUNDS-BOS &LR;      11-10 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-FUNDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENSUS CHIEF DECRIES DELAY IN APPROVAL OF COUNT METHOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The new director of the US Census Bureau said
Tuesday the continuing political fight over how to conduct the 2000
Census endangers the agency's ability to take an accurate count of
all Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longer the decision is delayed, the more difficult it will
be to conduct something of this magnitude,'' said Kenneth Prewitt,
who was appointed by President Clinton in May and confirmed by the
Senate just before it adjourned last month. ``Time is the only
resource you can't make up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau's method of counting people in 2000 has turned
into a huge brouhaha between Democrats and Republicans on Capitol
Hill. In October, Clinton and House GOP leaders agreed to disagree
in the 1999 catch-all spending bill by funding the bureau only
through June 15 and giving Congress eight more months to resolve
the issue.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the Supreme Court will hear arguments Nov. 30
on whether the Census Bureau may use statistical sampling, or
estimating, in its 2000 count. Historically, the agency has
depended entirely on a head-by-head enumeration to get census data,
and two lower courts have ruled this year that it is illegal to do
it any other way.
</P>
<P>
   By its own estimation, the Census Bureau in 1990 missed about 10
percent of the US population, with the most dramatic undercount
among African-Americans and Hispanics. The agency was charged with
finding a more accurate and inexpensive way to do the census in
2000; its solution was sampling.
</P>
<P>
   But because census data determines how the 435 House seats will
be divided among the states, members of Congress care deeply about
the count and changes in the populations of the districts that
elected them. The White House expects sampling would count more
minorities, who traditionally vote Democratic. Many Republicans see
sampling as a way for Democrats to cook the census books and then
redraw what are now GOP districts.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt said it is ``very, very far-fetched'' to suggest the
Census Bureau, a highly technical and professional bureaucracy,
could or would manipulate the samples to produce data to please
Democrats. ``No good statistician doesn't believe in sampling; it's
an oxymoron,'' said Prewitt, noting that the agency itself has
sampled the population in different surveys for years.
</P>
<P>
   But a decennial census is a multibillion-dollar undertaking that
recruits a 250,000-member army of enumerators and can take a decade
to plan. The problem for Prewitt is that his agency must be ready
on April 1, 2000, to kick off the census, which must be completed
by Dec. 31, 2000. Yet for the foreseeable future the administration
and the Congress will be at odds over how it will be conducted.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-December, Prewitt told reporters Tuesday, the bureau will
produce a blueprint for a traditional enumeration and follow-up
survey to gauge the undercount in the event the Supreme Court
disallows sampling or the GOP-led Congress passes a law barring
census sampling for reapportionment purposes. The White House has
asked for an expedited court decision; it is not expected before
March.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt, an Illinois native who headed the National Opinion
Research Center at the Univeristy of Chicago and has authored a
dozen books on social science, said he would not second-guess the
legal and political wrangling or predict whether the new GOP House
leaders would temper their opposition to sampling. But he
emphasized that every day of delay risks a Census Bureau less
prepared for its enormous task.
</P>
<P>
   One example, Prewitt said, is the design of the census telephone
system. Under a traditional headcount, which requires census takers
to make many calls to verify addresses and locate people, the
bureau needs a phone system that handles more outgoing than
incoming calls. A census with sampling would require just the
opposite, since the public theoretically would be calling in more
often to discuss survey questions. He said the telephone system
alone takes a year to set up.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over methodology has also caused the bureau to put a
hold on plans for its census-awareness advertising campaign, he
said, because no one is sure exactly what the campaign should
direct the public to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a certain point these decisions add up, in money and in
taking an accurate census,'' Prewitt said.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans wanted the bureau's funding to end in March,
forcing a political showdown then. But Clinton pressed for and won
June 15, putting more pressure on agency planners.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Director Prewitt is worried, he really needs to talk to
Bill Clinton,'' said Christin Tinsworth, a spokeswoman for GOP
Representative Dan Miller of Florida, chairman of the census
subcommittee and a sampling foe. ``We want a good relationship with
the new director, but there's a concern that the administration has
put so much emphasis on sampling as the panacea that it's hard for
them to back down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
