<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3884 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-EDUCATION-BOS &LR;      11-10 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-EDUCATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOARD OKS BILINGUAL EDUCATION, SPECIAL ED LIMITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JORDANA HART  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. _ The state Board of Education Tuesday voted to
ask state lawmakers to dramatically restrict the time a child
spends in a bilingual education class _ to one year _ and to make
it harder for students to qualify for special education classes.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the board decided that talented would-be teachers
should not have to go through an education school to become
certified.
</P>
<P>
   Board Chairman John Silber said potential teachers such as
highly educated people leaving the military or mothers looking to
reenter the work force should be able to become certified without
earning an education degree _ for example, by taking a training
course and passing the state's teacher test.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, only a small number enter teaching without attending
traditional teaching colleges.
</P>
<P>
   In its special education proposal, the board voted to ask the
Legislature to replace the state's special education mandate of
facilitating the ``maximum possible development'' of students with
the federal standard of providing a ``free and appropriate public
education.''
</P>
<P>
   At its meeting Tuesday, in the Seven Hills Charter School, the
board also voted to ask the state to force families to pay for
their own expert second opinions if the state declares their child
ineligible for special education and they wish to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed changes drew fire from special education advocates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents rely on'' the higher state standard ``to ensure their
children receive equal educational opportunity,'' said Julia
Landau, a lawyer with the Massachustets Advocacy Center, an
education watchdog agency in Boston. ``We would strongly oppose
those provisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Tom Louie, director of Mass English Plus, criticized
what he described as the board's efforts to ease the state toward
conservative English-only education policies. Currently, students
can be taught in their native language until they attain
proficiency in English _ which takes an average of three to five
years, according to advocates.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will be forcing students into the mainstream before they
are ready,'' Louie said. ``Ideologically, they want to move
everyone to English only. This is not based on educational
research.''
</P>
<P>
   Silber and other staunch critics of bilingual education said
children languish for years in segregated classrooms without
learning English quickly enough. Tuesday's proposed changes include
allowing districts to choose their own methods of teaching children
with limited English skills.
</P>
<P>
   The board also focused on refining efforts to recruit and retain
more highly qualified teachers, including a proposal that teachers
seeking master teacher status pass the state's teacher test to be
eligible for the annual $5,000 bonus.
</P>
<P>
   The board remained strangely silent on a proposal by newly
elected Governor Paul Cellucci to test all teachers, with Silber
Tuesday declining to discuss his own view on such widespread
testing.
</P>
<P>
   Board member James Peyser, who supports teacher testing, wants
the issue on next month's board agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, recertification means accumulating professional
development points,'' Peyser said in an interview. ``It doesn't
measure anything except how many workshops and graduate programs a
teacher attended.''
</P>
<P>
   The board Tuesday also asked the Legislature to reconsider how
the state plans to disburse the new $20,000 signing bonus, designed
to attract more highly qualified people to the teaching profession.
</P>
<P>
   Next fall, education officials said as many as 50 new teachers
will each get $8,000 the first year and $4,000 in each of the
following three years. The board, concerned that teachers will
simply leave after the first year's payment, wants lawmakers to
flip the formula so that new teachers get $4,000 in each of the
first three years and $8,000 in the fourth year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
