<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-EDWARDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chris Edwards makes own mark
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Georgia Tech linebacker Chris Edwards has felt his share of
pressure. That's what happens when you graduate with a Parade
All-American label from a high-school football powerhouse like
Washington County.
</P>
<P>
   Those expectations were compounded by the comparisons _
self-inflicted and otherwise _ to his cousin Robert Edwards and
friend Takeo Spikes, both Washington County graduates and now two
of the top rookies in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   So when Edwards spent most of his first two years at Georgia
Tech on the bench or in the training room with injuries, it was
tough to take. But not as tough as finally getting healthy this
season, having two linebacker spots open up with the departure of
Keith Brooking and Ron Rogers and still failing to break into the
starting lineup. Two games into this season, Edwards was ready to
quit.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't show up to practice one day during the off-week before
the North Carolina game. His coaches couldn't find him, and
linebackers coach Ted Roof called Edwards' mother back in Warthen
to let her know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubted about whether I still wanted to play or not,'' said
Edwards, who spent the day at a friend's house.
</P>
<P>
   After taking some time to himself, Edwards got on the phone. He
called his parents, his high-school coach Rick Tomberlin, his
cousin, his friend Spikes. All told him the same thing: he'd be
making a huge mistake to quit football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't understand it,'' his mother Sophia Edwards said.
``I told him even if you don't want the football part, you've got
to think of the education part. Don't work at Wal-Mart the rest of
your life like I do. . . . I told him he couldn't live in Robert's
shoes. Do what's right for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, who has been an honor student all along, took their
advice, talked with his coaches and returned to practice the
following day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just decided everything will work out,'' Edwards said. ``I
wanted to come back and practice hard and show them I was committed
to still playing football. Ever since then, I'm having more fun
playing. I'm glad I stayed.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards was playing about 20 snaps a game on defense, in
addition to his special-teams duties, when linebacker Matt
Uremovich got suspended, and Edwards got another opportunity for
more playing time.
</P>
<P>
   Against Florida State, O'Leary wanted to use Edwards more
because of his speed, so for much of the game he moved Delaunta
Cameron to inside linebacker and put Edwards at outside linebacker.
Edwards responded by tying for the team lead in tackles with nine.
He was rewarded with the second start of his career on Oct. 31
against Maryland and had another nine tackles. He's been working
with the starting unit since and should start when Tech plays
Clemson on Thursday in an ESPN game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now as I see Chris developing, he's playing with a lot
more confidence,'' coach George O'Leary said. ``He's making more
plays. Basically he's what we recruited.''
</P>
<P>
   For Edwards, reaching this point has been both a huge relief and
well worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any regrets,'' Edwards said. ``I've had to grow
up and learn from my mistakes. I think it's made me a stronger
person. . . . When I look back, I see a lot of things I could have
done differently. It was just a whole learning process. If you want
something, you've got to work hard for it. You're not going to be
able to do it on talent alone. You have to keep it in perspective.
When you come to college, everybody else is the same, just as good
as you. It makes you appreciate it more, the ability God gave you,
when you have to work for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
