<HEADER>
A3889 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS11-COX     11-10 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    49ers offense to be big test for Falcons defense
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta Falcons middle linebacker Jessie Tuggle took a
second on Tuesday to think about what it takes to build a good run
defense, one like Atlanta's, which is ranked No. 2 in the NFL and
allowing 76.6 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   It was a good question.
</P>
<P>
   When the Falcons (7-2) play the San Francisco 49ers (7-2) Sunday
in the soldout Georgia Dome for first place in the NFC West,
they'll face the No. 5 rushing team in the league.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons gave up a season-worst 161 yards to San Francisco in
losing Sept. 27. The run defense has improved since.
</P>
<P>
   Tuggle said it takes attitude, first and foremost. It takes
players such as Lester Archambeau, who has played very well not
only at left defensive end but also in relief of injured left
tackle Travis Hall.
</P>
<P>
   It was hardly a surprise. Archambeau leads the team with four
forced fumbles, is tied with right end Chuck Smith for the team
lead with seven sacks, is fourth with 54 tackles, fourth with 15
quarterback pressures, has recovered two fumbles and has two
tackles for losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lester is one of those guys who always comes in early, and
stays late,'' Tuggle said. ``He's one of the most intelligent guys
you could ever meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not the most talented guy on our defense, but he's a guy
you would want to take with you in a bar fight, because you know
he's going to battle. That's what you need on defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have been near the top of the NFL in run defense
most of the season, and when they held the Patriots to just 18
yards on 14 carries last Sunday, they jumped from No. 4 to No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Things didn't go so well when they played the 49ers in
September. Atlanta held 49ers running back Garrison Hearst -- who
was leading the NFL in rushing at the time -- to 57 yards on 18
carries.
</P>
<P>
   But quarterback Steve Young rushed for 50 yards, and fullback
Marc Edwards busted a 32-yarder on a misdirection play up the
middle -- the longest run Atlanta has given up this season.
</P>
<P>
   That play was symbolic of the way the 49ers running game works,
and Archambeau, Smith, Hall, right tackle Shane Dronett, Tuggle and
linebackers Cornelius Bennett and Henri Crockett will have to be on
the lookout for more of the same Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst was the deep back, and Edwards was offset behind the
right tackle. Both backs went right, except Hearst kept going, and
the Edwards cut back left, took a handoff and found running room
for a big gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``They even pulled a guard to make it look like a toss sweep,''
Archambeau said. ``Their offensive scheme is based on movement and
speed, pulling guards, and (cut-blocking).
</P>
<P>
   ``(Hearst has) got great speed and the quickness and run to the
corner. They try to spread you out so you can't maintain the gap
integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the Falcons have maintained the gap-control
scheme that is the basis of their run defense and the key to
eliminating cutback lanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the run has to be stopped by your front seven, . . .
and the biggest key is that (defensive line coach) Bill Kollar and
(linebacker coach) Don Blackmon have done a great job teaching
everyone how important gap control is,'' said Rich Brooks,
assistant head coach and defensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody maintains . . . a three-yard gap (between himself
and the next defender),'' Brooks said. ``They don't just start
chasing the ball all bunched together.''
</P>
<P>
   When Archambeau was traded from Green Bay in 1993, he had a
reputation as a light player who was quick and could play against
the run. In his early years in Atlanta, however, he was on the
sideline on passing downs.
</P>
<P>
   The nine-year veteran from Stanford has developed into an
all-around player, as his career-high 8.5 sacks last year would
attest. But he's still more respected against the run; his 54
tackles are fourth behind Bennett (75), Tuggle (61) and free safety
Eugene Robinson (55).
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, it's a couple things. One, I'm getting a lot more
opportunities than in the past,'' said Archambeau, who last year
forced five fumbles and recovered three. ``Plus, the more practice
you get at something, the better you get. And anytime you're
playing with a quality group, it elevates your play. Playing next
to Travis helps.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody likes to talk about the super-sized defensive linemen,
but Kollar is happy with the 6-foot-5, 275-pound Archambeau.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not that big. He's not that strong. He's just a football
player,'' Kollar said. ``Because he is so intelligent, . . . he
makes the formation calls out there. He's sort of the quarterback
for the defensive line.''
</P>
<P>
   Smarts and size are great, but Archambeau, 31, said attitude is
most important.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a front, we talk about being dominant, and not letting
anybody else knock us around,'' he said. ``We don't have a
330-pounder, but those guys can't play every down anyway, and they
can't run to the ball like we can.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely think attitude is a huge part of this game. If
you sit there and say, 'I'm an undersized guy,' you're going to get
killed. You have to say, 'I'm going to go toe to toe with this guy,
and he's going to have his hands full.'''
</P>
<P>
   That challenge comes on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
