<HEADER>
A3891 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-BISHER-DIMAGGIO-C     11-10 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BISHER-DIMAGGIO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commentary: Nobody else a DiMaggio
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Where have you gone, Joe DiMaggio?
</P>
<P>
   ``A nation turns its lonely eyes to you,
</P>
<P>
   ``Woo, woo, woo.... ``
</P>
<P>
   One generation knew him from that line in a song from the movie
``The Graduate.'' And probably wondered who he was. Maybe the only
ballplayer I know who had a song written about him, and it was so
full of yearning. Another generation knew him as Mr. Coffee. He
stood there and just as sincerely as could be told us about the
finer points of this coffee-making gadget. He made $100,000 a year
doing it, as much as he made playing centerfield for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   There may have been another ballplayer who played the game with
such grace as Joe DiMaggio, but I doubt it. You wonder what makes
the impression of such an athlete stick in your mind for so long.
You had to see him run, long, flowing strides, catch a fly ball,
make the artful throw back to the infield. Then you would have
known.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was his quiet reserve that set him apart. You'll
notice there has been no glut of ``Joe D., The Real DiMag'' or
``Joe DiMaggio _ My Story'' books on the market. He was, and is, a
very private man who never cared to sell himself. He was Joseph
Paul DiMaggio and he belonged to himself. I've had breakfast with
him, lunch with him, dinner with him, played golf with him and sat
watching the sun go down with him. I never had the courage to pry
into the inner DiMaggio. Sure as hell not to ask him about Marilyn
Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   There is the story worth repeating, of Marilyn returning from a
tour of our military bases overseas while they were married. Joe
met her at the plane and was asking her how the trip went.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, Joe,'' she gurgled, ``there were thousands of them. You
never heard such cheering.''
</P>
<P>
   Quietly, Joe said, ``Oh, I think I have.''
</P>
<P>
   Thank heaven, he played the game when he did. It would be
sickening to see him in those leotards players wear today, flopping
down around the ankles like pajamas. He was a player for the age he
lived in. In the right city, New York, New York. Jim Murray once
wrote, ``That's what a ballplayer should look like,'' and I second
the motion.
</P>
<P>
   He averaged .325 at bat and drove in 1,537 runs, but there is no
way you could translate the way he moved into statistics. One of my
first memories of him is a negative one. It was in the World Series
of 1947, sixth game, I think. He hit a drive deep into leftfield
and the little reserve Dodger outfielder, Al Gionfriddo, made the
catch leaning over the bullpen gate. DiMaggio rounded second and
kicked the dirt in frustration. For the record, Gionfriddo never
played in another major-league game.
</P>
<P>
   The record that DiMaggio still holds is the 56-game hitting
streak. It looks safe forever. I hope it is. Yet, he was not voted
into the Hall of Fame in the first round, if you can believe it.
</P>
<P>
   Joe is looking at the dark side of life now. Pneumonia and
assorted complications has him in a hospital in Florida. These
Yankee fans, who need a touch of his class, didn't get to see him
throw out the first ball in the World Series. This is not written
to beat the Grim Reaper but more to celebrate in advance his 84th
birthday, coming up Nov. 25.
</P>
<P>
   About the only line Red Smith wrote that I disagreed with had to
do with DiMaggio, the very last line Red ever wrote. ``Some day
there would be another Joe DiMaggio,'' he said in the last column
of his life.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think so. I hope not, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Furman Bisher is the editor of the Atlanta Journal. E-mail:
furman(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
