<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3892 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ARKANSAS-COX     11-10 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARKANSAS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Positive attitudes, exceeded expectations give Arkansas push
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTEVILLE, Ark. _ Running back Madre Hill, elder statesmen of
an Arkansas football team experiencing an unexpected renaissance,
refuses to be satisfied merely by getting in the game.
</P>
<P>
   After missing the last two seasons with twin surgeries to repair
ligament damage to both knees, Hill didn't want to play out the
string, salvaging some consolation at the end of a career that
could have been special.
</P>
<P>
   When Houston Nutt was hired last winter to replace Danny Ford,
the energetic former Arkansas backup quarterback immediately asked
his troops to engage in a series of grueling off-season workouts.
Nearly all of them jumped at the chance, including Hill, and his
revival in many ways reflects a bright future for a program that
has struggled since joining the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   The work _ and the upbeat attitude Nutt has injected along with
it _ has paid off handsomely for the 10th-ranked Razorbacks, who
play at top-ranked Tennessee on Saturday in a clash of undefeated
SEC teams.
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas is one of the biggest surprises of the year. The
Razorbacks sport an 8-0 record, its best in 10 seasons, and have a
perfect 5-0 slate in the SEC. After having trouble putting away
Kentucky, South Carolina and Auburn, the Razorbacks _ projected in
one preseason poll to finish last in the SEC West _ are now primed
for the Cotton Bowl. Other prospects include the Sugar and Citrus,
but Hill doesn't want to settle for those.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it great now for us? Sure it is. But it can get a whole lot
better,'' Hill said. ``I'd like to be sitting here talking about
having won the national championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas, which drubbed Ole Miss 34-0 last week, is seventh in
the Bowl Championship Series standings. An upset against the
Volunteers would thrust the Hogs closer to the Fiesta Bowl,
although both teams figure to meet again in the SEC championship
game next month.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, who suffered his first knee injury in Arkansas' loss to
Florida in the 1995 SEC title game, is 8th in the SEC in rushing
with 560 yards and gradually is looking like the man who set a
school record with 1,387 yards in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The returns of Hill and fellow tailback Chrys Chukwuma, who
missed last year with a back injury, have meant everything to the
Hogs on offense. Chukwuma's 562 yards is 5th in the SEC. Last year,
Arkansas had one of the poorest rushing games in the country, and
finished 4-7. Now, All-American guard candidate Brandon Burlsworth
helps pave the way for a balanced attack, and a more aggressive,
blitz-happy defense is fourth nationally against the run.
</P>
<P>
   But even Nutt, 41, who has been confident without the swagger,
seemed a little taken aback at his team's lofty status going into
its biggest challenge of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who would have thought we would be 8-0? he said. ``Now, we
thought we were going to have a good team, but to be 8-0 and
playing the No. 1 team in Knoxville?
</P>
<P>
   Nutt, who earned plaudits at Murray State and last year in his
only season at Boise State, was on the job at Arkansas for six
months before he signed a contract, in a gesture of goodwill. He is
his own offensive coordinator, hired his brother, Danny, to be his
running-backs coach and has a sharp eye for detail.
</P>
<P>
   On the sidelines, he is a constant whirlwind, congratulating
good plays with gusto and flailing his arms to the home fans to get
them off their feet. There's nothing fancy about his playbook,
although it's decidedly more wide open and modernized than Ford
ever contemplated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty much doing the same things we were doing last
year,'' starting linebacker Quenton Caver said. `` The coaches are
very alive, we believe in what they're doing, and it's easy to go
out there every day in practice and on Saturday and play hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Nutt has been careful to acknowledge the strong foundation laid
by his predecessor, with 19 of 22 starters returning from last
year, and says his veterans haven't needed much prodding: ``They
believe good things are going to happen to them, and they're
expecting to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior quarterback Clint Stoerner has been one of the
ringleaders. ``I think that attitude has helped us get here,''
Stoerner said. ``We know Tennessee is a great football team, but
we're going to go in there with a good attitude and a commitment to
win.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Parker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
