<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3907 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOP-IMPEACH-BOS &LR;      11-10 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-IMPEACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP MODERATES WANT SPEEDY RESOLUTION OF IMPEACHMENT CRISIS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With House Republicans torn over how far to push
the impeachment case against President Clinton, a bloc of moderate
GOP members Tuesday was poised to pressure party leaders to
speedily resolve the crisis, possibly short of an impeachment vote
in the full House.
</P>
<P>
   With as many as 40 members, the GOP moderate group could exert
powerful influence on Republican leaders by threatening to vote
with Democrats to kill the impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to the moderate bloc, led by Representative Nancy
L. Johnson of Connecticut, said several members are expected to
push for an alternative to Clinton's impeachment after the GOP
leadership races are resolved next week and the House Judiciary
Committee completes its inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   By most accounts, the Judiciary Committee, which is controlled
by some of the GOP's staunchest social conservatives, will approve
articles of impeachment against Clinton as soon as early December.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than prolong the process by voting to send the
articles to the Senate for a trial, the House moderates are
expected to press GOP leaders to forge a compromise that calls for
sanctioning Clinton short of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The possible alternatives include a motion to send the articles
of impeachment back to the Judiciary Committee with instructions to
replace them with a resolution calling for a reprimand or other
sanction.
</P>
<P>
   The moderate group, which played a key role in countering
conservative social and environmental initiatives in the current
Congress, includes two other New Englanders, Representatives
Charles F. Bass of New Hampshire and Christopher Shays of
Connecticut, as well as GOP lawmakers from across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen anything in the Starr report that would justify
removing the president from office,'' Shays said. ``We need to get
on with the nation's business.''
</P>
<P>
   Known as the Tuesday Club, the moderate group also includes
Banking Committee Chairman James A. Leach of Iowa, and several New
Yorkers, including Representatives Rick A. Lazio and Jack Quinn.
</P>
<P>
   The moderates have no connection to the so-called ``breakfast
club,'' a bipartisan group of Judiciary Committee members who are
considered open to alternatives to impeachment. Nearly every
Republican on the Judiciary Committee is considered conservative on
social issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the lesson from the '98 election was that too many
within the Republican Party, especially the leadership, focused too
much on issues like impeachment and were less concerned with the
bread-and-butter issues people care about,'' said Johnson's chief
of staff, Dave Karvelas. ``We can't go overboard in one area to the
detriment of other areas.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Judiciary Committee prepares to conduct its only major
hearing of the impeachment inquiry, a high-profile session next
week with independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr, Republicans were
not alone Tuesday in fretting about the course of the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the reluctance of moderate Republicans to prolong the
inquiry, the House Democratic leader said he believes the GOP's
``dominant view'' is to keep the case alive next year in the 106th
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Richard A. Gephardt issued the partisan analysis
a day after most Republicans on the Judiciary Committee reaffirmed
their commitment to vote on articles of impeachment against
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dominant view in the Republican Party is that this ought
to go on and on and at some point it will lead to impeachment in
the House,'' Gephardt said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt, who met Tuesday with Democrats on the Judiciary
Committee, said the process also could be prolonged by the scramble
for GOP leadership posts after the resignation of Speaker Newt
Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   ``My worry is that their lack of defined leadership will kick
this over to next year,'' Gephardt said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Judiciary Committee members from both parties geared
up for Starr's hearing on Nov. 19, an appearance that is expected
to rank among the top Capitol Hill spectacles in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans on the panel met to prepare strategy to defend Starr
against Democrats attacks on his eight-month, $4 million
investigation of Clinton's consensual sexual affair in the White
House with former intern Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the defense plan, GOP members reviewed a summary of
``positive'' talking points about Starr, including statements such
as, ``Judge Starr is one of the country's premier lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   Some committee Democrats, who earlier had pressed for Starr's
appearance, have grown less enthusiastic amid concerns that Starr
could shine as witness, seizing the public's approval as Oliver
North did in the Iran-Contra hearings.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility also exists that Starr could inflict additional
damage on Clinton by disclosing information about the independent
counsel's investigations into other matters, such as White House
political operatives possessing confidential FBI files and the
firing of White House travel office workers.
</P>
<P>
   But some committee Democrats appeared determined to
cross-examine Starr vigorously over his handling of the Lewinsky
matter and other areas of his four-year, $40 million investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is little doubt that Republicans are using this hearing
as a vehicle to try to rehabilitate Ken Starr's credibility amid
charges of conflict of interst, unlawfully leaking information, and
failing to disclose the basis on which he expanded his jurisdiction
to Lewinsky,'' said Representative Martin T. Meehan, a
Massachusetts Democrat on the Judiciary Committee. ``All of the
controversies have resulted in his credibility being undermined.''
</P>
<P>
   The highest ranking Judiciary Democrat, Representative John
Conyers Jr., has been among Starr's most vocal critics. Starr has
never been questioned under oath in Congress about his
investigation of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But Meehan said Republicans plan to place five-minute limits on
each committee member's cross-examination of Starr, which he said
could prevent a thorough review of the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to adequately cross-examine Ken Starr, a prosecutor
would need at least two days,'' said Meehan, a former county
prosecutor. ``All we're going to get is five minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican committee aides said Starr may testify for two days,
which would permit each of the panel's 37 members to conduct
additional rounds of questioning.
</P>
</TEXT>
