<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-INAUG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW GERMAN LEADER LAYS OUT GRAND AMBITIONS, BUT SCANT ON DETAILS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Proclaiming that Germany has ``come of age'' and should
feel ``neither superior nor inferior to anyone,'' Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder said Tuesday that the return of the capital to
Berlin next year represented ``a new beginning'' for a country
still divided and afflicted by high unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   In his inaugural speech to Parliament, Schroeder, the first
Social Democratic chancellor since Helmut Schmidt resigned in 1982,
laid out a program of sweeping ambitions but scant detail that
seemed unlikely to end questioning about what his ``New Middle'' in
German politics really means.
</P>
<P>
   The chancellor suggested that Germany had now emerged once and
for all from its postwar tutelage _ ``Today our democracy is no
longer a tender seedling, it is a strong upstanding tree'' _ but
appeared to leave open the question of exactly how the emergent
society he once again called the ``Berlin Republic'' would be
invigorated.
</P>
<P>
   The ``flagship project'' of the new ``Red-Green'' coalition of
Social Democrats and environmentalist Greens would be ``the
ecological renewal of our country in a spirit of solidarity, with a
modern, social market economy as our goal,'' Schroeder said in
Bonn, the current seat of government.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact is that the social-market model that was the basis
of Germany's postwar growth is under extreme pressure from the
rising costs of pensions and unemployment benefits and appears to
have lost the ability to create jobs. More than four million
Germans, more than 10 percent of the workforce, are without work.
</P>
<P>
   Ecological renewal will in practice be costly _ gasoline and
other energy prices are to rise as a result of new taxes, and the
nuclear power stations that provide about a third of Germany's
energy needs are to be gradually phased out. But Schroeder said he
would use the energy tax revenue to reduce labor costs, thus
providing a potential incentive for companies to hire, while the
quest for new sources of energy would eventually stimulate
innovative technology and job-creation.
</P>
<P>
   ``A speech by the new chancellor in a situation like ours should
have more concrete goals and steps for the coming months,'' said
Franz Schoser, a political analyst at the Association of German
Industry and Trade. ``Most companies will in reality have higher
taxation for the next two years, and we do not think this is the
way to tackle unemployment.''
</P>
<P>
   But Schroeder said German companies would ``eventually'' be
taxed at a maximum rate of 35 percent _ a sharp drop from the
current maximum rate of about 47 percent _ and announced that an
``Alliance for Jobs'' bringing together business and labor unions
to discuss new ways to create employment would convene for the
first time next month. Unions applauded this step.
</P>
<P>
   How jobs would be found was left unclear, and Schroeder appeared
to stand on both sides of the fence on the question of reforming
social security.
</P>
<P>
   He attacked the high cost of Germany's welfare state, saying
there are ``grounds for believing that it is our social security
system and its high costs that drive ever more people into
circumventing the system, into illegal jobs,'' and declaring that
``the way we organize social security is in fact endangering or
destroying jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   These statements amounted to a public avowal of what many
Germans privately concede: that they are often better off
collecting comprehensive benefits and working in the ``black''
economy than looking for a legal job.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, Schroeder announced that among his
government's most immediate steps would be the reversal of the very
limited cutbacks of social security undertaken by the previous
government. Curtailment of sick pay and limits on protection
against dismissal _ two measures passed by the center-right
government of Chancellor Helmut Kohl _ would be rescinded as of
Jan. 1, Schroeder said.
</P>
<P>
   His program was bluntly attacked by Wolfgang Schauble, the
combative new leader of the Christian Democrats, who replaced Kohl
this month. ``I have not found anything of the new center, but
plenty of the old left, and even more confusion,'' he said. ``Your
speech was remarkably vague.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Schroeder's message appeared vaguest on the most
critical and difficult question _ how to create jobs _ and bolder
on the idea that Germany has entered a new phase of national
self-confidence.
</P>
<P>
   German nationality would be opened to many more foreigners
because ``our national consciousness depends not on some `law of
descent' of Wilhelmine tradition but on the self-assured democracy
we have become,'' Schroeder said, referring to the 1913 citizenship
legislations. He plans to abandon that law's insistence on ``German
stock.''
</P>
<P>
   Fears that a ``Berlin Republic'' may sound ``too Prussian and
authoritarian, too centralist,'' are completely unfounded, the
chancellor said. Rather, the new capital would symbolize a
``completely nonaggressive'' vision of ``solidarity and innovation,
enterprise and civic spirit, ecological responsibility and
political leaders who see themselves as modern managers of
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Where Is Schroeder?'' the weekly magazine Der Spiegel asked
this week, on a cover showing the chancellor's blue eyes peeking
through the clouds. The question reflected a sense that he has not
yet asserted his authority over the new government.
</P>
<P>
   The answer Tuesday appeared to be that the chancellor has a
strong sense of the new German spirit he wishes to embody _ one
that has found a strong echo with his people _ without having firm
ideas about how to bring that spirit to life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
