<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-ISRAEL-410&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI CABINET SET TO ENDORSE PALESTINIAN PACT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also EXCLUSIVE-MIDEAST-SPY) 
(bl) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ After a nearly two-week delay, the Israeli Cabinet
will meet Wednesday to approve the new Israeli-Palestinian accord,
renewing deliberations suspended after a suicide bombing in
Jerusalem last Friday, the government announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Cabinet meeting was announced under intense U.S. pressure to
resume the process of ratifying the agreement, which has been
repeatedly postponed by Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu since the
accord, known as the Wye Memorandum, was signed in Washington on
Oct. 23.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, which calls for an Israeli troop withdrawal from
13 percent of the West Bank in exchange for a Palestinian crackdown
on violent militants, was supposed to be carried out over 12 weeks
from Nov. 2, but it has been delayed pending Israeli ratification.
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from rightist allies, including Cabinet members
critical of the accord, Netanyahu has demanded assurances that the
Palestinians are combating terrorism and arresting wanted suspects,
and that they will vote again to cancel clauses in the PLO charter
that call for Israel's destruction.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of Wednesday's Cabinet meeting cited
Palestinian anti-terrorist steps, but added that approval of the
accord would include a condition that the Palestine National
Council, the broadest decision-making body of the PLO, must vote to
change the charter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cabinet will meet tomorrow at noon to complete the
discussion and to approve the Wye Agreement,'' said a statement
from Netanyahu's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prime minister decided to convene the Cabinet after
receiving reports that the Palestinian Authority has begun taking
practical steps against the terrorist infrastructures and the
terrorists in its area,'' the statement added.
</P>
<P>
   After the attack in Jerusalem on Friday, in which 24 people were
wounded and the two bombers were killed, the Cabinet suspended its
deliberations, saying it would meet only when it was satisfied that
the Palestinian Authority is waging an ``all-out war'' on militants
who have carried out two suicide bombings since the accord was
signed.
</P>
<P>
   David Bar-Illan, a spokesman for Netanyahu, said Tuesday that
there had been ``satisfactory'' reports from Israeli security
agencies that the Palestinians had taken ``some concrete steps
against terrorists, and that they are planning to take even more
steps.'' He added that these steps ``are different, qualitatively
and quantitatively, than before.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   After Friday's attack, which was claimed by the Islamic Holy War
movement, the Palestinian security forces said they had rounded up
members of the organization in the West Bank. The Palestinians were
also reported to be pursuing the head of the cell that carried out
the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the Palestinian charter, the statement added: ``In
the event that the government ratifies the Wye agreement, the
following condition will be attached to the decision:
`Implementation of the rest of the agreement will be conditional
upon the convening of the Palestine National Council and on the
vote to amend the charter as promised.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians have insisted that the council will not hold a
vote in addition to a resolution it took in April 1996 to cancel
the clauses in its charter that call for Israel's destruction.
</P>
<P>
   The Wye agreement says council members and other Palestinian
officials will be invited to a meeting addressed by President
Clinton to ``reaffirm their support for the peace process'' and for
decisions by PLO executive bodies confirming nullification of the
offending clauses.
</P>
<P>
   After the Wye agreement is ratified by the Israeli Cabinet, it
will be be debated in Parliament, where it is expected to win broad
approval, with the support of the Labor opposition.
</P>
<P>
   But Netanyahu faces strong resistance from some members of his
rightist coalition who oppose the further handover of territory to
the Palestinians. They have vowed to join forces with the
opposition to topple the government in parliamentary votes later
on.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of Israeli ratification of the accord raised
cautious hopes among Palestinian officials, who have condemned the
repeated delays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they will ratify the accord, and I hope that they will
refrain from any statement to undermine the effort to build a level
of trust that is needed,'' said Saeb Erakat, a senior Palestinian
negotiator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope Netanyahu will look at the bigger picture,'' Erakat
added. ``We will continue carrying out our obligations to the
letter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
