<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SPEAKER-1STLEDEWRITETHR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVINGSTON PUTTING TOGETHER LEADERSHIP STAFF BEFORE WINNING
SPEAKER'S POST 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
EDITORS: 1STLEDEWRITETHRU corrects the day of the week in the first
paragraph to Tuesday instead of Monday By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Bob Livingston of Louisiana began putting
together new leadership staff and working on committee assignments
Tuesday even though he has not yet been officially elected as the
new speaker of the House.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston, who is expected to be tapped Republican members on
Nov. 18 to replace Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., met in the evening with
outgoing speaker to discuss the transition of power.
</P>
<P>
   Working in his office across from the Capitol, Livingston
continued placing phone calls to members to shore up support. He
told many of them that he would likely name Rep. C.W. ``Bill''
Young of Florida to take Livingston's old post as chairman of the
Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with CNN, Livingston said he hopes that his
tenure as speaker will be almost ``boring,'' when compared to
Gingrich's four-year tenure.
</P>
<P>
   He called himself a conservative, but said he would replace the
``flamboyance'' and partisan conservatism of the Gingrich era with
a more pragmatic management style designed to overcome legislative
logjams of the kind that forced two government shutdowns in 1995
and early 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being simply conservative and making grand speeches doesn't do
any good if we can't get the bills through the House and Senate and
on the president's desk,'' Livingston said.
</P>
<P>
   He also pledged to allow committee chairmen greater freedom than
Gingrich did and said he said he would not inject himself into the
impeachment inquiry being conducted by Judiciary Committee Chairman
Henry Hyde.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston promised that his first act as the new speaker will
be to introduce legislation that will take the Social Security
Trust Fund off budget. The surplus trust fund has been used in the
past to help balance the federal budget, a process that Livingston
and other members on both sides of the aisle say has undermined its
stability.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he has not been elected yet, Livingston said has
discussed all kinds of leadership business of leadership business
like arranging the schedule for ``freshmen orientation'' later this
week. The next speaker will also be involved in making revisions in
the House rules that often led to angry show-downs with Democrats
in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said Livingston told members plans to remain neutral in
the three other battles being waged for the jobs of majority
leader, GOP conference chairman and head of the Republican National
Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dick Armey of Irving currently holds the the No. 2 post of
majority leader, but faces a tough challenge from Reps. Jennifer
Dunn of Washington and Steve Largent of Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   There was also talk around Capitol Hill Monday that Rep. Bill
Thomas of California, who currently chairs the House Oversight
Committee, may decide to challenge Armey, whom many members blame
as much as they do Gingrich for the loss of five GOP House seats to
the Democrats in this year's election.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the opposition, Armey aides said he was confident that
he has enough committed votes to come out ahead of any of his
challengers when members meet next week to cast their secret
ballots for the new leadership team.
</P>
<P>
   Armey will have to get a majority of the 222 votes expected to
be cast in the Nov. 18 election. ``We know how to count votes,''
his press secretary Michelle Green said, when asked if Armey has
enough support.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Largent, a hard-line conservative and former pro football
star, said he was prepared to call what he described as an Armey
bluff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a head fake when I see one,'' he said, adding that his
internal counting shows the Texan way short of a majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that the incumbent majority leader hasn't locked up
his re-election bid . . . sends a clear signal that the caucus is
not behind Dick and is seriously weighing a change,'' Largent said.
</P>
<P>
   Armey's bid for re-election has apparently been undermined by
the fact that House Majority Whip Tom DeLay of Texas has yet to
throw the full weight of his vote-getting organization behind him.
Although DeLay is expected to vote for his fellow Texan, Republican
aides said that Armey has not yet asked his colleague for help.
</P>
<P>
   That may be because the two have not been on the best of terms
since last year when DeLay ended up taking most of the blame for a
failed coup that conservative members mounted against Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   Armey was involved early on in discussions among conservatives
about removing Gingrich, but bailed out of the insurrection after
it became clear that he might lose his leadership post in the
process. His flip-flop ended up alienating a lot of conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, who was blamed by some of his colleagues for the GOP
losses as well, is the only Republican leader who is not facing a
challenge in his re-election bid. Members who intend to support him
say that he is still considered the best at pulling together the
votes needed from both sides of the aisle to pass crucial
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Although DeLay, one of the most conservative members of
Congress, has said little since the election about the upheaval
within the leadership, he has moved quickly to mend fences with
angry Republicans who believe his job should be up for grabs as
well. In addition to throwing his whip organization behind
Livingston, he has also been calling members on behalf of moderate
Rep. Tom Davis of Virginia who challenging conservative John Linder
of Georgia for head of the party's congressional campaign
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Delay's support, Davis is believed to have the job
all wrapped up over Linder, who was appointed to his position two
years ago by Gingrich. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
