<HEADER>
A3912 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIR-STATION-ART-NYT     11-10 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIR-STATION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA WEIGHS RUSSIAN REQUEST TO CHANGE INTERNATIONAL SPACE STATION
ORBIT
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(dal) 
 By WARREN E. LEARY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NASA is considering a last-minute request from the
Russian Space Agency to change the planned orbit of the upcoming
International Space Station, officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   With the flight of the first part of the space station less than
two weeks away, the Russians have raised the possibility of putting
the new complex in an orbit much closer to their old Mir station
than originally planned.
</P>
<P>
   While NASA says it is considering the change proposed by Russia
at face value, some experts on the Russian space program question
the motives behind the request. Putting the new station near Mir
could be part of a plan to delay the decommissioning and
destruction of the older station, critics suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``This move on the orbital changes would open up all sort of
options for the Russians,'' James E. Oberg of Houston, a former
NASA engineer who is an expert on the Russian space program, said.
``The actual game plan may take a while to come clear.''
</P>
<P>
   The collapse of the Russian economy has resulted in little money
for the Russian Space Agency, raising doubts as to whether the
limited resources available could support both the new program and
Mir. To ease these concerns, the Russians have promised NASA they
would discard Mir next summer, but Russian nationalists have
campaigned recently to preserve the station, a symbol of the
nation's achievements in space.
</P>
<P>
   Dwayne Brown, a NASA spokesman, said Tuesday that the agency
received the Russian request late last week and would make a
decision on the proposed change by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russians said they wanted to transfer some equipment off
of Mir to the International Space Station and that this orbital
change would make it easier,'' Brown said. ``The request only
concerned moving internal equipment from Mir, not transferring
modules from Mir to the new station.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said Russian and American space planners were discussing
the ramifications of such an orbital change on building the new
station, as well as how any equipment transfer would take place.
Making such a change would require a lot of last-minute work,
including making new orbital calculations and adjusting the
timelines of upcoming missions that have to be coordinated with the
first flight, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and 15 other nations plan to begin building
the new space station in orbit on Nov. 20 when the Russians launch
a module called Zarya that will supply power and propulsion during
the early stages of construction. The Russians want to launch
Zarya, build in Russia under U.S. contract, 10 hours later than
planned so that its orbit ends up close to Mir's.
</P>
<P>
   The space shuttle Endeavour is scheduled to lift off in the
predawn hours of Dec. 3 with the second station part, an
American-built connecting passageway called Unity that will be
attached to Zarya. If the Russians change their launch time, the
shuttle takeoff also would have to change.
</P>
<P>
   Oberg said Tuesday that when the Russians reach agreements, it
is not uncommon for them to seek seemingly minor changes as a
deadline approaches. ``The fact that the Russians waited two weeks
before launch to pull this rabbit out of the hat suggests that
there is some kind of trick here,'' he said in a telephone
interview.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Russia suggested that two of the newer laboratory
modules on Mir, Spektr and Piroda, be moved to the new station to
substitute for new research modules it promised the new project but
cannot afford to build. However, the other station partners
rejected the notion.
</P>
<P>
   Having the two stations in close orbit makes it easier to send
material back and forth between them, or to divert cargoes from one
to another, Oberg said. For instance, he added, if Russia becomes
dissatisfied with the international project for any reason, he
said, this gives it an option of taking its modules off the new
station and attaching them to Mir.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
