A3917 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUN-CONTROL-HNS &LR;      11-10 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-CONTROL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUN CONTROL ADVOCATES, OPPONENTS PREDICT PROBLEMS WITH NEW `INSTANT
CHECK' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN DRAKE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gun control advocates and opponents Tuesday expressed concerns
about the new phase of the Brady gun control law that institutes
instant criminal background checks for firearms purchasers.
</P>
<P>
   The new phase, to begin Nov. 30, eliminates the five-day waiting
period to do a federal criminal background check for handgun
purchases. Instead federally licensed gun dealers will be required
to do an instant check on purchases of handgun and rifles.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI was to use an electronic system similar to those used
for credit cards to handle the instant checks, but that won't be
ready before January, according to Emet Rathbun, the FBI unit chief
in charge of setting up the system. Instead, FBI staff will man
toll-free telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
   State and local authorities will have the option of keeping a
waiting period and can conduct their own background checks, as
California will, for example. But Houston law enforcement officials
said they will convert to the new federal system.
</P>
<P>
   In the Houston area, both city police and sheriff departments
now check local, state and federal criminal records. Even an
outstanding warrant for an unpaid traffic ticket or missing an
appearance in court can disqualify a purchaser, said Capt. Don
McWilliams, spokesman for the sheriff's department.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff's office runs about 750 checks a month, 9,000 a
year; police have reviewed 2,649 and rejected 370 between 1994 and
1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Brady law, named after Ronald Reagan's press secretary who
was shot in a presidential assassination attempt, was passed in
1993. Pro-gun groups such as the National Rifle Association fought
the law in the courts.
</P>
<P>
   The Violence Policy Center, a national gun-control group, issued
a report Tuesday that raised questions about how the new federal
system will work, particularly in states such as Texas that will
drop local background checks.
</P>
<P>
   Gun control groups are concerned that local mental health
records won't be included in the new national database. Those
records are usually not on computer, and many states have records
protecting them.
</P>
<P>
   But Rathbun said the new federal system will contain about
350,000 records of the mentally unstable, though that does not
include people deemed unstable by private or local institutions.
</P>
<P>
   A new law about misdemeanor domestic violence convictions also
has gun control groups concerned, although it faces court tests
over its constitutionality. The Lautenberg law, named after
Democratic Senator Frank Lautenberg of New Jersey, prohibits law
enforcement officers and military personnel who have been convicted
of a domestic violence misdemeanor from carrying guns.
</P>
<P>
   Records often do not reflect domestic violence convictions,
listing it instead as a misdemeanor assault or disorderly conduct.
</P>
<P>
   If a buyer has a common name that matches a convicted felon's
name, the National Instant Check System (NICS) staff will tell the
gun dealer to delay the sale while they investigate the buyer.
</P>
<P>
   The burden of proof is on the FBI, though, to prove the case
within three federal working days, not counting the day of the
inquiry. After that, the buyer can purchase the firearm.
</P>
<P>
   Gun control advocates agree with pro-gun groups that the process
could overwhelm NICS staff. Most firearm purchases take place on a
Saturday and aren't spaced evenly through the week. The FBI could
get between 30,000 to 40,000 inquiries on a Saturday in November or
December, according to the FBI and the Texas Gun Owners
Association. The phase kicks in at the height of hunting season,
especially in Texas, and at the beginning of the gift-giving
holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI will have 200-300 people at the toll-free call-in
center, where operators will punch in a buyer's information. Eighty
percent of the time the operator will tell the dealer to proceed
with or deny the sale. But if the buyer appears to have a criminal
background, the operator passes the case to one of 513 workers who
must determine if the buyer really matches the record, and if that
record disqualifies the buyer.
</P>
<P>
   The center will operate 17 hours a day, seven days a week. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
