<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3919 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMERICAN-ARTS-ART-$AD     11-10 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-ARTS-ART-$ADV15-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN ARIAS FIND A GROOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Nov. 15)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(David Mermelstein lives in Los Angeles and writes about the
arts.) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID MERMELSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since the dawn of the recording era, collections of songs and
arias have held a special place in the hearts and on the shelves of
music lovers. Early on, listeners themselves bunched 78s together
to form extended programs. But with the advent of the long-playing
record in the late 1940s, full-length recitals and concept albums
arrived prepackaged.
</P>
<P>
   From the first, Italian opera arias commanded pride of place
within the genre, and they still do, as yet another recording from
the Three Tenors attests. But disks of German lieder or even French
and Russian repertory have never been in short supply. And
occasionally, a set of Spanish or even Scandinavian songs peppers
the mix.
</P>
<P>
   Arias from American operas, however, have not found much of a
home on record. Until recently, in fact, American operas themselves
have largely been ignored. Now the release of two CDs by the
sopranos Dawn Upshaw and Renee Fleming suggests that the tide may
be turning. The two albums, Ms. Upshaw's ``World So Wide''
(Nonesuch 79458-2) and Ms. Fleming's ``I Want Magic'' (London 289
460 567-2), concentrate on repertory that most listeners will find
unfamiliar, though several of the composers _ Gershwin, Copland,
Barber and Bernstein among them _ are household names.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, ``The World So Wide'' is a follow-up to ``I Wish
It So,'' Ms. Upshaw's exceptional 1994 collection of American
theater songs, also on Nonesuch. There, the soprano applied her
warm, agile, eager sound to music by Bernstein, Weill, Sondheim and
Marc Blitzstein. On her new record, the repertory falls primarily
into two categories: arias in some way associated with the American
heartland (selections by Copland, Carlisle Floyd and Douglas Moore)
and items in which an urban esthetic prevails (works by Bernstein,
Barber, Weill and John Adams). One piece, ``Oh Yemanja,'' composed
by the Cuban emigree Tania Leon, fits neither grouping.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Upshaw begins with ``Laurie's Song'' from Copland's 1954
opera ``The Tender Land,'' in which an intelligent but sheltered
girl on the cusp of adulthood muses about her future. The soprano's
earnest expression and crisp diction perfectly suit this music,
with its clean lines and simple orchestration.
</P>
<P>
   And the soprano is no less persuasive in ``This Is Prophetic''
from Adams' ``Nixon in China,'' which had its premiere in 1987. The
combination of the composer's repetitive style and the librettist
Alice Goodman's sententious lyrics might make this a dreary
exercise, but Ms. Upshaw, as Pat Nixon, finds poetry in these
hypnotic strains, and point, too. (When she utters the line, ``let
Gypsy Rose/ Kick off her high-heeled party shoes,'' it is
impossible not to crack a knowing smile.)
</P>
<P>
   ``What a Movie,'' an unapologetic showstopper from Bernstein's
``Trouble in Tahiti'' (1951), finds Ms. Upshaw, as a suburban
housewife named Dinah, relating the plot of a harebrained film.
Here, Ms. Upshaw, using a variety of inflections, reveals her
unrivaled affinity for musical comedy, which this pastiche
satirizes in grand fashion, complete with blaring brass, xylophone
and snare drum.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Leon's ``Oh Yemanja,'' from her 1994 chamber opera ``Scourge
of Hyacinths,'' is a mother's prayer for her son's well-being.
Based on a radio play by the Nigerian Wole Soyinka, the work
concerns a young man's attempt to flee persecution. In this spare
music, the soprano's focused timbre conveys both maternal concern
and a faintly exotic atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Upshaw is at her best in music like the languorous,
sentimental ``Willow Song'' from Douglas Moore's ``Ballad of Baby
Doe'' (1956), in which the singer's personal magnetism combines
with the material to form an irresistible mixture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lonely House,'' from Weill's evocative ``Street Scene'' of
1947, places the soprano in a very different world, singing words
Langston Hughes wrote for a tenor. Yet Ms. Upshaw, with all the
assurance of a jazz diva, lends this soliloquy an urbane
world-weariness.
</P>
<P>
   In a bold move, Ms. Upshaw tackles ``Give Me Some Music,'' one
of Cleopatra's arias from Barber's ill-fated ``Antony and
Cleopatra,'' composed for the 1966 opening of the new Metropolitan
Opera House in Lincoln Center. This is grandiose, even
grandiloquent, music, and though the soprano can't summon the
majesty one associates with Leontyne Price, who created the role,
Ms. Upshaw imparts an earnest eroticism to strains in need of a
human touch.
</P>
<P>
   The disk concludes with the ravishing ``Ain't It a Pretty
Night'' from Carlisle Floyd's ``Susannah'' (1955). A wrenching tale
of a woman wrongly accused of being ``of the devil,'' the work is a
rare example of an American opera that has enjoyed continual favor
and a measure of renown. Ms. Upshaw sings this moving aria of a
young woman's dreams and the comforts of home with a freshness and
sense of wonder few can match.
</P>
<P>
   For support, Ms. Upshaw could hardly do better than the
Orchestra of St. Luke's under David Zinman's direction; a keen
interpreter of American music, Zinman skillfully guides these
accomplished players through a host of American idioms.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fleming's ``I Want Magic'' also provides a superb showcase
for the rich variety of American operatic music. Moreover, it
presents Ms. Fleming's opulent, mellifluous, multi-hued soprano in
material well suited to her gifts.
</P>
<P>
   The disk opens on a haunting note, with ``I Have Dreamt'' from
Bernard Herrmann's ``Wuthering Heights,'' an opera completed in
1951 but not staged until 1982. As Emily Bronte's doomed heroine
Cathy, Ms. Fleming compellingly blends plushness with implicit
melancholy.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Letter Song'' from ``The Ballad of Baby Doe'' also works
well for the soprano. In this anguished aria, Ms. Fleming
communicates heartbreak without overstatement. And in ``Monica's
Waltz'' from Gian Carlo Menotti's ``Medium,'' which had its
premiere in 1946, the soprano handily masters the challenge of
voicing two characters, the medium's daughter and the servant,
Toby.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fleming even makes her mark in such familiar music as
``Summertime'' and ``My Man's Gone Now'' from Gershwin's 1935 opera
``Porgy and Bess.'' The competition may seem insurmountable, but
the soprano's sumptuous approach has legitimate appeal, and her
glittering sultriness is hard to dismiss.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Bernstein's ``Glitter and Be Gay,'' Cunegonde's campy
coloratura scena from ``Candide'' (1956), receives a strange,
pushed reading, with the soprano adopting and then abandoning what
sounds like a German accent. This account is less characterful than
Ms. Upshaw's performance on the ``I Wish It So'' album, nor can it
compete in vocal pyrotechnics with a version recorded live last
year by the French soprano Natalie Dessay at the EMI centenary
gala.
</P>
<P>
   In the two arias from ``Susannah,'' which she will sing at the
Metropolitan Opera in the spring, Ms. Fleming is at her most
inspired. Employing a subtle Southern drawl, she invests ``Ain't It
a Pretty Night'' with even greater emotional urgency than Ms.
Upshaw. And in ``The Trees on the Mountains,'' her straightforward
tenderness and incisive vocalism prove overpowering.
</P>
<P>
   ``No Word From Tom,'' from Stravinsky's ``Rake's Progress''
(1951), may seem an odd choice for this disk, but the Russian-born
composer had been an American citizen for several years when he
wrote the opera. Regardless, Ms. Fleming's vibrant, affecting
performance is its own defense.
</P>
<P>
   Like Ms. Upshaw, Ms. Fleming has included an aria by Barber, but
here the choice is ``He Has Come, He Has Come'' from ``Vanessa,''
which had its premiere in 1958. Ms. Fleming is convincingly fervid
in this music, but she lacks the neurotic appeal that made the
legendary Eleanor Steber so gripping in the role.
</P>
<P>
   Given that she just starred as Blanche in the premiere of Andre
Previn's ``Streetcar Named Desire,'' Ms. Fleming understandably
concludes her CD with an excerpt from the new opera, ``I Want
Magic!'' More arioso than aria, the piece represents Blanche's
credo as told to Mitch, and Ms. Fleming, her Southern accent firmly
in place, sings it with an ardency perhaps only a creator can
bestow.
</P>
<P>
   In what may be music's version of a royal flush, Ms. Fleming's
accompaniment comes from the Metropolitan Opera Orchestra and its
maestro, James Levine. Their support contributes to this album's
success not only by providing distinguished, polished playing, but
also by lending undeniable cachet to the enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   One hesitates to maintain that the release of two new
recordings, even such fine ones, marks a sea change in the fate of
American arias on disk. Yet by giving their voices to the cause,
Ms. Fleming and Ms. Upshaw have raised the profile of music they
hold dear. Lovers of great singing should take note (if they
haven't already) and turn their attentions to this repertory as
well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-10-98 2004EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
