<DOCNO> NYT19981110.0286 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3922 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      11-10 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: OF FROGS AND NEWTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MAUREEN DOWD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   One show was about a frog.
</P>
<P>
   The other, a Newt.
</P>
<P>
   I was trying to watch the last gasp of Newt Gingrich on C-Span
on Monday night. But when he held up that laminated copy of the
original Contract With America, bragging once again that it had
been printed in TV Guide, treating it as reverently as if it were a
sacred piece of 18th-century parchment, talking about the little
holes he had punched in the contract as each item became law, I
lost it.
</P>
<P>
   TV Guide. That's an excellent idea. What else is on?
</P>
<P>
   I clicked over to Fox. There, on ``Ally McBeal,'' was another
amphibian expiring in an undignified manner. The pet frog of Ally's
boss, a lawyer known as The Biscuit, ended up being served to him
as dinner in a Chinese restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   I began flipping back and forth between Ally and Newt,
mesmerized by the juxtaposition of two of the most neurotic
creatures of modern America. There they were, hollow cheek by plump
jowl. The lawyer in the micro-minis and the speaker in the
pinstripes. Two revolutionaries who have graced the cover of Time.
Two famously nutty, adolescent, undisciplined, self-absorbed
figures with eating problems, a habit of driving feminists crazy
and a talent for tantrums.
</P>
<P>
   They are chatty icons of the if-it's-about-me-it's-interesting
view of life. They spent all their time inventing and reinventing
themselves. Her inner thoughts are acted out as fantasy sequences.
His inner thoughts are also pathologically transparent.
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Noonan's observation in The Wall Street Journal about Newt
could also apply to Ally, that he ``did not sense that an unshared
thought can have power, that the face you have when you have an
observation that you're too circumspect to share is an interesting
face, and an interesting face has a certain mystery . . . and
mystery has a certain power.''
</P>
<P>
   What was really intriguing, flipping between them, is how
quickly revolutions in our culture grow stale. In the rush of TV
imagery, spectacles that are hot turn cold so swiftly they can
freeze meat. For Newt, the golden age was only four seasons ago.
For Ally, it was last season.
</P>
<P>
   In newspaper columns, Ms. Noonan and David Broder drew parallels
between Gingrich and Richard Nixon, predicting that the speaker was
relentless and would not be absent long from the political arena.
He could have used his Gopac dinner as a trampoline to leap into
the next phase of his career. But, like Ally, he turns himself
inside out, putting the wounded inner child on display for everyone
to see. He makes his frat-boy doppelgaenger at the other end of
Pennsylvania Avenue seem mature. The routines are so tired that one
of the Gopac zealots was caught on camera nodding off.
</P>
<P>
   I flipped back to Ally. Billy, the tiresome ex-love-of-her-life,
was still moping around the show, while she was consigning another
loser boyfriend to the Dumpster _ a sight gag from last season.
</P>
<P>
   I flipped back to Newt. Relief! ``Finally,'' he was finally
saying.
</P>
<P>
   I flipped back to Ally. They were back in the unisex bathroom, a
setting that has lost its novelty as a device for overhearing
confessions to the sound of rushing and flushing water.
</P>
<P>
   I flipped back to Newt. ``Second,'' he was saying. Uh-oh. Now he
was sounding like an old Quincy Jones production. ``The world has
been good to us,'' he said, ``and we have been good to the world.''
(The world refused to comment.)
</P>
<P>
   Just when I thought it couldn't get worse, C-Span touted on
screen the show next up: ``Impeachment interpretation hearing.
C-Span tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there's something to be said for commercials and ratings.
C-Span has turned politics into a TV series that nobody has the
power to pull.
</P>
<P>
   I flipped to Ally. I don't care what she says in interviews.
She's shrinking. Her hands look like claws. She needs an infusion
of Chubby Hubby.
</P>
<P>
   I flipped back to Newt. He's not shrinking. I was thinking about
some of the best closing lines of great political speeches, even by
losers.
</P>
<P>
   At the 1980 Democratic convention, Sen. Edward Kennedy brought
down the house with this finale: ``The work goes on, the cause
endures, the hope still lives _ and the dream shall never die.''
Newt, who so often overreached for grandiosity, also seemed to be
going for the poetry, but fell short with this clunker: ``The venue
changes and the cause lives on.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as Ally might say, the cause changes but the venue lives on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-10-98 2004EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981110.0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3923 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPIRITUAL-DANCES-2TAK     11-10 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPIRITUAL-DANCES-2TAKES-$ADV15-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CELEBRATION OF THE SPIRITUAL WHERE SOME SEE SIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Nov. 15)  
 (bl)  
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Life is a battle for the human soul between the
forces of the sacred and the profane. Or so it would seem even to a
casual voyager through theological musings on dance over the last
four centuries. Dance, like sex, was marginally allowable as a
duty, a way of maintaining a healthy body. Otherwise, dancing led
to perdition. ``Of the 500,000 fallen women in the United States,
over 300,000 started from the ballroom,'' W.W. Hamilton, a Baptist
minister from Virginia, stoutly proclaimed early this century.
</P>
<P>
   But dance has a connection to the spirit that is intimate,
immediate and unavoidable. An art that merges abstraction and the
literal physicality of the human body, dance became
self-referential in the mid-20th century, making a virtue of being
about nothing more than the body itself.
</P>
<P>
   Yet dance has remained singularly capable of evoking the spirit,
whether in the soul of a dancer who has achieved selflessness in
motion or in the soul of the viewer identifying with that physical
exaltation.
</P>
<P>
   This week, in theaters a few blocks apart in Brooklyn, two
programs will address and seek to incorporate and represent the
spirit. The dance in those programs is worlds apart in time,
history and geography. The Madras-based Chandralekha, whose new
full-evening ``Raga: In Search of Femininity'' is to open Wednesday
for four performances at the Majestic Theater, presented by the
Next Wave Festival of the Brooklyn Academy of Music, comes from the
East and a culture that at least by Western standards is permeated
with the spiritual.
</P>
<P>
   A performer of the Bharata Natyam school of stylized Indian
dance-drama, Chandralekha left the field to devote herself to
political activism. When she returned in the mid-1980s, it was to
create a form of dance that merges traditional Eastern and modern
Western movement forms in the service, largely, of summoning the
spiritual. Her ``Raga'' aims to embody the unseen self ``that
hovers in between,'' that ``is neither man nor woman,'' in the
words of a poem by the 10th-century poet Devara Daslmayya that
partly inspired the piece. Chandralekha's innovations, while
acclaimed internationally, have been controversial at home in
India. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The three choreographers whose work will be shown in ``Dance and
Spiritual Life,'' the second event, are a part of a long, though
largely unacknowledged, tradition in American modern dance.
Unusually, attention will be paid to the potential of dance to
connect the spirit and the body in the one-performance program
Saturday, which features choreography by Dianne McIntyre, Bebe
Miller and Jawole Willa Jo Zollar, three black choreographers who
have been prominent on the American modern-dance landscape during
the last several decades.
</P>
<P>
   Their work will be presented by 651, An Arts Center at the
Academy Opera House, with free ancillary workshops and discussions
on the subject of dance and the spirit, particularly in black
American culture, to be given this week in various locations in
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   What exactly does ``spirit'' mean in these far-flung contexts?
For Chandralekha, ``sensuality, sexuality, spirituality are all
unified in the body,'' as the choreographer told Shanta Gokhale in
a recent interview in Persona magazine. ``My work is about linking
inner and outer spaces. We live in the body without understanding
its vital parts and points and without the knowledge of how to
bridge the inner-outer divide.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, body and spirit are separate entities in the works
in ``Dance and Spiritual Life,'' with the yearning, vital distance
between them the subject of much of the choreography. The dancers,
singers and actors in Ms. McIntyre's ``Love Poems to God,'' a
collaboration with the composer and poet Hannibal Lokumbe, engage
in ``intimate conversations with God in a way that is very
personal,'' Ms. McIntyre said.
</P>
<P>
   A funny, sad and awesome vision of God emerges in Ms. Zollar's
``Transitions,'' a ritualistic piece built around the dancers'
taped memories of their ideas of God from childhood on. Ms.
Miller's ``Blessed,'' performed to a cappella gospel music by an
Australian group called the Cafe of the Gate of Salvation, comes
closest to an abstract blending of mind and soul.
</P>
<P>
   None of these works refers to specific religious tradition.
American dance studios, unlike foxholes, seem to be home to a fair
share of nonbelievers. ``Religious imagery is not paramount to the
delineation of spiritual content,'' the dance historian Joe Nash
said. Nash will participate in Dance in the Black Church, a ``Dance
and Spiritual Life'' discussion Thursday night at the Cornerstone
Baptist Church in the Bedford Stuyvesant section of Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martha Graham uses religious imagery to further her thesis
about the spiritual nature of Joan of Arc in `Seraphic
Dialogues,''' he said , but what about Doris Humphrey's ``Day on
Earth'' and the serene, quasi-spiritual look it takes at the human
life cycle? ``There's no religious imagery there, but the quality
comes through,'' Nash said. ``Eleo Pomare's `Blues for the Jungle,'
a dance about violence in the city, is a choreographer's response
to suffering humanity. The church finale in Alvin Ailey's
`Revelations' serves as the inspiration for the whole work, but the
spirituality that comes through is because of the rich images he
has created, the blending of the music and the movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Isadora Duncan said that dance is the divine expression of the
human soul. Ted Shawn and Ruth St. Denis talked about the spiritual
component of dance. ``Even in Merce Cunningham's `Summerspace,'
where the dancers blend with the background, there is a feeling of
mystery,'' Nash said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The spirit was always at the heart of American modern dance.
But scholars did not wish to write about this area. It wasn't until
years later, when people began to look more deeply into modern
dance, that they began to see the ritual aspects, the spiritual
elements. And now is a time when people are discussing this
question of spirituality.''
</P>
<P>
   Paleolithic-era cave drawings suggest that dance or formal,
ritualized movement symbolized everyday activities in primitive
life. Movement has been an integral part of religious ritual
through time, and there has been a recent resurgence of interest in
liturgical dance in America.
</P>
<P>
   Dance is finding its way back into religious services and the
personal investigation of faith in ways that range from Kathleen
Sumler's 20-year-old dance ministry at the Allen AME Church in
Jamaica, Queens, to JoAnne Tucker's newly developed workshops in
exploring Talmudic and Biblical texts through dance improvisation.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   There has been a huge increase in the number of black-dance
ministries in this country over the last two decades, although
dance as a vehicle of prayer is still frowned upon by many
traditional black churches. Much recent dance by black
choreographers makes room for the spiritual openly and in
distinctive ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's a very strong element in the African-American
community,'' said Ms. Zollar, who is black. ``It's not something
that we're embarrassed or cynical about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our culture accepts the externalization of the spirit through
speech and the emotions. I think for us it comes from Africa. A
pope once said that one reason he wanted to do so much work there
was that atheism didn't exist in Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   But burrow deep enough into the traditions and history of any
religion and it is possible to find a remarkable universality in
the expression of the spirit. And the traditions of the sacred, as
represented in churches and synagogues, and the profane, as
represented in dance studios and on dance stages, have much in
common.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tucker and her Avodah Dance Ensemble, a New York-based
Jewish liturgical dance company, have worked with Rev. Lloyd Casson
at the St Andrew's and St. Matthew's Episcopal Church in
Wilmington, Del., which has merged black and white congregations.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has talked about how important it is for each of us to go
as deep as we can in our own tradition to find, underneath, the
deep river from which we could all draw,'' said Ms. Tucker, who
also teaches at the Hebrew Union College. Like Chandralekha, Ms.
Tucker believes in the conservation of tradition. ``The deeper we
go in to understand how we work with what we have, the more that's
leading us to something very common.''
</P>
<P>
   There are startling similarities between Ms. Sumler's
description of her work and the choreographers' depictions of the
ways dancers open themselves up, as Ms. Zollar puts it, to allow
creative energy to flow through them. ``You come to a place where
you don't even know how you did what they did,'' she said. ``In
sports they call it the Zone, where you're almost not the doer.
When you see it happen, it is a religious experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sumler and her 300-member dance ministry, composed of men,
women and children from 7 to 77, begin services with an
improvisational dance of praise and worship, in which they empty
themselves of ``immediate things and center our thoughts on the
Lord.'' ``People are coming in with issues,'' Ms. Sumler, a former
dancer and currently a professor of dance at Hunter College, said
of the congregants. ``They're losing their home. They've lost their
job. The bill collectors are coming, or someone needs a heart
transplant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stand in the gap, as soldiers in the army dancing the fight
for them no matter what their issues are. They should be able to
leave there changed. If not, we're not doing our job. And that
means we have to get out of ourselves so that they don't see us
dancing, they see God in the dance.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McIntyre, in turn, talks of the process of surrender to the
dance, for performers and their audiences, in similarly mystical
terms. ``Some kind of love has taken the mover,'' she said. ``It's
in their movement. It's a deep commitment. They have surrendered to
the dance, and their dance is an offering, to the audience. They
have become that dance, that moment, that gesture. We don't see
their ego. All that is gone. They've let themselves be erased.''
</P>
<P>
   That kind of erasure of self is epitomized in Humphrey's ``Two
Ecstatic Themes,'' a 1931 solo in which the dancer becomes her
simple ``circular descent'' and ``pointed ascent.'' But it has not
been easy to find _ or articulate _ in Western dance. And the
possibilities for it have diminished over the centuries in Jewish
and Christian religious tradition, as the mind has taken over the
body in services.
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Tucker, the separation from an early Talmudic emphasis
on the earthy, on ``basicness,'' came when Jews lost their land and
went into exile. ``It used to be that you looked out your window
and you saw what time to pray,'' Ms. Tucker said. ``We're so cut
off from all that.'' Ms. Sumler speaks of the replacement of dance
as worship by ``law,'' the churchly precepts of right and wrong.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, however, it has never been possible to separate
completely the body and the soul in dance or religion. ``From the
15th century to the present, `graceful' has been the single
adjective most used to describe good dancing,'' Ann Wagner writes
in ``Adversaries of Dance: From the Puritans to the Present,'' a
book published last year by the University of Illinois Press.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the antidance literature, the absence of grace in its
theological and esthetic dimensions, coupled with the presence of
law, is striking. The fruits of the law are fear and retribution.
The law can produce justice but not joy. By contrast, a positive
affirmation of life flows from the concept of grace.'' Dancing, Ms.
Wagner writes, is in its essence celebration: ``It is testimony to
God's creation _ a human being with an infinite capacity for
expression and joy in motion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
