<HEADLINE>
BOY, 9, FACES PROSECUTION IN RAPE CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLEMENT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A 9-year-old Boston boy is facing criminal charges
after he allegedly raped a 9-year-old girl in June, authorities
said Tuesday. The boy is the youngest criminal defendant in recent
Suffolk County history.
</P>
<P>
   Suffolk District Attorney Ralph C. Martin 2d Tuesday confirmed
the prosecution and said the boy is the youngest person his office
has charged since he became district attorney in 1992. The Boston
police Sexual Assault unit has investigated cases involving young
children, but the 9-year-old boy is the youngest to face charges,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's attorney said the complaint was unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   But Martin said the allegation against the boy raises broad
questions about the negative, societal influences that lead some
children to allegedly commit adult crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not self-learned'' behavior, Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of questions that have to be answered,'' about
the case, Martin said. ``We're figuring out how it is going to be
resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Boston police spokeswoman Sergeant Margot Hill, the
girl reported the alleged attack to a third person who informed the
girl's mother in late July. The mother telephoned Boston police on
the emergency line that day, Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives from the Sexual Assault Unit interviewed the girl
this summer. She was interviewed again on Aug. 20 and Martin's
Child Abuse Unit asked police to obtain criminal complaints in
Boston Juvenile Court, Hill said. A charge of rape against the boy
was issued following the hearing, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's Boston attorney, Chester Darling, said Tuesday he
hopes Martin's office will quickly resolve the case without further
damaging the boy and his family, whom he described as a ``family of
hard-working people.'' The boy is with his family.
</P>
<P>
   Darling added, ``I have every confidence that a complete review
of the case by a reasonable person at the office of DA Martin will
result in the withdrawal of this outrageous and essentially
unfounded complaint.''
</P>
<P>
   Darling criticized the quality of the Boston police
investigation, calling it an ``atrocity. The investigation in this
case was just the very least they could do in order to generate the
(criminal) complaint.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hill defended the quality of the investigation and dismissed
Darling's criticism of police as a commonplace defense attorney
tactic. ``It was done by the book,'' she said. ``The investigation
will prove its worth in court.''
</P>
<P>
   Under state law, children as young as 7 years old can be
criminally prosecuted and committed to the Department of Youth
Services once found delinquent by the courts, according to DYS
spokesman Glenn Daly. Daly said DYS can retain custody, in certain
cases, to the age of 21.
</P>
<P>
   In the current DYS population, courts have committed 356
children who are 13 years old or younger. Daly said DYS now has
custody of five children who are 10 years old; nine children who
are 11 years old; 76 children who are 12 years old and 266 who are
13 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Some are kept in locked facilities while others are living with
their families, although they remain committed to DYS. Still others
are in residential treatment facilities appropriate for their age
group, Daly said. Teenagers and the pre-teens are not mixed by DYS.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining 2,608 youths in DYS custody cover the ages from 14
to 18, Daly said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Boston case, it is possible the boy will not end up being
committed to DYS. Some other form of intervention, such as
counseling, could be ordered, officials said. A pre-trial
conference is set for Boston Juvenile Court in the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert Krane, a urologist at the Boston University Medical
Center, said Tuesday that men from infancy to old age get erections
and thus it is physically possible for a 9-year-old to commit a
rape.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
