<HEADLINE>
NIGHTTIME HEART ATTACKS MORE LIKELY TO KILL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RUTH SoRELLE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Beware the Monday nights of winter. A heart attack
could be lurking.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do the risks of heart attack increase on Mondays and in
the winter, but a heart attack at night is more likely to kill than
one that occurs during the day, said researchers at the 71st
scientific sessions of the American Heart Association here.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. C. Michael Gibson, director of invasive cardiology at
Allegheny General Hospital in Pittsburgh, Pa., compared 813
patients who went to the emergency department for a heart attack
between 6 a.m. and 6 p.m. with 433 who arrived between 6 p.m. and 6
a.m.
</P>
<P>
   He found the risk of dying for the evening patients was nearly
twice that of the daytime patients.
</P>
<P>
   The major difference between the two groups was the time delay
between recognition of symptoms and arrival at the hospital.
Evening patients tended to arrive at least 30 minutes later, Gibson
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said treatment for the two groups was the same as was the
type of medications. Patients underwent angioplasty as often at
night as during the day, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This underscores the importance of people coming to the
hospital as soon as possible at night,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If night is dangerous, so is winter, said Dr. Robert A. Kloner,
director of research at Good Samaritan Hospital in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   He analyzed the deaths from heart disease that occurred in Los
Angeles from 1985 until 1996. Most of the 9,328 deaths occurred in
December and January, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although researchers had pinpointed the winter months as more
risky for heart attacks earlier, they had done the work farther
north where the cold weather stressed hearts, Kloner said.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles weather is mild, indicating that other factors could
be at work, he said. Conversely, the lowest numbers of deaths
occurred in June, July, August and September, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rates in December and January were 33 percent higher''
than the rates in those hot weather months, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The stress of holidays appears to be at fault, Kloner said.
Death rates appeared fairly steady until Thanksgiving, when they
started to rise, he said. The increase continued until about a week
after the New Year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He advised avoiding stress, salt and excess alcohol during these
difficult months.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael K. Gruska, a post-graduate student at
Hanuschkrankenhaus in Vienna, Austria, found that heart attacks are
more likely to occur on Monday, even in the retirees among the
1,500 people who suffered heart attacks between January 1995 and
December 1996.
</P>
<P>
   He said the risk of having a heart attack on Monday is 1.2 to
1.4 times greater than on other days in the week.
</P>
<P>
   For workers, going back to the job could trigger the attacks, he
said. Retirees could suffer attacks because of returning to normal
social activities, he said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
