<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3936 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-VETERAN11     11-10 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-VETERAN11 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    World War I veteran part of a vanishing breed
 &HT;    By Bill Torpy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The macabre vision is 80 years old but remains shockingly alive
in James Lindsey's mind.
</P>
<P>
   On the edge of a bomb crater, a legless German soldier sits
upright in death, staring ahead as if awaiting Lindsey's unit. The
dead man's pack is still strapped to his back, propping him up. In
his pack, the soldier carries a rotten loaf of bread and three
photos: one with three proud mustashioed men in uniform. Another
has one of those men posing with a woman and a small boy. The third
has the woman alone with the boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was his wife and baby,'' said Lindsey, a reed-thin,
102-year-old Jonesboro resident who in 1918 was an artillery gunner
with American Expeditionary Forces as the Yanks blasted through a
tough but sagging German Army.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey keeps the photos in a box in his home. They are among
the few mementos he retains of the Great War, save some medals,
discharge papers and a vivid memory. A few years ago, a friend
tried to track down the dead German's name, to no avail. The man
remains anonymous, one of millions who virtually vanished on the
battlefields of World War I, a conflict that ended 80 years ago
today with Germany's surrender.
</P>
<P>
   Originally called Armistice Day, the Nov. 11 holiday was changed
in 1954 to Veterans Day to commemorate all Americans who have
served, although many believe the celebration has faded like the
old soldiers it honors.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you move further away from a war, people forget their
veterans,'' said Bob Ritter, an Air Force pilot and Vietnam vet who
oversees Atlanta's Veteran's Day parade, the nation's second
largest. The 135-unit parade starts today at 11 a.m. at Peachtree
Street near Pershing Point, traveling south to 11th Street.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey himself is truly a vanishing breed, a relic of a war
that has faded in American memory. Out of 4.7 million Americans who
served in World War I, fewer than 3,000 are still alive, said
Muriel Sue Parkhurst, director of the Veterans of World War I of
USA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost the forgotten war and they are the forgotten
veterans,'' said Parkhurst. But those vets don't worry about that,
she said, ``They're more concerned with going to X-rays, or about
meals on wheels or a great-grandchild coming for a visit.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey, too, doesn't dwell much on the past. He eats big (Red
Lobster is a favorite), drives a new Saturn, drinks an occasional
beer or whiskey sour and dates a 83-year-old woman. ``No
hanky-panky,'' says the widower of 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The other night, Lindsey was watching TV when the grainy and
jerky images of World War I appeared. He can't believe how ancient
it all now seems.
</P>
<P>
   But his own recollections aren't grainy.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 11, 1918, Lindsey was in the Argonne Forest in Belgium.
``The Argonne was desolate. All the trees were shot up. No leafs.
No branches. Just trenches and mud,'' he said with a far-away
stare. ``I can still see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rumors of the pending armistice were thick and soldiers were
light-hearted, remarkably jovial. But then came word that Americans
were going over the top. ``We heard the machine guns,'' he said.
``Some of those boys were killed.''
</P>
<P>
   And then it was still. ``Eleven o'clock,'' he recalls, breaking
into a smile that shows nearly all his dentures. ``Boy, what a
happy day.''
</P>
<P>
   The celebrating ebbed when hordes of gray, haggard men appeared
on the horizon, pleading for food. The once mighty German army was
now a straggling band of beggars.
</P>
<P>
   Out there, Lindsey saw a bit of his grandfather, the original
James Lindsey, a Confederate sharp-shooter, who also tasted bitter
defeat. ``He told me once he was once so hungry that they ate corn
out of horse manure,'' said Lindsey.
</P>
<P>
   The old veteran then paused to recount his war's legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We called it the Great War to End All Wars, that was our
slogan. Of course, twenty years later we were back at it'' in War
War II.
</P>
<P>
   After that, there was Korea. And Vietnam. And the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   World War I was a historical maelstrom that tore apart the
Russian, German, Turkish and Austro-Hungarian empires and laid the
groundwork for World War II and the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   More than 10 million died in the war (about 115,000 Americans)
where modern technology outstripped antiquated military tactics and
legions were mowed down in futile frontal charges against machine
guns, obliterated by artillery barrages or were gassed.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey, who two years ago toured a local elementary school to
tell his long-ago stories, survived the gas attacks and artillery
barrages so bright ``you could read a newspaper at night.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, with an almost bubbly enthusiasm, he recalls the
aerial battles that broke up the grim monotony of the soldiers
below in the trenches.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dogfights were something,'' he remembered. ``We'd stop
what we were doing and watch. They'd be shooting and swirling and
diving.''
</P>
<P>
   His hands weave circles, ``We'd cheer when one went down. Now
that was exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Parkhurst said old vets like Lindsey are treasured links to the
past. ``Were a society of fresh faces and don't have time for
them,'' she said. ``One day, they'll be gone, along with their
stories. And we're going to regret it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-10-98 2015EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
