A3939 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAS-VENTURE-COX     11-10 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAS-VENTURE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Amway climbs natural gas pyramid
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Amway's 25,000 Georgia distributors _ known for
selling everything from cosmetics and skin care products to
dishwashing liquid and dietary supplements _ will try their hand at
natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   In a novel arrangement, the consumer products company will
promote natural gas sold by Virginia-based Columbia Energy, which
is trying to capture some of Atlanta Gas Light's 1.4 million
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its deregulation law, Georgia is the first target for
what the two companies said will be a coast-to-coast joint energy
marketing program that will add electricity and other products and
services as state deregulation laws permit.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Dawson, Columbia Energy vice president and general manager
of mass marketing, said that Amway is ``uniquely positioned to link
consumers with the savings they can realize through deregulation.''
</P>
<P>
   Columbia Energy is one of 19 companies that have been certified
to sell natural gas in the Georgia market.
</P>
<P>
   John Parker, Amway's director of North American distributor
relations, said the privately held company's part-time Georgia
distributors would tout Columbia Energy when selling other Amway
products to consumers. The consumers will be referred to a
dedicated Amway toll-free telephone number at Columbia Energy,
where they can contract for natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   Amway customers will be asked for their distributor's
identification number, which will allow the distributors to earn
$15 commissions per customer, Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   Additional bonuses and commissions will be paid to Amway
distributors under the company's multilevel marketing plan. Parker
declined to identify the totals. He said Amway will pay commissions
to its distributors and receive payments from Columbia based on how
many customers sign up.
</P>
<P>
   Parker said Amway has similar arrangements with MCI, Avis car
rentals and Voice Tel, a voice mail service. He said Amway
customers would get no deal that Columbia is not offering to the
general public.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Davis, a spokesman for the Public Service Commission, said
the commission would ``monitor the sales tactics'' Amway uses for
natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   The company has been highly controversial because of its
reliance on multilevel marketing and revival-type meetings to rev
up the sales force. The Federal Trade Commission ruled in 1979 that
Amway's marketing arrangement was not an illegal pyramid scheme but
ordered the company to stop setting retail prices for its
distributors.
</P>
<P>
   Amway reports $5.7 billion in annual sales,14,000 employees and
a network of 1.2 million distributors in the United States. It
houses its distribution center for the Southeast in Norcross, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia Energy is a subsidiary of Columbia Energy Group, which
is also parent of Columbia Gas of Ohio and distributes gas to 7
million customers in15 states and the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew C. Quinn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
