<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3943 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNN-ELECTION-COX     11-10 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-ELECTION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TV and the Web declare victory
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's election night at CNN Interactive. This is
serious business and all hands are on deck. Spread out over three
floors of Atlanta's CNN Center, the online team includes editors,
producers, programmers and extra staffers flown in from Washington,
D.C., to augment CNN's Atlanta staff. Workstations have been moved
down to the election newsroom/command center where the election
news pages will be designed and posted to the Web site at
http://www.cnn.com.
</P>
<P>
   The CNN team has been ready to roll since 2:30 in the afternoon,
with a Web site designed to mirror the TV coverage as closely as
possible. As the night unfolded, behind the scenes action
intensified moment by moment. Here's a two-hour slice of that
night.
</P>
<P>
   _ 6 p.m.: Polls have closed in Kentucky and Indiana and that's
the green light for the intensive election coverage to begin. The
interactive team swings into action. The interactive newsroom is
wired into the cable network's control room so online
editor-in-chief Scott Woelfel and his staff can hear the network's
election calls when their TV counterparts do. What this means for
the Web site is they'll be posting election results in tandem with
the network. The disembodied voice of CNN political director Tom
Hannon is filtered over loudspeakers to the Web team. During the
evening, he'd announce which races are about to be called on air
and the Web site team responded by posting a ``news alert'' at the
top of the site.
</P>
<P>
   _ 6:15 p.m.: CNN spokesman Kerrin Roberts says the 24 writers
and six technical support people working in the CNN.com newsroom is
a considerable increase from normal news days. There are also 10
staffers operating the ``Web farm'' that monitors traffic to the
site, and tracks the online ads and stress on the servers. Nearly
everyone at CNN.com has been called in for the election coverage
except eight people who remain upstairs covering non-election news,
including Hurricane Mitch and John Glenn's space mission.
</P>
<P>
   _ 6:30 p.m.: CNN.com's editor-in-chief Scott Woelfel sits in the
center of the newsroom directing the action. ``This is one of the
best uses of the Net for real-time news,'' he says. ``You can drill
down in the site and find as much information as you want while the
TV carries you forward through the evening. It's a nice
combination.''
</P>
<P>
   Election director Carin Dessauer is a few seats away talking on
the phone and operating a computer terminal. Piles of Papa John's
pizza boxes, soda, and leftover Halloween candy clutter a table
under a bank of monitors of CNN's various networks. A huge easel is
set up where election results are recorded by hand as they are
announced.
</P>
<P>
   _ 7:05 p.m.: Polls have closed in most of the Eastern time zone
and returns are expected to start rolling in fast and furious.
``Our job right now is to make sure the pages are light and we have
adequate bandwidth,'' says technical product manager Dennis Backus,
who agrees with Woelfel that TV and the Web make an idea
combination for election night news and information. ``People want
info and they want it now. Our job is to figure out how to keep
them interested beyond the headlines.''
</P>
<P>
   Over in a corner of the room where the live video is fed to the
Web, someone suggests the real story of the evening is all the male
staffers are wearing ties.
</P>
<P>
   _ 7:15 p.m.: Things are beginning to get busy. Several people
are talking on cell phones, checking their pagers and huddling over
computers. Programmers upstairs monitor server capacity to make
sure every user who tries to access the CNN site is able to. ``This
is so much more relaxed than in '96,'' says technical product
manager Rob Leary, despite the frenzy going on around him. ``We're
still tweaking stuff,'' he says, ``but that's so much better than
pages not showing up at all.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want users to be able to get to the information they want
in no more than three clicks,'' he says. ``We also want a simple
and familiar design that we can break down into separate pages if
the traffic gets too heavy.''
</P>
<P>
   _ 7:30 p.m.: Several executives are crowded around one computer
screen checking out competing election coverage on MSNBC and
ABCNews.com. While people are amused by ABCNews.com's gaffe, which
sent dummy election results out over the Web on Monday night, the
network is careful not to be too smug. ``There but for the grace of
God, it could have been us,'' someone says and suddenly
ABCNews.com's misfire isn't quite as amusing.
</P>
<P>
   _ 7:45 p.m.: Soon it becomes clear many races across the
country, including the Georgia gubernatorial race, are too close to
call. ``Should we make a 'too close to call' area?'' someone shouts
to no one in particular. It's deemed to be an excellent idea and a
list of states with tight races is compiled and posted.
</P>
<P>
   After a time, someone notices Georgia is missing from the list.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just too bad, isn't it. It's going to have to wait,''
says a harried producer, working two terminals at once. However,
others insist it can't wait and someone is dispatched to add
Georgia to the 'too close to call' list, and add it as quickly as
possible. Vice president and general manager Mark Bernstein says
the things CNN does on the fly are what make the Web site really
work. ``We have a passion for news, and it shows in the things we
can do on the fly.''
</P>
<P>
   _ 7:46: A call for a ``winner card'' comes over the speakers for
South Carolina Sen. Ernest Hollings. CNN.com posts a news alert
projecting Hollings winning the Senate race. While the cable
network is in a commercial break, CNN.com posts a news alert on the
Web site, edging out the network by a few minutes.
</P>
<P>
   _ 8 p.m.: Staffers in the CNN ``Web farm'' monitoring traffic to
the site estimate CNN.com is getting viewed at the rate of
12,000-13,000 pages per minute. While traffic is steady, the
biggest surge is expected in the morning when users are trying to
access election results as well as other information.
</P>
<P>
   _ Election producer Dessauer says her main concern throughout
the evening was to make sure the lines of communication between the
Web site and the cable network were open. ``Given we were the two
CNN networks doing live election coverage, we wanted to be sure we
were organizing our coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can never know what's going to happen in terms of the
whole election story,'' says Dessauer, a veteran political reporter
with 13 years experience. ``For an election night, editorially, you
can't predict every story _ each time there is a new story we know
there are more people coming to the site and making sure we can
provide the data in real time and that went like clockwork.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
