<SLUG> BC-COX-DIGITAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cox Communications making digital strides
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The numbers aren't big but Cox Communications is
starting to show some impressive jumps in the numbers of customers
signing up for its new digital services during the past six months.
</P>
<P>
   In total, the company now has about 110,000 customers using
either its new high-speed access to the Internet, digital
television or digital telephone services. That number represents a
tiny portion of the company's 3.8 million subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, it's a sizeable increase from the 7,000 a year ago
who signed up for the company's initial digital service, high-speed
access to the Internet through Cox(at)Home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We consider this a terrific accomplishment,'' said Jimmy
Hayes, Cox Communications' chief financial officer. ``There's a
clear appetite for these services. We're seeing penetration rates
higher than initially thought.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, the number of customers ordering Cox
Communications' digital telephone service jumped more than 100
percent between June and September to 18,200, according to the
company's latest figures.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications now offers telephone service in five of its
10 markets and this business generated $8.7 million in revenue from
both commercial and residential customers in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are impressive early numbers,'' says Bruce Leichtman, a
media analyst at industry consultant the Yankee Group. But
Leichtman, added, it was important to remember the number of
digital customers remain small compared to overall subscribers _ at
least for now.
</P>
<P>
   Digital services are the key to Cox Communications' growth
strategy. The company is trying to reposition itself as a provider
of all kinds of telecommunications services.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Cox Communications has spent hundreds of millions
of dollars during the past several years rebuilding its cable
systems to handle digital traffic. Such capacity is necessary if
the company's networks are to carry everything from telephone calls
to e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Now that rebuild is almost completed and the company is slowly
but surely marketing new digital services to its customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cox is probably tops in the industry for using all the weapons
in cable TV's arsenal of new digital services,'' says Leichtman.
``The company is doing more with their cable plant than any other
operator.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications' biggest seller so far is digital television,
which offers both sharper pictures and many more channels. As of
Sept. 30, the company had 54,609 customers ordering digital
television. That represents a 70 percent increase from June.
</P>
<P>
   For high speed Internet access through cable modems, Cox
Communications had 46,777 customers as of Sept. 30, up 37 percent
from June. This service, sold under the Cox(at)Home brand name,
generated $5.1 million in revenue during the third quarter. It's
now offered in eight markets.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
