<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HITECH-INDIAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Indian-American session first of its kind in region
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Indians have cut a wide swath in high-tech
entrepreneurial. This week in Atlanta, that business know-how will
try to capture the imagination and money of potential investors.
</P>
<P>
   The Southeast's first workshop designed to introduce the
nation's venture capitalists to Atlanta's Indian-American high-tech
community, Entrepreneurs' Workshop '98, starts Friday and runs
through Saturday, at the Swissotel in Buckhead near Lenox Square
mall. Similar events have been held in California and
Massachusetts, but this is the first in Atlanta, and in the
Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   The founders of three of the five most successful Indian-founded
companies in the U.S. are scheduled to speak, including Ashutosh
Roy, co-founder of WhoWhere?, an Internet directory bought in
August by Lycos for $133 million in stock; Shrikanth Chari,
co-founder of CyberMedia, which was bought in July by Network
Associates for $133 million; Yogesh Sharma, editor of SiliconIndia
magazine; Sunil Wadhwani, co-founder of Mastech; and Ajay Shah,
co-founder of SMART Modular Technologies, a California-based maker
of computer memory products. Mike McQuary, president of Atlanta's
MindSpring, the Southeast's largest ISP, also will speak.
</P>
<P>
   Indian-Americans and start-up money are not strangers.
Synchrologic, a company that recently moved from the Georgia Tech
Advanced Technology Development Center to Alpharetta, was founded
by Sanjoy Malik in 1995. Manhattan Associates, an Atlanta company
that makes software for distribution centers, was co-founded by
Deepal Raghavan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like that cultural group has some knack for
entrepreneurship,'' said Alan Taetle, of Noro-Moseley Partners, an
Atlanta venture capital firm and co-sponsor of the workshop.
</P>
<P>
   Ravi Kalakota, head of Georgia State University's Center for
Digital Commerce, attributes the success of Indians in America to
the Immigration and Naturalization Services' involuntary and
thorough screening process.
</P>
<P>
   Kalakota said there were two waves of recent Indian immigration.
Those who made up the first wave, in the 1970s and 1980s, were
highly educated and came out of Indian universities, as did
Kalakota in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very difficult to come in those days,'' he said.
``Getting a visa was very difficult back then; you had to have
financial aid at a top American university just to get one. The
process weeded out a lot, so the people who came up to 1990-1991
were really the best people India produced.''
</P>
<P>
   Kalakota also attributes the success of Indians in America to
the Indian education system. He said the typical math taught in
American universities is what is taught in Indian high schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Math and science are emphasized. That sort of raises that
threshold quite well and it makes a big difference,'' he said.
``But it's only math and science. We have none of the social
skills, so it evens out in the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Clothier writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
