<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3962 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUDGE-CONTEMPT-HNS &LR;      11-10 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDGE-CONTEMPT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE SENTENCES MAN TO 30 DAYS IN JAIL FOR FAILING TO FILL OUT
JUROR QUESTIONNAIRE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE BREWER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A man who defied a judge by refusing to fill out a
juror questionnaire in a capital murder case was found in contempt
of court Tuesday and jailed for 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   State District Judge W.R. Voigt also fined Harold Leland Crouch
$500. The judge said afterward he felt the sentence necessary to
protect the integrity of the court and the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saying to the court, `I'm not going to participate in the
process because I don't agree with the law,' that's not the way it
works,'' Voigt said.
</P>
<P>
   Crouch spent part of the day in a holding cell near the
courtroom and was still being booked into the county jail late
Tuesday. He was being held without bail because none is normally
granted in this kind of contempt case.
</P>
<P>
   Summoned to jury service, Crouch ended up in Voigt's court,
where a jury is being selected for the upcoming capital murder
trial of Raymond Reese, 50, who is accused of killing his
common-law wife's daughter and son-in-law on Oct. 27, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The state is seeking the death penalty and that requires
individual questioning, or ``voir dire,'' of potential jurors. As
part of that process, those summoned must fill out a standard juror
information form and a longer capital murder questionnaire before
being questioned by lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The forms save prosecutors and defense attorneys time and helps
them to spot potential biases or other problems while agreeing to a
jury. And that helps prevent costly retrials and appellate
problems.
</P>
<P>
   But, according to Voigt and lawyers involved in the case, Crouch
would not fill out the forms and said the mere fact that he was
summoned qualified him for jury duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intent of the jury system is to select qualified people at
random and assume them to be representative of the population,''
Crouch wrote on his capital murder questionnaire. ``Everybody
meeting the qualifications on the jury summons is qualified to sit
on this jury. The court needs no additional information.''
</P>
<P>
   In the rest of the spaces for answers on the forms, Crouch wrote
``not available,'' Voigt said. Court officials weren't even sure of
his age or address.
</P>
<P>
   Voigt called Crouch forward, told him that state law requires
jurors to submit to voir dire and ordered him to fill out the
forms. He also warned him of the possible penalties _ up to six
months in jail and a $500 fine.
</P>
<P>
   But Crouch said he wasn't familiar with any such legal
requirements and continued to refuse to fill out the forms.
</P>
<P>
   Voigt wasn't buying his argument about being automatically
qualified.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to get 12 fair jurors who hold no bias for either side
and who are prepared to receive the law and the evidence,'' Voigt
said later. ``Until you question them (potential jurors) and
examine them, you don't know that.''
</P>
<P>
   No information about Crouch was available because he hadn't been
booked into jail and jailers would not relay to him a reporter's
request for an interview, saying they were not sure if he had a
lawyer yet.
</P>
<P>
   Courthouse sources did not know his exact age or address, but
believed him to be in the mid-40s and possibly from Kingwood,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   A phone listed under the same name in Kingwood was picked up by
an answering machine with the recorded voice of a man identifying
himself as ``Harold.'' No relatives of Crouch's could be located
for comment either.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Kari Sckerl, who is handling the Reese case, knew
nothing about Crouch. But she and defense attorney Brian Coyne, who
is representing the defendant, praised Voigt and said they were
frustrated by Crouch's actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never seen it happen before and I was offended by the
juror's refusal to be part of the process,'' Sckerl said. ``If we
live in this country and we take advantages of the benefits of this
country then we have a duty to follow the laws of this country. He
was in direct violation of the law and a court order, I was
offended and glad the judge held him in contempt.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyne echoed that sentiment, saying the juror forms are an
important tool and help ensure a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
   Word of Voigt's action was greeted with grins, shaking heads and
raised eyebrows around the courthouse. Many prosecutors and lawyers
expressed strong support, but some others, who didn't want to be
named because they appear before Voigt, thought the 30 days was a
bit severe.
</P>
<P>
   Voigt, who was defeated in the Republican primary and leaves the
bench at the end of the year, has held jurors in contempt before,
including one who had overslept.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel (jury service) is very important and that's why I did
this,'' Voigt said. ``(Crouch) had an obligation to carry out his
duties as a citizen and if we get to a point where people say, `I
follow the laws that suit me,' then we have anarchy.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Crouch was found in ``direct'' contempt he actually has
no due-process rights, other than to file a direct appeal with the
Texas Court of Criminal Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Direct'' contempt is when someone disobeys a judge's order in
the courtroom. There is no review hearing and no bail, unless the
person cited is an officer of the court. That's because a judge,
who has wide discretion in such cases, can issue a final finding
when the contempt occurs.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court in Austin could grant Crouch a bail while they
review his case, but several attorneys said Tuesday that hardly
ever happens unless the punishment for ``direct'' contempt is
considered too severe. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
