<HEADLINE>
CREDIT CARD CRUNCH: LENDERS' NEW RULES HIT CONSUMERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN DRAKE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Consumers are paying a higher price for borrowing with plastic
as lenders continue to raise their fees by changing the rules for
little-noticed credit card penalties.
</P>
<P>
   The rules make credit cards more costly in several ways,
including making late fees more common and expensive, slapping on
higher default rates more often and enabling consumers to run
higher balances adding to their interest costs and fees.
</P>
<P>
   The report shows how ``banks are pulling out all stops in order
to increase profits from fee income,'' said Linda Sherry, editorial
director of the group Consumer Action, which did the survey.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers say the critical report ignores the many cards available
to consumers with lower interest rates and fees that don't include
those added charges.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates admit that credit card interest rates are
much lower, especially introductory offers ranging from zero to
four percent. But strict conditions and harsh penalties are buried
in fine print that the consumer groups say most consumers never
read or won't understand until the fee hits.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer Action surveyed 117 cards from 74 banks during August
and September and released the report jointly with the Consumer
Federation of America.
</P>
<P>
   Even though there are thousands of different credit cards,
Sherry said the survey is representative because the survey focused
on the handful of large lenders who hold a lion's share of the
market, issuing cards through different companies.
</P>
<P>
   This leads to consumers using a low-interest credit card for
initial, expensive purchases. After they build up a balance, which
will be easy to do this time of year with the holiday spending
season looming, they are stuck with a card with a lot of burdensome
fees attached.
</P>
<P>
   The companies make it easier to keep the balance by reducing the
required minimum payment. If customers pay at this rate, it will
take far longer to repay the amount as interest on the debt builds
up.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, companies are shortening the time customers
have to send their payments in and the leniency periods _ the time
after the payment is due before companies slap on a late fee _ and
that fee is also going up.
</P>
<P>
   They make it easier to fatten your balance by setting soft
limits _ rather than denying charges when a borrower hits a limit
they charge a fee of $20 or more.
</P>
<P>
   The fees make falling behind on a large balance an increasingly
expensive mistake. Companies use expensive penalty rates _ a higher
interest rate imposed after missing several payments. Penalty rates
can be as much as 25 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, Consumer Action's Sherry said the practices
described in the survey ``will entrap people who are deadbeats or
poor, and it will get the rest of us who are busy or on vacation or
lose a bill.''
</P>
<P>
   But the American Bankers Association said now is a great time to
shop for a card, and the big borrowers mostly likely to be hit by
these fees are a slim minority of credit card users.
</P>
<P>
   ``Annual fees are almost non-existent on standard cards and
interest rates have dropped,'' said Donald Ogilvie, an executive
vice president for the bankers association, in a statement. ``To
find the right card, consumers can choose from thousands of
products created by more than 6,000 card issuers. The current
credit card environment gives them more and cheaper options than
ever.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the increased and higher fees the survey reports, Ogilvie
said nine of 10 people avoid fees by paying their accounts on time
and a majority of consumers pay $3 or less a month.
</P>
<P>
   George McCain of First USA, the credit card division of Bank
One, disagreed with consumer advocates' entrapment theory - that
credit companies in general target people they know can't pay so
they can reap profits from late fees and penalty rates. He said his
company seeks out customers with good credit history.
</P>
<P>
   Bank One's fee and rate practices were typical of many companies
profiled in the survey.
</P>
<P>
   Bank One has no leniency period after the due date, before it
slaps on a $29 late fee. Its default interest rate of 22.99 percent
kicks in after paying late by 30 days twice in six months, or
paying late by 60 days once in 6 months _ a typical industry
practice.
</P>
<P>
   John Russell, head of Bank One's corporate communications,
placed the issue in terms of market behavior. Interest rates were
18 to 24 percent in 1995, and now have dropped to around 6 percent.
``So, as interest rates have gone down, these fees have gone up,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The industry wide trends ``are a reflection of what's happened
in the market'' and a response to consumer behavior, said Kathleen
Shilkret, spokeswoman for Wells Fargo.
</P>
<P>
   As for credit practices of Wells Fargo, Shilkret said ``we're
trying to provide consumers with the right sort of credit for
them,'' based on their credit history.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo has four different cards with varying interest
rates, 12.50 percent to 20.5 percent, that are issued based on
credit history _ better rates for consumers with better credit
histories. All four cards have a penalty rate of 23.90 percent,
which is sixth highest on the list.
</P>
<P>
   Also, there is no leniency period, so the $29 late fee is
imposed immediately after the due date, if the payment does not
arrive. The report noted this late fee was a mere $5 in 1995. The
annual fee is $18 and the over-the-limit fee is $29.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of America, another bank with operations in Houston (and
which recently merged with Nations Bank), does not have a leniency
period, has a 22.4 percent penalty rate and an interest rate as
high as 21.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Wyss, spokesperson for the company, referred questions to
the American Bankers Association because ``we view the report as an
industry matter.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
