<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-MCLAREN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCLAREN FITS RIGHT IN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ At the end of the workout, he rested on his knees at
the far end of the ice, sweating, panting, and looking spent.
However, Kyle McLaren more than survived his first practice of
1998-99 with the Bruins and was officially back in the fold. Coach
Pat Burns said the 21-year-old defenseman, who came to terms late
Monday night on a three-year contract, was good enough to jump
right into the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins next play the Rangers Friday night, and barring
anything unforeseen, McLaren, who missed the first 15 games of the
year in a contract dispute, will be in uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like another training camp starting over with
everybody in,'' said Burns, who in the last week welcomed back
Anson Carter and said goodbye to Ted Donato, who was traded to the
Islanders for mammoth forward Ken Belanger. ``We're certainly a lot
bigger, I noticed that. Ray Bourque looks like a little guy out
there. So, that's going to help us.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good because management has made the commitment that they
want to win and the coaching staff has certainly made our
commitment. Now the players have to make the same commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   McLaren confessed to being a little tired after his workout at
the rink outside Boston. He had been skating with a junior team in
Rhode Island, but as both coach and player said, the pace just
isn't the same as the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think they're working hard and they think they're in top
shape until they get a couple of these practices in and then the
reality sets in that they're not in as great a shape as they
thought they were,'' said Burns with a wicked grin. ``Skating at
their pace and skating at my pace are two different paces, that I
can assure you.''
</P>
<P>
   While McLaren is working on shaking off the rust, shaking off
his residual bitterness at the negotiations may not be as easy. He
took the difficult haggling very personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough,'' he said, ``I've missed 15 games which I don't
think I should've missed. It could've easily been done in August or
early September but it dragged on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to turn the page now. It's something I'll never
forget. It's tough, because it's the way they do business, it's the
way they've always done business, and I don't see it changing in
the future. I just hope when some younger guys come up like Joe
(Thornton) and (Sergei Samsonov), they don't have to go through
what I did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was frustrated. Each day goes by and you wonder if you're
doing the right thing. My options were limited.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, they were nearly nonexistent. The IHL is no longer
accepting NHL holdouts, McLaren couldn't join Team Canada unless he
had the Bruins' permission (he didn't), and sitting out all year
would have been counterproductive to everyone's best interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was either sign the deal or sit out, and I think it was a
time of my life where I had to choose between playing hockey and
not playing hockey,'' he said. ``I don't think it's the greatest
deal for me but it's satisfactory where I can get the job done here
and see what happens after the three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put in three years of good hockey and I wanted to be
rewarded. I didn't like the way they negotiated with me but I'm
going to turn the page and just play hockey. Right now, I'm a
little frustrated. I don't know why it didn't get done earlier. I
was just happy to be with the guys and the coaching staff. Right
now, I'm not worried about my contract, it's over, it's in the
past.''
</P>
<P>
   McLaren resents the fact that other players, in his mind, were
taken care of better than he was by the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were in need of offense at the beginning of the season so
they signed Jason (Allison),'' he said. ``They felt they could get
away without me and they have. I don't feel I'm giving in right
now, I feel like I'm accepting the best offer I could've gotten.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was frustrated they were offering me insufficient numbers.
We battled for two months just to get it up a little bit, but
trying to squeeze blood out of a rock, it's hard to do.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, McLaren sees himself as a victim of his own
union's collective bargaining agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm one of the first players that came out of the new CBA
where the middle (career) players have no rights,'' he said. ``I
knew that. But if you have three strong years, maybe you should
throw that out and just go by (the merit of) their years and (the
Bruins) didn't do that. They basically wanted to say I have no
rights and the leverage is in their hands and that's why I was
frustrated. Any players who have three good years should get
rewarded for it and I don't think I was. I'm for the NHLPA and what
they've done, but I don't like the fact that teams can say, `You've
got no rights.'''
</P>
<P>
   McLaren admitted to second guessing himself occasionally during
the lonely times he was sitting out while the team was playing.
But, ultimately, he trusted his gut instincts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I did the right thing,'' he said. ``I'll keep saying
it my whole career.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
