<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4024 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FSU-COX     11-10 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FSU-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FSU understudy under pressure
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Don't start changing the Rooster's nickname
to ``After,'' coach Bobby Bowden pleads, but yes, if you must know,
Marcus Outzen was recruited as an afterthought, a backup, a bit
role player.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, that's the same guy now quarterbacking the fifth-ranked
Florida State Seminoles, whose chance at playing for a national
title shot up last week when Ohio State lost and then faltered with
starter Chris Weinke's season-ending neck injury. They face Wake
Forest on Saturday and Florida next week.
</P>
<P>
   Weinke, 26, will have neck surgery Friday to remove a bone chip
and repair a herniated disk sustained Saturday against Virginia.
The sophomore, who probably won't return before August, is
disappointed but confident in his replacement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, Marcus is going to be nervous. He's going to be
playing in the two biggest games of his life,'' Weinke said. ``But
just because I'm leaving, this is not a decline for the team.''
</P>
<P>
   FSU's receivers and tailbacks are healthy, strong and talented,
and its defense ranks No. 1 in the nation. But Florida State teams
center around their quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Make that their starting quarterbacks. Outzen, 20, was recruited
in 1995 from Fort Walton Beach, specifically for emergencies and to
finish off games already won.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt like we needed another quarterback, not a Weinke or a
(Danny) Kanell,'' Bowden said. ``You've got to have a backup
quarterback. You've got to have a third-team quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   But he was promoted from third-team to backup when Dan Kendra
sustained a season-ending knee injury in spring practice, then
moved to fullback.
</P>
<P>
   Outzen wasn't surprised by that. Before his shoulder injury in
the spring, Outzen had been challenging Weinke for the No. 2
position, and he had always believed he would get a chance to
really play and display his abilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``His dream was always to get to go to Florida State,'' said
Joey Rankin, his high school coach. ``He's just the kind of guy
that's determined enough do it. He wanted to keep at it until he
got it.''
</P>
<P>
   But he still fought frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, he thought briefly about transferring because of the
long list of players ahead of him. At the time, the quarterback
order expected this year was: starter Kendra, codger Weinke and
afterthought Outzen. Then, freshman Jared Jones, the team's third
high school Parade All-America, signed on in February and the only
quarterback definitely behind Outzen was walk-on Rich Maher.
</P>
<P>
   Rankin, who hasn't talked to Outzen yet this week, encouraged
him last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just said, 'Keep your head up and keep working,' `` Rankin
said. `` `You've got to realize that at Florida State, especially,
quarterbacks sometimes don't get to play their first couple of
years.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Outzen persisted by remembering his relative youth (redshirt
sophomore this year) and why he chose Florida State over Auburn,
South Carolina and the other schools that recruited him.
</P>
<P>
   That was because he had grown up a Seminoles fan. His father, a
real estate agent in Destin, had taken him to his first games when
he was 9. He had his picture taken with Bowden at a boosters dinner
as a child. Bowden says he's known Outzen ``ever since he was a
baby, nearly.''
</P>
<P>
   Coaches knew they needed a backup in 1996, partly because they
had too many star quarterbacks to get another. They pursued Outzen,
Spencer Romine of Alabama (now at Duke) and Ben Leard of Georgia
(now at Auburn).
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt, looking at those three, that Outzen was a Florida boy
and we liked him as much as we did any of the others,'' Bowden
said.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly resounding words of praise, but Outzen took the
scholarship and Bowden has been pleased with him. He compared him
to Weegie Thompson, an NFL receiver who started as an FSU
quarterback. Like Thompson, Outzen primarily ran the ball in high
school, making it hard for coaches to judge his passing ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he throws better than we thought,'' Bowden said. ``I like
him. He's got some confidence about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden encouraged Outzen to stay last year and then saw him
improve during the spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that made him realize he could play and no matter how
good Kendra was or Weinke was, he still might could beat them
out,'' Bowden said. ``He stayed with it and I'm glad.''
</P>
<P>
   So is Outzen. Now that he owns the starting job, he needs to
grow in confidence and become one of the team's strongest voices.
``It's something I've always dreamed about,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He will not step into the exact spot Weinke left. Outzen runs
better than Weinke so coaches will try to take advantage of that.
His range probably isn't quite as far so coaches will try to work
around that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see a whole lot of changes (in the offense),''
offensive coordinator and quarterbacks coach Mark Richt said.
``We'll certainly have to let Marcus play ball a little bit more
than we did (Saturday) and have him pass.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest difference will be Outzen's inexperience. Even
Weinke, a former professional baseball player, needed several weeks
and a simplified offense to feel comfortable leading the Seminoles'
high-power passing game. Weinke's favorite target, however, isn't
worried about the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did better than I thought he was going to do,'' receiver
Peter Warrick said. ``He's got to make the big plays now. And maybe
we just have to hit short routes and make something out of
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Coaches also were calm and hopeful, emphasizing that the offense
already relies on the run to some degree (36 percent of offensive
yards) and has successfully adapted to one inexperienced
quarterback. With Florida looming, though, Outzen knows he has a
lot to live up to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wake is not the same caliber as Florida and I don't know if
we've ever had a quarterback go in to play UF with just one
start,'' Outzen said. ``The experience factor is a big deal when
you're playing someone like UF.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden, on Sunday at least, wasn't concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel bad about him at all,'' Bowden said. ``To me,
he's already passed the test.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Noteworthy: Sophomore free safety Shawn McCorkel, who was
suspended from Florida State's football team indefinently last
week, will have a hearing on Wednesday in Ala. regarding his DUI
charges, Bowden said.
</P>
<P>
   McCorkel will not play this weekend, but his future with the
team depends on the outcome of his hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Clarke writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
