<HEADLINE>
RANGERS STILL IN RUNNING FOR RANDY JOHNSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The winning bid for the services of free-agent pitcher Randy
Johnson could be a three-year contract worth between $39 million
and $42 million.
</P>
<P>
   That's the consensus of major-league officials and sources
familiar with the situation, and the Rangers appear to have as good
a chance as any of the teams in hot pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the negotiations are veiled in secrecy. Some things are
known:
</P>
<P>
   Agent Barry Meister will try to get a four-year offer or three
years and an option. But Johnson, 35, only wants to pitch three
more years. Knowing this is his last contract, he'll want to get
the maximum value for it.
</P>
<P>
   So far the offers have been in the $10 million-$12 million per
year range, but that could increase as the bidding gets hotter.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson wants to stay close to his home in suburban Phoenix.
That puts the Arizona Diamondbacks in the picture, but they're also
in the National League and are still a few years away from being
competitive. Johnson toured the Diamondbacks' Bank One Ballpark
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Jerry Colangelo is aggressively pursuing Johnson, but the
Diamondbacks' staff isn't as enthusiastic. There is a strong
feeling within the organization that they should continue to build
from within for a few years before getting involved in big-name
free agents. There is also sentiment to go after center fielder
Bernie Williams instead.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson wants to pitch in the American League and wants to pitch
on a contender. Both factors favor the Rangers. They also play in a
ballpark that favors left-handed pitching.
</P>
<P>
   A factor working against the Rangers is that they conduct spring
training in Florida. Johnson would like to sign with a team that
trains in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Meister said the Rangers have not made the highest offer.
Rangers president Tom Schieffer said the offer would not make
Johnson the highest-paid pitcher in baseball, an honor held by
Pedro Martinez at an average of $12.5 million per year.
</P>
<P>
   Most likely the Rangers offered less than $36 million, although
Schieffer will emphasize that Texas doesn't have a state income
tax. Both Arizona and California do.
</P>
<P>
   The Anaheim Angels have many of the factors Johnson wants: an
American League team, in contention, that trains in Arizona. But
they are also pursuing first baseman Mo Vaughn and aren't likely to
spring for both. The Angels have also offered a contract to pitcher
Todd Stottlemyre.
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego Padres, an hour's flight west of Phoenix, have a
good chance if they can muster a bid close to the others. Their
first priority is Kevin Brown, but he might go elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers could step up their pursuit if they can trade Gary
Sheffield's huge contract to San Diego. The two sides have
discussed a deal that would send Sheffield and shortstop Mark
Grudzielanek to San Diego for outfielder Greg Vaughn, shortstop
Chris Gomez and pitcher Randy Myers.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's history of a bad back is troubling. But some teams are
mollified by Johnson's demand for a three-to-four-year deal. Kevin
Brown, the other ace pitcher in the free-agent market, is looking
for a six- or seven-year contract, which is scaring off some teams.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers manager Johnny Oates said he's not concerned about
Johnson's back, pointing out what Rangers slugger Juan Gonzalez has
done despite past back problems. Oates is also not concerned about
Johnson's reputation of being difficult to deal with.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are too many positives,'' Oates said. ``I look at what a
change of scenery \Rin Houston\S did for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees are about as far away from Phoenix as you
can get, but two factors work in their favor. They offer the best
chance to get Johnson into the World Series and owner George
Steinbrenner is not one to get outbid by anybody, including
Colangelo.
</P>
<P>
   But smart agents hATQ0Z ATQ0Z +++7 &UR; f XHV.{
</P>
