<HEADLINE>
CONTINENTAL MECHANICS REJECT DEAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LAURA GOLDBERG 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ More than 2,900 mechanics for Continental Airlines
overwhelmingly rejected a tentative contract agreement with the
company, according to ballots counted Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The carrier and the International Brotherhood of Teamsters
announced in mid-October that a tentative agreement had been
reached.
</P>
<P>
   But the rank-and-file didn't like the deal. Of the votes cast,
2,085 were against the contract, 257 were for it and about 80 were
invalid.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston-based carrier began negotiating with the Teamsters
in November 1997 for a new contract. At that time, the union said
key issues for the mechanics included job security and pay.
</P>
<P>
   The mechanics voted to join the Teamsters in July of that year
after 14 years without union representation.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Lacefield, a Washington, D.C., Teamsters spokesman, said
the employees are ``going to fight to get a better contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Lacefield referred questions about details of the tentative
agreement and the union's next move to another union official, who
did not return calls.
</P>
<P>
   A Continental spokesman would say only that the company had been
in touch with the Teamsters and was discussing the next steps.
</P>
<P>
   Continental's mechanics are not alone in their actions. Across
the airline industry, the rank-and-file are rejecting tentative
agreements negotiated at bargaining tables by union and company
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Airline workers, who are keenly aware of the record profits
being churned out by airlines, aren't convinced airline executives
want to pay them fairly.
</P>
<P>
   Some also remember the early '90s when airlines were in
bad-to-desperate financial shape and employees took pay cuts and
other concessions.
</P>
<P>
   The mechanics rejection comes after the company and pilots at
Continental Express, Continental's regional carrier, reached a
second tentative agreement late last month.
</P>
<P>
   The first was rejected by the pilots in June. It would have
given the more than 1,100 pilots, about half of whom the union says
make less than $15,000 a year, an average 35 percent raise. The
pilots said that contract still would have meant half of them
making less than $19,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The board of the Independent Association of Continental Pilots
is likely this week to send the second agreement to the pilots for
a vote. Agreement details haven't been released.
</P>
<P>
   At Continental Express, the company is also in negotiations with
the mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   For the main carrier, the mechanics contract is the only one
outstanding. In June, Continental pilots ratified a five-year deal
granting average 47 percent pay raises over the contract's life. It
also included vacation and pension improvements, and stronger job
security language. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
