A4031 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-ATL-BROADCOM-COX     11-10 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ATL-BROADCOM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smarter than the average high-tech firm
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Broadcom, an upstart chip maker based in California,
is turning out to be one smart investment by Atlanta-based
Scientific-Atlanta Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Scientific-Atlanta, which at one point owned 3.8 percent of
Broadcom, has profited handsomely from its stake. In the past six
months, the company has booked $112 million in gains from its
Broadcom stake.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcom shares are up more than 123 percent since going public
in April. And that climb has escalated in the past two days,
gaining $4 Tuesday and $8.75 the day before. ``It's been a good
investment,'' said Scientific-Atlanta spokesman Bob Meyers. ``The
company has excellent management and engineering talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Meyers said Scientific-Atlanta seeks well-positioned but small
companies in its industry for investment. ``That way we can share
in their success,'' he said. ``We were an early investor in
Broadcom for these reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientific-Atlanta initially bought 1.5 million shares but sold
off all but 500,000 in the second quarter of this fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Although Scientific-Atlanta has reduced its stake, the company
expects to continue working with Broadcom. The two companies have
been working closely since the early 1990s. They met while helping
Time Warner experiment with digital television in Orlando in the
early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a fantastic working relationship and expect that to
continue,'' said Dr. Henry T. Nicholas, Broadcom's president and
chief executive. ``Even if Scientific-Atlanta doesn't buy our new
chip set, we expect to share our technology with them.''
</P>
<P>
   What triggered Broadcom's most recent stock climb was the
company's announcement Monday of a new chip that would enable
televisions to simultaneously display Web pages and TV shows. This
was the latest in a string of product innovations.
</P>
<P>
   Based in Irvine, Calif., Broadcom makes hardware that
accelerates the transmission of TV shows, music and data over cable
and telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
   Scientific-Atlanta, which supplies the cable TV industry with
networks and equipment, uses Broadcom chips in its products. The
company hasn't yet decided whether to buy Broadcom's latest chip.
</P>
<P>
   Scientific-Atlanta's digital system, called Explorer 2000,
already offers simultaneous display of Web pages and television.
The company is aggressively marketing this system to cable
operators nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Scientific-Atlanta executives welcomed Broadcom's newest
chip _ and not just for the innovation it represents. They believe
the chip will heat up an already hot competition among its chip
suppliers. And that, executives hope, will help keep prices level
to declining.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
