A4034 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WWI-VETS-COX     11-10 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WWI-VETS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WWI veterans harder to come by
 &HT;    By Trebor Banstetter and Eliot Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Al Ross stands alone.
</P>
<P>
   He became the last survivor of Barracks 507, a West Palm Beach
World War I veterans' group, when George Bucknell of Lake Worth
died in February.
</P>
<P>
   A generation ago, the group's membership stood at more than 200.
Five years ago it was down to 12, with only five strong enough even
to attend gatherings. Now there's only Ross, who at 97 will be
keynote speaker at today's Veterans Day parade and ceremony on
Clematis Street in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty years after the guns of the Great War stopped, the ranks
of those who fought it are down to a scattered few. Five years ago,
there were 49 known veterans in Palm Beach, Martin, St. Lucie,
Indian River and Okeechobee Counties. Now there are four.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, the number of World War I veterans nationwide was
750,000. Today, there are perhaps 3,000 now, according to Muriel
Sue Parkhurst of Veterans of World War I of the U.S.A. Inc. in
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Their average age is 98; ages range from 95 to a 116-year-old in
Kansas, Parkhurst said.
</P>
<P>
   Ross, 97, still does public relations for The Palm Beach Daily
News and still drives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm 27,'' said Ross.
</P>
<P>
   When he was 15-1/2, he lied about his age at to get into the
U.S. Navy, but never saw action.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the war to end all wars, but it never worked out that
way,'' Ross said.
</P>
<P>
   George Archer remembers being intrigued by the stunts of
barnstorming pilots at county fairs in his native Alabama when he
was 17. So he lied about his age and joined the U.S. Army Air Force
in 1917.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my friends said I had to be crazy to fly one of those
things,'' said Archer, 99, of Palm Beach. ``I think it helped.''
</P>
<P>
   He got to Europe, but Armistice Day came before his first
mission. It was Nov. 11, 1918, the 11th hour of the 11th day of the
11th month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not much of a parader,'' he said. ``And there can't be
many of us still around to celebrate.''
</P>
<P>
   Parkhurst, the unpaid executive director and only employee of
her organization, lists about 250 active members who pay $3 a year,
plus another 1,800 life members who paid a one-time $25 fee in the
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   She said she believes many of those have died, but that their
widows haven't told her because they want to keep receiving the
newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've gone from outhouses to outer space,'' Parkhurst said
of the last veterans. ''They've seen more changes in their lifetime
than any other generation in history.''
</P>
<P>
   Trebor Banstetter and Eliot Kleinberg writes for the Palm Beach
Post, West Palm Beach, Fla. Staff researcher Lynne Palombo
contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
