<HEADER>
A4038 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARINE-SKILIFT-INQUIR     11-10 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARINE-SKILIFT-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROBLEMS BESET MARINES IN SKI CRASH, TRANSCRIPT SHOWS
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Something was wrong, Capt. Scott Roys knew, with
the way his Marine Corps squadron kept reference documents for
planning flights in the Italian Alps. In secret testimony this
summer, he said that the binder had been stuffed with information
laughably old or relevant only to fighter planes the squadron did
not fly.
</P>
<P>
   No single error doomed the 20 people on the Cermis ski lift in
the Alps, who fell 264 feet to their death on Feb. 3 when a plane
from Roys' squadron severed the cable holding their gondola. But
the story of that thick binder emerges from a transcript of a
secret hearing at Camp Lejeune, N.C., as an example of broad
management problems in the Marine Corps' operation in Aviano,
Italy. The transcript also shows that the skiers, unlikely though
it seems, became indirect casualties of the war in Bosnia and
Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
   As the investigation continues in preparation for courts-martial
of the plane's pilot and navigator early next year, it is clear
that problems built up over years leading to the deadly accident in
a period when the Marine squadrons were rotating between Cherry
Point, N.C., and duty in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   When the Air Force wanted to copy data on obstructions like the
ski lift, it asked the Italians for the wrong map. In Washington,
the Defense Mapping Agency kept maps that did not show the ski lift
because it used ineffective guidelines to decide what hazards to
display. And the four Marine squadrons fitted in poorly as a
``tenant'' squadron with their hosts at Aviano, the U.S. Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Air Force kind of treated them as a second-class
citizen,'' Lt. Col. Michael Cross, the chief of staff of the Second
Marine Air Wing, of which the squadron is a part, said in testimony
at the hearing in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were not as forthcoming with the flight information,''
Cross said. For example, when the Air Force sent an important
document to one of its own squadrons, it made the squadron sign for
it. For the Marines, he said, ``they just threw it in the mail box;
and if they got it, they got it; and if they didn't, nobody knew
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when the Air Force supplied information, the Marines found
problems. Members of the squadron had a mix of new and old
publications; there were never enough new ones to go around.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to beg, borrow and steal to get more,'' Lt. Col.
Richard Muegge, the squadron commander since November 1996, said at
the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing also documented contradictions in flight
restrictions among the various items in the reference binder.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing, convened by Lt. Gen. Peter Pace, the commanding
general of Marine Forces Atlantic, was not to investigate the
communications breakdown that preceded the accident, but to
consider disciplining four officers of the squadron for their roles
in the case. After the hearing, Pace relieved the squadron
commander of his command and inserted a letter of reprimand into
the file of the squadron's safety officer.
</P>
<P>
   The transcript lays out a detailed picture of one of the central
puzzles of the accident: the Air Force listed a minimum altitude of
2,000 feet above the ground in the area of the ski lift, the Marine
squadron had a copy of this Air Force document, but hardly anyone
in the squadron _ including the pilot involved in the accident _
knew about it.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing shed little light on the question of why the pilot
and navigator of the plane that hit the cable, who face
court-martial next February, were flying as low as the cables, less
than 300 feet above ground, when they thought their minimum
altitude was 1,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force document listing the 2,000-foot restriction was an
August 1997 Flight Crew Information File. Within the Air Force,
someone from each squadron had to initial that the document had
been received. The Air Force put one in an ``out'' box for the
Marine squadron, and later asked if it had been received, according
to testimony at the hearing. But Roys' squadron received neither
the document nor the subsequent query.
</P>
<P>
   In early November 1997, though, about six weeks after the
squadron had rotated in, Roys took it upon himself to go into a
classified room at the headquarters for flights over Bosnia and
photocopy anything that looked relevant to the kind of plane his
squadron flew, the EA-6B. The plane, known as the Prowler, is an
aging but still able electronic warfare jet that can jam enemy
radars or hit them with missiles.
</P>
<P>
   He weeded out old material from the binder, which started out
three inches thick, and took it back to his squadron at a thickness
of about an inch. Roys said he gave the material to Maj. Max
Caramanian, the director of safety standardization for the
squadron. Then he left for two weeks of temporary duty at another
location, and a week of vacation. When he came back, the folder was
still on Caramanian's desk, unread.
</P>
<P>
   But Roys was not easily put off. On Dec. 15, shortly after his
return, the squadron held one of its regular meetings, gathering
pilots and electronics countermeasures officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``After we conducted our regular business,'' the captain
testified, ``I stood up in front of them and said, `This is a new
read binder' or `This binder has new, current information in it. It
replaces the old binder.'''
</P>
<P>
   And he said he ``basically indicated that this binder was a
third of the size of the old binder, which was stuffed full of
irrelevant'' material, ``and that it needed to be read.''
</P>
<P>
   Within days, Muegge flew the route in question, at a planned
altitude of 1,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Col. John G. Koran, the executive officer of the squadron,
who was released from the hearing without punishment, also flew the
route within days, at a planned altitude of 1,000 feet. And on Feb.
3, with deadly results, so did Capt. Richard Ashby, as pilot, and
Capt. Joseph Schweitzer, as navigator; it is they who now face
courts-martial.
</P>
<P>
   Why, Pace asked, had Roys not called the document to the
attention of his superiors more forcefully?
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite honestly, sir, I don't believe I even reread the binder
after I got back,'' he told Pace.
</P>
<P>
   And, the general asked, ``Why would an entire squadron of
officers not react to a fellow officer saying, `There's stuff in
here to be read'?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Muegge, the commanding officer, told Pace, ``Why didn't I stand
up and tell my operations officer, `Take a look at that binder'?
Probably because I thought he had, but why didn't I go and do
that?''
</P>
<P>
   Muegge said that he or his designee attended weekly meetings
with the Air Force, but that the 2,000-foot restriction was never
discussed.
</P>
<P>
   He also identified another reason the crucial document went
unnoticed, a reason perhaps characteristic of military culture.
Referring to Roys, he said, ``We had a situation where the
information came in at a low level instead of a high level, which
is the way we were used to receiving information.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is, for whatever reason, we didn't do it; and
there's thousands of reasons, but it wasn't because we didn't care
and we weren't trying to do our job the best we can,'' Muegge said.
``Just somehow, no one got the right message.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
