<HEADER>
A4044 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ORGAN-BANK-ART-NYT     11-10 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORGAN-BANK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLDEST ORGAN BANK, TURNING 30, BEMOANS SHORTAGE OF DONORS
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(dal) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ At this particular anniversary party, no one was giving
silver or diamonds. The only gifts that the guests cared about were
human organs, and the difference between life and death.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Boston, where organ transplantation got much of its
start, the New England Organ Bank, the oldest of more than 60
around the country, marked its 30th anniversary on Monday with all
the expressions of pride from doctors and thanks from patients that
one might expect in a medical field that did not exist half a
century ago and now saves thousands of lives annually.
</P>
<P>
   The embodiment of those 30 years, Lynda Uperti, a Delaware nurse
who received a kidney transplant in 1968 and is still doing fine at
the age of 52, told the gathering, ``Words really can't adequately
describe the feeling of gratitude for the ability to have that
second chance, that second life.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were feelings other than gratitude and pride at play.
Even at such a celebration, with its emphasis on successes, the
message from transplant experts, who provided a snapshot of the
current state of organ donation and procurement, was that this is a
field in crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The splashy announcement last week that scientists had succeeded
in cultivating human embryonic stem cells, which may someday be
used to grow organs outside the body for transplantation, concerns
the realm of the future. So does all the tantalizing talk of
``xeno-transplantation'': the use of animal organs to replace human
ones.
</P>
<P>
   For now, say organ procurement officials like those at the
nonprofit New England Organ Bank, they are facing a problem of
almost Malthusian dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The waiting lists are getting longer and longer and longer,''
said Dr. William E. Harmon, the organization's chairman.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Harmon said, 41,000 people around the country are
on the kidney transplant waiting list, but only 8,500 transplants
using cadaver kidneys are expected this year. About 58,000 people
are waiting for kidneys, lungs, livers or hearts, and about 10 die
each day.
</P>
<P>
   Organ donation has been gradually increasing, particularly in
recent years as organs from older people have become more
acceptable, but at nowhere near the rate of the growth in demand.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, doctors and organ-bank officials note with
unconcealed pain, a tremendous amount of time and debate has gone
into the question that most transplant experts call ``allocation''
but that those who speak more bluntly would call ``rationing'': Who
gets the available organs? The sickest patients? Those with the
best prognosis? Those geographically closest to the donor?
</P>
<P>
   ``The present tenor of the national allocation debate is not a
constructive one, and it is not likely to result in solution,''
warned Dr. Marc I. Lorber, a Yale Medical School professor who is
the regional representative for the United Network for Organ
Sharing, a private network of transplant centers.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government stepped into the fray this spring. To
help increase the supply of donor organs, it decreed that beginning
in August, hospitals had to report all deaths to organ banks,
increasing the likelihood that the banks' staffs, well trained in
persuasion, can lead relatives to donate the organs of the
deceased.
</P>
<P>
   Already, said Richard S. Luskin, executive director of the New
England Organ Bank, that rule has increased calls to the bank from
about 1,000 in August to 2,000 in October.
</P>
<P>
   Trickier, however, was a push by the government to reorganize
the system of distributing organs so that geography mattered less.
It proposed more of a national plan that would equalize the waiting
time for organs among regions, which now varies dramatically, and
give organs first to those who need them most.
</P>
<P>
   That proposal, held up last month by Congress so the issue could
be studied for another year, is still hotly debated, to the chagrin
of organ procurement officials. Even within the New England Organ
Bank, said Harmon, the chairman, ``the issue of allocation has
almost torn us apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, several speakers at the anniversary celebration said,
the focus should be on maximizing organ donations.
</P>
<P>
   Despite opinion polls showing that nearly 80 percent of the
American population approves of organ donation, only between 45 and
55 percent of possible donation consents are obtained nationwide,
Luskin said.
</P>
<P>
   The New England Organ Bank does somewhat better at 55 to 65
percent, he said, but that is not enough; the target should be the
full 80 percent. There has not been a ``concerted, coordinated
national public education campaign,'' he said, and organ donation
suffers from something of an image problem, its name tarnished by
jokes and conspiracy yarns about schemes in which the donation is
not exactly voluntary.
</P>
<P>
   Others at the gathering blamed doctors in part for the lag in
donations, noting that when families are not convinced that a
medical staff has done everything possible for their loved ones,
they are less likely to consent to organ donation. Furthermore,
these speakers said, a misconception remains among many doctors
that asking a family to donate a relative's organs will only
increase its pain.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, said Sheila McIntyre, a nurse from Quincy, Mass., who
donated her 19-year-old son's kidneys and eyes after he was killed
in a fall 15 years ago, many grieving relatives are happy to have
the opportunity to do some good.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do they have available to them,'' she said, ``except this
consolation?''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Moakley, a Massachusetts congressman who received a liver
transplant in 1995, recommended that when families gather for
Thanksgiving or the winter holidays this year, they discuss their
organ donation wishes. Because, organ bank officials pointed out,
even if someone has an organ donation sticker on his license or
other proof of a desire to donate, a dead person has no rights, and
it is ultimately the next-of-kin who decides.
</P>
<P>
   ``You must make your intentions known at the kitchen table, the
dining room table,'' said Moakley. ``As you celebrate the holidays
with your family, please make your intentions known. You may save
someone's life, just as someone saved mine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
