<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4046 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-REDS-HUMME     11-10 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-REDS-HUMMER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commentary: Braves still wrinkled after facelift
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Having done some superficial lifting and tucking among
their coaches, the Braves officially have begun making over those
employees who work in fair territory. This step is somewhat more
significant.
</P>
<P>
   The first Braves to be shown the door were those least
responsible for the latest NLCS collapse. Michael Tucker hit .385
against the Padres, winning Game 5 with a home run and five RBIs.
His benching the next game created legitimate groundswells. And the
Braves won Denny Neagle's Game 4 start. They both are dispatched to
Cincinnati bearing only good wishes.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves listened to the cry to use their surplus of starters
as barter for everyday help. It turns out you can have too much
pitching _ when it limits your flexibility in the field. Neagle
departs as one of the more under-appreciated Braves, because no one
could fully emerge from the tall forest of Maddux, Glavine and
Smoltz. He cheerfully bore his place in this society of pitchers,
but deserves to flourish as somebody's alpha wolf.
</P>
<P>
   In return, the Reds send this way a left arm capable of some
velocity but unspecific location. The rest of Mike Remlinger was
thrown in at no extra cost. The headliner was Bret Boone, the
second baseman who could make the right side of the infield as
impenetrable as an hour of C-Span. No one will be able to get
through it.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, the deal may not seem all that spectacular.
Especially if the pitching prospect the Braves threw into the deal
_ Rob Bell _ becomes real. We are not here today to begin
preparations for a Peachtree parade in the fall of '99.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do we gather, surprise, to rush to judgment. If the money
set free along with Neagle happens to multiply and land on a free
agent _ say Brian Jordan _ then the transaction starts to give off
a much better aroma.
</P>
<P>
   Right away, genealogists will love the deal. This summer, Boone
became the first third-generation All-Star. Preceding him to that
show were father Bob (a catcher) and grandfather Ray (an
infielder). The line of ballplaying Boones goes back even further
than the beginnings of Steve DeBerg's career.
</P>
<P>
   The family claims ol' Daniel Boone as a direct descendant, which
may speak to young Bret's competitive nature. The staid Braves can
use a little frontier spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Boone could have been had for a whole lot less just a year ago,
when during a .223 season he was briefly demoted to the minors. New
Braves hitting coach Don Baylor will have a project here, because
Boone is far from a finished offensive product. This year he
shortened his swing a little and enjoyed career highs in home runs
(24) and RBIs (95). But make no mistake, this is no leadoff type.
</P>
<P>
   Defense will be his signature. He won a Gold Glove this year,
and should have last when he set a record for highest fielding
percentage by a second baseman (.997). Recall that defense is
something the Braves used to be able to play.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides, of course, came out of the deal claiming that their
worlds are better off for having made it. This is an interesting
little tweak, perfectly in keeping with the Schuerholz Method of
putting faith in guys who can catch the ball. But Brett Boone is
hardly the final word on the needs of a team not as good as it
thinks it is.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Hummer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
