<SLUG> BC-TALL-TX-CAPITOL-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas Capitol may be taller than U.S. Capitol
</P>
<P>
   By Mike Ward
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texans for years have bragged that their pink
granite statehouse is taller than the nation's capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Six feet taller, maybe seven.
</P>
<P>
   Now, hoping to end 110 years of Texas-sized guessing, the state
agency in charge of the Capitol is planning to ``put this to rest
once and for all,'' said Ali Turley, the capitol's education
curator.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to take two measurements later this year _ one to
the top of the dome, to the Goddess' toes, and the other all the
way to the top of the Goddess,'' Turley said. ``We know exactly how
tall the Goddess (of Liberty statue) is, so we'll have a way of
verifying the exact measurement.''
</P>
<P>
   No date has been set for the measurement, which capitol
officials said will likely be conducted by survey teams from the
Texas Department of Transportation or General Land Office. After
all, officials said, you can't just run a measuring tape from the
front steps to the tip of the gilded goddess' outstretched arm.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, the official height of the Lone Star State's
most famous and revered dome has grown like Pinocchio's nose.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the Capitol was dedicated in May 1888, its
builders pegged it as 7 feet taller than the 288-foot U.S. Capitol
in Washington. By the 1920s, when it was briefly painted white in
an official faux pas that angered Texans, it was reported to be
more than 300 feet high.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1970s, the official height had grown to 308 feet 4
inches. A few years later, it was 311 feet. By 1995, it had shrunk
to 309 feet 8 inches based on calculations engineering drawings
used in its just-completed restoration. While there's little chance
the new measurement will debunk Texas' bragging rights over the
U.S. Capitol, it promises to trim down to size another oft-repeated
legend: Texas' statehouse is taller than that of any other state.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana's 450-foot office tower is the tallest, and Illinois'
405-foot statehouse _ including flagpole _ is the tallest with a
traditional dome.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Ward writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
