<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUNNE-GOP-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON STATE CLOUT WOULD RISE WITH DUNN AS MAJORITY LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Jennifer Dunn spent her first full day as a
candidate for House majority leader calling everyone she knows and
asking for help.
</P>
<P>
   But should she win next week, suddenly everyone she knows will
be seeking aid from her.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn, R-Wash., is seeking is the No. 2 post in the House, which
brings with it considerable power to influence national policy, a
bully pulpit from which to influence national politics, and a
traditional role for steering federal dollars and programs back
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be great if she got it _ it would mean a lot for the
state _ because it would put her in a position where every
committee chair in the House would be beholden to her, and it would
also give her clout with the (Clinton) administration,'' said Rep.
Norm Dicks, D-Wash., the dean of the state's congressional
delegation. ``There are always issues that come up, things
affecting the Boeing Co. or Microsoft, and when you're in the
leadership, you're going to have additional clout.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Rep. Rod Chandler, R-Wash., said Dunn would be in a
position not only to help the state, but to help the Republican
Party keep control of the House in 2000, and thereby, from his
perspective, help the American people with tax cuts and other
policy initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a visible position _ much more so than anything other
than speaker _ and it is also a position from which the policy of
the (Republican) conference is established and carried out,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Washington state, it's a huge bump in influence that
Jennifer would have over what she has now,'' he said. ``That just
goes without saying.''
</P>
<P>
   Chandler is one of a handful of longtime Dunn allies, most from
Washington state, who have rallied to her side in an effort to
boost her campaign to unseat House Majority Leader Dick Armey,
R-Texas. Reps. George Nethercutt and Doc Hastings, R-Wash., were
making calls on Dunn's behalf; her longtime political consultant,
John Meyers, flew in from Bellevue and joined another longtime
former aide-turned lobbysist, Phil Bond, in helping her campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us in the West, it means a lot, because we need to have
someone ... stitting at the negotiating table to make sure our
region is represented well,'' Nethercutt said.
</P>
<P>
   Nethercutt defeated the last House leader from Washington state
_ Tom Foley, a Democrat who had previously served as majority
leader. Nethercutt said Washingtonians should not expect Dunn to
use her post as a vehicle for sending pork back to the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``She would have a greater opportunity to deliver the right
product to our region, but the right product may be cutting
spending and lowering taxes, allowing us not to have the Bonneville
Power Administration sold and not to have the (Snake River) dams
breached,'' Nethercutt said. ``Just bringing money home _ I don't
think that's her style. We all want good expenditures, but
legitimately so, and not just because they have our name on them.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dunn would clearly be in a position to help two major
projects in Washington state that depend on federal largesse _ the
cleanup of the Hanford Nuclear Reservation and the construction of
the Sound Transit network of rail and bus lines and carpool lanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jennifer has always been interested in finding bipartisan
solutions, so that would probably be good news for our state,''
said Gov. Gary Locke, a Democrat. Locke's spokesman, Keith Love,
said, ``Losing Tom Foley hurt us a lot. Anytime you have someone
from your state in a leadership position, it's got to be helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn would also give a strong voice for Washington's corporate
citizens, including Boeing and Microsoft. Both companies are wary
of saying much for now, since they will have to work with whoever
wins. And Microsoft, in particular, has a very close relationship
with Armey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be inappropriate for Boeing to comment on the
internal decision-making process of either political party,'' said
Boeing spokesman Doug Kennett. ``That being said, Jennifer Dunn has
an excellent record serving the needs of her constituents, a large
number of whom are Boeing employees and their families. She has
also been an active supporter of Boeing objectives and programs,
and we are pleased to be considered one of her constituents.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn claimed Tuesday to have called all 222 of her fellow
Republicans _ although she didn't reach all of them _ to make her
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Armey appeared to be holding support from many of the
long-serving and powerful GOP committee chairmen, while former
Seattle Seahawk Steve Largent, R-Okla., was gathering support from
the most conservative wing of the party.
</P>
<P>
   Although many committee chairmen are supporting Armey,
Transportation Committee Chairman Bud Shuster, R-Penn., is
supporting Dunn, according to two sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``This race is a whole lot different than the races we ran Nov.
3, because you have a defined number of people you need to talk to,
and you know exactly what your universe is,'' said Hastings. ``You
can't sell a sitting majority leader short, but there is probably
some softness that is perceived there, and that's why Largent and
Dunn are in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
