<HEADER>
A4049 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-U.S.-ART-NYT &LR;      11-10 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.S.-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAISING PRESSURE ON IRAQ, U.S. RULES OUT TALKS ON ARMS SEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration stepped up its threats
against Iraq on Tuesday, ruling out a negotiated end to President
Saddam Hussein's defiance of international arms inspectors while
threatening to significantly reduce his ability to make chemical
and biological weapons if he does not back down.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is not needed _ and there is no plan for it _ is
negotiations with Saddam Hussein,'' said State Department spokesman
James Rubin on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton met with his senior national security advisers
at the White House for the second time in three days. They were
joined by senior commanders from the Joint Chiefs of Staff, who are
refining plans to mount air and missile strikes against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also telephoned the leaders of several important allies,
including Prime Ministers Tony Blair of Britain, Benjamin Netanyahu
of Israel, Jean Chretien of Canada and Massimo d'Alemo of Italy in
the U.S. campaign to isolate Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Tuesday's meeting at the White House, Defense
Secretary William Cohen announced that Clinton had agreed to speed
up by three days the arrival of a second aircraft carrier to the
Persian Gulf. The Enterprise, which recently left Norfolk, Va., and
its escort ships will now arrive by Nov. 23, joining the Dwight D.
Eisenhower and 13 other warships.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said the Enterprise was being sent to replace the
Eisenhower, which is due to leave Nov. 19, and not to bolster U.S.
firepower in the region. Other officials said the fact the second
carrier would not be in the Gulf for 13 days did not rule out the
possibility of a strike before then, using the 170 aircraft and the
250 to 350 cruise missiles already poised in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Using some of the blunt language the administration has used in
previous confrontations with Saddam but largely avoided so far this
time, Cohen warned that time was ``running out'' for Saddam to
reverse his decision on Oct. 31 to end cooperation with United
Nations weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diplomacy always should have every opportunity to dance,''
Cohen said during an appearance with Tony Tan, the deputy prime
minister and defense minister of Singapore. ``But at some point a
dance has a beginning and an end.''
</P>
<P>
   At the State Department, in what officials described as a
coordinator effort to intensify warnings to Saddam, Rubin said:
``This can't go on indefinitely. Saddam Hussein is not an abstract
threat.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the latest showdown, the administration has declined
to issue an ultimatum and said there is no timetable for an attack.
But the White House has drawn contingency plans for Clinton's
departure for Asia, which it has already pushed back a day, to
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials have said they still hope for a
diplomatic solution to avert the use of force, but they have done
nothing to promote one, insisting that only an unequivocal reversal
by Saddam is acceptable at this point.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Security Council's credibility is on the line,'' Cohen
said. ``The U.N.'s credibility is on the line and, I think, U.S.
credibility as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon's planners have drawn up two basic military
options: a swift, sharp strike that could begin at any time and a
larger, more punishing strike that would require the dispatch of
additional forces.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has significant air, naval and ground forces on
call for a larger strike, but so far has issued no orders to send
them.
</P>
<P>
   At Tuesday's White House meeting, which lasted 90 minutes, the
president's questions focused on the effectiveness of strikes and
the potential for civilian casualties, administration officials
said. The chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Gen. Henry
Shelton, attended with other senior members of the Joint staff,
including the director of operations, Vice Adm. Vernon Clark, and
the director of intelligence, Rear Adm. Thomas Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said that any strike would be aimed at making sure Saddam
was unable to rebuild chemical and biological weapons, the task
that until Oct. 31 was being done by the United Nations inspection
team known as Unscom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly would consider the possibility of degrading his
capability of manufacturing these weapons of mass destruction or
the means of delivering them and posing a threat to the region,''
Cohen said, echoing warnings the administration delivered during
the last crisis with Iraq over the winter. ``Beyond that, I don't
think it helpful or productive for me to comment in terms of how
much damage could be done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon also announced that a Marine Corps attack force
aboard the Belleau Wood would also speed up its arrival in the
Persian Gulf. It is expected to replace a similar force now aboard
the Essex.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
