<SLUG> BC-COMPAQ-STRATEGY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPAQ DIRECT-SELL PLAN LIKELY TO ANGER DEALERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Compaq Computer, the largest manufacturer of personal
computers, will start selling its machines directly by telephone
and over the Internet at prices lower than those now charged by
local dealers, people with knowledge of the company's new strategy
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   While the plan, scheduled to be announced Wednesday in New York,
is expected to anger the local dealers who sell the vast majority
of Compaq's computers, the company is taking the step to fend off a
potent rival, Dell Computer, which has always marketed its machines
directly and now threatens Compaq's market lead.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual attempt to mollify its dealers, Compaq is offering
to pay them a referral fee of 6 percent to 7 percent of the
purchase price on orders they send to Compaq's direct-sales unit.
</P>
<P>
   A Compaq spokesman declined to confirm the report.
</P>
<P>
   Antony Ibarguen, president of Tech Data Corp., one of the
largest computer wholesalers, said: ``There are dealers who tend to
be paranoid'' about a company that adopts a direct-marketing
strategy. ``They may not choose to sell that manufacture's
products.''
</P>
<P>
   Other manufacturers saw an opportunity in Compaq's move.
</P>
<P>
   Jim McDonnell, the marketing manager for Hewlett-Packard's
personal computer products, said, ``We hope that what Compaq is
doing will drive some resellers into our camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, many analysts praised Compaq's move as essential.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compaq has no choice but to do something,'' said Robert
Anastasi, a computer stock analyst with Robinson Humphrey in
Atlanta. ``Dell has been so successful it has conditioned customers
to ask to buy direct. You can only say no for so long.''
</P>
<P>
   Compaq has been losing market share to Dell, now No. 3, which
has grown faster and been more profitable because of the efficiency
of its direct-sales model.
</P>
<P>
   IBM Corp., the No. 2 personal computer seller, has also been
moving to sell more machines directly, although it has mainly
focused on its traditional base of large companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have the capacity to sell to all our customers
directly,'' said David Thomas, senior vice president of IBM in
charge of its PC group. ``For small businesses, our focus is on the
small resellers' channel. We will focus our direct efforts on the
large enterprise market.''
</P>
<P>
   Compaq's new effort is aimed mainly at small to medium-sized
businesses, a market that until now has bought fewer computers from
direct sellers than either big businesses or consumers have.
</P>
<P>
   ``The small and midsized business market is growing rapidly, but
until now it has been very fragmented,'' said Andy Bose, president
of Access Media International-USA. The majority of small business
owners, he said, buy what the industry calls ``white box''
computers, machines assembled by local dealers. He said there was a
huge opportunity for direct sales to small businesses because many
companies were no longer buying their first computer. Companies are
more secure and need less help when replacing machines.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, small business will account for about 9 million of the
36 million computers that will be sold this year, Bose said.
</P>
<P>
   Long recognizing the threat from Dell, Compaq has spent years
improving its manufacturing efficiency and reducing inventory, a
costly hot potato in a market in which computer prices often fall
by 1 percent to 2 percent a week.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Compaq introduced a direct-to-consumer sales
effort via toll-free telephone calls. But the results have been
tepid, mainly because Compaq kept its prices high to avoid angering
dealers.
</P>
<P>
   ``For nearly five years, we've been hearing that Compaq was
going to get more efficient to compete with the likes of Dell,
Gateway and Micron,'' said Joel Kocher, chief executive of Micron
Computer, a direct sales company that targets small business. ``To
date, their efforts have been less than successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Compaq's plan to build a ``hybrid'' model that combines direct
sales with dealer sales is fraught with peril, analysts say. NEC, a
huge Japanese computer manufacturer, shifted two years ago from
dealers to an all-direct-sales model and has seen its market share
plummet.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot be all things to all people in all places in all
industries,'' said Tony Amico, an analyst with International Data.
``You need resellers that know about specific industries and who
can reach out to America beyond the big cities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
