<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOFA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Lawsuit Says BofA Sold Too Cheaply  &HT;       
 By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
A Burlingame law firm has filed a class-action lawsuit accusing the
old BankAmerica Corp. and North Carolina's NationsBank Corp. of
cheating BofA shareholders by falsely claiming their $43 billion
combination was a ``merger of equals.''
<P>
   In a suit filed last week in San Francisco Superior Court,
Cotchett, Pitre &AMP; Simon characterized the transaction as a
NationsBank takeover of the old BofA, not a merger. As such, the
firm said, stockholders of the old BofA were entitled to a premium
price for their shares.
</P>
<P>
   The suit doesn't specify the amount of damages. But Bruce Simon,
the lead attorney on the case, said shareholders ultimately could
collect more than $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   San Mateo resident Gregory Baker is plaintiff in the case,
acting on behalf of all California stockholders of the old BofA at
the end of September, when shareholders voted on the deal.
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank, which now uses the BankAmerica name, has been
slapped with two dozen or more lawsuits since the transaction
closed September 30. The suits charge it with concealing trading
and investment banking losses. The bank said it made losses public
as it learned of them.
</P>
<P>
   This is apparently the first suit to focus on the issue of the
nature of the transaction itself, Simon said.
</P>
<P>
   In disclosure documents distributed to shareholders before the
vote to approve the transaction, the old BofA said both parties
were committed ``to a true merger of equals in which control is
shared, so no control premium would be appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent, the proxy statement told the old BofA
shareholders the transaction was a merger of equals, it was
misleading,'' Simon said.
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank said both banks properly disclosed the nature of the
transaction to shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think there's any validity to these claims and we
intend to contest them vigorously,'' spokesman Richard Stilley
said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the deal was announced in April, analysts have
consistently described it as a takeover, not a merger.
</P>
<P>
   After the combination took effect September 30, NationsBank
Chief Executive Officer Hugh McColl moved quickly to force out
David Coulter, his counterpart at the old BofA, extend his own
tenure and consolidate his grip on the combined organization.
</P>
<P>
   In a takeover, shareholders of the acquired company typically
get paid something above the market price of their stock in
exchange for giving up control. The typical takeover premium is 9
percent above the market price, Simon said.
</P>
<P>
   Independent legal experts said the suit raises an important
issue, but that BofA could defend itself by pointing out that
shareholders were told that NationsBank would control the combined
bank's board and chief executive slot, and that the headquarters
would remain in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   James Rockett, a banking lawyer with the San Francisco firm
McCutchen, Doyle, Brown &AMP; Enersen, said those disclosures would
allow any reasonable person to realize NationsBank was actually
buying BofA. ``Those terms in and of themselves would show that the
transaction was less than a merger of equals,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-10-98 2134EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981110.0356 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4055 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREET-SFCHRON &LR;      11-10 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 It's Already Christmastime for Internet's Biggest Darling _ eBay  &HT;       
 By Mark Veverka  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
It's back.
<P>
   After a late summer slumber, Internet mania has returned with a
vengeance _ just in time for the holidays. And once again, there is
little sane justification for some of the ridiculous stock
valuations that many Web darlings are fetching.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the usual suspects took part in yesterday's Net stock
bonanza. Yahoo was up 8 percent, and Amazon.com closed about 4
percent higher.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the most egregious examples of investor lunacy to hit
the Net is the run-up of eBay, the online auctioneer that has been
public for about a nanosecond. (It actually went public in
September.) Yesterday, eBay's shares vaulted $27.88 a share, or 27
percent, to close at $130.88.
</P>
<P>
   Yup. The stock soared nearly 28 whopping points in a single day.
And that was coming off Monday's 22 percent rise.
</P>
<P>
   So, what in Santa's name could have triggered such a phenomenon?
Is eBay being bought by Microsoft? Has the e-tailer made a hostile
bid for Wal-Mart? Is eBay giving away free Beanie Babies?
</P>
<P>
   Nope. Nothing like that. The Net stocks' rout was actually
triggered by short-selling and momentum buying, but more on that
later.
</P>
<P>
   The catalyst most-credited by the Street for the surge is an
industry research report that boldly predicts that holiday shoppers
are going to buy more gifts over the Internet this year compared to
last. Jupiter Communications estimates that online shoppers are
expected to spend $2.3 billion during this holiday season, up from
$1.1 billion a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Stop the presses. More fruitcakes are going to be sold over the
Internet, so let's bid up electronic commerce and portal stocks
beyond comprehension during a downtrodden day for the Dow. Somebody
better e-mail  &LR; st.nick(at sign)betterbegood.com  &LR; and alert the
elves that they'll need to add capacity to their Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not news. It's an excuse. Wall Street was beating (the
holiday traffic) tom-tom since last September,'' says David Simons,
managing partner of Digital Video Investments of New York.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that just about any tangible event that might bring
more people to the Web is being used to hype the value of Internet
stocks, Simons says. While there are more sophisticated ways to
measure the growth in customers and revenues, there still is no
rational way to justify the current prices of many top Internet
stocks, Simons says.
</P>
<P>
   Consider CDNow. For most of October, the online seller of music
had been trading around $7 or $8 a share. Investors were so
unenthralled with the company's low-margin business of selling
compact discs over the Internet, not even its planned buyout of
competitor N2K could give its shares a lift.
</P>
<P>
   But yesterday, CDNow shares skyrocketed about 50 percent to
close at $12. ``So what changed, did people realize that Christmas
was coming?'' Simons asks.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, hedge fund manager Andy Kessler thinks there is at
least one way to measure a Web stock's value. Kessler, of Velocity
Capital Management in Palo Alto, argues that electronic commerce or
portal companies can justify their lofty stock prices by defining
their growth in terms of gaining new customers.
</P>
<P>
   As long as sales and marketing expenses are used judiciously to
generate new customers, the company is building meaningful market
share that will bring greater profits down the road. This approach
demonstrates ``that there is an underlying business,` Kessler says.
</P>
<P>
   However, what's actually driving Internet mania are market
forces that have little to do with Santa or Web site visits,
Kessler says. Such dramatic stock spikes are likely caused by
short-sellers that need to cover negative bets made during the
recent bear market and by fund managers trying to make up lost
ground during the late innings of a difficult year, Kessler says.
The shorts ``were getting squeezed,'' Kessler says.
</P>
<P>
   Simons agrees. What's more, he contends that sell-side analysts
are fueling the Internet fire by raising the target prices on
stocks they cover. Last summer, before the market meltdown,
brokerage house analysts began to downgrade stocks, such as
Amazon.com, once the stocks hit share prices projected by their
models. But this time around, analysts are raising their price
targets _ which can often give stocks short-term boosts, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, just yesterday, a Goldman Sachs analyst published a
research note that raised his price target for eBay to $150 and
increased his estimates for 1999 revenues to $84.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Simons thinks that brokerage analysts are
not-so-subtly trying to give the investment bank sides of their
firms some help. It's no secret that initial offerings are down,
which is hurting the bottom lines at investment banks that perform
a significant amount of technology underwriting. During this latest
wave of Net mania, you are likely to see more cheerleading by
sell-side analysts, Simons says.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's different this time around is that the Street has a
greater incentive to keep the market going and give the IPO market
a lift,'' Simons says.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a reticence of institutions to back Internet IPOs,
and keeping the mania perking is just what the banks need to get
the institutions off the bench,'' Simons says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(at sign)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
