<SLUG> BC-ORACLE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Intel Touts New Strategy At Oracle's Big Trade Show  &HT;       
 By Dan Fost  
 &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Intel Corp. is pushing into the high end of the computing market,
and yesterday it touted that move at a major trade show sponsored
by database leader Oracle.
<P>
   Intel, which already sells the lion's share of microprocessors
for personal computers, is aggressively seeking to sell the chips
for servers and workstations.
</P>
<P>
   By next year, the Santa Clara chip giant will devote half its
development dollars to its high-end efforts, Intel Executive Vice
President Paul Otellini said in an interview following his speech
at the Oracle Open World, which is packing the Moscone Center in
San Francisco this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge investment, a multibillion-dollar investment, and
we've spent years to get here and we're not done yet,'' Otellini
said. But with increasing demand for speedy chips, Otellini said,
``The wind is with us on this one.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  More than 18,000 people are attending the Oracle show, which
ends tomorrow. Oracle is the world's second-largest software
company and the biggest maker of the massive database software that
runs such applications as airline bookings and credit card
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Such high-volume software needs powerful chips. ``It had been
the realm of the supercomputer,'' Otellini said. ``It used to be
you'd need three guys in white coats to help you.''
</P>
<P>
   Databases will move away from the mainframe and toward the
desktop as chips get faster and that will give Intel a leg up, said
analyst Dan Hutcheson, president of VLSI Research in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Intel's manufacturing capability and its ability to
pack so many transistors onto a chip, a move to Intel chips for
high-end machines is ``almost inevitable,'' Hutcheson said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  That's what Otellini hopes. Where once companies needed to
buy $40,000 or $50,000 Sun or Silicon Graphics machines, he said,
now they can spend $4,000 or $5,000 for the same performance.
</P>
<P>
   Chip technology will continue to advance, he said, ultimately
bringing mainframe-level performance out of the ``back end'' of a
company's computer operations and right onto front-line workers'
desktops.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this back end is going to enable a whole different
class of applications for users,'' Otellini said. ``Nobody can deal
with seas and seas of numbers. They have to see it in pictures ...
and that's all done on a desktop. ... It's pretty compelling, but
it takes a lot of processing power.''
</P>
</TEXT>
