<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Experts Crucial When Starting Out  &HT;       
 By Peter Sinton  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Question: &LR;  Are there some outside experts new entrepreneurs need &LR; 
 &LR; to assist them in starting a business? Normally, start-up funds &LR; 
 &LR; are tight and new owners avoid hiring people they think are &LR; 
 &LR; going to cost a fortune. &LR;
<P>
   Answer: It's no fun spending money before you make it, but
experts suggest that it is important to tap a few professionals
before embarking on a new venture.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Fred Steingold, author of the popular ``Legal Guide for
Starting &AMP; Running a Small Business'' published by Nolo Press
( &LR; www.nolo.com &LR; ) names four: a lawyer to help determine the best
structure (sole proprietorship, partnership, corporation or limited
liability company) and to take care of required filings, a CPA to
answer tax questions and to recommend sound bookkeeping and payroll
practices, an insurance agent to make sure the business has the
right coverage and possibly a real estate broker to find the best
location.
</P>
<P>
   Steingold has written self-help guides, including legal forms,
for small businesses and believes ``self-help types can save a lot
of money _ especially on lawyer and CPA fees.'' But he recommends
that ``even the most intrepid self-helper may want to briefly
double-check with a professional before proceeding. Mistakes can be
costly.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Q: I want to start an artisan bakery in a small, northern
California coastal community between Humboldt County and San
Francisco. How do I do market research for locations that meet my
criteria for potential, growth, competition, demographics,
community character and so forth. I am currently living in another
state and cannot afford to travel up and down the coast to make a
personal search.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; A: Deciding on where to locate a business without a visit
probably makes about as much sense as buying a house without
checking the foundations and visiting the neighborhood or buying a
car without seeing how it runs.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Levinson, author of the Guerrilla Marketing series,
recommends driving up and down the California coast, checking the
towns that appeal to you and talking with business owners and
others. ``It might take you two weeks, but that will be a very wise
investment of time,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you can do plenty of homework on the Internet and
through the phone book. Levinson suggests checking out Web sites
for coastal towns and their chambers of commerce and going to the
library to peruse yellow page directories for the 707 and 415 area
codes.
</P>
<P>
   If the town has the right population and no or few little
bakeries, that might be a cue for you to open yours.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Five years ago when I was going into business, I found all
sorts of hints. What I really need now are tips on how to get out
of business. My shipping and mailbox store is less than successful
and after much heartache and disappointment and five years without
a vacation, I want out. It's a sole proprietorship with annual
sales of about $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Knowing how to bail out of a business is as important as
getting in, just as it is in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   New York management consultant Stephen Schiffman, who just wrote
his  &LR; twelfth  &LR; 12th book, ``Make It Your Business,'' suggests
putting out word to lawyers, accountants and consultants whose
clients might be interested in your business. You might also place
an ad in trade industry publications, newspapers or online sites.
Or put out word at an industry trade show where you can also meet
potential buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, find someone who already operates a business like
yours in your area and may want to expand into your location.
</P>
<P>
   If you are down on your business, Schiffman instructs, ``Don't
let it show.'' Be honest but put the best face on the business;
make sure things are neat and the records tidy.
</P>
<P>
   If the prospective buyer suspects it is a distress sale, he or
she will certainly not pay you a fair price, which Schiffman
suggests might be four to seven times your pretax earnings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send small-business questions to  &LR; entrepreneur(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR;  or to Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
