<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIVACY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Beef Up Patient Privacy Rules, Health Groups Say  &HT;       
 By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Consumer and patient rights groups must move quickly to put privacy
safeguards in place before health providers launch a national
database of medical records.
<P>
   That call to action was issued yesterday in Oakland, where
health advocacy groups spent the day talking about the government's
push to make all doctors, pharmacists and insurers start using the
same record-keeping computer systems within the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are worried we'll create a national database of health
information before we have adequate privacy rules to say what can
and can't be done with the data,'' said Janlori Goldman, director
of the Health Privacy Project at Georgetown University.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting in Oakland was the fifth in a series of privacy
gatherings in the state sponsored by Consumer's Union and the
California Health Care Foundation. Goldman, the key expert at the
session, is organizing similar consumer lobbying efforts in 10
other states.
</P>
<P>
   This group is trying to influence the federal government's push
for what is called ``administrative simplification.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services is in
the final stages of publishing regulations that would require all
health care entities, from doctors to insurance companies, to adopt
a single set of computerized record-keeping systems.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Karp, chief information officer for Oakland's California
Health Care Foundation, said uniform record-keeping would have
benefits that go beyond paying bills or detecting fraud.
Computerized records would be easier to find if patients move or
change providers.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers would also be able to scan millions of patient
records to see which treatments proved most effective, presumably
giving that information back to doctors so that they can make
better diagnoses in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Though they see the benefits of computerization, consumer
advocates are worried about the lack of privacy safeguards.
Although HHS is expected to publish its computerization rules late
this year or early next year, Congress has so far stalled on
passing privacy legislation, Goldman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no federal rules that protect the confidentiality of
medical records,'' Goldman said.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of clear guidelines, some medical information is
already being used in marketing campaigns, such as pregnant women
getting solicitations from diaper companies. Moreover, Goldman said
people are coming forward to claim they lost their jobs after
employers learned they were taking medications for depression or
had other health problems.
</P>
<P>
   With national medical databases expected to take shape in the
next few years, consumer advocates say there is a pressing need to
set rules for how information can be used.
</P>
<P>
   Attendees at yesterday's meeting spanned the range from
immigrant groups, worried that Immigration and Naturalization would
tap into records to pursue illegals, to women's groups concerned
that abortion-seekers would become targets for violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many women who have insurance pay cash for an abortion because
they don't want to have a paper trail,'' said Debra Titmus,
regional director for Planned Parenthood in San Rafael.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's privacy meeting was a prelude to a larger gathering
planned by the California Health Care Foundation for January in
Oakland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
