<HEADER>
A4062 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDUC-ACCREDITATION-2T     11-10 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUC-ACCREDITATION-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE ACCREDITATION SYSTEM OUT OF CONTROL, ADMINISTRATORS SAY
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   How do you draw the line between diploma mills and storefront
``law schools,'' on the one hand, and programs in higher education
that meet at least minimum standards?
</P>
<P>
   The answer has long been an accrediting process that gives a
stamp of approval to worthy programs and institutions and withholds
it from others.
</P>
<P>
   But increasingly, academic administrators, like those who raised
the issue at the annual meeting of the American Association of
Universities at Berkeley last month, believe that the system is out
of control. They argue that visiting inspection teams tie up
valuable staff time by asking hundreds of questions on issues large
and small, a process that costs Duke University, for example,
$250,000 for each once-a-decade review. Some educational leaders
are concerned that many accrediting agencies wield such power that
they threaten to distort institutional priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's become a huge problem,'' said Malcolm Gillis, president
of Rice University in Houston. ``The accreditors are not interested
in what or how the students learn, but how many square feet of
classroom space we have per student.''
</P>
<P>
   But Arthur Wise, president of the National Council for
Accreditation of Teacher Education, defends the system. ``We know
we're not popular with college presidents,'' he said, ``but the
fact is the public needs to know. There must be accountability.
That's the mission of my organization.''
</P>
<P>
   The tension arises from the diffuse system of higher education
in the United States. Unlike many nations that have a central
authority dictating, the American system relies on voluntary,
nongovernmental peer review.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the accreditors in higher education come in two types.
First, there are the eight regional accrediting agencies that
certify institutions in their areas every decade. The second type
consists of specialized or occupational agencies that deal with
subjects like sociology and fields like medicine and law.
</P>
<P>
   The first type, the regionals, as they are known, focus on broad
criteria like fiscal stability and administration effectiveness,
and potentially wield great power. A denial of accreditation by a
regional can be a death knell, leading to a denial of federal loans
and grants and frightening away students and their parents.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, when it became known that the North Central
Association of Colleges and Schools, one of the eight regionals,
was about to withdraw accreditation from the venerable Phillips
University in Enid, Okla., because it had failed to correct such
deficiencies as proof of fiscal stability and the ability to
attract a sufficient number of students, the university declared
bankruptcy and closed its doors.
</P>
<P>
   Only a very few institutions, like Bob Jones University, a
well-financed evangelical Christian university in Greenville, S.C.,
can survive without accreditation.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Ruderman, vice provost for academic services at Duke
University, puts the cost of the process to the university at
$250,000, not including the many hours put in by faculty and
administrators.
</P>
<P>
   ``This last time around,'' Ms. Ruderman said, ``they told us and
the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill that we were not in
compliance with their requirement to demonstrate that graduates
were competent in the use of computers. It wasn't that the
graduates were not competent, but that they said we had failed to
demonstrate their competence. So we had to start all over again.''
</P>
<P>
   A major complaint against the regionals, however, is not that
they are college-killers but that _ intimidated by their own power
_ they shrink from using it, and allow substandard institutions to
persist.
</P>
<P>
   ``What good is accrediting if almost nobody ever gets
rejected?'' said James F. Carlin, the tough-talking chairman of the
Massachusetts Board of Higher Education. ``It's just a wet kiss.''
</P>
<P>
   Judith Eaton, president of the Council for Higher Education
Accreditation which approves, or disapproves, accrediting agencies,
counters by observing that the peer review process is intended not
merely to separate winners from losers but to help good
institutions achieve greater efficiency and form strategic plans.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The other type of accrediting agency, the specialized or
occupational groups, is of even greater concern to educational
administrators.
</P>
<P>
   Almost no one denies Wise's point that many of these
organizations, which certify everything from dental schools to
teacher training programs, are necessary. Who would oppose the
accreditation or licensing of schools of pharmacy or engineering?
</P>
<P>
   But academic administrators are troubled by the fact that there
are so many of these agencies _ at least 75, according to an
estimate by the Association of Specialized and Professional
Accreditors, which represents 42 of them. A medical school may be
examined by 40 or 50 separate accrediting agencies. And answering
all the questions posed by visiting teams of accreditors can
swallow large amounts of faculty and administrative attention and
effort.
</P>
<P>
   At least occasionally, the accreditors respond to criticism.
Just last week, leaders of the Accreditation Board for Engineering
and Technology and the Computing Sciences Accreditation Board
approved a merger that, they said, would save colleges money and
time by reducing site visits.
</P>
<P>
   Worse than the red tape, in the view of some educators, is that
many specialized accreditors have lobbied themselves into the
position of gatekeeper of federal money.
</P>
<P>
   ``They blackmail us,'' said John V. Lombardi, the president of
the University of Florida and like Gillis one of the few top
university leaders willing to discuss the issue openly. ``If they
say your department of astrophysics needs 12 spaceships and you
have only 10, you had better get the other two.''
</P>
<P>
   He added wryly, ``You take the money from the history department
because it doesn't have an accrediting lobby to protect it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't go along with their demands,'' Lombardi said,
``they can deny accreditation in whatever it is that they
represent, and then, even if they don't control federal loans and
grants, they can tell the state Legislature that you lost your
accreditation and the Legislature will fire all of the top people
who run the institution.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want more classroom space, you give it to them,'' he
continued. ``If they want a 500-page report written in green ink,
you give it to them in green ink.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Magrath, president of the National Association of State
Universities and Land-Grant Colleges and a former president of the
University of Missouri, recalled doing battle with a powerful
specialized accreditor.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was president of the University of Missouri, the law
school at our Columbia campus was housed in a relatively old but
serviceable building,'' he said. ``The accrediting committee from
the American Bar Association insisted that we should have a new
building.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, maybe we didn't look like Harvard or Yale,'' he
continued, ``but we were doing just fine in having our students
pass the bar exam, and by any other reasonable standard, but they
told us that if we didn't get a new building, our accreditation
would be in jeopardy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I went ballistic,'' Magrath recalled. ``But they withdrew our
full-term accreditation, and it took us getting a new building
before they would restore it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem was that you had people making decisions about the
use of university resources who didn't have an overall
perspective,'' Magrath said.
</P>
<P>
   College administrators who are loath to cross swords with these
lobbies won a partial victory two years ago when the U.S.
Department of Justice, aroused by complaints that an accrediting
committee of the American Bar Association was dictating such
matters as the salaries of professors of law and the number of
books in law school libraries, took the association to court.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting consent decree directed the bar group to concern
itself with academic quality instead of resources. Since then, some
college administrators have cited the consent decree in bargaining
with accrediting agencies, but they are not always able to persuade
the specialized accreditors to scale back their demands.
</P>
<P>
   And so, the struggle continues. The land-grant college group
recently adopted a strongly worded resolution declaring that the
member universities would insist that accreditors limit themselves
to the consideration of academic quality and leave the allocation
of resources to the college administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our resolution is not binding,'' said David Shulenburger,
provost of the University of Kansas at Lawrence, who drafted it.
``But it spread the word about the consent decree and made it clear
that if the agencies say they want two lamps in every office, we
can say no.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
