A4064 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HITECH-TSHIRT-COX     11-10 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HITECH-TSHIRT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    T-shirt motherboard reads vitals on new level
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ By most accounts the flight of the space shuttle
carrying John Glenn and others last week was a fine success. But
Sundaresan Jayaraman, a sharp-eyed Georgia Tech researcher, thought
it could have gone a little bit better.
</P>
<P>
   One problem, which he read about in news accounts, concerned a
troublesome system of electronic leads that had to be attached to
Glenn to get readings on his vital signs during sleep experiments.
News stories reported it took an hour to get the system attached,
and they had to do it four times.
</P>
<P>
   Jayaraman, who leads a team of specialists in the School of
Textile and Fiber Engineering, has come up with just the ticket
that could have saved time _ a huge consideration on a busy and
expensive mission where, he calculates, astronauts' time comes to
about $593,000 an hour each.
</P>
<P>
   What Jayaraman and his team have fashioned is a wearable
motherboard, a kind of light T-shirt that contains a web of wiring
capable of monitoring many life signs at once. And the shirt, which
has been featured in Life magazine, could sell for about $25,
Jayaraman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Light, practical and inexpensive, it could be available for
monitoring continuously,'' said Jayaraman.
</P>
<P>
   The garment could be configured in many ways, he said, but it
could certainly keep continuous readings on heart rate,
temperature, breathing and other functions, which could be fed into
a box and communicated to remote centers such as the space
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The primary purpose of the wearable motherboard, as it happens,
is to be worn by soldiers and sailors in the field, where it could
record injuries and wounds, and transmit the information to medical
officers.
</P>
<P>
   Signals would indicate exactly where a bullet pierced a
soldier's body, and readings of vital signs would indicate the
severity of the injury. Also, the system could be programmed to
indicate the exact whereabouts of the injured trooper in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``In multiple injuries, the system could give information for
grading the injuries so that assistance could be given according to
priority,'' Jayaraman said.
</P>
<P>
   The latest generation of the electronic T-shirt even has a means
to transmit voice to the monitoring center.
</P>
<P>
   Jayaraman, who might be a serious marketing man if he weren't so
busy being a scientist, said the system could have a great variety
of applications.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system could be used by safety forces, particularly
firefighters, where you could measure oxygen content of the person
as well as other vital signs,'' Jayaraman said.
</P>
<P>
   This automatic monitoring of vital signs could be very important
for firefighters, where the excitement and adrenaline rush could
sometimes mask the real health dangers to the actual firefighter
but could be very apparent to medical technicians monitoring them
at work.
</P>
<P>
   In the area of health care, the wearable motherboard could help
monitor the condition of post-operation patients, even in their
homes after they leave the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as the home security business grows,'' said Jayaraman,
``this wearable technology just might spawn a new industry for the
effective and reliable monitoring of patients at home and maybe
transform health care delivery.''
</P>
<P>
   Research on the wearable motherboard has been born mostly by the
Navy Department, Tech officials say. Working with Jayaraman are
several others, including Rangaswamy Rajamanickam, a research
engineer; research associates Sungmee Park and Chandramohan
Gopalsamy; and Joohyun Hong, a research assistant.
</P>
<P>
   For further information, see the research Web site: http://
</P>
<P>
   vishwa.tfe.gatech.edu/gtwm
</P>
<P>
   /gtwm.html.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Holsendolph writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
