A4066 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-BILBRAY-NYT &LR;      11-10 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-BILBRAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REP. BRIAN BILBRAY: COMPLAINTS FROM A MAINSTREAM DISTRICT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Shortly before Congress adjourned last month,
Speaker Newt Gingrich approached Rep. Brian Bilbray, one of the two
dozen Republicans whom Democrats were concentrating on ousting in
this year's elections, and asked what Republican leaders could do
to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I snapped at him,'' Bilbray recalled last week. ``I told him,
`It's a little late to be asking now, Newt.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bilbray survived in last week's election _ barely. In his 49th
District of California, which includes about half of San Diego and
runs to the Mexican border, he defeated a San Diego Councilwoman,
Christine Kehoe, by 4,000 votes, less than 3 percent of the votes
cast.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the campaign, he said, his party's leaders were an
albatross around his neck. ``All this talk about impeachment, all
this right-wing jargon,'' Bilbray complained. ``It's extremely
frustrating for those of us who represent mainstream districts. It
puts off people in mainstream America.''
</P>
<P>
   Bilbray is not a typical Republican congressman. He is one of
the few who do not have safe seats. Of the 212 Republicans who ran
for re-election last week, only five were defeated and only 14 won
re-election by margins of less than 10 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   But these few swing seats determine the balance of power in the
House.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, Bilbray was interviewed at length after the
election to see what he thought his party needed to do to make sure
these seats remained Republican so the party could maintain control
of the House in the next election. He was interviewed again over
the weekend, after Gingrich announced he would step down as
speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Bilbray's answer, not surprisingly, was that the party's policy
makers needed to pay less attention to the firebrands whose seats
are not in jeopardy and more to Republicans like him who are
hanging on by a thread.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders, he said, should concentrate less on attacking President
Clinton and ``throwing raw meat to the base,'' and more on matters
like taxes and Social Security that ``mainstream voters care
about.''
</P>
<P>
   The 47-year-old Bilbray was first elected in the Republican
sweep in 1994, defeating a Democrat, Lynn Schenck. He endorsed
Gingrich's Contract With America. And for the most part, he has
voted with the leadership, although he broke ranks occasionally, on
issues like gun control, campaign finance and state financing for
abortions.
</P>
<P>
   This year he was one of only nine Republicans who voted against
his party's plan to cut taxes by $100 billion over the next five
years. He argued that making the Social Security system solvent was
a higher priority than cutting taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Bilbray said he was in debt to Gingrich for giving him a plum
assignment to the Commerce Committee, which has broader
jurisdiction than any other committee in the House except two, Ways
and Means, and Appropriations.
</P>
<P>
   But Bilbray added, ``What the leadership does on policy, that
makes much more of a difference to us than all the money and all
the assignments and all the influence in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Bilbray said that he had received several calls at home from
candidates running for leadership positions who wanted his support.
``I give them all a 15-minute dissertation on the systemic problem
with the structure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, as he sees it, is that the current leaders and
those who hope to replace them come from safe districts and they
reflect the views of those districts. But those are not the more
moderate views of the swing districts like his or of the country as
a whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Dick Armey talks to his constituents,'' Bilbray said,
referring to the majority leader, a Texan, ``they love what he's
saying, but his district doesn't represent the broad consensus of
Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Bilbray said he was especially upset by how Rep. Bob Barr of
Georgia, a staunch conservative on the House Judiciary Committee,
had been allowed to become a GOP spokesman on impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Bob Barr,'' Bilbray said. ``I'm sure he's very popular
in his district, but he's the worst spokesman imaginable in the
49th.''
</P>
<P>
   So what does he expect from those who emerge as the new leaders
of the party in the House?
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect them to take counsel from us, to integrate those of
us from marginal districts into their policy-making,'' Bilbray
replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell them,'' he concluded, ``that if they don't, their
leadership will be only two years long.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
