<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG TOBACCO AND 8 STATES ARE NEAR DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Colo., N.C., N.Y., N.D., Okla., Pa. Wash)  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Negotiators for eight states and representatives of the tobacco
industry have largely finished work on a deal to settle state
lawsuits against cigarette companies and could announce it as soon
as Friday, two lawyers involved in the talks said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The value of the settlement could reach $200 billion, depending
on the number of states that participate, the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   The attorneys general of the eight states involved in the talks
_ California, Colorado, New York, North Carolina, North Dakota,
Oklahoma, Pennsylvania and Washington _ expect to brief 38 other
states on the plan in the hope of their joining the settlement. The
38 states will have about a week to decide whether to take part in
the deal or to continue pursuing independent legal action, the
lawyers said. The remaining four states, Florida, Minnesota,
Mississippi and Texas, have reached individual settlements that,
combined, exceed $40 billion over 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   The new agreement is the result of more than five months of
talks, the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Christine Gregoire of Washington, the lead
negotiator for the states, was traveling to New York and could not
be reached for comment. Other state attorneys general declined to
comment. Tobacco executives and industry lawyers also declined to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris Cos.; R.J. Reynolds Tobacco, a subsidiary of RJR
Nabisco Holdings Corp.; Lorillard Tobacco, a subsidiary of the
Loews Corp., and Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco, a subsidiary of BAT
Industries, have agreed to pay as much as $200 billion over 25
years to settle lawsuits seeking to recover Medicaid costs for
treating smokers, the lawyers involved in the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   The companies have also apparently agreed to remove cigarette
billboard advertisements, pay more than $1 billion for anti-tobacco
advertisements, halt distribution of merchandise with tobacco logos
and finance a national foundation that would try to reducing
smoking by teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   An agreement could lead to the largest civil settlement in U.S.
history and would free tobacco companies of their most serious
legal challenge.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-10-98 2140EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981110.0367 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4068 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARTUP-SFCHRON &LR;      11-10 1282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARTUP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Being Your Own Boss  &HT;       
 By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Tara Phelps realized it was time to go into business for herself
after she received a relocation request from Hewlett-Packard last
year.
<P>
   For the previous two years, Phelps had been a project manager
for the Palo Alto company's medical products group, where she
successfully handled proposals for such major clients as 3M and
Columbia HCA and helped solve data management problems.
</P>
<P>
   When her division went through a major downsizing, Phelps was
offered what she calls ``a wonderful position'' in Bethesda, Md.
But after putting in 80-hour weeks for HP, much of it on the road
and in the air, Phelps decided she was ready for a change.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Rather than create a business, Phelps elected to find an
existing one where she could apply her experience in process
development and design.
</P>
<P>
   She wound up buying a business from a friend who owned Novazonic
Semiconductor Products, a little Santa Clara maker of wet process
tanks that are used for various etching and cleaning applications
in the manufacturing of semiconductors and flat-panel displays.
</P>
<P>
   For Phelps and others who have spent years working for others,
the experience of launching a small business is both liberating and
sobering.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key question is whether you're prepared to give up the
security of a paycheck and the structure of a corporation. The
trade-off is independence, freedom of action and the opportunity to
earn a lot more money,'' said Fred Steingold, attorney and author
of a ``Legal Guide for Starting and Running a Small Business''
published by Nolo Press.
</P>
<P>
   Owners who take on something they are interested in and know
something about are likeliest to succeed, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Steingold also suggests you consider these things before you
make the leap:
</P>
<P>
   _ Do you know how to accomplish the principal tasks of the
business?
</P>
<P>
   _ If the business involves working with others, do you handle
this well? If not, consider a one-person business.
</P>
<P>
   _ Do you understand basic business tasks, such as bookkeeping
and how to prepare a profit-and-loss forecast and cash-flow
analysis? If not, learn before, not after, you begin.
</P>
<P>
   _ Does the business fit your personality? If you are a shy
introvert, avoid businesses that require lots of personal selling.
If you are easily bored, find a business that lets you regularly
deal with new material.
</P>
<P>
   In Phelp's case, she was ready to leave. ``I had enough
experience with corporate America,'' said the divorced mother of
two, who got a business degree at Woodbury University in Los
Angeles while working full time in computer departments of several
companies. ``I wanted to have my own company with a solid product
and the opportunity to grow if managed properly.''
</P>
<P>
   She  &LR; said  &LR; told her friend who owned Novazonic Semiconductor
Products that she wanted to do something different.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `like what?' and I said run a business like yours.''
She ended up buying Novazonic a little over a year ago using her
savings from HP and some financial assistance from the previous
owner.
</P>
<P>
   Phelps declined to reveal the purchase price except to say it
was ``six figures.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the semiconductor equipment industry peaked just as
Phelps took over the company and has been in the doldrums ever
since, Novazonic has flourished with annual sales having jumped by
nearly 50 percent _ to $650,000 this year from $450,000 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Phelps, whose staff has grown from two to five, attributes her
success to focusing ``not on selling products but on solving
problems and creating relationships.'' For example, by adopting
computer-aided design, she was able to get drawings of product
modifications to clients much more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   She also said that she ignored some advice and went after
competitors' customers.
</P>
<P>
   Phelps has several tips to would-be entrepreneurs:
</P>
<P>
   _ Have faith and be persistent. Watch out for naysayers and
gloom and doom talk.
</P>
<P>
   _ Be resilient. Like Indiana Jones, you have to be able to
address any type of challenge.
</P>
<P>
   _ Have vision. You must have a mission statement and business
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Phelps' goal is to create a $5 million company within five
years.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Going the Consulting Route
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Rochwarger Vared, 43, took another route to make the
transition from being a cog in a big corporation to economic self
control.
</P>
<P>
   Rochwarger Vared bailed out of her job as corporate training
officer at Wells Fargo Bank in 1984 to broaden her experience at a
consulting firm before starting her own business, Strategic
Resources, three years later.
</P>
<P>
   She got her inspiration from books by John Naisbitt and Alvin
Toffler on the coming information age and growth of cottage
industries. What would be useful in the future, Rochwarger Vered
decided, was an outsourcing firm that could provide companies with
professional talent whenever and wherever they were needed.
</P>
<P>
   She turned out to be right. The Irvine company has an office in
Alameda headed by another Wells Fargo graduate and places more than
200 consultants in jobs each year. Work ranges from interim project
management to handling marketing assignments and Year 2000 computer
problems. Strategic Resources consultants generate about $5 million
in annual revenue and the company takes 20 percent of the project
fees.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies are cutting full-time jobs and hiring consultants
for the same work.
</P>
<P>
   But before you join the ranks of outsourced professionals,
Rochwarger Vered suggests that you have enough money to live on for
at least six months. Also be ready for nonstop networking among
colleagues, friends and acquaintances to win business and be ready
to take orders rather than give them.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Schiffman, author of ``Make It Your Business'' and a New
York management consultant, advises that starting a business
``requires a certain amount of obsession.'' In the first year or
two, you probably shouldn't plan on a vacation.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; The Drawbacks
</P>
<P>
   Although owning your own business is often portrayed as the
American dream, Schiffman says many of the assumptions are myths.
Chief among them is the idea ``I'm free! I no longer have a boss!''
Entrepreneurs not only have to account to themselves, Schiffman
notes, ``but hundreds or thousands of people called customers,''
who are more demanding and more nitpicky than most any supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   There are countless success stories of entrepreneurs striking it
rich. But many who heed the small business siren song end up in the
financial ditch.
</P>
<P>
   About 15 percent of new businesses don't last a year, according
to Cognetics Inc., a Cambridge, Mass., economic research firm.
Another 15 percent drop out the second year and 8 percent disappear
in the third. After five years only half of new businesses are
still around.
</P>
<P>
   But statistics on business closings can be misleading. Although
many dropouts failed to meet their financial goals, Cognetics
President David Birch notes that only 5 to 10 percent of them were
actually insolvent, owing more money than they had.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most are not failures,'' he said. ``They played the game for a
while and had more at the end than at the beginning.'' But often,
they didn't have enough to stick with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't know how hard it is to start and grow a
business,'' said Birch. ``Often they start with a product or
service, something they are good at, but underestimate the need to
sell.''
</P>
<P>
   Neophyte entrepreneurs also frequently underestimate the time it
will take to break even &UR; . &LR;  Another common problem is failure to
assess the likely stress and toll it may take on their families.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
