<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-NEELY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEELY TO PRACTICE WITH BRUINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ There was no stall designated for him at the practice
rink in suburban Wilmington Tuesday, no equipment with the familiar
No. 8 on it, no outward sign that he was about to join his former
team on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   However, when the Bruins assemble Wednesday at 11:45 a.m. at the
Ristuccia Center, retired (and perhaps future?) right wing Cam
Neely will be with them.
</P>
<P>
   Neely, who hung up his skates before the 1996-97 season because
of a chronic hip injury, has been working out hard with an eye
toward a comeback and is now ready to step up his regimen. In the
next 10 days, he will practice with the Bruins, determining whether
the goal is possible or whether his NHL playing career really, and
finally, is over.
</P>
<P>
   After a cautious start in September, Neely, 33, has felt well
enough to take it this far. Sources said that in recent days, he
has skated several times with Bruins head coach Pat Burns and
assistant Jacques Laperriere, both of whom endorsed Neely's
participation in a full-team workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been encouraged in my workouts so far in that my hip
has been sore after skating but the pain has not lingered,'' said
Neely in a statement. ``In talking with (therapist Dan Dyrek), we
decided that although I have been skating on a high tempo on my
own, the only way to determine if I have a realistic chance of
playing again is to increase my workouts in a normal hockey
practice. Dan believes that we will not be able to make an accurate
assessment until after 10 days to two weeks at a higher level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have said before that if I make a return to the game, it
will be this season and now is the time to take this next step.''
</P>
<P>
   Neely added in the statement that he doesn't want his
participation to become a distraction for the team, though it is
bound to have an impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be happy to give a brief update when I get off the ice
each day,'' he said, ``but we will not have any substantive
announcement until after the entire trial period is over and we
have reevaluated my hip.''
</P>
<P>
   Neely, who became a father for the first time less than a week
ago when his wife, Paulina, gave birth to son Jack Cameron, last
played for the Bruins on Feb. 21, 1996, in Anaheim, Calif. But his
hip was too sore to allow him to continue his career. When he made
his tearful retirement announcement before training camp that fall,
Neely thought he would need an eventual hip replacement. Now it
seems that this therapy could make it possible for him to do more.
</P>
<P>
   It's likely to be a strange dressing room for Neely. Only Ray
Bourque, Steve Heinze, and Don Sweeney remain from the team with
which he last suited up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be really weird for me,'' said Bourque. ``I know
it's going to be great. It's going to be a situation where nobody
knows where it's going to go from when he starts skating. We'll all
just have to wait and see how it goes. If it only lasted for a
month or it lasts to the point where he's able to play, it would be
great being out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, it will be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque said he and Neely have kept in touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen him much but I've talked to him on the phone
quite a bit,'' said Bourque.
</P>
<P>
   The long layoff will be a factor. It has been 2 years 9 months
since Neely played.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why nobody knows what to expect or how this is all
going to go,'' said Bourque. ``Cam, I'm sure, doesn't know himself.
I don't know. I don't know how it's going to unfold or how it's
going to end up, but he's going to give it a chance, give it a
shot, and see how he feels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll all keep our fingers crossed and hope they go well for
him. If they go well for him, it could mean something special for
everybody, but it's so far off. All we're going to do is welcome
him here, and I know for me, it's going to be fun to see him out
there and try to get to somewhere which for him would really be
great. He'd be happy and I'd be happy for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Pipe dream or reality? We'll know soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
