<HEADER>
A4074 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-REDS-TRADE     11-10 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-REDS-TRADE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves land Boone; Neagle, Tucker sent to Reds
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The policy shift became official at 5:30 p.m. EST
Tuesday. The Atlanta Braves finally cracked open the pitching
treasury.
</P>
<P>
   Striking the majors' first big deal of the offseason, the Braves
acquired Gold Glove second baseman Bret Boone and left-hander Mike
Remlinger from the Cincinnati Reds in exchange for Fab Four
left-hander Denny Neagle, outfielder Michael Tucker and minor
league pitching prospect Rob Bell, whom the Reds insisted upon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a neat experience,'' Boone said from a Las
Vegas golf junket. ``Very, very cool.''
</P>
<P>
   He hardly comes cheaply. Neagle, 38-19 in just over two seasons
with the club, leaves a hole for Bruce Chen in the rotation. Tucker
started 212 games in right field since 1997, while Bell, the
organization's pitcher of the year at Class A Danville, led the
Carolina League in strikeouts. But Reds general manager Jim Bowden,
who received inquiries from six teams about Boone, stipulated that
only an overwhelming offer would pry Boone away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave up good talent. It was a rich deal,'' Atlanta GM John
Schuerholz said from Naples, Fla., where the trade was announced as
the general managers meeting. ``But we have the riches. And some
may say it was overly rich. But we got the best second baseman in
baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Braves also have a vacancy in the outfield. Gerald
Williams currently claims sole rights to right field, though
veteran Schuerholz watchers know a second deal for another
outfielder must be in the offing. Tuesday's trade frees up nearly
$3 million in payroll the next two years, but when asked how soon
the next move might come, Schuerholz replied, ``There's no shoe
poised for falling.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but Jim Turner, agent for free agent outfielder Brian
Jordan, said he has been in contact with the front office Atlanta
weekly since the filing period began. Jordan, who still lives in
Stone Mountain, has also drawn interest from the New York Mets and
Yankees and Baltimore Orioles but while maintaining nothing was
imminent, Turner viewed Tucker's departure with heightened
interest.
</P>
<P>
   ''Certainly things became more clear today,'' Turner said.
''With the moves (the Braves) made and things that might follow . .
. that obviously enchances a lot of possibilities. The Braves have
admired Brian and the way he plays for some time now.''
</P>
<P>
   Boone, 29, is entering the third season of a four-year
$11.4-million contract that will pay him $2.9 million in 1999 and
$3.7 million in 2000. The Braves own a $4 million option for 2001
with a $250,000 buyout clause but since he was traded in
mid-contract, Boone is eligible to renegotiate his contract after
next season. His 24 home runs and 95 RBI were second only to San
Francisco's Jeff Kent (31-128) in production among National League
second basemen.
</P>
<P>
   ''Atlanta is a great team,'' Boone said. ''I want to do my part
and maybe I can even help them be a little better.''
</P>
<P>
   Having commited just 11 errors in the last two seasons combined,
Boone becomes the first Gold Glover to play second for the Braves
since Felix Millan (1972). His 1998 numbers (.267 average, 63
extra-base hits) reflect a breakout season, though he reached the
100-strikeout mark for the third straight year. Just one season
ago, he was shipped to Class AAA when a prolonged slump dropped his
average to .205.
</P>
<P>
   His arrival certainly signals Tony Graffanino's release, after
he hit .211 in 68 starts at second while left-handed hitting Keith
Lockhart is expected to be retained, if just for his pinch-hit
ability. The Braves had been set on acquiring Milwaukee second
baseman Fernando Vina, who would have also filled a need for
leadoff hitter, but talks turned to the Reds over the weekend
before the deal was settled in a late-night Monday session.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Vina deal was on the front burner for a long time,''
Schuerholz said. ''This only came up in the last couple days. I was
able to expand the deal to include Remlinger, which for a variety
of reasons was more beneficial to us than just making a straight-up
deal for Vina. Vina is a fine player. We like Boone more, purely
and simply.''
</P>
<P>
   Neagle, the league's only 20-game winner a year ago, was traded
for the third time in six years after having his name mentioned so
often trade rumors that he had made a comedy routine of announcing
his departure. Remlinger (8-15, 4.82) heads for the bullpen after
starting 28 games last season.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker literally swung his way off the team, his strikeout ratio
(112 in 414 at-bats) the worst on the Braves. After hitting .302 in
his first three months after being acquired March 27, 1997, he hit
just .248 afteer that, including a miserable .190 in the second
half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Staff writer Len Pasquarelli contributed to this
report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
