<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PACBELL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Pac Bell Wireless Faces Lawsuit Over Ads  &HT;       
 By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
A lawsuit filed  &LR; Tuesday  &LR; charges that Pacific Bell Wireless has
been misleading customers in California with false and deceptive
advertising and should be forced to stop.
<P>
   The company, which has been heavily marketing wireless phone
service for less than 5 cents per minute, is actually charging
consumers much more, except in very specific cases, the suit
alleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way you can get 5 cents a minute is if you use up all
your free minutes, which are designated for certain times and
certain days. That's not clear in the ads,'' said Michael Linfield,
a Pasadena attorney who filed the suit in Los Angeles Superior
Court. ``In some cases, you're actually paying 49 cents a minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Bell officials said they had not seen the suit and could
not comment.
</P>
<P>
   Under the company's 5-cent plan, wireless customers who sign up
for the 5-cent package pay $19.95 a month for 500 free weekend
minutes and 20 free weekday minutes. If a customer uses all those
minutes on the designated days, the cost per minute is less than 5
cents. However, if a customer uses only 100 of the free minutes on
the weekends, the cost comes out to about 20 cents per minute,
Linfield said.
</P>
<P>
   And once customers use up their 20 free weekday minutes, they
are charged significantly more for weekday calls, sometimes 49
cents per minute.
</P>
<P>
   Linfield said Pac Bell can charge whatever it wants, but the ads
fool people into thinking they are getting a 5-cent rate all the
time. He filed the suit on behalf of a Pac Bell Wireless customer
who ``is not getting what she thought she was paying for,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Linfield, who specializes in consumer rights, said he plans to
file a similar suit against Sprint PCS  &LR; on Thursday &LR; . That suit
focuses on an ad campaign that offers Sprint PCS service for 10
cents per minute.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint PCS officials had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``These ads are deceptive and they're something you'd expect
from small-time operators,'' Linfield said. ``We want a court to
force them to stop the misleading advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit comes on the heels of another filing against wireless
carriers in California. In August, a San Diego attorney sued Pac
Bell, AirTouch, Sprint PCS and GTE Wireless for charging customers
by the minute, instead of by the second. That suit is still
pending.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates say the explosion of wireless service has
made it easy for companies to confuse customers. They warn people
to read the fine print before signing up for any service and to
make sure they get everything in writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as the wireless companies like to tout the simplicity
of their rates, some rates are designed to confuse,'' said Charles
Carbone of the Utility Consumers' Action Network, a state consumer
group. ``They don't want customers to go out and sufficiently shop
the market. So when you actually subscribe to a service, you find
out the rate structures are quite confusing and not clear-cut like
the advertisements suggest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
