<SLUG> BC-LENDING-BLACKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LENDERS SLAMMING LOAN DOORS IN THE FACES OF AFRICAN-AMERICANS,
HISPANICS, GROUP CLAIMS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA YIP 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ African-Americans and Hispanics are still having a
hard time getting approved for home loans in Houston, according to
a national survey released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston between 1995 and 1997, nearly half of all
African-Americans who applied for a home loan were rejected and
more than a third of Hispanic applicants were rejected, according
to the Association of Community Organizations for Reform Now, a
community activist group also known as ACORN.
</P>
<P>
   Those figures are significantly higher than the 30 percent
rejection rate for whites in 1997 for conventional
non-government-backed home loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``With unemployment at a 30-year low and interest rates at their
lowest in decades _ conditions which have historically erased
racial disparity _ these trends are unacceptable,'' Glenda Kizzee,
an ACORN board member in Houston, said Tuesday. ``Instead of being
able to take advantage of these good times to walk into new homes,
African-Americans and Hispanics are having the doors slammed in
their faces by lenders.''
</P>
<P>
   The study surveyed 9,041 lenders in 35 cities to examine the
patterns and prevalence of racial disparity in home mortgage
lending between 1995 and 1997. ACORN officials said they didn't
include statistics on Asians because they tend to have a relatively
easier time of obtaining home loans than other minorities and many
times, even whites.
</P>
<P>
   ACORN and federal housing officials said some Houston lenders
have become complacent and lost the sense of commitment to
increasing homeownership among blacks and Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a definite feeling that because the economy is so
good, banks are taking the easy road and making the easy loans,''
said George Rodriguez, senior community builder at the Houston
office of the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development.
``Why should they care about the little guys when they can make the
big bucks?''
</P>
<P>
   It's particularly hard to get mortgage companies involved
because unlike banks, they don't have to comply with the federal
Community Reinvestment Act or CRA, Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   The CRA is aimed at encouraging banks and thrifts to lend to
residents in low- and moderate-income neighborhoods. The law
requires public disclosure of an evaluation and rating for each
financial institution that undergoes a CRA examination by
regulators.
</P>
<P>
   While some mortgage companies are supportive, ``other mortgage
companies don't seem to be picking up a finger,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Lenders, however, said they haven't lost their commitment to
lending to low- and moderate-income families.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, we've been strong on this front and I'm sure the
commitment will continue,'' said David Byford, spokesman for Chase
Bank of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt that we make more money off of a larger loan,
but we're still focused on that $40,000 home buyer, nonetheless,''
said David Wood, vice president and community development officer
at Bank One, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Other community organizations said while they find lenders still
interested in making home loans to minorities, they can do more.
</P>
<P>
   ``There needs to be a more concerted effort on the part of some
lenders to reach out to minorities in such a way that will be
helpful,'' said Christopher Oliver, assistant director of Sunnyside
Up, which represents the Sunnyside neighborhood in southeast
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, lenders can hold more home-buying fairs where
people can learn about the home-buying process and how to get
financial help in buying a home, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't know how to buy a house,'' Oliver said.
``A lot of people don't know what takes place at closing.''
</P>
<P>
   Housing Opportunities of Houston, a non-profit group that works
with the city and lenders to raise home ownership among low-income
consumers, has been helping lots of people, said David Rosales,
executive director.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do more loans through that program in one month than most
other cities do in a whole year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His organization last week helped its 1,000th family this year
to buy a home through affordable housing programs, and it helped
about 1,100 families last year, Rosales said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure we're going to go over 1,200 this year,'' he said.
``There are no other cities in the country that have those kinds of
numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   ACORN and Rosales said Houston is doing better than the rest of
the nation in helping low-income families buy homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The national picture is pathetic,'' Rosales said.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the increase in lending conventional mortgages to
white borrowers was almost five times as large as it was for
blacks, ACORN said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, lending to Hispanics fell by more than 1
percent, the group said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made some strides in Houston recently, and now (Texas
Sen.) Phil Gramm's attempts to wipe out the Community Reinvestment
Act will threaten all gains we've made,'' Kizzee said.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Neal, Gramm's spokesman, said Gramm isn't out to kill the
CRA when he assumes chairmanship of the Senate Banking Committee
next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a rather stunning misstatement,'' he said of ACORN's
claim. ``He supports CRA. He wants to focus it where it belongs _
on real people who really need loans to buy real things in the
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Gramm wants to rid the CRA process of community activists who
file complaints on banks with regulators, then fall silent when
they're paid by banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the cash appears, the complaints disappear,'' Neal said.
``Sen. Gramm views that as tantamount to extortion.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
