<TEXT>
<P>
   _ Augusta _ The Morris Museum of Art presents ``Spirit of the
North: The Art of Eustace Paul Ziegler,'' a retrospective
exhibition of nearly 100 paintings, drawings, etchings and
illustrative works by one of Alaska's best-known artists. Opening
reception Thursday evening features a slide lecture by curator
Kesler Woodward, art professor at the University of Alaska,
Fairbanks. Through Jan. 31. 706-828-3800.
</P>
<P>
   _ Macon _ The only remaining fully-restored WWII B24J Liberator
bomber and its sister bomber, the B-17 Flying Fortress, will be at
Lowe Aviation at the Macon Airport Friday through Sunday under the
sponsorship of the Museum of Aviation and Comfort Inn in Warner
Robins. Brigadier Gen. Robert L. Scott Jr, 90, will pilot the B-17
on its flight from Augusta to Macon on Friday. Tours of both
aircraft ($7; $3 children) and flights at dawn or dusk (donation to
Collings Foundation, which owns the aircraft) will be offered.
Museum of Aviation: 912-926-6870; Lowe Aviation: 912-788-3491.
</P>
<P>
   _ Perry _ The Ninth Annual Southeastern Showdown Rodeo, the
largest rodeo east of the Mississippi, features 700 participants
from six states competing Friday through Sunday at the Georgia
National Fairgrounds &AMP; Agricenter. 912-987-3247.
</P>
<P>
   _ Madison _ Madison's downtown merchants host the annual Holiday
Open House Friday through Sunday with antebellum costumes, free
carriage rides, holiday food tastings, antiques, arts,
demonstrations and gift-giving ideas. 706-342-1251, Ext. 6.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lumpkin _ Westville Village's annual Fair of 1850 features
fall harvest activities, including syrup making and cotton ginning,
along with the town's daily antebellum-style operations. Wagon
rides, historical displays, bootmaking and pottery demonstrations.
Through Sunday. 1-888-733-1850.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pigeon Forge, Tenn. _ Tonight's free Winterfest Kickoff and
Street Dance, featuring festival food and live entertainment in
Patriot Park, launches the town's annual festival of lights.
Winterfest Trolley Tour of Lights will be offered at 6:30 p.m.
Mondays, Wednesdays and Fridays during November and December ($3
per person; reservations recommended) from the Funtime Trolley
Station. 423-453-6444.
</P>
<P>
   _ McMinnville, Tenn. _ The McMinn County Living Heritage Museum
presents the exhibit ``Reflections on Tennessee: A Photographic
Essay of Tennessee Vistas'' by Nashville photographer David Wright.
Opening Thursday; through Dec. 31. During the same period, the
museum hosts its Eighth Annual Doll Show. 423-745-0329.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nashville _ Ray Stevens debuts his new show at the Acuff
Theatre at Opryland USA. Stevens will showcase his 35-year music
career and his signature novelty songs including ``Ahab the Arab''
and ``Gitarzan'' and Grammy-winning hits such as ``Everything Is
Beautiful.'' Through Dec. 23. 615-889-3960.
</P>
<P>
   _ Asheville _ Grovewood Gallery's second annual ``Ornament for
the Season'' show Friday through Dec. 31 features ornaments created
by gallery artists displayed on live Frasier firs. Also, large
Santa dolls by Bob McAdams of Knobstone Studio; angels dolls,
skiers, snowmen and carolers by Carol Kara; silver mezuzahs by
Authur and Wendy Silver; pieced-wood menorahs by Phillip Anne
Levine; and colorful glass dreidels by Susan Fullenbaum.
828-253-7651.
</P>
<P>
   _ Asheville _ The Southern Highland Craft Guild presents the
fourth annual ``Appalachian Melody'' at the Folk Art Center
Saturday. The event includes Celtic and mountain music played on
traditional instruments such as hammered dulcimer, lap dulcimer,
banjo and guitar as well as a cappella selections and shaped-note
singing. 828-298-7928.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mount Pleasant, S.C. _ The reenactment of the Battle of
Secessionville Saturday and Sunday at Boone Hall Plantation
includes battles both days, living history demonstrations, marching
drills, fashions, period church service and vendors of Civil War
prints and books. 803-795-4039.
</P>
<P>
   _ Charleston, S.C. _ The Charleston Museum celebrates its 225th
birthday with the exhibition ``Queens &AMP; Commoners of Egypt's New
Kingdom'' from the British Museum. Through June 30. 360 Meeting St.
843-722-2996 or online at http://www.charlestonmuseum
</P>
<P>
   .com.
</P>
<P>
   _ Miami _ The Miami Book Fair International Sunday through Nov.
22 offers a week of literary activities culminating in a three-day
outdoor street fair featuring hundreds of the world's most
celebrated authors. 305-237-3258.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cypress Gardens, Fla. _ The tropical theme park's 1998 Mum
Festival features 3 million blooms in a 35-foot cascading waterfall
of mums, 8-foot floral arches, mum-filled gazebos, swan and
heart-shaped topiaries and 20,000 potted mums. 1-800-282-2123.
</P>
<P>
   _ Athens _ The Georgia Museum of Art is the first U.S. museum to
present ``Rembrandt: Treasures From the Rembrandt House,
Amsterdam.'' The exhibition, continuing through Jan. 10, includes
82 etchings and two copperplates that give a thorough
representation of Rembrandt's body of work in printmaking,
1628-1659. 706-542-0487.
</P>
<P>
   _ Montgomery _ The Alabama Shakespeare Festival presents a world
premiere stage adaptation of Lee Smith's 1988 novel ``Fair and
Tender Ladies,'' with script by Eric Schmiedl and music and lyrics
by Nashville songwriters Tommy Goldsmith, Tom House and Karen Pell.
Saturday through Dec. 23. 1-800-841-4273.
</P>
<P>
   _ Memphis _ ``World War II Through Russian Eyes,'' continuing at
the Pyramid through Jan. 31, features more than 500 artifacts never
before seen outside Russia, including personal belongings of Adolf
Hitler and Josef Stalin. 1-800-263-6744.
</P>
