<DOCNO> NYT19981110.0384 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4092 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BO     11-10 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEELY GIVES US SOMETHING TO FEEL GOOD ABOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   First John Glenn, now Cam Neely.
</P>
<P>
   What's next? Jim Lonborg on the mound Opening Day at Fenway?
John Hannah leading the blocking for Robert Edwards? John Havlicek
running the fast break for Rick Pitino?
</P>
<P>
   Neely, the onetime prototype power forward, plans to practice
with the Bruins Wednesday in an ongoing effort to return to the
NHL. He played his last NHL game Feb. 21, 1996, almost three years
ago, and retired with a degenerative hip condition later that year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the long odds, Neely's comeback attempt can only be a
happy development. The Boston sports landscape in recent days has
been scorched by the prospect of Mo Vaughn's departure, the
flame-out of the vapid (dare we say gutless?) Patriots, and the
hideous NBA strike. So now we have a heroic golden oldie, who
retired before his time, attempting to make a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   There is no downside to the Neely comeback attempt. If Cam
returns to practice and finds he no longer has the strength,
energy, or skating ability to play in the NHL, we are no poorer. In
our minds, we've already lost him. And he owes it to himself to
make sure there is no possibility of a return.
</P>
<P>
   But suppose there's something still there. Suppose there's a
little gas left in the tank. Suppose the Camster could still stand
in the slot and bang home power-play passes from Jason Allison and
Sergei Samsonov. What would black-and-gold sweater-clad fans pay to
see that again? The return of Neely would be the Zamboni equivalent
of Larry Bird coming back to make no-look passes to Travis Knight
and Antoine Walker.
</P>
<P>
   Neely is scheduled to practice with the team Wednesday at the
Ristuccia Center in Wilmington, a Boston suburb. He wants to skate
with the fellas for about 10 days to see how he feels.
</P>
<P>
   Neely's return could put second-year coach Pat Burns in an
awkward position. But the belief here is that Neely won't fool
himself if it's obvious he can no longer play at the highest level
of his sport.
</P>
<P>
   Neely played three years with the Vancouver Canucks and 10 with
the Bruins before hanging up the skates because of a hip ailment
that would not go away. He was 31 when he retired. He's 33
Wednesday. When he retired, the Bruins were coached by Steve
Kasper. It was Kasper who made the dumb decision to bench Neely and
Kevin Stevens in January 1996 when the Bruins were losing a game in
Toronto. Neely and Bruins fans never forgave the snub, and Kasper
never recovered from the negative fallout.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Bruins are a mid-level NHL team, starving for attention
in a sports-saturated market. They are having trouble selling
tickets, and Neely no doubt would fill seats and sell hot dogs.
</P>
<P>
   But let's hope this is not a public relations stunt. Let's hope
this is something more than Willie Mays playing in the World Series
for the 1973 Mets or Jim Palmer trying to come back with the
Baltimore Orioles when he was better suited to be pitching for the
Money Store. Let's hope this is not another punch-drunk boxer (fill
in the blank) making a comeback for one last payday.
</P>
<P>
   The Cam-Corder wasn't talking last night. In a statement, he
said, ``I have been encouraged in my workouts so far in that my hip
has been sore after skating but the pain has not lingered. I have
said before that if I make a return to the game, it will be this
season and now is the time to take this next step.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday he'll skate in front of all the cameras and probably
do a dozen standup interviews after the session.
</P>
<P>
   Boston can be a tough town for professional athletes. We've got
maniacal/vigilant fans, nitwit radio voices, competitive TV
anchors, and sportswriters who try to hit as hard as Lawyer Milloy.
But try to find anybody who wishes anything but the best for Cam
Neely in his comeback try. It's the feel-good story of a feel-bad
autumn.
</P>
<P>
   Here's wishing Neely all the best. Long may he skate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
