<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR WEDNESDAY, NOVEMBER 11
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Wednesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-REPUBS-ASSESS-NYT (moved on Saturday, Nov. 7.)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Saturday, Nov. 7,
about Speaker Newt Gingrich misstated the background of a critic,
Dr. James C. Dobson. He holds a doctorate in psychology; he is not
a minister.
</P>
<P>
   BC-ADWEEK-AD-COLUMN-NYT (moved on Monday, Nov. 9.)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Nov. 9,
about a special 20th-anniversary issue of Adweek, misspelled the
surname of the magazine's designer. He is Walter Bernard, not
Berhard. The column also used an erroneous name supplied by the
magazine for the typeface of its nameplate. The face is Anzeigen
Grotesk Bold, not Ankzeiden Grotesque.
</P>
<P>
   BC-MARTHASTEWART-PRETENDERS-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Oct. 28)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Oct.
28, about home improvement experts who are seeking to emulate the
success of Martha Stewart in publishing and on television
misidentified one who plans to start a magazine within a year. She
is Barbara Smith, not Chris Casson Madden.
</P>
