<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-BAPTISTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAPTIST CONSERVATIVES SEVER TIES TO SOUTHERN BAPTIST GENERAL
CONVENTION OF TEXAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICHARD VARA 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ With loud ``Amens!'' and jubiliant applause, Texas
Baptist conservatives Tuesday formed a new state convention
dedicated to missions, evangelism and robust support of the
Southern Baptist Convention.
</P>
<P>
   More than 500 messengers, as delegates are called, from 200
Texas churches formed the Southern Baptists of Texas Convention at
Woodforest Baptist Church in northeast Houston.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, they severed ties to the Baptist General Convention
of Texas, which was celebrating its sesquicentennial annual meeting
at the George R. Brown Convention Center in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The two-day annual meeting, which attracted more than 5,300
messengers, concluded its business Tuesday, including a prayer
session for leaders of the conservative convention.
</P>
<P>
   The formation of the new convention brings to a head nearly two
decades of bitter feuding over biblical and theological issues
between the state's conservatives and moderates. Conservatives
control the 16 million-member national convention but moderates
dominate the state convention, which has 2.7 million members and
more than 5,600 churches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are here because we have chosen to remain Southern
Baptists,'' said the Rev. Ronnie Yarber, the new convention's
administrative director. ``I am a Southern Baptist first and a
Texas Baptist second.''
</P>
<P>
   But across town, an influential Texas moderate leader proposed
yet another Texas-based convention unaffiliated with the SBC.
Herbert Reynolds, retired president of Baylor University and now
the school's chancellor, proposed that Texas Baptists form an
international ``Baptist Convention of the Americas'' that would
avoid ``the destructive influences of the leadership of the
Southern Baptist Convention.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds, a scathing critic of conservatives, proposed that
Texas be the center of a convention extending from Alaska to South
America connecting like-minded state conventions and churches
through modern telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives said Reynolds' proposal supports their charges
that Texas Baptist leaders are moving away from the national
convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``In two years, they will entirely withdraw from the SBC,'' said
the Rev. Rick Scarborough, pastor of First Baptist Church in
Pearland, Texas. ``I hope I am wrong, but that is my prediction.''
</P>
<P>
   Scarborough said he could no longer support the policies of the
state general convention, citing its approval of a new annual
meeting representation policy requiring churches to contribute
funds to state causes if they wanted more than the minimum of two
messengers. Scarborough said that was ``blackmail'' because it
forces conservatives to fund causes they oppose.
</P>
<P>
   The conservatives elected the Rev. Stan Coffey of Amarillo,
Texas, as president and approved an annual budget of more than
$900,000. They pledged that 50 percent of contributions would go to
the national convention. In contrast the state general convention
passed a record $49.7 million budget for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has been the epicenter of much of the bitter
conservative-moderate battle that has embroiled the state and
national denominations. Texas conservative leaders, including Paul
Pressler of Houston, have helped lead the ``conservative
resurgence'' that took control of the national convention beginning
in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Reynolds infuriated state conservatives by leading
Baylor University in Waco, Texas, to declare autonomy from the
state convention. Reynolds feared that conservatives would
eventually take over the state organization and appoint like-minded
trustees for the school, the largest Baptist university in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Dilday, current president of the general convention, was
fired as president of Southwestern Baptist Theological Seminary in
1994 by the school's conservative board. The firing angered some
Texas leaders and started the strained relationship that still
exists with the national convention.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds' proposal for an international convention was
accompanied with sharp criticism for the national convention.
Reynolds said Texas Baptists contribute about $98 million for state
and worldwide causes annually. That figure includes special annual
collections for home and foreign missions and other contributions
that are not tabulated in the state budget. About $43 million is
funneled to the national convention, a contribution he described as
an ``annual tribute'' to ``SBC fundamentalists.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fundamentalists have said and done about everything they
wanted to say or do for 20 years, (so) why should we in Texas give
any credence whatsoever to movements of this sort?'' Reynolds told
a receptive breakfast meeting of Texas Baptists Committed, a
moderate organization.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds blasted a recent conservative amendment to the Baptist
Faith and Message asking wives to ``submit graciously to the
servant leadership of her husband.'' The Baptist Faith and Message
is the denomination statement of beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds said the amendment is ``asinine and ludicrous'' because
it demeans women. Approved last June, the amendment has caused some
churches to leave the national convention. Some professors at
Southwestern Seminary are retiring or resigning rather than sign
the amended statement.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds said he has no time frame for the creation of the
international convention but wants Texas Baptists to curtail or end
the annual contribution to the annual convention within a few
years.
</P>
<P>
   In concluding actions, BGCT messengers approved a resolution
supporting the ``biblical equality'' of men and women. The
resolution, seen as a response to the Baptist Faith and Message
amendment, affirmed ``the freedom and responsibility of women and
men to respond to the call of Christ to serve as they are gifted by
God.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
