<SLUG> BC-INTEL-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEL SEES HIGHER-THAN-EXPECTED PROFITS
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Intel Corp. said Tuesday that its
fourth-quarter results will be above expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Intel said stronger-than-anticipated demand for personal
computers across all market segments and global regions will
increase revenues and profit margins for the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's announcement came after the close of the market, but its
shares had already risen in anticipation of strong PC sales,
together with those of the Dell Computer Corp. Shares of Intel
closed at $97.5625, up $1.5625, while Dell rose $1.3125, to
$70.3125, both in Nasdaq trading.
</P>
<P>
   In after hours trading, Intel rose to $100.25. Intel reported
stronger-than-expected earnings last month, but said then that it
expected fourth-quarter revenue to be up only slightly relative to
the third quarter's $6.7 billion. On Tuesday Intel said it expects
revenue to be up about 8 percent to 10 percent from the third
quarter, and that profit margins would be up a couple of points
from 53 percent in the third quarter. Higher margins reflect both
higher sales, and the mix of products sold during the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Although Intel did not specifically say that earnings would
exceed the consensus estimate, Wall Street analysts said they would
be raising their numbers. Analysts had expected Intel to earn 95
cents a share in the quarter. Intel earned 98 cents a share in the
fourth quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``PC demand is solid; it's seasonally strong, and Intel has been
in an extremely strong position to benefit both from the uptick in
demand and the end of a pretty severe inventory correction,'' said
Mark Edelstone, an analyst with Morgan Stanley. Noting that Intel
had reduced inventories at the end of the last quarter to their
lowest level in a dozen years, he said, ``You have to believe their
factories are running flat out, and that is always good for
margins.'' Intel said it expects expenses in the fourth quarter to
be about 8 percent to 10 percent higher than third-quarter expenses
of $1.4 billion, up from its earlier guidance of 3 to 5 percent
higher. Expenses are dependent in part on the level of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Intel said that it expects to be within a few hundred people of
its previously announced staff reduction goal of approximately
3,000 employees by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   For the third quarter, ended Sept. 26, Intel reported earnings
of $1.56 billion, or 89 cents a diluted share, down slightly from
$1.57 billion, or 88 cents a share. Per share figures reflect an
increase in the number of shares outstanding. Revenues grew 9
percent, to $6.73 billion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
