<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FHS-HEALTHNET-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUNDATION HEALTH REPORTS 52 PERCENT DROP IN PROFITS, KEY
RESIGNATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEN SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On the same day it reported a 52 &UR;  &LR; percent drop in
third-quarter profit, managed care specialist Foundation Health
Systems Inc. said the president and chief executive of its largest
health plan has resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Southam, who headed Foundation's main California HMO,
Health Net, will be replaced by an as-yet-unnamed outside successor
who was tapped for the top spot earlier this month, a company
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Southam, who was widely regarded in Southern California's
managed care community as one of the industry's brightest stars,
was pushed out by Foundation Chief Executive Jay Gellert, sources
familiar with the situation say.
</P>
<P>
   Gellert was also reportedly behind the resignation last month of
Robert Natt, who headed Foundation's Northeast Division. The
California and Northeast markets are Foundation's most lucrative
and are considered key to Foundation's successful recovery from a
yearlong earnings slump.
</P>
<P>
   In a memo sent to Health Net employees, Southam hinted he will
remain involved in the local health-care business. ``I'm sure that
many of us will have the opportunity to work with each other in the
future,'' he told employees.
</P>
<P>
   Southam's ouster is seen as the result of lower-than-anticipated
profit within the Health Net plan. Unlike many Foundation
divisions, the 2.3 &UR;  &LR; million-member HMO is profitable, but not
enough so, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``That ain't good enough,'' Michael LeConey at Security Capital
Trading in New York said of the plan's bottom line. ``You can be
founder of the company or its largest shareholder and still (be
fired).''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Gellert himself replaced Foundation's former CEO and
Health Net founder Malik Hasan in August after the company stumbled
synchronizing the half-dozen or so managed care firms that merged
or were acquired to create Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   With that departure, Southam _ Hasan's successor at Health Net _
saw his political base within Foundation diminish, LeConey said.
</P>
<P>
   Southam's resignation was announced Tuesday along with
Foundation's third-quarter results, which saw profit from
continuing operations drop 52 &UR;  &LR; percent. The company had warned
analysts last week to expect the dismal results.
</P>
<P>
   Pre-charge, Foundation earned $28.7 &UR;  &LR; million, or 24 cents a
share, down from $59.8 &UR;  &LR; million (49 cents) in 1997. Revenue rose
22 &UR;  &LR; percent to $2.2 &UR;  &LR; billion from $1.8 &UR;  &LR; billion a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   All told, Foundation took charges of $117 &UR;  &LR; million this quarter
related to its cost-cutting measures, including $21 &UR;  &LR; million in
severance payments for workers fired at its Pueblo, Colo., service
center; $22 &UR;  &LR; million lost on a real estate deal with the
now-bankrupt FPA Medical Management Inc.; and $37 &UR;  &LR; million in money
lost on Medicare patients or set aside to serve as reserves on some
remaining health plans. The charges gave Foundation a real
third-quarter loss of $88.6 &UR;  &LR; million, or 73 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   ``The results were awful, as advertised,'' said Mary O'Connell,
an analyst at Josephthal &AMP; Co. in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Under Gellert's three-month tutelage, Foundation has sought to
shed unprofitable businesses and to wring more earnings out of
performers like Health Net. The company's shares got a boost last
week after a firm slated to buy Foundation's money-losing workers'
compensation insurance business announced it received financing to
complete the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Foundation shares rose 31.25 cents Tuesday to close at $14.875. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
