</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOONE-REDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Boone learns of trade on golf course
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Bret Boone was on a golf course in Las Vegas when
his cell phone rang.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who is this bothering me?'' he said. ``I'm in the middle of a
career round.''
</P>
<P>
   Career round? An interesting choice of words.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone call was from Cincinnati Reds general manager Jim
Bowden, informing Boone that he was about to make a career move.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden told Boone he was taking his just-won Gold Glove, his 24
home runs and his 95 RBIs to the Atlanta Braves _ traded along with
pitcher Mike Remlinger for left-handed starter Denny Neagle,
outfielder Michael Tucker and right-handed minor-league pitcher Rob
Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Boone was surprised, but not shocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I might not win the Gold Glove this year, but I
didn't think I'd be traded after the season I had,'' Boone said.
``Frankly, good luck to them (the Reds). They're going to need it.
And I know (shortstop) Barry Larkin is going to be mad about
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Larkin is on a promotional tour for Nike and couldn't be
reached, but he was on record as saying he didn't want Boone
traded.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds tried to trade Boone during the off-season the past two
years, including last spring training, but could find no takers.
After his career-best 1998, teams lined up trying to acquire him _
Atanta, Toronto, Pittsburgh, St. Louis, the New York Mets., Tampa
Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to lose Boone, he is a terrific player, a hard worker
and a good person,'' manager Jack McKeon said. ``But it's like
Branch Rickey used to say. . .better to trade them a year too early
than a year too late. Heck, a year ago we couldn't give him away.''
</P>
<P>
   Second base becomes the property of 25-year-old Pokey Reese, a
natural shortstop who played outstandingly at third base last year
before tearing a ligament in his right thumb on July 30, causing
him to miss the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fortunate to have a good young player like Pokey Reese
to play second base,'' McKeon said. ``We were looking to upgrade
our pitching and with Neagle that gives us a better chance to win.
And Tucker gives us depth in the outfield. The name of the game for
us right now is getting better and that's what this trade does for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Reese is home in Columbia, S.C, continuing rehabilitation on his
thumb, but said he'll be full-go for spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows I like shortstop best, but that belongs to
Barry,'' Reese said. ``I liked playing third-base last year, too.
But you know what position I like best? The one that gets me in the
lineup every day and that, right now, is second base. I'm ready for
it.
</P>
<P>
   Hal McCoy writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
