u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-VAUGHN-BOS     11-10 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-VAUGHN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME SEE `HOMETOWN DISCOUNT' IN SOX' OFFER TO VAUGHN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAPLES, Fla. _ On the one hand, the Red Sox have offered Mo
Vaughn more money ($60 million) for more years (five) than they
ever have, a deal eclipsed in club history only by the six-year,
$75 million contract they gave pitcher Pedro Martinez last
December.
</P>
<P>
   On the other, the proposal is one year and $12 million less than
the guaranteed six-year, $72 million deal offered by the Anaheim
Angels, who remain the only other club at this time to have an
offer on the table for the free agent first baseman. And a party
familiar with the Anaheim strategy said Tuesday that the Angels may
increase their offer, if they feel it will expedite Vaughn's
signing.
</P>
<P>
   This is the risk the Red Sox ran by inviting Vaughn's agents to
shop around for other offers before Boston weighed in. Had they
made their bid at the All-Star break, for example, or before their
exclusive bargaining window with Vaughn expired last Thursday
night, the Sox' offer might have been better received.
</P>
<P>
   But now, there is sentiment in Vaughn's camp that the Sox'
proposal was obsolete before it was proffered. To those subscribing
to that view, it smacks of another attempt at inducing Vaughn to
accept a ``hometown discount'' _ especially one of that size _ when
the Red Sox forfeited their right to ask for one by allowing him to
become a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Those taking a dim view of the Sox' offer say that they offered
just enough to convince their fans that they made a sincere
attempt, and that in the end, the Sox will say Vaughn's decision
came down to dollars _ in essence, making him the heavy, just as
they did with Roger Clemens two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In support of that position, they say, the Red Sox can be
expected to roll out Vaughn's own words that he would be willing to
take less money if the Sox gave him a five-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   That dismissive attitude is not being disseminated by Vaughn's
agents, at least not yet. They have been very circumspect about the
Sox' proposal, going so far as to describe talks with the team as
``business as usual.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, meanwhile, did not answer calls to his home, but it is
believed that his initial reaction to the Sox' proposal was shock
and disappointment. Beyond the financial terms, the Sox apparently
did not include the type of no-trade provisions Vaughn was seeking.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette said Tuesday that he had
one conversation with Vaughn's agent, Tom Reich. ``We still hope
our offer leads to a deal,'' said Duquette, who would not say
whether he has set a deadline for Vaughn to accept or reject the
team's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Duquette said he expected to know by Thursday, when
the GM returns to Boston, whether Vaughn would stay with the Red
Sox.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have not said how long their offer will remain on the
table, though club sources said the team will not wait
indefinitely. Vaughn was impressed by a letter from the Angels that
expressed how much they wanted him.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette has said the Sox are ``well-positioned'' to pursue
other players in the event Vaughn rejects their proposal. He said
he had conversations Tuesday with agents for several free agents,
as well as with a few clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Boras, the agent for free agent center fielder Bernie
Williams, has said the Red Sox requested to meet with Williams, an
indication that he could become Boston's prime focus if Vaughn goes
elsewhere. Arn Tellem, agent for free agent Albert Belle, also has
spoken with the Red Sox, as has Johnny Boggs, agent for Gold Glove
third baseman Robin Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   Why would the Red Sox, who already have John Valentin at third
base, be interested in Ventura? Because Ventura is a lefthanded bat
with power who might be open to moving to first base. It's also
possible, though unlikely, that the Red Sox could ask Valentin to
move back to second if Jeff Frye is not fully recovered from knee
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want John Valentin to suddenly have a coronary _ `I'm
being moved to another position,''' said Boggs, saying that Sox
assistant GM Mike Port did not discuss possible lineup
permutations.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to call this a preliminary discussion. I think the
Sox are just covering their bases if Vaughn leaves. We may be one
of 10 players they're looking at. But Robin is the type of player
who if he sees his club has a chance to win, he'll do whatever it
takes.''
</P>
<P>
   The names of sluggers such as San Diego left fielder Greg Vaughn
and Los Angeles right fielder Gary Sheffield have surfaced as
players who could be available in a trade.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, among other teams, met Tuesday with the Pittsburgh
Pirates and are believed to have inquired about lefthanded reliever
Ricardo Rincon and righthanded starter Francisco Cordova. Another
pitching possibility is free agent righthander Armando Reynoso, who
has had major arm trouble but was 7-3 with a 3.82 ERA for the Mets
last season. Reynoso's agent, Oscar Suarez, said he has been in
contact with the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox have said they are seeking a No. 2 starter. They are not
in the bidding for top-echelon free agents Randy Johnson and Kevin
Brown, nor have they inquired about righthander Todd Stottlemyre,
according to that pitcher's agent, Tony Attanasio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
