<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: N.Y. AIRPORTS EMBRACE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  (duplication notice: also sent with `t' code) 
 (bl)  
 By JANE L. LEVERE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Access to the World Wide Web is increasing at New
York area airports, as the Port Authority of New York and New
Jersey installs Internet kiosks at La Guardia and Newark
International Airports, and Host Marriott Services experiments with
similar computing equipment at several of its airport food outlets.
</P>
<P>
   According to Carl Selinger, manager of business development for
the aviation department of the Port Authority, there are currently
14 Internet kiosks at Newark, in Terminal C and in the gate areas
of United Airlines and American Airlines in Terminal A; 20 more
will be installed throughout the airport by Jan. 1. At La Guardia,
there are now 17 Internet units, at American's and United's gates
and near the food court in the central terminal, and also in the
Delta Air Lines shuttle terminal. The Internet equipment is being
provided by Atcominfo; Get2Net, a subsidiary of Great Universal,
and Internet Free for All, a unit of Facilities Communications
International Ltd.; Quick ATM also operates some equipment in
Newark.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Internet kiosks are operating on a trial basis,
temporarily offering users free access to the Web. Selinger said
the providers were determining rates for the service, which he
expects to be about $3.50 for 10 minutes' use.
</P>
<P>
   The Port Authority's long-term goal is to have 100 Internet
kiosks functioning at Newark and La Guardia, as well as Kennedy
International Airport, by next April.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, for the last month Host Marriott Services has been
conducting its own trial of Get2Net's Cyberflyer Internet equipment
at its cocktail lounges at Newark and La Guardia, and at CK's
Restaurant in the Delta terminal at La Guardia. Use of these
computers is now free, though Stan Novack, Host Marriott's vice
president for concept development, said Get2Net would soon start
charging. So far, travelers have used the machines mostly to read
their e-mail, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Early in 1999, Host Marriott plans to open a Cyberflyer Club, an
Internet-themed restaurant containing approximately 10 Cyberflyer
units, at Lambert International Airport in St. Louis. Novack said
it was possible Host Marriott would later open similar restaurants
at Kennedy and San Jose International Airport in California.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
