<HEADER>
A4121 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-REDS-TRADE-COX     11-10 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-TRADE-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Boone, Remlinger traded to Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   By Hal McCoy
</P>
<P>
   Dayton Daily News
</P>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The Cincinnati Reds publicity department needs to
come up with another coverboy for its 1999 media guide.
</P>
<P>
   They planned to put second baseman Bret Boone on the cover, but
it wouldn't look good if the Reds had Atlanta's second baseman
there.
</P>
<P>
   Boone, the subject of several trade discussions since the season
ended, was part of a five-player trade Tuesday the Reds made with
the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Boone and left-handed pitcher Mike Remlinger were sent to the
Braves for left-handed pitcher Denny Neagle, outfielder Michael
Tucker and minor-league right-handed pitcher Rob Bell.
</P>
<P>
   The trade fills one need for the Reds . . . starting pitcher
Neagle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small-market teams can't survive without good starting
pitchers,'' general manager Jim Bowden said after making the trade
in Naples, Fla., during the general managers meetings. ``We can't
afford a big bat and we can't afford free-agent pitchers, so a
trade is the only way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden said a few days ago he didn't want to trade Boone and
break up one of baseball's best double-play combinations _ Boone
and shortstop Barry Larkin. But he also said he would do it to get
a pitcher who can win 15 to 20 games.
</P>
<P>
   Neagle, 30, has won 16 or more games the past three seasons,
including a 20-6 year in 1997 for the Braves. He was 16-11 last
year.
</P>
<P>
   He is 81-55 with a 3.78 earned run average for his career and
had five complete games last season, one less than the entire Reds'
staff, and three shutouts last season, the same as the entire Reds'
staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to the trade was Neagle,'' Bowden said. ``With him,
Pete Harnisch and Brett Tomko, we now have three pitchers who can
win between 15 to 20 games and that gives us a starting rotation
comparable to any team in our division _ including if the Astros
re-sign Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``In addition, Neagle has great make-up and a solid clubhouse
presence so that he can help our younger pitchers,'' Bowden said.
</P>
<P>
   While he was reluctant to trade Boone, Bowden said his staff,
including manager Jack McKeon and Boone's father, Reds special
adviser Bob Boone, agreed it was a solid baseball trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know for whom this trade was more painful, me or Bob
Boone,'' Bowden said. ``But I told Bret he is going to one of the
finest organizations in baseball and has a chance to be in the
playoffs right away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bret Boone is one of my favorite players and one of my
favorite people,'' Bowden said. ``But my staff is right . . . this
is a good baseball trade.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds also are seeking a center fielder, but Tucker is not
that man, even though Bob Boone believes he can play center field.
Bowden said Tucker, 27, was acquired to add a left-handed bat.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden has tried to trade for Tucker several times in the past
few years and publicity director Rob Butcher said, ``It seems like
I've typed up press releases about eight times when we came close
to trading for him, but the others always fell through.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds had an offer on the table to the Kansas City Royals in
the spring of 1997, but the Royals accepted an offer from the
Braves for Tucker, ruining Bowden's day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no speed in our lineup last year and not enough
left-handed bats,'' Bowden said. ``Tucker gives us both. During the
playoffs this year it looked as if Tucker was finally making the
adjustments he needs to make that he hasn't made in the past that
kept him from reaching his potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Tucker hit .244 with three homers and 46 RBI last season, a drop
from his 1997 season when he hit .283 with 14 homers and 56 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't get Tucker to play center field,'' Bowden said. ``He
goes into the outfield mix with Jeffrey Hammonds, Reggie Sanders
and Dmitri Young, unless we can make another trade.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden is trying diligently to trade Sanders and is working hard
trying to make a deal for Anaheim center fielder Jim Edmonds.
</P>
<P>
   The third player coming to the Reds, 21-year-old right-hander
Bell, was 14-7 with a 3.68 earned run average at Class A Macon, but
slipped to 7-9 in 28 starts at Class A Danville last year. But he
was rated the best right-hander in the Carolina League last year
after striking out 197 in 178.1 innings and walking only 46.
</P>
<P>
   ``We consider him a John Smoltz/Darryl Kile type pitcher,''
Bowden said. ``He is 6-4, about 220 with a Kile-type curve and an
average change-up. He's another guy who down the road can win 15 to
20 games for us.
</P>
<P>
   Hal McCoy writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
