<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHARES OF INTEL HIT NEW HIGH ON STRONG PROFIT ESTIMATES
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Intel rose $1.5625, to $97.5625, andclimbed to $100.25
in after-hours trading after the semiconductor maker said that
fourth-quarter results would be above analysts' expectations. Intel
said stronger-than-expected demand for personal computers across
all market segments and geographies would increase revenue and
profit for the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   PRESIDENT WARNS AGAINST DUMPING
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said the United States would not tolerate the
``flooding of our markets'' with low-cost goods from Asia and
Russia, particularly steel, that are threatening the jobs of
American workers. The President's statement came days after a White
House meeting of top executives of steel companies and the United
Steelworkers of America, which helped get out the vote for
Democrats last week.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS DECLINE FOR A SECOND DAY
</P>
<P>
   Stocks slipped as sellers emerged late in the day to push prices
down for a second consecutive session. Traders and analysts cited a
variety of reasons for the selloff, including concern about a
slowdown in the growth of corporate earnings and doubts that the
Federal Reserve's policy-making committee will cut interest rates
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint Capital sold $5 billion of bonds in the second-biggest
corporate sale ever.
</P>
<P>
   News Corp. raised $2.8 billion with the sale of 124.8 million
shares of Fox Entertainment Group. It was the third-largest initial
public offering ever.
</P>
<P>
   OLD E-MAIL HAS BECOME A LIABILITY
</P>
<P>
   Companies are learning from the antitrust lawsuit against
Microsoft that old e-mail can be a mine field of legal liability,
not to mention a source of public embarrassment. So now companies
are imposing new restrictions on e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Higgins, vice president of the Interactive Media Group at
Microsoft since late 1996, is taking a leave from the company and
is expected to return to a different job next year. He had recently
headed Microsoft's effort to make the company a dominant player in
new media, but that move has had disappointing financial results.
</P>
<P>
   NEWSWEEK NAMES WHITAKER EDITOR
</P>
<P>
   As expected, Mark Whitaker was named editor of Newsweek. He
succeeds Maynard Parker, who died last month. Whitaker joined the
news magazine in 1977 as an intern and oversaw its technology and
business coverage before becoming managing editor. Newsweek
attracted attention this year for its coverage of the Monica
Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   LONG-TERM CAPITAL EARNED A PROFIT
</P>
<P>
   Helped by a sharp rebound in bond markets worldwide, Long-Term
Capital earned a small paper profit for the banks and brokerage
firms that saved it from bankruptcy in six weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTIVITY OF WORKERS RISES
</P>
<P>
   The productivity of American workers rose at a 2.3 percent
annual rate in the third quarter, offsetting higher labor costs and
giving Federal Reserve policy makers room to cut interest rates if
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   BANANAS AT ISSUE IN TRADE RIFT
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton Administration threatened to impose 100 percent
tariffs on wine, cheese and other European imports if the European
Union did not lift its trade curbs on bananas sold by American
companies.
</P>
<P>
   BRISTOL-MYERS NAMES NEW OFFICIALS
</P>
<P>
   Bristol-Myers Squibb, long known for its well-mannered culture,
announced a series of executive assignments that analysts say may
soon set off a battle royal for the company's top office.
</P>
<P>
   BOND MARKET CLOSED; OTHERS OPEN
</P>
<P>
   Government offices, most banks and the Treasury bond market will
be closed Wednesday in observance of Veterans Day. But stock and
commodity markets will be open.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
