A4125 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-HMO-RATINGS-COX     11-10 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-HMO-RATINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Customers rate local HMOs as 'good' in state survey
 &HT;    By John Murawski and Shirish Date
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ A state consumer survey of 22 health
maintenance organizations released Tuesday showed that most were
rated good overall, but none were rated excellent or poor.
</P>
<P>
   The Agency for Health Care Administration's ``Florida Health
Plan Checkup'' showed that 13 HMOs serving Palm Beach County and
the Treasure Coast were all rated ``good'' by their customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have built a healthy managed care industry. It is not
perfect, but it is good,'' said Doug Cook, secretary of the Agency
for Health Care Administration, at a press conference in
Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   The 13 HMOs serving Palm Beach County and the Treasure Coast
received scores ranging from 63 to 71 on a scale where 61 to 80 is
good. Customers were asked to rate their HMO as poor, fair, good or
excellent. The composite scores represent an average of customer
responses. The scores represent customers' answers to about two
dozen questions concerning access to doctors, ease of referrals to
specialists and paperwork hassles.
</P>
<P>
   The agency asked HMOs to submit names of their customers in each
of 11 state regulatory districts where they do business. The
customers had to be in the HMO at least six months. State
regulators didn't include HMOs that produced fewer than 85 complete
survey responses.
</P>
<P>
   The health-care agency said that 12 HMOs serving the regulatory
district of Palm Beach, Martin, St. Lucie, Indian River and
Okeechobee counties were not included in the survey because they
were either too small, too new to the district or unwilling to
submit names of their customers.
</P>
<P>
   Cook said some of those who would not participate declined to do
so for fear of a low rating.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Florida, which offers the Health
Options HMO in Palm Beach and Martin counties, was one of the HMOs
that didn't participate. The company said it was a waste of
taxpayers' money to rate HMOs that have been accredited and
licensed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe this project is duplicative and places an
unnecessary burden on taxpayers,'' said Blue Cross spokesman James
Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   But two HMOs listed as nonparticipating said they were surprised
to learn they were not included in Tuesday's announcement.
Neighborhood Health Partnership, in Miami, and Well Care HMO, in
Tampa, both said they had submitted their customers' names for the
survey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to look as though we didn't want to participate,''
said Nancy Gareu, vice president for operations at Well Care HMO.
``It's disheartening.''
</P>
<P>
   An agency spokesman said Well Care had submitted incomplete
information and did not know Tuesday why Neighborhood Health
Partnership was excluded.
</P>
<P>
   Of the state's 37 commercial HMOs, 22 were included in the
study.
</P>
<P>
   The highest overall score in the state was 77 for Florida 1st
Health Plan, which serves the Fort Myers region, and the lowest
overall score was 56 for Foundation Health in the Tampa region.
More6 than 20,000 Floridians were surveyed by phone from January
through March.
</P>
<P>
   John Murawski and Shirish Date write for the Palm Beach Post,
West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
