<DOCNO> NYT19981110.0410 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4127 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FINS-COX     11-10 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FINS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pass inference catching flak
 &HT;    By Tom D'Angelo
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ The most scrutinized 338 words in the NFL rule
book this season can be found under the heading PASS INTERFERENCE,
section 4, sub-paragraphs (a)-(f).
</P>
<P>
   And many coaches and players, Miami's Jimmy Johnson among them,
must be wondering if the officials have bothered to read the fine
print.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I see the flag down I have no idea which way they are
going to call it,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Pass interference and defensive holding in the secondary have
become one of the hottest topics in the NFL. Although the league is
down playing the controversy, they did their best to thrust it into
the spotlight three weeks ago by making public their views on two
calls that effected the outcome of the 49ers-Colts game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the toughest judgment call you have and it's a call
that's right up front,'' said Jerry Seeman, the NFL's director of
officiating.
</P>
<P>
   The league made the unprecedented decision to publicize its
findings that officials blew two calls that aided San Francisco's
34-31 victory over the Colts last month. Never before has the
league publicly apologized to a team for taking away a victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a one-time thing,'' said Seeman, who would not
elaborate on the reason why findings were announced.
</P>
<P>
   Both calls were defensive holding and negated interceptions by
the Colts. Both times the 49ers scored while rallying from a 21-3
deficit.
</P>
<P>
   The league also decided not to fine Colts coach Jim Mora for his
post game outburst.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're giving everything they can to the offense and I think
they're really making it tough to play pass defense in this
league,'' Mora said.
</P>
<P>
   Mora will get no argument from Dolphins cornerback Terrell
Buckley, who is a victim of at least one pass interference almost
every week.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley is shorter (5-foot-9) than most receivers and relies on
a gambling, aggressive style. He was flagged three times in the
Rams and Patriots games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very tough to cover these guys,'' he said. ``When I
first came into the league, they let certain guys get way with
things. Today you have to be intelligent, really study tape, study
formations, know the other guy, know your defense, know when you
can do something and when you can't do something and know the
situation of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Seeman insists neither the rule nor the interpretation
has changed, he said the league emphasized the passing game during
their meetings with the competition committee last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure everyone fully understands what pass
interference is, that is must restrict, it is visually evident, it
must impede. And there must be an effect,'' Seeman said. ``Because
of the difficulty of the call we wanted to make sure (the
officials) continue to work to be in position to make the call.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, although defensive pass interference calls declined
the first six weeks of the season as compared to a year ago
according to Seeman, illegal contact, defensive holding and
offensive pass interference calls increased. An indication that
officials are looking closer at the call whether that was the
intention or not.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is upset by the inconsistency of the call. During
Sunday's victory against the Colts, the Dolphins benefited by a
penalty against Jason Belser, who was called for defensive
interference on a pass to Oronde Gadsden, but were the victims
three plays later when Gadsden was flagged for offensive pass
interference, negating a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Gadsden said neither was a penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had half dozen close calls that could have gone either way
or could have been non calls,'' said Johnson, who spoke with Seeman
before Sunday's game about his concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Mora believes the officials are reacting to a league preference
for more scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The emphasis is to score points,'' Mora said. ``That's what
people like to see, and I think they're going to do things to
encourage that and hurt the defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeman said his staff, which includes six assistants, spends 5
1/2 hours reviewing each game and every call. Officials are graded
and notified if an abundance of mistakes are spotted. Seeman has
not seen an increase in bad calls related to passing plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe they are saying, ``We're going to emphasize it more
this year,''' Buckley said. ``And if your boss tells you to
concentrate on one area over another you do it. As players we
always have to adjust, not worry about it and play the way we know
how to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom D'Angelo writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
