<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-FULL-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 11/10/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) NEW YORK -- Nov. 10, 1998 --BBO-SOSA-BAT, 11-10 -- Mayor
Rudolph W. Giuliani held the bat Tuesday that he says Sammy Sosa
told him he used to hit his 66th, and last, home run of the season.
The Hall of Fame says it has the bat. (Marilynn K. Yee/New York
Times Photo)*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- Nov. 10, 1998 --HURRICANE-RELIEF, 11-10
--Fernando Mateo, left, head of a Dominican taxi drivers group,
joined Zachary Fisher, who helped organize Hurricane Georges
relief, at the Intrepid Sea-Air-Space Museum to announce Hurricane
Mitch relief efforts. Building on their success organizing relief
efforts for victims of Hurricane Georges on the island of
Hispaniola, a group of Dominican taxi drivers are now working to
aid people in Central America whose lives were uprooted by
Hurricane Mitch. (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- Nov. 10, 1998 -- NEWSWEEK-EDITOR, 11-10 --
Newsweek's new management team, from left, Ann McDaniel, Mark
Whitaker and Jon Meachaum. Whitaker, 41, who began his career at
Newsweek as a college intern in 1977 and went on to expand the
magazine's technology and business coverage and then oversee the
pyrotechnics of the Monica Lewinsky story, has been named editor of
the magazine. (Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 10, 1998 -- ALTERNATIVE-MEDICINE,
11-10 -- As more Americans turn to herbal remedies, chiropractors
and massage therapists, spending at least $27 billion a year on
those and other forms of alternative health care, the medical
profession is scrambling to catch up to the trend. Dr. George
Lundberg, editor of the American Medical Association's main journal
spoke on Tuesday in Washington. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 10, 1998 -- WILLIAMS-DC-MAYOR, 11-10
-- New parking meters near the Washington Monument are among the
signs that the District of Columbia has begun to treat its urban
ills. In small ways and large, the nation's capital is on the mend.
A near decade of financial chaos, rising crime rates and spiritual
malaise has given way to balanced budgets, business expansion,
safer streets and the possibility of true reform in the city
government. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- Nov. 10, 1998 -- NY-MET-APPOINT, 11-10 --
From right, James Houghton, Philippe De Montebello and David
McKinney. Houghton has been named chairman of the Metropolitan
Museum of Art. The museum also announced McKinney's appointment as
the next president of the Met. De Montebello, who has been the
museum's director for 21 years, has been named to the new position
of chief executive officer, putting him in charge of all museum
operations. (Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- Nov. 10, 1998 -- WATER-THEATER-REVIEW, 11-10
-- From left, Seana Kofoed, J. Smith-Cameron and Suzanne Bertish as
sisters in ``The Memory of Water,'' the new play by Shelagh
Stephenson at the Manhattan Theater Club. This story of sibling
resentment and filial ambivalence, set in a seaside town in North
Yorkshire, considers the notion that what we remember from our
pasts is as much invention as fact. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) LHASA, Tibet -- Nov. 10, 1998 -- CHINA-TIBET-3, 11-10 --
Tibetan pilgrims visit Ganden Monastery, outside Lhasa, where
private donations have rebuilt several chapels that were demolished
by the Chinese. Tibetans have preserved a remarkably intense form
of religious devotion despite decades of persecution by the
Chinese. The tiny nation is now in the next stage of a grindingly
long battle between Tibetan tradition and Chinese modernity. (Seth
Faison/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 10, 1998 -- EMAIL-EVIDENCE, 11-10 --
Never mind monopoly power in the marketplace; in the Microsoft
antitrust trial, E-mail has emerged as the star witness - a fact
that appears to be giving pause to corporate executives accustomed
to clicking ``send'' without a second thought. (Justin Lane/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Nov. 10, 1998 -- NIGERIANS-MAIL-SCAM, 11-10
-- Postal inspectors have seized mail from Nigeria offering bogus
business deals at New York's John F. Kennedy Airport. The letters,
often referred to as ``419'' letters after the Nigerian statue that
makes them illegal, were found to have counterfeit Nigerian
postage, and promoted fraudulent business proposals. (Marilynn K.
Yee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) JONESBORO, Ga. -- Nov. 10, 1998 -- VETERAN-COX, 11-10 --
This year marks the 80th anniversary of ``Armistice Day'' - the day
World War I ended on Nov. 11, 1918. For years, speeches and large,
military-style parades highlighted the day around the country.
Those practices continued in the years following World War II, when
the holiday was renamed ``Veteran's Day.'' James Lindsey, 102,
served in France on an artillery crew and then became a medic
during World War I. (Alicia Hansen/Atlanta Journal-Constitution
Photo)*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON, -- Nov. 10, 1998 -- CLINTON-IMPEACH, 11-10
-- President Clinton greeting members of the audience after
addressing a town hall meeting of the President's Export Council at
the Ronald Reagan Building and International Trade Center in
Washington. After their election debacle and growing public fatigue
over the inquiry against Clinton, House Republicans are still
feuding about the impeachment end game. (Stephen Crowley/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) LHASA, Tibet -- Nov. 10, 1998 -- CHINA-TIBET-3, 11-10 --
- Two monks descending stairs at Drepung Monastery, once the
largest monastery in the world, now under tighter control by
Chinese authorities. Tibetans have preserved a remarkably intense
form of religious devotion despite decades of persecution by the
Chinese. The tiny nation is now in the next stage of a grindingly
long battle between Tibetan tradition and Chinese modernity. (Seth
Faison/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) LHASA, Tibet -- Nov. 10, 1998 -- CHINA-TIBET-2, 11-10 --
Two women embrace on a road in Lhasa, Tibet. Tibetans have
preserved a remarkably intense form of religious devotion despite
decades of persecution by the Chinese. The tiny nation is now in
the next stage of a grindingly long battle between Tibetan
tradition and Chinese modernity. (Seth Faison/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) LHASA, Tibet -- Nov. 10, 1998 -- CHINA-TIBET, 11-10 --
Tibetan pilgrims light candles of yak butter inside the Jokhang
Temple in Lhasa, Tibet. Tibetans have preserved a remarkably
intense form of religious devotion despite decades of persecution
by the Chinese. The tiny nation is now in the next stage of a
grindingly long battle between Tibetan tradition and Chinese
modernity. (Seth Faison/New York Times Photo)*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) BOSTON -- Nov. 10, 1998 -- SPORTS-MONEY-BOS, 11-10 --
Sports lawyer Lyman Bullard Jr., 43, has been involved in some of
the largest sports financing deals of the decade and, by all
evidence, he is one of the top sports lawyers in the country. Since
June 1991, Bullard has been a counsel in establishing a total of
$1.01 billion in lines of credit for sports enterprises. (Mark
Wilson/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) JOHANNESBURG, South Africa -- Nov. 10, 1998 --
SAFRICA-TRUTH-BOS-B&AMP;W, 11-10 -- This scene, captured in
Johannesburg four years before the first all-race elections,
depicts the gulf between South African blacks and whites that the
Truth and Reconciliation Commision hopes to bridge. (Tom
Rathe/Boston Graphic Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 10, 1998 -- CONGRESS-LEADERS-2, 11-10
-- Rep. Jennifer Dunn, left, running for House majority leader,
confers with Rep. Richard ``Doc'' Hastings, right, and his staff
aide, Ed Cassidy, on Tuesday in Dunn's Washington office. Turmoil
intensified Tuesday in the House contest for the No. 2 leadership
position, as Rep. Dick Armey seemed unable to cement the support
needed to stave off his challengers. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 10, 1998 -- CONGRESS-LEADERS, 11-10
-- Rep. Steve Largent (R-Okla), center, works the phones in his
Washington office as the race for House majority leader heated up.
Working the phones with Largent is Terry Allen, left, and Craig
Richardson, right. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 10, 1998 -- DALAI-LAMA, 11-10 -- The
Dalai Lama talks to reporters after meeting with President Clinton
at the White House. The Dalai Lama, Tibet's exiled leader, is in
Washington this week seeking support for his efforts to persuade
Chinese leaders to allow more self-rule for Tibet, even if it is
under Chinese sovereignity. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- Nov. 10, 1998 -- WINETALK-B&AMP;W, 11-10 --
American winemakers can put a place on their wines, like the Rogue
Valley in Oregon and the Russian River and Guenoc Valleys in
California, if a certain percentage of grapes pressed to make the
wine are from those places. But their counterparts in France must
follow stricter rules that are closely enforced. (Naum Kazhdan/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- Nov. 10, 1998 -- HOLIDAY-GUIDES, 11-10 --
Bittersweet Pastries of Orangeburg, N.Y. off the bourbon pecan
tart, left, for $32.95, and a classic chocolate truffle cake that
goes for $36.95. Both can be ordered from the company through mail
order. (Boyd Hagen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- Nov. 10, 1998 -- MIR-STATION, 11-10 -- The
Russian space agency proposes changing the orbit of the future
international space station to match the orbit of Mir. The stated
reason is to transfer elements from Mir to the station, but some
Russian nationalist leaders are also arguing that Mir should be
kept alive as Russia's own symbol in space. (NASA/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Nov. 10, 1998 -- SPINNY-BIGBIRD-PROFILE,
11-10 -- Caroll Spinney, the 64 year old puppeteer who has played
Big Bird on Sesame Street for over 25 years, has had his down
moments: There was the time his first wife left him and one day, on
set, he found himself sobbing inside his 8 foot bird costume. But
that was a long time ago and now he is a happy old bird. (Librado
Romero/New York Times Photo)*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Nov. 10, 1998 -- TOM-WOLFE-PROFILE, 11-10 --
Tom Wolfe's new book, ``A Man in Full,'' set in contemporary
Georgia, presents an opportunity for looking beneath the writer's
familiar urban dandy exterior. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) ROCHESTER, N.Y. -- Nov. 10, 1998 -- FAGAN-DANCE-PROFILE,
11-10 -- Garth Fagan, foreground, in Rochester at a rehearsal of
``Two Pieces of One: Green,'' which is having its premiere in New
York this week. After he finished choreographing ``The Lion King,''
won his Tony Award and returned home to Rochester, Fagan was
relieved to be back with his beloved dance company. (Phil Matt/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) ABOARD USS ENTERPRISE -- Nov. 10, 1998 --IRAQ-US, 11-10
-- An F-14B is ready to launch from the aircraft carrier USS
Enterprise earlier this week. The carrier left its home port of
Norfolk, Va., last Friday for a tour of duty that will take it to
the Persian Gulf. The choices confronting President Clinton as he
ponders attacking Iraq are stark, according to American military
and intelligence officials: punishment, coercion, or control. (Mate
2nd Class Michael W. Pendergrass/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Nov. 10, 1998 -- SUB-ZAGAT-GUIDES, 11-10 --
Tim and Nina Zagat, owners and editors of the Zagat Survey of
restaurants, talk with employees in their office near New York's
Columbus Circle. Twenty years ago this week, Tim Zagat published
the first of his populist restaurant guides and changed the way
Americans assess restaurants. (Marty Katz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BIGGS, Calif. -- Nov. 10, 1998 -- CALIF-RICE, 11-10 --
Harbhajan Singh Toor, in foreground, Sansar Singh Sihota, left, and
Sarwan Singh examine Basmati rice growing at the Rice Experiment
Station in Biggs. A fascination with the cuisines of Asia and the
Middle East has put the spotlight on exotic rices like Indian
Basmati, promting California's rice breeders and farmers to jump
into farming this type of rice. (Terrence McCarthy/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
