<SLUG> BC-BKC-WILNER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SCOOP ON COLLEGE HOOP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Say what you will about the sleazy street agents
and summer coaches who control recruiting. Complain all you want
about the NBA exodus, mediocre talent, megalomaniacal coaches and
exorbitant shoe deals.
</P>
<P>
   At least the NCAA season started on time.
</P>
<P>
   This year's defining characteristics _ both from area and
national perspectives _ are the return of parity and the quality
depth in the Pacific-10 Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The dominant teams of recent years (North Carolina, Kentucky and
Arizona) have rejoined the pack, leaving a slew of pretenders in
their exhaust. Duke, Temple, Stanford, Maryland, Connecticut and
Michigan State are supposedly the new wrecking crew. Combined,
they've played in one Final Four in the last four years.
</P>
<P>
   Around here, Lorenzo Romar's building a West Coast Conference
power at Pepperdine while Bobby Braswell welcomes the enigmatic
Rico Harris to Cal State Northridge. USC coach Henry Bibby and
UCLA's Steve Lavin are preparing 20 freshmen and sophomores for the
most talented Pac-10 ever.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking ACC-caliber competition, with elite teams and a
sturdy mid-section _ a mid-section that includes UCLA and Arizona.
When the big guns are fighting for fourth place, you've arrived.
</P>
<P>
   So here we go _ five months, hundreds of teams and thousands of
games in 800 words:
</P>
<P>
   Final Four: Duke, Connecticut, Maryland and Temple.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils have the best combination of athletes, size and
depth, including powerful, gifted sophomore Elton Brand, who's more
polished than Karl Malone was at Louisiana Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut has the nation's best scorer, wing guard Richard
``Rip'' Hamilton, himself a reincarnation of Ray Allen, although
bigger. Maryland has the nation's best junior college transfer,
guard Steve Francis. And Temple finally has the offense (Rasheed
Brokenborough and fabulous freshman Mark Karcher) to match coach
John Chaney's confounding zone defense.
</P>
<P>
   Five to thrive: Brand, Hamilton, Utah guard Andre Miller,
Michigan State guard Mateen Cleaves and Duke guard Trajan Langdon.
Next best: New Mexico forward Kenny Thomas, South Carolina guard
B.J. McKie, Kentucky forward Scott Padgett, Texas Christian forward
Lee Nailon and Miami (Ohio) forward Wally Szczerbiak.
</P>
<P>
   Conspicuous by their absence: Seven-footers. Brand is 6-8 and an
NBA power forward. Thomas, Nailon and Padgett are more adept from
12 feet than five feet. It's a wing man's game.
</P>
<P>
   Rising stars: Indiana forward Luke Recker, Tennessee guard Tony
Harris, Georgia forward Jumaine Jones, Wake Forest guard Robert
O'Kelley and Ohio State guard Michael Redd.
</P>
<P>
   Recker is Indiana's best player since Calbert Cheaney and will
lead a Hoosier revival. Bobby Knight finally has talented players
who actually like him.
</P>
<P>
   Top freshmen: North Carolina's Jason Capel and Ron Curry, who
doubles as the Tar Heels' quarterback, DePaul's Quentin Richardson
and UNLV's Chris Richardson (no relation), Indiana's Dane Fife and
Florida's Mike Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Best transfers: Francis and Fresno State's Courtney Alexander
(formerly of Virginia) are the best of the bunch.
</P>
<P>
   Francis, a 6-foot-3 junior, teams with wing man LaRon Profit,
point guard Terrell Stokes and center Obinna Ekezie to give
Maryland its most talent lineup since the Buck Williams-Albert King
teams of the early 80s. The Terps are scheduled to play UCLA in the
second round of the San Juan Shootout, and that means big trouble
for the boys in blue.
</P>
<P>
   Pac-10 order of finish: 1.Stanford, 2.Cal, 3.Washington,
4.Arizona, 5.UCLA, 6.Arizona State, 7.USC, 8.Oregon, 9.Washington
State, 10.Oregon State.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford has the most experience, the most size, the most depth,
the best system and the best coach. Other than that, there's not
much to like.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA and Arizona will rely heavily on freshmen, each team
starting as many as three. But the Wildcats have two starting
seniors (point guard Jason Terry and center A.J. Bramlett) for
leadership while the Bruins have sophomores.
</P>
<P>
   And don't expect much from Baron Davis. Once he's cleared to
play _ perhaps early December _ it'll take him weeks to regain
timing and months to learn to play without his pre-injury
explosion. He should be near 100 percent for the 1999-2000 season,
if he stays in school.
</P>
<P>
   Pac-10's best 10: Arizona State forward Bobby Lazor, Cal guard
Geno Carlisle and forward Sean Lampley, Stanford guard Arthur Lee
and forward Mark Madsen, Washington center Todd MacCulloch and
guard Donald Watts, Oregon State guard Deaundra Tanner, Arizona
center Bramlett and UCLA freshman forward JaRon Rush.
</P>
<P>
   Madsen, Tanner and Lampley are the league's rising stars _ Rush
won't be around long enough _ but the most valuable player may be
Watts. If he's good, consistently good, the Huskies will have a
breakthrough season. If not, Washington will wallow in the middle
of the Pac.
</P>
<P>
   Pac-10's best freshmen: Rush is the best of them all, more
athletic than Kris Johnson, more skilled than Toby Bailey. Also,
watch for Arizona's Michael Wright, Oregon's Freddie Jones, USC's
Sam Clancy, Washington's Senque Carey and Cal's Shahar Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   The early word: Arizona freshman Ruben Douglas, a Bell-Jeff High
grad, is more polished than UCLA's Ray Young.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
