<SLUG> BC-GINGRICH-SUCCESSOR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gingrich favors Isakson as successor
 &HT;    By Clint Williams and Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As Johnny Isakson made plans to formally announce for
the congressional seat vacated by House Speaker Newt Gingrich, he
got more than a nudge Tuesday from the incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope Johnny Isakson will run,'' Gingrich said in a statement
released by his district office. ``He is a very close personal
friend and I believe he would do a great job of representing
Georgia's 6th District.''
</P>
<P>
   Isakson is expected to announce his candidacy today.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's statement likely was intended to send a message to
other Republicans contemplating the race, said Cobb County GOP
Chairman Don Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Newt wants a clean election,'' Hill said. ``The more
Republican names that are in the race, the more of a chance there
is for a Democrat to emerge.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time Georgia faced a special election to fill a
congressional seat was in 1983, after U.S. Rep. Larry McDonald died
in the crash of a Korean airliner shot down by a Soviet fighter.
The contest drew 20 candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said he and other party leaders spent Tuesday on the phone,
trying to figure out who else is interested in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Currently chairman of the state Board of Education, Isakson has
run two statewide campaigns. He lost a 1990 race to Zell Miller for
governor and a 1996 GOP primary for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for some candidates who lost their races last week but
whose campaigns are relatively intact, the opportunity is tempting.
The name of Democrat Michael Coles, who lost the U.S. Senate race
to Paul Coverdell, has been mentioned, but a spokesman for Coles
said he hasn't reached any decision.
</P>
<P>
   At least two Republicans, state Rep. Mitchell Kaye of Marietta
and Bruce Hatfield of Kennesaw, have said they will run regardless
of Isakson's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Newt's endorsement doesn't influence my decision,'' said
Hatfield, who finished fourth in the Republican gubernatorial
primary in July with 2 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye is a conservative first elected to the General Assembly in
1992. Kaye conceded Isakson would be the front-runner in the race,
but added, ``I'll surprise people. I'll be the Jesse `the Body'
Ventura of Georgia politics.''
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Chuck Clay said he continues to consider the race and
that Isakson's candidacy won't affect his decision.
</P>
<P>
   Even though many Republicans in the 6th District are pressing
for quick selection of Gingrich's successor, state elections
officials played down the possibility of a special election before
early 1999.
</P>
<P>
   After getting Gingrich's formal resignation, the governor has 10
days to call for a special election, which has to be at least 30
days after the governor's declaration.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich would have to resign before Friday and Gov. Zell Miller
would have to declare the special election within hours of
receiving the House speaker's letter for the contest to occur in
mid-December.
</P>
<P>
   Clint Williams and Kathey Pruitt write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
