<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIMSDELAY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA MAY POSTPONE HIGH-SCHOOL GRADUATION TEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CATHRYN CRENO,  
 LORI BAKER AND MELISSA JONES  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Class of 2001 may get a reprieve from Arizona's new
high-school graduation test requirement because the state schools
chief fears many kids aren't taking enough math to pass.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Graham Keegan, the state superintendent of public
instruction, announced Tuesday that she intends to ask the Arizona
Board of Education to give the Class of 2001 a break.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not happy about it,'' Keegan said. ``I wonder what is
going on with the leadership in our schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps half our our kids are not receiving the basic
algebra-geometry series that used to be high school math. What we
are teaching is pre-alegbra and commercial math. To know that maybe
half of our kids aren't taking that basic core is a distressing
place to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't think we should make our students pay the penalty
for what their schools didn't offer.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she recently reviewed raw scores from an AIMS pilot
test _ a test taken by 11th- and 12th-graders to weed out bad
questions _ and said the results were poor.
</P>
<P>
   The state school board adopted new academic standards and began
plans for the AIMS test _ Arizona Instrument to Measure Standards _
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning this spring, 10th-graders will have five chances to
pass two language and five math portions of the test. If Keegan has
her way, sophomores will still take the AIMS test up to five times,
but won't have to pass it to get a diploma. That requirement would
start with the Class of 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The state school board is expected to discuss the matter at a
Nov. 18 study session and, possibly, to vote on the change at its
regular Nov. 23 meeting.
</P>
<P>
   K.R. Scott, a Mountain Pointe High School teacher who ran as a
write-in candidate for Keegan's seat in the general election, said,
``We are happy to see that there's some reality creeping into the
Department of Education.''
</P>
<P>
   Keegan said she made the decision to ask for the reprieve after
numerous discussions with Gov. Jane Hull, Arizona Education
Association President Penny Kotterman, school district officials
and parents.
</P>
<P>
   Jaime Molera, Hull's education adviser, said the governor
supports delaying the graduation requirement, even until 2003 if
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Keegan said Tuesday that, although her staff sent copies of the
new academic standards to all districts two years ago and has spent
the past year traveling the state to discuss the AIMS, many
teachers are still unfamiliar with the stand ards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our methods of communication from the state to the
classroom level are not as efficient as they could be,'' Kotterman
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you send a notice to a district, sometimes that means it
goes to the superintendent and sometimes to the director of
curriculum, but it definitely does not go to teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   District officials, meanwhile, breathed a collective sigh of
relief Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wanted extra time,'' said Ralph Cadwallader,
associate superintendent for the Tempe Union High School District.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, districts including Mesa, Flagstaff and Safford wrote
letters to the state warning that many of their sophomores would
not be ready for the AIMS by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa Superintendent Jim Zaharis sent a five-page letter to the
state school board last month asking that the state reconsider the
timing of the test _ or forgo the graduation requirement altogether
and honor kids who pass the AIMS with special diplomas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't trying to be stubborn,'' he said. ``We have a
professional responsibility to say what we think will be
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Delaying the test will allow students more time to enroll in
courses they'll need to pass the test, said Zaharis, who would like
the graduation requirement to be held off even longer, to this
year's seventh-graders, the Class of 2004.
</P>
<P>
   But even one year is helpful, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It remained unclear Tuesday whether the entire state school
board would go for Keegan's idea.
</P>
<P>
   Board President Ken Bennett said Keegan had not discussed it
with him, although he added he would not oppose delaying the
graduation requirement if that proves necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Lisa is feeling like maybe we are ahead of where we need to
be or districts aren't as prepared as they were telling us early
on, we need to address that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Board members Bruce Kelp and Janet Martin, however, maintained
that they think the Class of 2001 should take the test _ and take
it seriously. Perhaps, they said, the cutoff point for passing
should be lowered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The implementation of the test needs to get started,'' Martin
said. ``But what a proficient score will look like still needs to
be determined.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Republic writers Patricia Biggs and Betty Reid contributed to
this article. &QL; 
The Republic's education writers can be reached at
education(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
