<HEADLINE>
SCORE 1 FOR CUOMO 
RELIVING TRIUMPH 
BEHIND THE BUBBLES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JAMES BARRON with C.J. SATTERWHITE, JOE BRESCIA and KIMBERLY
STEVENS 
 
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Next week it will reopen with clouds freshly painted
on the ceiling, windows that had been blacked out during World War
II uncovered, and computers installed for all to use.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, the Main Reading Room at the New York Public
Library on Fifth Avenue at 42nd Street was a dining room. Several
hundred patrons had paid a minimum of $1,500 each to attend the
Library Lions dinner, which raised $1.7 million for the library.
</P>
<P>
   ``The single most profitable evening in the library's history,''
the president, Paul LeClerc, said.
</P>
<P>
   The before-dinner drinks were served on one side of the reading
room. Then the guests _ who included Vernon Jordan, Andrew S.
Heiskell, Bianca Jagger and George Plimpton _ moved to the north
side, where the reading tables had been set up by Robert Isabell,
the designer, to look like dining tables from Elizabethan England.
</P>
<P>
   Which may explain why the talk at Table No. 45 turned to
Shakespeare. And before long, former Gov. Mario Cuomo had made a
bet about the origin of the line, ``Music has charms to soothe a
savage breast.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellie Cullman, whose husband is Edgar M. Cullman, the cigar
titan, said it was from ``Twelfth Night.'' Richard K. Descherer, a
senior partner at Willkie, Farr &AMP; Gallagher, said it was ``
`Twelfth Night' or some other Shakespeare.'' Cipa Dichter, the
pianist, and Thomas Morgan, the former head of WNYC-TV, also said
Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   But Cuomo bet ``two glasses of really good wine'' that it was
not.
</P>
<P>
   Then he said, ``As long as we're in the library, let's look it
up.'' He asked Andrew Kimball, the library's director of
governmental affairs, to find a copy of ``Bartlett's Familiar
Quotations.''
</P>
<P>
   Kimball said that he could find the answer faster on the new
computers. He logged on, hit the Bartlett's link and found that the
answer was not Shakespeare, but William Congreve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just won,'' Cuomo declared, adding that he had learned
everything he knew _ well, a lot, anyway _ at Public School 50, and
that the ``cumulative academic credentials of the people who said
it was Shakespeare is worth 30 Ph.D.'s.''
</P>
<P>
   Reliving Triumph
</P>
<P>
   How fortunate that the Yankees were the invited guests at a
party for the official 1998 World Series home video: Joe Torre
arrived saying that he was looking forward to actually seeing what
he missed during Games 1, 2, 3 and 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between talking to Zimmer and Stottlemyre,'' he said,
referring to Don and Mel, the coaches on the bench, ``you really
don't get to see much.'' Then Torre put his arm around his wife,
Alice, and watched the Yankees win the World Series again, this
time on big-screen monitors.
</P>
<P>
   When the lights came up, Torre looked to the back of the room
and said, ``I love you, Arthur Richman.'' It was Richman, an
adviser to Steinbrenner, who recommended Torre as Buck Showalter's
replacement after the 1995 season.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the Bubbles
</P>
<P>
   ``I was definitely the veteran of the party,'' said Claude
Taittinger, the 71-year-old owner of the centuries-old Champagne
maker that bears his family's name. ``But wearing a mask allowed me
to talk and flirt freely with all the young people. I looked like
an old Casanova, but no one could tell it was me.''
</P>
<P>
   And no wonder. Hoping to remake the company's image, he gave a
masquerade ball with Visionaire, the fashion magazine. Nearly 1,000
regulars from the downtown party circuit crowded into 88 Ninth
Avenue (the old Covenant House, now a nightclub).
</P>
<P>
   Among them were comedian Sandra Bernhardt, actress Marissa
Tomei, designer Calvin Klein and at least 15 guests in body paint
and nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   Except, of course, the obligatory masks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the Visionaire crowd would appreciate the fact that
Champagne has always been a drink that stimulates the creative
spirit,'' said Taittinger, sighing happily.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
