<DOCNO> NYT19981110.0445 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 23:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4359 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SCHUMER-UPSTATE-50     11-10 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHUMER-UPSTATE-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHUMER TRIES TO WIN OVER WARY UPSTATERS
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By GINGER THOMPSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OGDENSBURG, N.Y. _ Charles E. Schumer ventured into a part of
upstate New York Tuesday that both he and his hosts acknowledged
was hostile political territory for him, areas that voted
decisively for Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, who criticized Schumer for
voting against winter storm aid for the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know you don't know me,'' Schumer, a Democrat, told a small
gathering at a stop here, as he continued his statewide victory
tour following his defeat of D'Amato last week. ``I know there's a
lot of questions: `Is this guy from New York City going to care
about me?' All I can say is, give me a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Flying in a Piper Navajo under gray, rainy skies, Schumer,
rushed like a whirlwind through Watertown, Ogdensburg, Utica and
Elmira, carrying on more like a candidate than a senator-elect and
acting as though the campaign against D'Amato had never ended.
</P>
<P>
   Buoyant and confident, Schumer got warm receptions at every
stop. A couple of dozen people cheered as he got off the plane in
Utica. Almost 100 people gathered at a carpenters union hall in
Elmira.
</P>
<P>
   But the tone turned briefly serious when Schumer acknowledged
reports that he has received death threats since the election and
is now traveling with a security guard.
</P>
<P>
   The threats were first reported Tuesday in The Daily News.
Schumer said that he did not know who was responsible, but that the
New York City police were investigating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I have taken on the terrorists, I've taken on the
militias, and so you have people who are on the extreme right or
the extreme left who are not happy,'' he said in Utica. ``I'm not
really afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of the day, Schumer concentrated on trying to win over
his new upstate constituents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't let people divide us,'' he said in Ogdensburg. ``We only
lose when we fight one another.''
</P>
<P>
   After one of the most hard-fought races in the country this
year, Schumer defeated D'Amato in large part by outpolling the
Republican incumbent nearly 3 to 1 in New York City. But in
suburban areas, Schumer trailed 51 to 48 percent, and upstate,
voters preferred D'Amato, 54 to 44 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At each stop on his tour, people remarked that he was treading
on usually hostile territory. In Watertown, one man said there
might be enough Democrats in town to field a baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   But there were also signs that some people were warming up to
Schumer. Mayor Jeffrey Graham of Watertown _ once a Democrat, once
a Republican and now an independent _ handed Schumer a plaque
proclaiming him an honorary upstater. In Ogdensburg, Mayor Richard
Lockwood, a Democrat who had close ties to D'Amato, had been quoted
in The Ogdensburg Journal as saying that he was concerned about
losing D'Amato. But on Tuesday, after meeting Schumer, he said: ``I
think he'll be good for upstate. I called him yesterday. He's here
today. That's a pretty good sign.''
</P>
<P>
   The trip was the last such for Schumer before he leaves on
Thursday for a Florida vacation.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a union hall, at newspaper offices and in airports, Schumer
promised to bring jobs back to upstate New York. He said high power
costs and property taxes had priced companies out of the region,
and promised to support legislation to regulate power companies'
rates.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer also said he would support measures so that any federal
money from a tobacco settlement for the state _ an estimated $4
billion to $12 billion _ would be sent directly to county
governments to be used for tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   And touching on a local issue of great interest, Schumer said he
would urge discount airlines to open new routes to upstate
communities.
</P>
<P>
   The sharpest question came from a reporter in Watertown who
asked why Schumer had not visited the town during the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer replied: ``Would you rather have someone who comes
before the election, makes promises and never comes again? Or would
you rather have the guy who comes after winning, who promises to
work? I'm going to be that second guy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
