A4366 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKEES-WILLIAMS-     11-10 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-WILLIAMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR WILLIAMS, A SEARCH FOR RESPECT
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: BBA-YANKEES) 
(nk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAPLES, Fla. _ As Bernie Williams prepares for what is perhaps
the most critical decision of his career, the prevailing feeling is
that the path will not lead back to New York. The question is, why
not?
</P>
<P>
   Williams, one theory holds, has never forgiven the Yankees for
renewing his contract in 1994 and 1995 rather than negotiating his
salary. Now comes another possible explanation: His wife, Waleska,
no longer wants to be in New York and wants him to play elsewhere,
an official in the Yankees' organization said.
</P>
<P>
   The official declined to discuss publicly why she might not want
to remain in New York, but Scott Boras, Williams' agent, Tuesday
denied that animosity over previous contracts or the wishes of
Williams' wife were factors in the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Waleska informed everyone that she wanted Bernie to play where
Bernie was most happy, and if Bernie was most happy in New York
City that was something she was agreeable to and supportive of,''
Boras said.
</P>
<P>
   When Brian Cashman, the Yankees' general manager, was asked
about that, he said, ``I don't know that to be true.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams was in southern California on Tuesday with Boras. In
the center fielder's first job-hunting trip as a free agent, he
will visit the Arizona Diamondbacks on Wednesday. Because Buck
Showalter, Williams' former manager with the Yankees, is the
Diamondbacks' manager, the team has great interest in Williams and
is expected to make an attractive offer.
</P>
<P>
   Although Boras seeks a seven-year contract for perhaps $100
million, it is unclear how widespread the market is for Williams,
who this year won the American League batting championship and a
Gold Glove. The Los Angeles Dodgers and the Colorado Rockies, two
teams that had expressed early interest in Williams, have signed
center fielders in the past week.
</P>
<P>
   So have the Red Sox, but Darren Lewis can also play right field,
and Boston is expected to pursue Williams if they lose Mo Vaughn,
their run-producing first baseman, who also is a free agent. The
Baltimore Orioles plan to consider Williams, but they do not want
to pay Boras' price.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have not indicated what they will offer their
home-grown star. George Steinbrenner, the Yankees' principal owner,
is apparently waiting to see where the market goes for him. But the
club has seemed reluctant to offer the kind of deal Boras seeks.
The club's view of him, or at least the view of some club
officials, has fueled Williams' ill feeling.
</P>
<P>
   The contract renewals started it. For two seasons, when Williams
had no negotiating leverage, the Yankees renewed his contract with
a minimal increase. When Williams was finally eligible for salary
arbitration in 1996, the Yankees were prepared to settle close to
Williams' figure of $3 million a year without a hearing before an
arbitrator. But Williams told Boras he could not settle. Always a
fiery competitor, Williams was determined to go to arbitration and
beat the Yankees. He did just that.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides settled their salary differences the next two
seasons, but that didn't mean they avoided rancorous developments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem wasn't in business decisions,'' Boras said. ``They
went public and said Bernie wasn't a star player. This was Bob
Watson.''
</P>
<P>
   Boras contended that Watson, Cashman's predecessor as general
manager who left last off season, said he had taken a poll of
Yankee people and they had said ``Bernie was a good player but not
a great player.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson, Boras said, offered $24 million for five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `This is probably the best offer you're going to
get,''' Boras recounted. A year ago, he went on, Watson offered
$37.5 million for five years, saying, ``This is star money for a
nonstar player.''
</P>
<P>
   Boras also recalled flying to Tampa, Fla., to meet with
Steinbrenner in May 1996. ``He said he'd get back to us, and he
never did,'' the agent said.
</P>
<P>
   But all of that was in the past, Boras said with emphasis. The
business relationship turned around last winter when he and
Williams offered to compromise with the Yankees on their
arbitration numbers if the club agreed not to try to negotiate a
new contract during the season. Williams, Boras said, wanted to
concentrate on playing and did not want contract talk to interfere.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise worked for both player and team. Williams had an
outstanding season, and the Yankees won the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the past conduct opened the door for competition to
filter into this negotiation,'' Boras said, ``but as I've told the
Yankees numerous times, the Yankees are certainly one of the strong
considerations with Bernie.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, Boras added, have told them that Williams is their
No. 1 priority. ``I have no reason not to believe that,'' he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
