<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-10 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4373 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPINNEY-BIGBIRD-PROFI     11-10 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPINNEY-BIGBIRD-PROFILE-ART_NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
30 HAPPY YEARS AS AN 8-FOOT-TALL YELLOW BIRD
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(dal) 
 JOYCE WADLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Given that Big Bird is about to celebrate his 30th
birthday, one perhaps should not ask about disappointment and
frustration. But as the scorpion said after attacking the frog, ``I
can't help it _ I'm a scorpion,'' so let's get to it:
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't Caroll Spinney, the 64-year-old puppeteer who has played
Big Bird since its creation, feel frustrated in his work?
</P>
<P>
   Can ``Here we go, feathers, please'' be the cue of which an
actor has dreamed? What about range? Don't tell us lines like
``It's big! Really big!'' provide an actor with a satisfying range.
</P>
<P>
   A dissent from the affable Spinney, taking a break in his
dressing room at the Kaufman Astoria Studios, in his Big Bird leg
pants and a ``Sesame Street'' T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a huge dramatic range,'' says Spinney, whose offstage
voice, while not a baritone, is not nearly as high-pitched as Big
Bird's. ``I've gone from blubbering tears to wild happiness. It's
very satisfying. A mother on the Saskatchewan plains wrote me after
I did a show where Big Bird is too young to go to school with the
other children and feels very lonesome. Her son, who had no one to
play with, said, `Big Bird is just like me.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sesame Street,'' the award-winning children's show, begins its
30th season on Monday. Spinney has played both Big Bird _ a
6-year-old in the body of an 8-foot 2-inch canary _ and Oscar the
Grouch.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Big Bird, in his fluffy yellow feathers (turkey for
the body, ostrich for the tail, both dyed), who is the most loved,
perhaps because the bird asks the sort of questions the viewers
ask. Big Bird is also a very kind bird. He has performed in the
White House for every president since Nixon. (Don't get Spinney
started on Nancy Reagan; he found her very rude.) He has conducted
the Boston Pops and starred in his own movie.
</P>
<P>
   Spinney himself stands 5 feet 10 inches.
</P>
<P>
   (``What does puny mean?'' a classmate of the young Spinney asked
a teacher long ago. ``Caroll,'' the teacher said. ``Caroll is
puny.'')
</P>
<P>
   The man who plays the Bird has gone through some rough patches.
There was the time his first wife left him and he found himself
sobbing, on set, inside his yellow bird suit.
</P>
<P>
   But he is remarried now and happy. His gabled house in rural
Connecticut looks as if it were modeled after a house in a nicer
Grimm Brothers fairy tale: a place where Goldilocks, after a little
therapy, might learn about boundaries and coexist with the bears.
</P>
<P>
   Spinney fought his demons without a shrink.
</P>
<P>
   His theory about puppeteers is that they all once felt
themselves to be misfits. This was his experience, growing up
outside Boston, awkward and shy and unhappy in his physical self.
Spinney's father worked in a watch factory; his mother, a clothing
designer, gave up her career to raise her three sons.
</P>
<P>
   In school, Spinney was teased for being the shortest and
smallest boy in class. At home, he was in terror of his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a terrible temper, terrible temper,'' Spinney says.
``Once, when I was a kid, I fell out of a tree and got this huge
gash in my head and had to go to the emergency room. It cost all of
$2. My father said I was trying to put him in the poorhouse. He was
yelling instead of worried about his son, standing there in
bandages. Me.''
</P>
<P>
   Spinney saw his first puppet show when he was in kindergarten
and was smitten. He bought hand puppets, his mother made him
others, and at 12 he had 70 puppets and was doing shows at birthday
parties. His attraction to puppets, he says, is easy to explain.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a puppeteer you can hide whatever you are at the moment and
be only what they can see,'' Spinney says. ``And you could get the
adults to laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   Spinney had his first puppet show at 21, in Las Vegas. He
married, had three children and worked as a clown and puppeteer on
``The Bozo Show,'' in Boston. In 1968, at a puppet festival in Salt
Lake City, Spinney met Jim Henson, creator of the Muppets, who
invited him to join his new show.
</P>
<P>
   Was Spinney familiar with Henson's work?
</P>
<P>
   ``God, yes!'' Spinney says.``He was so devastatingly clever.
Most of puppetry was generally'' _ here, a word unsuitable for
newspapers and 5-year-olds. ``Like what I was doing. Jim Henson was
the Beatles of the puppet world.''
</P>
<P>
   In a way, Spinney, with his delight in play, would have seemed
the perfect family man; in his home in Connecticut, he built a
child's room with a secret passageway, from which a child could spy
down on the grown-ups in the dining room. But he was too busy too
often with the Muppets in New York. When he was 38, he and his wife
broke up. A year and a half later, Spinney met Debra Gilroy, a
secretary in the Muppets office. They have been married for 25
years: ``the happiest 25 years of my life,'' Spinney says.
</P>
<P>
   Life is good. The Bird earns more than $100,000 a year. The
Connecticut property includes a roller-skating rink and six picnic
areas. And, of course, Christmas is coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deb and I live for Christmas,'' Spinney says. ``A lot of
people complain they decorate the stores too early. It doesn't
bother me. We stay at home, watch the Dickens `Christmas Carol'
movies. I never get tired of Scrooge becoming nice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
