A4375 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-HEALTH-CLUBS-NYT &LR;      11-10 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HEALTH-CLUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN WORKING OUT IS ACTING OUT: GYMS CREATE FANTASY 
</HEADLINE>
  (duplication notice: also sent with `L' code) 
(bl) 
 By GINGER THOMPSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ By day Chad Klopotek, an investment consultant, lives
a mild-mannered existence. But at least one night a week, he gets
to play Firefighter Rookie No. 1, scaling a burning skyscraper,
saving a life and keeping off that little roll around his waist
that once came between him and his favorite pair of jeans.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Swiezy, a marketing associate, escapes the monotony of
conducting telephone surveys (and hopes to whittle down to her old
size 8 figure) by pretending she is a principal dancer of the New
York City Ballet. Dr. Louis Wolf, an oral surgeon, has enlisted in
``boot camp,'' doing pushups and situps on barked orders from a
former marine.
</P>
<P>
   In a craze that health experts describe as the fusion between
fitness and fantasy, these kinds of elaborate workouts are being
staged every day in gyms throughout New York and in big cities
across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Dismissed as passe and utterly mind-numbing are standard
routines like aerobics, step aerobics and body sculpting. The new
trend in workouts is hourlong sessions of sweaty, high-energy
theater _ complete with props, live music and instructors who
actually live what they teach _ that club owners hope will drive up
the growth of health club membership, which began a surge 10 years
ago that has leveled off in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most popular new workouts in Minneapolis is Funjah, a
class that teaches Afro-Cuban dance moves. Music for some Los
Angeles workouts is performed by live gospel choirs.
</P>
<P>
   But no place matches the number of the gimmicky workouts
available in New York. New York Sports Clubs hold workouts led by
former NFL football players in which people learn to pass and dodge
tackles. At the World Gym in the Village, there are swing dance
workouts modeled after the latest Gap commercials. Several New York
gyms offer ``Abs, Thighs and Gossip,'' a muscle-toning workout led
by a man in drag.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was starting to get bored with running and lifting
weights,'' said Klopotek, 24, after a recent firefighter workout at
Crunch on the East Side of Manhattan. ``This workout gives me
something new.''
</P>
<P>
   Surveys by the International Health, Racquet &AMP; Sportsclub
Association, a trade organization, indicate that over the last few
years health club memberships have grown by only the slimmest of
margins. Less than 10 percent of Americans are gym members,
according to the association. New York has a slightly higher
percent, 11.2, but that figure represents an increase of only 2
percentage points over the last six years.
</P>
<P>
   Health club managers have come to realize that they can't keep
members just with the latest exercise equipment because people
often buy their own machines these days. What people cannot buy for
their homes, however, are experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Crunch is the only gym in New York to offer the firefighter
workout. It is led by Eric Torres, a beefy New York City
firefighter.
</P>
<P>
   The scene is set with the sound of a radio dispatcher's call for
help. There's a 10-75, the voice pleads through static, firefighter
code for a burning building. Then come the sirens, and the red and
white flashes of light. Torres, often decked out in full gear,
pretends the fire has grown to three alarms.
</P>
<P>
   He orders his battalion of rookies _ the participants in his
class _ to pick up their hoses, bundles of the real thing that
weigh 15 to 25 pounds. Then he shouts: ``The elevator's broken.
We'll have to climb the stairs! Let's go rookies, 80 flights.''
</P>
<P>
   The class groans. But they step as fast as they can _ up and
down and up and down _ on a step bench. After they have climbed and
climbed, their leader shouts for them to pick up weighted bars and
act as though they are battering down a wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on rookies, pull down that wall _ one, two, three,'' he
shouts. ``We've added air to the fire! Backdraft! Get down! Crawl.
One, two, three . . .''
</P>
<P>
   A collective groan comes from the class. They fall and drag
themselves on their knees and elbows across the floor. Dozens of
backdrafts and flights of stairs later, they find a victim _ a
125-pound crash-test dummy _ lying on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The rookies grimace as they take turns dragging the dummy to
safety. When Klopotek steps up, Torres decides to increase the
load. The firefighter, a solid 200 pounds, falls to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need help, rookie!'' he shouts at Klopotek, a class veteran.
``Come and get me.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the one-hour workout, Klopotek is drenched with
sweat and gasping so hard for air that it is hard to tell that he
feels good until he catches his breath and heaves out a few words.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Another workout at Crunch, ``Abs, Thighs and Gossip,'' gets more
mixed reviews. Offered several times a week, it is a lot like a
body-sculpting routine with weight training and low-impact
aerobics. But the antics of its instructor, Anthony Truly, have
made the class one of the most talked-about gym stories in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Truly, who describes his class as a mix of weight training, pop
culture, diva worship and a little male bashing, teaches in drag.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a new outfit I've been dying to premiere,'' he gushed
on a recent Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The transformation took only a few minutes. He pulled off his
baggy blue jeans, revealing tight spandex shorts and black fishnet
stockings. Then he slipped into a pair of white platform Converse
sneakers and a black tulle jacket with tails. He finished off the
outfit with his signature auburn wig, glittery peach lipstick and
eyeliner.
</P>
<P>
   After an unsuccessful flirtation with professional acting, Truly
now performs only in front of sweating students. During the
hourlong classes, he jokes about his relationship with his lover,
rates on a scale of 1 to 10 the physique of the men who walk by the
window, and explores the latest tabloid gossip, all the while
lifting hand weights and leading his disciples in squats and
stomach crunches.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Lennard, who manages a restaurant near the West Village
club, was not amused. ``For me, the humor was a little over the
top,'' Ms. Lennard, 37, said. ``I'd probably like it better with a
little less joking around.''
</P>
<P>
   A little laughter is just what Joy Gazzoli, 45, and Al
DiRaffaele, 52, felt was missing from their workouts. So a few
weeks ago, they started to swing, by taking swing dance classes on
Saturday afternoons at the World Gym on Mercer Street in the
Village. The class is an hour of big band jazz and high-speed
twirls.
</P>
<P>
   The couple does not hit every dance step just right, but they
have a lot of fun and figure that they each burn off about 300
calories each class. And now, they are swing dancing inside the gym
and out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were walking down near Battery Park last week and we heard
swing dance music on a loudspeaker,'' DiRaffaele said. ``So we
stopped right there on the sidewalk and started dancing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives us something fun to do together,'' Ms. Gazzoli
said, ``and you find yourself laughing, which you don't do a lot of
times in a gym.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
