<HEADLINE>
LAMBRIGHT, HUARD NOT THE ROOT OF HUSKY EVIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Here's some friendly, unsolicited, nevertheless
brilliant advice for Jim Lambright and Brock Huard, the two most
put-upon guys in the University of Washington football program.
</P>
<P>
   It's OK.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly Churchillian in inspiration and cleverness, is it?
Well, sometimes the simple approach is best. We are, after all,
talking college football.
</P>
<P>
   Given the growing dismay over a 5-4 Husky team that could wind
up with its first losing season since before the Kingdome was
built, Lambright and Huard should know that somebody around here
isn't convinced they're vampires or something.
</P>
<P>
   Besides being torqued over losing to Oregon last Saturday, Huard
came home to some further bad news, at least in his mind.
</P>
<P>
   After overthrowing receiver Andre DeSaussure, who had blown his
route, the network TV cameras caught the quarterback, palms up,
mouthing the words, ``'Dre, what the (heck) are you doing?''
</P>
<P>
   Returning from Eugene, he called his girlfriend, Molly, who
said, ``You really let it slip on national TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Huard saw her tape of the game, which also showed lesser moments
of pique.
</P>
<P>
   Over-responsible guy that he is, Huard apologized to his team,
his pastor, his family and just about everyone else in Christendom.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could openly see my frustration,'' he said. ``I heard from
quite a few people. That's bad. I wasn't too pleased with my vocal
swearing on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Huard apparently is taking calls on the matter, here's a
comment from Art from Seattle: Hallelujah.
</P>
<P>
   About bloody time, Brock. I don't care whether you swear, but a
little more irascibility and a little less effort at perfection
would seem to be a healthy thing.
</P>
<P>
   Huard is such a committed Christian, such a role model, such a
leader and such a bearer of high expectations that I'm amazed the
guy hasn't turned into a diamond from all the pressure on him.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, he has handled the burden superbly. But the
fact is, he's a very good college quarterback and the only proven
skill player on the offense, where nearly everyone else is letting
him down. He's the guy who passed on the NFL to come back, and his
mates are blowing routes, dropping balls, and generally comporting
themselves as the bewildered underclassmen that they are.
</P>
<P>
   Huard can't help a lot of that. But he's certainly not going to
hurt much by occasionally getting in his teammates' faces, and not
worrying about consequences. At least he'll feel better.
</P>
<P>
   Huard seemed to acknowledge a little annoyance with the burden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not always,'' he said with a small smile, ``the golden
boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Regarding his coach, Lambright has come under the expectable
hail of oral gunfire for the 5-4 season. Losing four out of five to
Oregon will do that, and indeed some of the brickbats are well
deserved.
</P>
<P>
   The part that isn't deserved is the suggestion that Don James
would never let such things happen. Or is it forgotten that James,
late in his Husky career, was a .500 coach for a considerable
stretch?
</P>
<P>
   After two wins to start the 1987 season, the Huskies under James
closed out with 4-4-1 record. The '88 season was a 6-5
disappointment that ended the Husky bowl streak. The '89 season
began with easy wins over Texas A&AMP;M and Purdue, then defeats to
Arizona 20-17, Colorado 45-28, and Southern Cal 24-16.
</P>
<P>
   That added up to a 25-game mark of 12-12-1 over parts of three
seasons for the coach Sports Illustrated labeled first, second and
third on its list of best coaches. Of course, James is remembered
mostly for what happened two years later _ the national
co-championship.
</P>
<P>
   But two years after that, the Huskies were busted by the Pac-10
for cheating, James quit, and the program is still picking up the
pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lambright was part of the misdeeds, he is also around
for the consequences, which this week for the UCLA game means the
Huskies have four seniors starting on offense and two on defense.
</P>
<P>
   Many Husky fans have grown weary of the sanctions excuse. But
there's no disputing that when the scholarship losses combined with
the early departures of offensive linemen Olin Kreutz and Benji
Olson and defensive back Mel Miller (suspended), the Huskies this
season have a mediocre talent base.
</P>
<P>
   One big difference between James and Lambright is that James had
three Rose Bowls in his pocket before his record slumped. Another
big difference is James never had to argue against the sanctions
smear in recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   Lambright gets no slack for the same kind of recruiting and
playcalling shortcomings that James, and every head coach, commits.
Every time he makes baffling play calls, as was done against
Oregon, or fumbles personnel issues such as with Shane Fortney or
Nick Lentz, he burns up political capital he doesn't have.
</P>
<P>
   As with Huard, the margin for error is negligible. He should
feel just as free to say bad words on national TV, although I
suspect Lambright will be nailed for mispronunciation.
</P>
<P>
   Difference is, God will likely forgive Huard before Husky
boosters forgive Lambright.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-10-98 2351EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
