<SLUG> BC-DOLE-MEMORIAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLE AIMS TO ENLIST HOLLYWOOD IN CAMPAIGN FOR WWII MEMORIAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY JIM SKEEN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hollywood uses World War II as a backdrop for
scores of films _ most recently Steven Spielberg's ``Saving Private
Ryan'' _ but former presidential candidate Bob Dole says the movie
industry is missing in action when it comes to honoring the
veterans of that war.
</P>
<P>
   Dole, the national chairman of the campaign to raise $100
million for a World War II memorial, said the movie industry could
provide a big boost for fund-raising efforts, but thus far hasn't
shown any interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had no luck with the movie industry. I've been turned
down twice by (Disney chief) Michael Eisner,'' Dole said in a
recent telephone interview from his Washington, D.C. law office.
``If there is an industry that should be contributing it is the
movie industry with all those great World War II movies, like
`Saving Private Ryan.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Dole said he will continue to push movie executives for
donations and that filmmaker Steven Spielberg will be among those
called.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to get this thing done,'' Dole said. ``We need the
movie industry to come in with $10 million.''
</P>
<P>
   A Disney representative said the corporation gives heavily to
charity, but has not signed up for the war memorial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already made substantial commitments to the Disney
Concert Hall in Los Angeles and other charitable causes,'' said
Claudia Peters, a spokeswoman for Disney, which reported 1997
profits of $296 million. ``We are deferring any decision on the
memorial for the time being.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Spielberg said the DreamWorks SKG founder is
awaiting a call from the former lawmaker, but didn't know whether a
donation would be forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve has been supportive in a number of ways to veterans
groups,'' said Spielberg spokesman Marvin Levy. ``I'm sure this is
a conversation he is looking forward to.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole and co-Chairman Frederick Smith, chief executive officer of
FDX Corp., are leading the fund-raising charge on behalf of the
American Battle Monuments Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is overseeing efforts to build a World War II
memorial on 5.5 acres on the National Mall between the Lincoln
Memorial and the Washington Monument.
</P>
<P>
   While there are memorials dedicated to those who fought in World
War II, notably the USS Arizona memorial at Pearl Harbor and the
Iwo Jima memorial at Arlington National Cemetery, there is no
national monument. The Vietnam and Korean wars, smaller conflicts
with fewer American casualties than World War II, have national
memorials.
</P>
<P>
   That means there is no national recognition for the more than
140,000 World War II veterans in Los Angeles County, monument
proponents say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an oversight. No one really thought about it,'' Dole
said.
</P>
<P>
   The design for the World War II memorial is an oval plaza, about
seven feet below street level, around an area known as the Rainbow
Pool. The memorial will have two granite arches with bronze laurel
wreaths, symbolizing valor and victory, suspended beneath them.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters had hoped to dedicate the memorial on Veterans Day in
2000, but Dole said he doesn't expect they will be able to meet
that goal. Dole hopes they will at least have broken ground on the
memorial by that date.
</P>
<P>
   Dole was an army lieutenant in World War II, earning a Bronze
Star and two Purple Hearts. Dole was wounded during a battle in
Italy, and lost the use of his right arm.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 17, 1997, the day he was awarded the Medal of Freedom by
President Clinton, Dole was approached by the memorial supporters
about the possibility of leading the campaign. Dole estimates he
and Smith conduct anywhere from 10 to 30 conference calls a week
seeking donations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of a day that goes by when I'm not talking about
it,'' Dole said. ``It's going to be hard to raise this money. We
have $35 million to $40 million, but it's hard to raise $100
million from the private sector.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the federal legislation authorizing the memorial's
construction, the American Battle Monuments Commission has until
May 2000 to obtain the construction permit. All money must be in
hand and the final design must be approved before that permit can
be issued.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want something 20, 30 years from now when there are no
veterans around so there will be something there for the
children,'' Dole said. ``We want to get this thing done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
