<SLUG> BC-BBO-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL'S CRAZY DAYS ARE HERE AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ You might hear the Dodgers are about to unload
Gary Sheffield's crushing salary on the San Diego Padres and get a
stronger bullpen in return. But then, you might hear a lot of funny
things these days.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball, like golf, has a silly season, and it's upon us again,
with the winter meeting under way in Naples, Fla. Major-league
general managers and a bunch of sportswriters are locked in a hotel
together with nothing to do except invent deals that might or might
not have a prayer of happening.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday morning, the sports wire carried 46 baseball stories,
which was more than college football, more than college basketball,
more than pro hockey and more than pro basketball. More than any
sport except pro football, which has the advantage of actually
having results to report.
</P>
<P>
   It's a great time of year to be a baseball fan, as long as
you're not the sort who demands a game to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Even more than the optimistic days of spring training, it's the
time of year when all things are possible, from purposeful spending
by the Angels to a pennant for the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   A Giants fan learns his team is raising its salary budget. A
Tigers fan learns his team made an offer to Padres third baseman
Ken Caminiti. A Diamondbacks fan learns his team's owner is getting
cozy with free-agent pitcher Randy Johnson. A Red Sox fan learns
his team has raised its offer to first baseman Mo Vaughn from four
years and $37 million to five years and $60 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox fan also sees where general manager Dan Duquette
claims the Angels' recent six-year, $72 million offer to Vaughn
``doesn't matter to me'' and had nothing to do with the upgrade,
which is either a false statement or a foolish one.
</P>
<P>
   Onto the scene of such loose and fanciful talk steps Kevin
Malone, the new Dodgers general manager who likes to talk ball as
much as the next guy.
</P>
<P>
   Malone didn't much like it when some of us wrote last month that
the extraordinary openness of the Dodgers manager search raised
expectations and caused him embarrassment when Felipe Alou said no.
Malone thought, I go out of my way to return reporters' phone calls
and this is the thanks I get?
</P>
<P>
   No offense was intended. His personality will result in more
good than bad.
</P>
<P>
   He's perfect for the winter meetings, a garrulous guy who'll
chat up everybody in Naples and keep the news wire burbling with
optimistic speculation about this trade and that free agent. He's
perfect for Dodgers fans, who could use some holiday cheer.
</P>
<P>
   But the question for Malone this week is, should he go so far as
to encourage dreams of the trade that was the talk of L.A. sports
Tuesday, the one that would send outfielder Gary Sheffield and
shortstop Mark Grudzielanek to San Diego in exchange for outfielder
Greg Vaughn, relief pitcher Randy Myers and shortstop Chris Gomez?
</P>
<P>
   It's a fantasy deal that would do all this for the Dodgers: Dump
Sheffield's $50 million in salary during the next five years,
freeing Australian dollars with which Malone could pay David Cone,
Kevin Brown or Randy Johnson to be the team's much-needed pitching
ace; bring in a 50-home-run left fielder to replace Sheffield; and
give them, in the prickly person of Myers, a set-up man for closer
Jeff Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds great. Sounds impossible, too.
</P>
<P>
   Cutting the Dodgers' $139 million in future payroll commitments
is job one for Malone, but getting out from under Sheffield won't
be easy. And it won't involve the Padres, who lost $11 million
while winning the pennant and are bent on cutting last season's $53
million payroll while re-signing Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield will have to go to a large-market team with a large
vault.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Malone is in no position to pull off the kind
of blockbuster free-agent signings that would transform the team.
We'll have to be content with building-block moves like the signing
of 35-year-old center fielder Devon White and the re-signing of
Shaw last week.
</P>
<P>
   So don't judge Malone's accomplishments this winter based on the
sort of best-case scenarios you'll hear about this week. We'll have
to be content with smaller steps, many of which will sound familiar
to wishful Dodgers fans _ adding some left-handed power, and adding
a set-up man or deciding Scott Radinsky is good enough in that
role.
</P>
<P>
   Until the ledger books are balanced, idle chatter about bigger
moves will be just that.
</P>
<P>
   A friend from the Denver area told me it's an L.A. thing and
kidded, ``You don't get that in cities that have pro football.''
</P>
<P>
   But you do get that, anywhere they're talking baseball. It's the
time of year. &QL; 
Kevin Modesti's column appears in the Daily News three days a week.
He can be reached at (818) 713-3616.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
